<html><head><title> More than one way to quench a thirst</title><!!keys: ></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600"><img src="../../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right><h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <ahref="../../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right><p><h2 align=center> More than one way to quench a thirst</h2></p><p><font size=4><font size=+2>B</font>ritain suffered a dry summer? In India, drought affects not lawns but whole lives. ACTIONAID's help varies according to the needs - and skills - of each community.</font><hr><TABLE BORDER=0 width=260 align=left hspace=10 vspace=10><TR><TH><TABLE BORDER=0 width=250><TR><TD> <img src="12.jpg" align=left hspace=4 vspace=4 width=250 height=162 border=1></TD></TR><TR><TD> <font size=small face=helvetica, arial>Photo: Mark Slide</font> &copy;.<p></TH></TR></TABLE></TD></TR></TABLE><p>As taps ran dry in British homes this summer, people once again became used to bans on watering their lawns, and saw standpipes installed in their streets. A nuisance, certainly - and a special irritation in a typically rainy country - but not a threat to livelihoods. <p>Thousands of miles away in southern India's arid Karnataka state, though, during the summer drought it is not lawns that go thirsty, but families and crops. Here, temperatures reach 46<font=small>o</font>C during the day, and rain falls on just 41 days of the year. Summer crops wither for lack of moisture, and water for drinking and washing is harder to find.<p>When water is so precious, people become especially inventive in developing ways to find, save and store it. The people of Karnataka are no different, but in the past have not always had the money or the technical expertise to solve the long-term problem. <p>Now, using loans or expertise from ACTIONAID - the type of help provided depends on the community's existing resources - they are able to do just that. As a result, farmers can grow full summer crops for the first time in living memory and an increasing number of people will have access to safe drinking water.In the Raichur district of Karnataka state, ACTIONAID supports a local organisation called Samuha, which in Sanskrit - the ancient language of India - means an organised group or society. <p>Samuha brings together poor families to analyse their problems and identify solutions. Work focuses on improving  people's economic status through agricultural and water development projects, and through savings and credit programmes.<p>In Karnataka, Samuha has offered the most appropriate help to different communities, leading to some very varied types of project.<p><p><b>1) The oil engine</b><p>At a small settlement near Samuha's headquarters in Raichur district, the English words 'oil engine' are relayed by villagers with infectious enthusiasm to a visiting member of the Samuha team. <p>	The centre of conversation, a diesel-powered water pump about the size of the engine of a family car, has been purchased by locals with the help of a loan from Samuha's savings and credit scheme. Under this scheme, members save a small amount each month and in return have access to loans from a central fund provided by ACTIONAID but administered by the community. <p>	The pump draws water from open wells, which is then sprayed meticulously into selected furrows - a significant leap forward after years of having to onerously extract water from an open well using an ox-skin sack pulled by two bullocks.<p>Sales from the crops of sunflowers and groundnuts that spring up as a result provide a new income for villagers who, before the engine's arrival, faced each summer with dread. Thanks to this, the loan is now paid off, and talk is of buying 'Oil engine 2'. <TABLE BORDER=0 width=180 hspace=10 vspace=10 align=right><TR><TH><TABLE BORDER=0 width=160 bgcolor=FFCC99><TR><TD><img src="13.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=6 width=150 height=206></TD><tr><TD><p><font size=small face=helvetica>A detailed landscape map of Herundi (left), drawn up by the villagers, has helped Samuha design an irrigation and drainage system for the village. At a small settlement near Samuha's headquarters in Raichur district, people have to draw water laboriously from an open well using an ox-skin sack (top of page). Now, a loan from Samuha has allowed them to buy a diesel-powered pump.<p>(Mark Slide</font> &copy;).</TD></TR></TABLE></TH></TR></TABLE><br clear=left><p><b>2) The satellite</b><p>In the nearby village of Herundi, 20-year-old Mallana is diligently ploughing fields with the help of his oxen. Despite being only yards from the River Krishna, he knows that a good cotton crop is dependent on the river receiving a steady supply of rainfall from the Monsoon - flash floods will cause it to overflow, washing away the fertile topsoil and, with it, vital income for Mallana's family.<p>Here, Samuha has helped by providing technological support which Mallana could not have had access to by himself, but which will revolutionise his life and those of other farmers in the area. Using satellite images of soils and drainage patterns from the India Space Research station at  Bangalore, together with detail from a landscape map drafted by the village, Samuha has designed an irrigation and drainage system that will allow water from the river to be pumped at controlled levels, over the surrounding crops.<p>Sangana Guoda (45) is one of the farmers who have given time and precious savings to support the scheme. &quot;We have been experiencing drought here for the past 20 years, and the only way to survive a bad summer has been to take a loan from the bank. Now, this year's bank loan will be our last. All the families in the village are behind the plan because they know it will give them a lifestyle that has never before been possible.&quot;<p><b>3) The committees</b><p>Sometimes, the money exists to make improvements, but not the methods to put them into effect - while still ensuring that the communities themselves take part in, maintain and 'own' the programmes. Here, ACTIONAID may need to provide not money but its skills and experience in social organisation.<p>The World Bank-sponsored Integrated Rural Water Supply and Environmental Sanitation project in Karnataka covers about 1200 villages in 12 districts. Here, for the first time, the government of India  is attempting systematically to involve people in the planning, funding, implementation and maintenance of a water and sanitation project.<p> Samuha and another ACTIONAID partner, the Development Promotion Group, have taken up the work in Raichur and Bellary districts respectively. <p>They have helped to establish village committees to examine and approve plans, and raise funds to cover 30 per cent of the environmental sanitation costs. In some cases, villagers who cannot afford the money will contribute to the costs by providing free labour.<p>&quot;The people's contribution to the expenditure on environmental sanitation is the most critical component of the project,&quot; says Samuha Project Leader GL Janardhan. &quot;Without it, their participation will not be truly recognised, either by themselves or the government.&quot;Money, technology or social institutions: there is more than one way to help the people of Karnataka solve their chronic drought problems. Whatever the circumstance, ACTIONAID is looking to find the best - and the most cost-effective - way of achieving change. <p>Access to clean water is a vital part of ACTIONAID'S development work, and is the subject of a current appeal.<p><p><hr><p><a href="../../home.html"><img src="../../pix/home.gif" width=46height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><a href="../../fight/index.html" target="_parent"><imgsrc="../../pix/globe1.gif" width=46height=41hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a> <a href="../index.html"><img src="../../pix/back.gif" width=46height=41hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><font size=1 face=helvetica, arial><li type=square><b><a href="../../home.html">Home Page</a></b> <li type=square><b><ahref="../../fight/index.html" target="_parent">JoinACTIONAID</a></b> <li type=square><b><a href="../index.html">Common Cause</a></b></font><br clear=all><p></body></html>␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀␀
