<html><head><title> Fighting the food gap</title><!!keys: ></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600"><img src="../../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right><h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <ahref="../../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right><p><h2 align=center> Fighting the food gap</h2></p><p><TABLE BORDER=0 width=230 align=right hspace=10 vspace=10><TR><TD><TABLE BORDER=0 width=210><TR><TD> <img src="14.jpg" align=right hspace=4 vspace=4 width=200 height=154 border=1></TD></TR><TR><TD> <font size=small face=helvetica, arial>Photo: Adrian Arbib</font> &copy;.</TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR></TABLE><p><p><font size=4><font size=+2>T</font>here may be real hope of finding solutions to Ethiopia's problems - but poor communities still go without food during the hungry season. Savings and credit schemes can help them through this 'food gap'. </font><p><hr><p>In a small village near Dalocha in   southern Ethiopia, 25 men and women are seated in a circle on the ground in the shade of a large tree. It is eight o'clock in the morning and they have gathered before they start work in the fields. This is the weekly meeting of the Tofik savings and credit group, one of over a hundred groups established with ACTIONAID assistance in the Dalocha area. <p>It is with savings and credit groups such as these that ACTIONAID is working to create real and lasting changes in people's lives. The principle is quite simple. Very often all a farmer needs to improve the productivity of his land is some fertiliser. Or, if he had his own ox to plough his land, he could save the two thirds of his crops that he would normally pay to use a richer farmer's animal. <p>Small improvements such as these can mean substantial changes for a family, but to achieve them requires income that few have. Nor do the poorest farmers in Dalocha have access to credit - few banks would lend to somebody with no security, and private loans, if available, can mean hefty interest rates. This is where ACTIONAID comes in. Through its savings and credit scheme, farmers have access to loans that enable them to improve their own lives and build greater security for their families in the longer term. This week, members of the Tofik group are discussing how they will organise repayment of loans for oxen, seed and fertiliser. There is much disagreement about how much they can afford and the right levels of credit, but eventually a decision is reached. <p>Being part of the group, the members say, has boosted their confidence and raised their status within the community. According to Chairman Kemal Detgeber: &quot;Before, being the poorest farmers, we were nothing. Now, because of the group, we can be confident of having materials for the next planting season and we are proud of what we have achieved. Even the rich farmers are asking to join!&quot;<p>Helping find a solution for all the community to last year's food shortages, achieved much of this 'status' for the Tofik group and other ACTIONAID savings and credit groups around Dalocha. Problems of pestilence and severe hail storms in 1993 had left food reserves across the country very low. In 1994, the April/May belg rains failed to arrive and the main krempt rains were late, so farmers were having to make food, already in short supply, last through to the next harvest in November. It also meant many would be tempted to eat the seed needed for planting. Some families in Dalocha were reduced to eating one meal a day. <p>ACTIONAID field workers met weekly with villagers in Dalocha to discuss the problems they faced and to monitor hunger levels. According to Programme Manager Mohammed Halo: &quot;By June we were concerned for the longer term interests of the community. Some were starting to sell their livestock and the rights to their land or the next harvest in an effort to buy grain at escalated prices.&quot;  <p>The Ethiopian government, recognising the early signs of a potentially devastating situation, called upon the world community for help. Pledges of nearly one million tonnes of food aid were made and preparations began for distribution across the country. <p>However, at an emergency meeting with all the savings and credit groups in Dalocha, the leaders told ACTIONAID they did not want handouts of food or seed. This was not, said the groups, how ACTIONAID had helped them in the past, so why should it be the case now? Instead they asked for additional credit of seeds, fertiliser and blankets to help them through, which they would repay on special terms. <p>The groups also proposed that 9,000 households in the community, including non group members, should be given 100kg of grain each for consumption, to tide them over for the three months until the next harvest. This was provided by ACTIONAID on an interest-free credit basis, with a long-term repayment option for members who already had other credit payments owing. <p>In total, 50,000 people in the Dalocha area were able to survive the crisis thanks to the partnership established between the groups and ACTIONAID. Fortunately the main rains in 1994, when they came, were sufficient to ensure a reasonable    harvest, and by December the farmers had already started to pay back the additional loans.    <p> However, it is a deep-rooted problem which has not gone away. Already this year the Ethiopian government has recognised a likely shortfall of food supplies and has requested help in the form of half a million tonnes of grain. <p>The reasons for this regular food deficit are many. Two decades of an oppressive communist regime has taken its toll, with high expenditure on the      military detracting from investment in industries - including agriculture, which is the backbone of the economy - and in infrastructure, hampering distribution across the country. <p>Erratic rainfall and environmental degradation also challenge agricultural production, while a growing population is continuing to put pressure on the country's resources. <p>Since 1991, though, there has been cause for optimism. With peace and political stability, there have been clear steps towards economic liberalisation and an increase in expenditure on health, education and infrastructure. With elections due in May, there are high hopes in the new government. <p>It would be unrealistic to expect a rapid improvement in Ethiopia's food security, though. In the meantime, if famine on the scale seen in 1984/85 is to be averted again, preventative measures as found with the savings and credit groups are vital. <p>They, together with systems to give early warning of hunger, must be the priority - as any member of the Tofik savings and credit group will tell you.<hr><TABLE BORDER=0 width=280 align=left hspace=10 vspace=10><TR><TD><TABLE BORDER=0 width=260><TR><TD> <img src="16.jpg" align=left hspace=4 vspace=4 width=250 height=154 border=1></TD></TR><TR><TD> <font size=small face=helvetica, arial>Photo: Adrian Arbib</font> &copy;.</TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR></TABLE><h3>Being the 'bank manager'     in your spare time...</h3><p>Belene Aday ( left) is facing a difficult meeting. As Chairman of the Bale Geze  savings and credit group in Koysha, south west Ethiopia, he must help the group deal with a member, Asafa, who is now two weeks behind with his repayments. <p>The group is taking a hard line - if one person gets behind with their payments, this can threaten the scheme for all of them - but Belene urges them not to be hasty in casting out a fellow member. Asafa is, after all, a peasant farmer, struggling to make ends meet like the rest of them.<p>However, Belene knows that should Asafa continue not to pay, this could involve him in a great deal of extra work. The ultimate sanction in such a case would be to take Asafa to the court of their local Peasant Association. As chairman, this would be Belene's responsibility. &quot;I am worried about the time this will take,&quot; he says. &quot;I will have to find a compromise between my farm work and my role as chairman.&quot;<p>The group chose Belene as their chairman and he takes his responsibilities very seriously. &quot;It is my job to co-ordinate the group, to ensure we are disciplined at meet-ings and to keep members motivated to make their payments on time,&quot; he explains. <p>Each member saves 25 cents (three pence) a week - an amount which, in an area where cash is scarce, can be difficult to maintain. But Belene is clear of the benefits. When the Bale Geze group started eight months ago, Belene was one of the first to take credit - for a draught ox. He will share this with another member and together they will take four years to pay for it. Before, Belene had to borrow an ox to plough his land and the cost was high - two thirds of the crop yield. <p>And he has further ambitions: &quot;I personally would like to do more than just dig the land. I want to get involved in income generating activities, even to own my own shop.&quot;<p><TABLE BORDER=0 width=230 align=right hspace=10 vspace=10><TR><TD><TABLE BORDER=0 width=210 bgcolor=FFCC99><TR><TD> <img src="15.jpg" align=right hspace=4 vspace=4 width=200 height=143></TD></TR><TR><TD> <p><font size=small face=helvetica>Each member of the Bale Geze savings and credit group saves 25 cents (about 3p) a week. It's a big sum for the farmers - but the benefits can be equally large.</font><p> <font size=small face=helvetica, arial>Photo: Adrian Arbib</font> &copy;.<p></TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR></TABLE><p>However, like the other farmers of Bale Geze, Belene's primary concern is ensuring his family is fed and clothed. Crop failures due to the late rains in 1994 have left most facing a difficult year, and Belene worries that without enough clothes and nutrition his son, Bedeke, will not be able to continue going to school.Belene grows teff, beans, peas and sorghum in his fields, and hopes with the help of the ox he will produce enough for his family to eat and some to sell. Only by selling some produce do they have cash for clothes and other essentials. Belene has already planned what he will do once he has paid for the ox: &quot;I will take credit to buy a cow.&quot;<p>At the end of the weekly meeting the Bale Geze savings and credit group decides to allow Asafa to remain a member providing he improves his repayment record in the coming month. Belene is relieved. They have also decided to impose a new penalty - 50 cents for members who are late for the meeting. <p><b>Key facts: ACTIONAID in Ethiopia</b><p>Dalocha and Koysha, featured in this article, are two of four ACTIONAID development areas in Ethiopia. The others are in Tigray and Addis Ababa. In all, 130,000 people benefit from development activities.  <p><TABLE BORDER=0 width=180 align=left hspace=10 vspace=10><TR><TD><TABLE BORDER=0 width=160 bgcolor=FFCC99><TR><TD> <img src="17.jpg" align=left hspace=4 vspace=4 width=150 height=198></TD></TR><TR><TD> <p><font size=small face=helvetica>Neseria Ahmed, pictured here with her four children, has saved 12 bir (£1.50) since becoming a member of an ACTIONAID savings and credit group a year ago. So far she has taken a goat on credit and, during the food shortages of 1994, took blankets, wheat, seed and fertiliser. By selling the kids borne of the goat, she will be able to take further credit this year. (Adrian Arbib</font> &copy;).</TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR></TABLE><ul><li>ACTIONAID began work in Ethiopia in 1988.<p><li>Procter and Gamble Italy has raised substantial funds to support the development of healthcare provision and water supply in the Dalocha area.<p><li>By the end of 1995 the whole population of the Dalocha area will have access to clean water for the first time.<p><li>16 health posts have been built and the Dalocha clinic upgraded to provide improved health care.<p><li>In Koysha, where ACTIONAID has been working since 1992, 20 new community literacy centres and improved school facilities are helping more than 4,000 children gain an education.<p><li>The creation of community managed nurseries and the distribution of tree seedlings are helping to combat environmental degradation in both areas.<p><li>In Addis Ababa ACTIONAID is helping the people of the slum district in Entoto improve the quality of their lives through better access to healthcare, income generation, and savings and credit schemes.<p><li>In November 1994, ACTIONAID began work with the local organisation REST in Tigray.<p><li>ACTIONAID is collaborating with Ethiopian organisation DAY to promote AIDS awareness.</ul><br clear=left><hr><p>Find out more about ACTIONAID's work in <b><a href="../../info/ethiopia.html">Ethiopia</a></b><p><hr><p><a href="../../home.html"><img src="../../pix/home.gif" width=46height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><a href="../../fight/index.html" target="_parent"><imgsrc="../../pix/globe1.gif" width=46height=41hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a> <a href="../index.html"><img src="../../pix/back.gif" width=46height=41hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><font size=1 face=helvetica, arial><li type=square><b><a href="../../home.html">Home Page</a></b> <li type=square><b><ahref="../../fight/index.html" target="_parent">JoinACTIONAID</a></b> <li type=square><b><a href="../index.html">Common Cause</a></b></font><br clear=all><p></body></html>
