<html><head><title> The circle of life - a time to live</title><!!keys: ></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600" background="../../pix/circleor.jpg"><img src="../../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right><h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <ahref="../../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right><p><h2 align=center> The circle of life - a time to live</h2></p><p><font size=4><font size=+2>T</font>radition is central to the lives of people with whom ACTIONAID works. Here, we look at customs marking the first step in life - the arrival of a baby. </font><hr><p>A myriad of customs welcome children into the world. Developed over thousands of years, these customs celebrate the child's birth, protect it from harm and give it a first identity. <h3>Celebration...</h3>&quot;All births are a gift from God and should be celebrated,&quot; says Asma, a traditional birth attendant (TBA) in ACTIONAID's programme area in Kalinger, Pakistan. <p>Spirituality and festivity often combine in the ceremonies that welcome new babies. The first words a child in Kalinger will hear is a call to prayer whispered into their ear, signifying he or she is Muslim. In Usulutan, El Salvador, babies first hear ritual prayers spoken by the traditional midwife around a candle. Frequently, special foods form part of the ceremony. Just as the first time a Sikh child visits the temple his or her parents will take flour, butter and sugar to make kara parashad  - a sweet pudding shared with other worshippers - so a Hindu baby, even before it tastes breast milk, will taste honey when the sacred symbol, AUM (pronounced Om), is written on its tongue. <p>But not all births are met with enthusiasm. In Kalinger, the proud father of a boy hires a local barber to convey the news to relatives; the birth of a girl often goes unannounced. This discrimination against girls is a feature of many societies. In Usulutan, traditional midwives often charge extra if they deliver a baby boy.<p><h3>Protection... </h3>Poor living conditions throughout the developing world mean that birth does not always end with a safe delivery. As many as one infant in four dies within its first year. Though, traditionally, the loss of babies at this stage is described in spiritual terms - the baby itself often being perceived as a pure spirit, not yet human - the ceremonies which seek to protect infants are often immensely practical.<p>For the first 14 days after giving birth in Sindhupalchowk, Nepal, mothers and infants of the Mahji - a traditional fishing community - stay in a warm room attended only by the midwife. By massaging the mother and child's body with mustard oil and wood from the Sal tree, the midwife keeps them both warm and, it is believed, reduces the swelling which might ensue from exposure. <p>In Sella Limba, Sierra Leone, babies and young children are seen as particularly vulnerable to a disease known as kuwanki, which causes convulsions. Among both Christians and Muslims, the fear of kuwanki is so great that babies are ceremonially bathed in a special herbal medicine on leaving the birthing hut.<p><h3>Identity... </h3>In many communities, names are chosen not as a reflection of fashion but for their religious meaning or because they symbolise significant events around the time of birth. They are just as likely to be selected by close relatives, birth attendants or spiritual leaders as by the parents themselves. <p>Naming ceremonies in Sella Limba, for example, are very elaborate. &quot;The baby's head is shaved, some herb mixture is poured on its head and the name is publicly announced by the herbalist,&quot; explains Isatu Koroma, Sponsorship Services Officer. <p><TABLE BORDER=0 width=180 align=left hspace=10 vspace=10><TR><TD><TABLE BORDER=0 width=160><TR><TD> <img src="18.jpg" hspace=4 vspace=4 width=150 height=209 border=1> </TD></TR><TR><TD> <font size=small face=helvetica, arial>Photo: Jerry Flynn</font> &copy;.</TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR></TABLE><p>Ceremonies like these take place in all the countries in which ACTIONAID works. In all of them, ACTIONAID seeks not to replace but to augment tradition, and to give all children - girls as well as boys - the best start in life. ACTIONAID activities are important both in improving post-natal care generally, and in making sure girls are seen as equally valuable members of society. <p>Research by: Isatu Koroma, ACTIONAID Sierra Leone; Khushi Zaman, ACTIONAID Pakistan; Mohammad Salim, Kalinger community member;  Candice Macqueen, ACTIONAID El Salvador; Sanjay Rana, ACTIONAID Nepal.<br clear=left><p><hr><p><a href="../../home.html"><img src="../../pix/home.gif" width=46height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><a href="../../fight/index.html" target="_parent"><imgsrc="../../pix/globe1.gif" width=46height=41hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a> <a href="../index.html"><img src="../../pix/back.gif" width=46height=41hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><font size=1 face=helvetica, arial><li type=square><b><a href="../../home.html">Home Page</a></b> <li type=square><b><ahref="../../fight/index.html" target="_parent">JoinACTIONAID</a></b> <li type=square><b><a href="../index.html">Common Cause</a></b></font><br clear=all><p></body></html>
