<html><head><title> Holding onto home</title><!!keys: ></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600"><img src="../../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right><h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <ahref="../../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right><p><h2 align=center> Holding onto home</h2></p><p><font size=4><font size=+2>L</font>ife can be hard for the people of Llactun, a small mountain community high in the Peruvian Andes. Tales of the opportunities of life in the cities regularly reach them. So why do they stay?</font><hr><p>Twice a week, for six years, Alfonso Palacio walked the twelve-hour journey from Llactun to the provincial capital Huaraz. As president of this dispersed mountain community from 1983 until 1989, he needed to attend regular meetings to discuss the administration of the community. It is a slow journey, at 3,200 metres above sea level through the Andean mountains which, although normally green, are now suffering the effects of a three- year drought.<p><TABLE BORDER=0 width=280 align=left hspace=10 vspace=10><TR><TH><TABLE BORDER=0 width=260 bgcolor=FFCC99><TR><TH><img src="29.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=6 width=220 height=144></TH><TR><TD> <p> <font size=small face=helvetica>Ana and Alfonso on their Llactun farmstead. They say &quot;The best thing about living in Llactun is helping each other&quot;. (Ava-Cezelia Gonzalex</font> &copy;).</TD></TR><TR><TH><img src="31.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=6 width=220 height=144></TH><TR><TD><p><font size=small face=helvetica> Reaping rewards: the communal potato harvest is an important event. The potatoes are divided up according to how much work each individual has put in. The harvest is followed by a festival. (Ava-Cezelia Gonzalex</font> &copy;).</TD></TR></TABLE></TH></TR></TABLE><p>Alfonso should not have been president for that long but with guerilla activity and civil war creating fear and uncertainty in the region and death threats against community leaders not uncommon, the job lacked takers. Without a representative the community may have broken up so, refusing to bow to the pressure, Alfonso continued as president well beyond the usual tenure of four years. He did this because he loves Llactun. Alfonso would not want to live anywhere else. This commitment is typical of many people in the community.<p>It is this same commitment that encouraged them to seek the assistance of ACTIONAID to help improve the quality of life in Llactun. Four years on, the relationship has brought a safe drinking water supply, seed credit on which they can rely, improvements to their cheese factory and help to develop invaluable agricultural expertise.<p>Yet Llactun has not always been the unified community that it appears to be today.<p>Twenty-five years ago Llactun housed a disparate group of families who worked as wage labourers for local landlords. In return for their work, they received a small portion of what they harvested. Alfonso recalls when his father worked growing maize and potato for the landlord. &quot;We planted half the land for him, and half for us, but it was not enough and we were often hungry,&quot; he says.<p>After the 1969 Land Reform Act, for the first time native Peruvians had the chance to own the land their families had worked on for generations. In order to take advantage of these new laws people had to form organised communities. The families in the Llactun region came together to claim their land from the landowners, winning only after seven court cases and prison sentences for many of the activists. Independence was followed by an earthquake and a drought which nearly destroyed the community. <p>Today, for those in Llactun who remember the struggle and the threats to their community, the gains are held dear. &quot;If I ever see anyone who wants to take advantage of the community or the land    it makes me mad,&quot; says Don Guzman.       &quot;I am going to fight until the day I die to keep the land for all of us.&quot;<p>Today, the biggest threat to Llactun is migration, as more and more young people head for the big cities in search of opportunity and a better life. The lure of the bright lights is deceptive. The majority will join the growing army of casual workers eking out a living in the mushrooming shanty towns situated on the outskirts of all of Peru's major cities. Now 70 per cent of the country's 22.5 million population live in urban areas. In 1940, the figure was only 40 per cent, and most of the movement has been since 1976.<p>With pressures on the local economy due to structural adjustment policies, a three-year drought that has threatened the livelihoods of many in Llactun and the day-to-day struggle villagers face, it is perhaps not difficult to understand why so many are tempted by city life. Less dramatic, though still insidious, is the gradual undermining of Andean culture and age-old traditions as the values and culture of the coastal cities filter into the hilltop  communities via car-battery-powered television and advertising. The influence of television is strong and with schools staffed by teachers from the cities teaching a curriculum most relevant to children living in towns, the Andean people are losing sight of their own culture. They are also losing the collective knowledge of how to make best use of the resources they have. Where once Huaraz was known for its water-powered stone mills for grinding flour, today these have fallen into disuse as important water management skills have been lost. Llactun's community leaders fear that without the traditional farming skills, new techniques and even new industries will make it increasingly difficult for communities such as theirs to survive.<p><TABLE BORDER=0 width=180 align=right hspace=10 vspace=10><TR><TD><TABLE BORDER=0 width=160 bgcolor=FFCC99><TR><TH><img src="30.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=6 width=150 height=226></TH><TR><TD> <p><font size=small face=helvetica> William and Jesus Palacio with a woolly friend.  (Ava-Cezelia Gonzalex</font> &copy;).</TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR></TABLE>At the request of the communities, ACTIONAID Peruvian staff are helping to address their problems through a range  of measures which include a new curriculum for rural schools, an agricultural programme which increases self sufficiency for families, and an outlook which enhances the communities' belief in themselves and their culture.<p>Ecological Education is a project, currently in a pilot phase in Cordillera Negra, which directly addresses the growing gulf between the national curriculum and the reality of life in the Andes. Staffed with specially trained teachers the project provides children with a renewed sense of pride  in their culture and important skills           in traditional technology, methods of afforestation and cattle rearing.<p>In other areas the focus is on music as children explore, with the help of a teacher and instruments provided by ACTIONAID, traditional songs that were once performed to celebrate the value of communal agricultural work that underpinned Andean lifestyles. Says Pepe, ACTIONAID'S educational adviser in Tarata: &quot;Children now practise the quena (Andean reed flute) on the way to the fields and last year local families organised a music festival.&quot;<p>The main thrust of ACTIONAID'S programme in Peru however is to ensure that families are able to grow enough food to eat and are no longer so vulnerable to erratic weather conditions. Advice in fertiliser technology, seed credit and support with rearing animals provides communities with a larger and more reliable food supply.<p>Rural life in Llactun is tough. Both women and men work many hours a day just to ensure subsistence for their families. Yet, despite these hardships, there is a clear feeling in the community that they are lucky to be living in Llactun. This may be to do with the collective memory of the struggle they had to secure the land. It is almost certainly in part a recognition of the beauty of the mountains, the clean air and the wild fruits that you will never find in the city.<p><TABLE BORDER=0 width=250 align=left hspace=10 vspace=10><TR><TD><TABLE BORDER=0 width=230 bgcolor=FFCC99><TR><TH><img src="32.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=6 width=220 height=143></TH><TR><TD> <p><font size=small face=helvetica> Photo: Ava-Cezelia Gonzalex</font> &copy;.</TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR></TABLE>The community have many causes for celebration. The annual August festival is a major event which all families help to organise. &quot;There are groups in charge of everything including the band and dancers,&quot; says Blas Leon Antonis. The highlight of the day is the meal, a traditional feast of meat soup followed by guinea pig and potato, washed down with Chicha, a home-made alcoholic brew made from fermented corn. &quot;It's just to refresh ourselves,&quot; says Blas, laughing.<p>All but one of Marina Wanolo Layba's children have moved to Lima, yet she has no desire to follow them. &quot;In Lima, if you don't work you have nothing. Here when we work together, we talk and laugh and we share everything. The air is clean and healthy and there is always food to eat.&quot;<p>It is for people like Marina that Alfonso made his footsore journey twice a week. <br clear=all><p><hr><p><a href="../../home.html"><img src="../../pix/home.gif" width=46height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><a href="../../fight/index.html" target="_parent"><imgsrc="../../pix/globe1.gif" width=46height=41hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a> <a href="../index.html"><img src="../../pix/back.gif" width=46height=41hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><font size=1 face=helvetica, arial><li type=square><b><a href="../../home.html">Home Page</a></b> <li type=square><b><ahref="../../fight/index.html" target="_parent">JoinACTIONAID</a></b> <li type=square><b><a href="../index.html">Common Cause</a></b></font><br clear=all><p></body></html>
