<html>
<head>
<title>Building on tradition</title>
<!!keys: >
</head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600">
<img src="../../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right>
<h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <a
href="../../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right>
<p>
<h2 align=center>Building on tradition</h2></p>


<p>
<font size=4><font size=+2>C</font>onstructing a water supply scheme in rural Pakistan involves more
than laying hundreds of feet of pipes.
Ensuring everybody has a say means overcoming vested interests. </font>
<hr>
<TABLE BORDER=0 width=180 align=left hspace=10 vspace=10>
<TR><TD><TABLE BORDER=0 width=160 bgcolor=FFCC99>
<TR><TD><img src="33.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=6 width=150 height=220></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><p><font size=small face=helvetica>Photo: Richard Edwards</font> &copy;.
</TD></TR></TABLE></TD>
</TR></TABLE><p>
Before the new water supply scheme was built in Maira village the women spent many back-breaking
hours collecting water from distant wells. &quot;While the others were saying their morning prayers,
we
had to
go and fetch water. Most women suffer from headaches or back problems because they had to carry
such heavy loads of water pitchers every day. They go through life with this problem,&quot; says
Shams
Bibi, a
woman of Maira village. <p>
The old scheme consisted of seven lines supplying water to each household for only ten minutes every
alternate day. Rather than wait for their ten minute slot, the women used to take their water from
the
wells. <p>
The situation in nearby Swabi was, if anything, worse. This scheme consisted of an open pipeline
which
was only supplying water to the mosque and the local primary school. The only water source for
villagers
was the lake, which regularly dried up, and nearby wells. One Swabi woman said: &quot;My nine year
old
daughter would go to the well every day and night to collect five pitchers of water to meet our daily
needs. Sometimes we would go to the well three times a day. Each   trip used to take us half an
hour.&quot;<p>
Furthermore, to collect the water women had to pass through the fields where the men were working,
thus contravening the rules of Purdah.<p>
The need for an adequate water supply was obvious. The villagers were keen to take part in
constructing
a new one. The problem was, how to do this within the traditional power structures while ensuring
everyone had an equal say in how it was done.<p>
In Kalinger Union Council, villages are run by the Jirga system - a committee of influential village
elders -
which is one of the most powerful institutions in the region. The word 'jirga' comes from the Persian
language and means 'justice'. The system's functions are primarily to resolve conflicts, undertake
fundraising, ensure mosque development and settle differences between families.<p>
However, as ACTIONAID Pakistan staff found out, the Jirga is more just to some than to others.
Representing traditionally powerful members of a community, the Jirga is not accountable to the
poorest villagers, particularly the women, who had most interest in seeing that the water scheme was
fairly planned with standposts near their homes.<p>
To ensure the water scheme met everybody's needs and could be maintained without ACTIONAID's
involvement, ACTIONAID Pakistan staff realised that the villages would need a new organ- isation that
represented the whole community, but one that the Jirga would support.<p>
Creating this was started by inviting villagers to a series of public meetings, announced through the
public
address systems of mosques and by sending  messengers to each household.<p>
The first groups in Swabi and Maira were largely composed of village elders,  though some of them
were
too frail even to undertake monitoring the implementation work. They soon realised themselves that
younger people must take part.<p>
There was also the problem of vested interests, as Malik Ali former member of the Maira community
management structure explains: &quot;Some people joined the organisation because they were
interested in
the development of the area, while others were looking for individual and political gains.&quot;
Another
member
Khwaj Mohammed adds, &quot;Some tried their best to provide benefits to the rich and influential
people
in the
village with the hope that they would be able to get support in the future, if ever they faced any
difficulties.&quot;<p>
Others, like Haider Zaman, simply joined because they wanted to make a difference: &quot;I accepted
the
responsibility of representing my biradri (household grouping) because I believe I can work with
ACTIONAID
for the development of my area. I will try to instil a sense of trust and responsibility among my
people.&quot;<p>
<TABLE BORDER=0 width=100%>
<TR><TH><TABLE BORDER=0 width=240 bgcolor=FFCC99>
<TR><TD><img src="35.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=6 width=230 height=150></TD></TR>
<TR><TD> <p> <font size=small face=helvetica>Water sports: now water is plentiful and the
nearest
standpipe is never far from
home. (Richard Edwards</font> &copy;).
</TD></TR></TABLE></TH>
<TH><TABLE BORDER=0 width=240 bgcolor=FFCC99>
<TR><TD><img src="34.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=6 width=230 height=150></TD></TR>
<TR><TD> <p>
<font size=small face=helvetica> Villagers and officials from the whole district attended an
open-air ceremony to mark
completion of the scheme. (Richard Edwards</font> &copy;).
</TD></TR></TABLE></TH>
</TR></TABLE>
<br clear=all>
<br>

At each stage of construction, differences had to be resolved. For example the distribution system
involved incorporating pipes from an older, defunct scheme, but once the pipes were dismantled, some
people removed them to use them for individual household connections. The onus was on the
community management structure to settle any disputes and ensure the principles of equity and
commitment to the scheme were upheld.<p>
Social and cultural constraints in the area do not allow the formation of mixed- gender community
groups, so involving the women in decision making was more difficult. Building on existing social
groups
such as the Koranic Recitation Meeting and the Tea Gathering (rather like a coffee morning),
ACTIONAID
was able to encourage the women to discuss together the implications of the scheme. Instigation of a
Standpost Location Meeting, perhaps the most important group, allowed the women to take part in
decisions about where the standposts would be.<p>
The women's Tea Gathering was invited to the completion ceremony, although they had to sit in a
separate house to maintain the traditions of purdah. One woman said: &quot;We are very pleased that
you
have invited us for this occasion. We want you to know that we are with you.&quot;<p>
Guldad, a Maira villager, sums it up by saying: &quot;I have now realised that there is a need for an
active
organisation in our village to work for the development of our area. The organisation can plan for
resources and implement projects. Now I will divert all my energy and efforts towards setting up and
working for such an organisation.&quot;
<p>

<hr>
<p>
Find out more about ACTIONAID's work in <b><a href="../../info/pakistan.html">Pakistan</a></b>
<p><hr>
