<html><head><title> Talking Taboos</title><!!keys: ></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600"><img src="../../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right><h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <ahref="../../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right><br><h2 align=center>Talking Taboos</h2></p><p><font size=4><font size=+2>D</font>o the modern ideas of development workers clash with communities' long-held beliefs and traditions? </font><hr><p>Ayakoliga is a small village in the Sapeliga chiefdom of Ghana where respect for tradition and culture is still strong. The only regular visitors are people like ACTIONAID staff, who largely come from other parts of Ghana.<p>During a recent planning and development meeting with the Ayakoliga community, discussions drifted towards the growing disregard for traditional values.<p>&quot;When I was a young boy,&quot; says village elder Asuribun Aketim, &quot;I used to sit by the fireside, sometimes late into the night, while my father talked to me about taboos and traditional values such as honesty and hard work. But these days our young men think that because they know books (educated), they have no need for traditional values. This is wrong.&quot;<p>&quot;Taboos (kisuk) are an important aspect of our way of life. They are a source of moral and spiritual guidance to our community. To disregard them is to disrespect 'Winaam', the supreme creator or God who is the author of all life, the maker of all divine laws.&quot; says another elder, Anugbilla Akoligo. Without written laws as in the case of Christian or Muslim religions, taboos play an important role by serving as 'community laws' to ensure harmony among and within communities.<p>&quot;For us,&quot; explains Akparibo Ayeebo, &quot;prayers alone are not enough. One has to comply with tradition and custom and especially respect traditional laws (taboos), otherwise one incurs the wrath of the ancestors and the displeasure of God.<p><TABLE BORDER=0 width=100%><TR><TH><TABLE BORDER=0 width=230 bgcolor=CCFFFF><TR><TD><img src="37.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=6 width=220 height=146></TD></TR><TR><TD> <p><font size=small face=helvetica> Ayaakoliga villagers discuss local traditions with an ACTIONAID worker. (Charles Owusu</font> &copy;).</TD></TR></TABLE></TH><TH><TABLE BORDER=0 width=230 bgcolor=CCFFFF><TR><TD><img src="39.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=6 width=220 height=146></TD></TR><TR><TD> <p> <font size=small face=helvetica>Planting, weeding, harvesting and even eating has to be done with the permission and support of the ancestral spirits. (Jerry Flynn</font> &copy;).</TD></TR></TABLE></TH></TR></TABLE><br clear=all>&quot;When taboos are broken or disobeyed, the ancestors can only be appeased through specific and timely sacrifices. This is the only way to stop them from taking punitive action,&quot; says Nba Akoligo.In Ayakoliga, adultery is considered one of the most serious taboos. &quot;If a woman commits adultery,&quot; explains Anaba Abere, &quot;she is not supposed to cook for the husband, otherwise he would die. She must confess so sacrifices can be performed to pacify the ancestors. If the woman does not confess, she would face difficulties during childbirth and she may die during labour. There have been many examples in this area and even health workers encourage women who experience problems during labour to speak out.&quot;<p><TABLE BORDER=0 width=180 align=left vspace=10 hspace=10><TR><TH><TABLE BORDER=0 width=160 bgcolor=CCFFFF><TR><TD><img src="36.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=6 width=150 height=222></TD></TR><TR><TD> <p> <font size=small face=helvetica>A pyramid of offerings at a traditional Ghanian funeral. No funeral is performed if a person dies alone. This belief helps ensure the sick and very old always have people to attend their needs. (Charles Owusu</font> &copy;).</TD></TR></TABLE></TH></TR><TR><TH><TABLE BORDER=0 width=160 bgcolor=CCFFFF><TR><TD><img src="38.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=6 width=150 height=222></TD></TR><TR><TD> <p> <font size=small face=helvetica>&quot;When taboos are respected and obeyed, our ancestors show appreciation by blessing us with rains, good yields, many children, peace and happiness,&quot; says Akparibo Ayeebo. (Charles Owusu</font> &copy;).</TD></TR></TABLE></TH></TR></TABLE><p>Once a woman has confessed to an affair, she has to be cleansed before she enters her husband's home. The husband buys a chicken, its legs are broken and it is then beaten to death with thorns, burnt, and the ashes are thrown away. The woman then enters the house naked and is cleansed by an older woman. She is now considered clean again.<p>Another taboo forbids intercourse between husband and wife during pregnancy and for at least two years after birth. &quot;This is to ensure that the baby is not disturbed during pregnancy and the mother does not pick another seed before the child is old enough to be weaned. It is exactly what the modern people call Aduamak (family planning),&quot; says Aketim. &quot;And this is why our society is polygamous, to avoid the strain that the man would certainly go through during this long period of abstinence. Women in a polygamous marriage consider themselves as sisters. There is absolutely no rivalry or bitterness since they all have an equal chance to share the man.&quot;<p>With little or no access to health   facilities traditional medicine plays an important role in the treatment of various diseases.<p>&quot;The best of our medicine men know many ancient remedies of which orthodox medicine is ignorant,&quot; says Arugbilla Akoligo. &quot;Our local medicine men can cure compound fractures, snake bites, asthma, fits, impotency.&quot;<p>Akparibo Ayeebo concludes: &quot;The world has changed so much that the conditions under which certain taboos were made do not exist any more. This means we need to modify certain aspects of our taboos. One taboo says that if a cow moos in the night it must be killed or the owner would die. In the days of old most farmers had several herds of cattle and it did not matter if one or two were killed. These days very few people have cattle. Imagine the plight of the farmer who has to kill his only bullock just because the poor animal got excited and mooed at night.&quot;<p>ACTIONAID field workers are very sensitive to local culture when working with communities. Sometimes taboos and traditional practices can help the progress of development work. The traditional respect for the land and the acknowledgement that it is precious and must be held in trust, for example, is a good basis on which to discuss environmental issues. It is more difficult, though, when staff see how certain taboos and practices can be detrimental, particularly to health. In some African countries children are prohibited from eating eggs, even in the hungry season when levels of malnutrition rise. A more stark example is the practice of female circumcision which is widespread in many parts of Africa and is surrounded by a number of taboos.<p>Knowing when to speak out and when to accept practices can only be learned over time. With staff and communities working closely together on planning and implementing projects a trust and confidence grows that makes it possible to discuss these issues quite openly.<br clear=all><p><hr><p>Find out more about ACTIONAID's work in <b><a href="../../info/ghana.html">Ghana</a></b><p><p><hr><p><a href="../../home.html"><img src="../../pix/home.gif" width=46height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><a href="../../fight/index.html" target="_parent"><imgsrc="../../pix/globe1.gif" width=46height=41hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a> <a href="../index.html"><img src="../../pix/back.gif" width=46height=41hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><font size=1 face=helvetica, arial><li type=square><b><a href="../../home.html">Home Page</a></b> <li type=square><b><ahref="../../fight/index.html" target="_parent">JoinACTIONAID</a></b> <li type=square><b><a href="../index.html">Common Cause</a></b></font><br clear=all><p></body></html>
