 <html><head><title> Resources for key stage 4</title><!!keys: ></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600"><a href="../info/index.html"><img src="../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <ahref="../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right><br><h2 align=center> Resources for key stage 4</h2><p><h3>Economic issues facing Bangladesh</h3><i>- with new  activities and updated statistics</i> <p>A package of three resources examining some of the economic issues that face the people of Bangladesh:<ul><p><b>Four families in Bangladesh</b><br>A simulation activity which follows the fortunes of four families over six years. Includes graph work on 'quality of life' indicators.<p><b>Multinationals in Bangladesh</b><br>Enables pupils to analyse the advantages and disadvantages of multinationals. With Unilever as an example, pupils learn of the power and influence of large companies.<p><b>Industries in Bangladesh</b><br>Pupils examine possible alternatives to multinationals, focusing on the textile industry in Bangladesh.</ul><p><b>Activity packs £8.00</b><hr><p><h3>Development in Brazil </h3><p>Pack of five resources examining aspects of development in Brazil:<ul><p><b>Brazil country profile</b> <br>Pupils use basic statistics, maps and information to develop a background knowledge of Brazil.<p><b>History of the Amazon</b><br>Using maps, sketches, newspaper reports and a time-line, pupils analyse the effects of colonisation on the indigenous and landless people of the Amazon.<p><b>Indigenous people and Amazon development</b><br>Different perceptions of the Amazon Indian way of life are shown through card activities. Pupils evaluate the impact of hydro-electric power schemes on the Amazon communities.<p><b>The Greater Carajas programme</b><br>Using secondary sources pupils are asked to write a magazine article outlining how different groups of people are affected by the Greater Carajas programme.<p><b>Land for the landless</b><br>Population and migration flows in the Amazon are examined through a board game using four family case studies.</ul><p><b>Activity packs £15.00</b><hr><p><h3>Can development be measured? </h3> - new version with updated statistics <p>Shows how different social and economic indicators can be used to measure development and illustrates their shortcomings.<p><b>Activity pack £3.00</b><hr><p><h3>How many children? </h3> - updated version<p>Explores the reasons behind different family sizes. Compares six families, ranging from Hungary to Kenya. Uses census data for work on birth rates and population pyramids. <p><b>Activity pack £3.00</b>  <hr><p><b><a href="video.html#kale">Kale Nyabo - women farmers in Uganda</a></b> and <b><a href="video.html#bags">Bags of money - handicraft producers in Kenya</a></b> video packs are also suitable for key stage 4 learning.<p><hr><p><a href="../home.html"><img src="../pix/home.gif" width=46 height=41 hspace=10vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><a href="../fight/index.html" target="_parent"><img src="../pix/globe1.gif" width=46 height=41hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a> <a href="resource.html"><img src="../pix/back.gif" width=46height=41hspace=10 vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a><font size=1 face=helvetica, arial><b><li type=square><a href="../home.html">Home Page</a> <li type=square><ahref="../fight/index.html" target="_parent">JoinACTIONAID</a> <li type=square><a href="resource.html">Resources for teachers</a></b></font><br clear=all><p></body></html>
