<html>
<head>
<title> PAKISTAN</title>
<!!keys: >
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600">
<font face="arial, helvetica"><a href="../info/index.html"><img src="../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96
height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a>
<h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <a
href="../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right>
<br>

<h2 align=center> PAKISTAN</h2>
<p align=center>
<img src="../pix/pakistan.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=2 width=414 height=267 alt="Map of Pakistan">
</p>
<hr>

<p><b>Key National Statistics</b>

<p>Population	144 million

<p>Population growth rate	3.2% a year

<p>Under-five child mortality	137
(deaths per 1,000 live births)

<p>Rural population with 	50%
access to safe water

<p>Adult literacy rate	36%	
<br clear=left>
<p><hr>
<h3>Programme Overview </h3>

<p>ACTIONAID began work in Pakistan in 1992 and through work in two development areas is reaching a
population of nearly 50,000. 

<p>The key issues for the poor communities in these rural areas is access to clean water, poor
sanitation, limited health care facilities and low agricultural yields. In Bahawalnagar, where a
programme is currently being planned, work will specifically help communities tackle the severe
waterlogging and salinity problems which hamper agricultural production in the area. 

<h3>Examples of ACTIONAID's work in Pakistan:</h3>

<p><ul><li>ACTIONAID has worked with the people of Kalinger Union Council to develop a water and
sanitation project that has made safe water available to all 38,000 people in the area. All members
of the community  - the elders, farmers, women and young people - have contributed to the planning,
implementation and management of the new facilities, from laying pipes to deciding where standpipes
should be located.

<p><li>many women in rural villages are attended to by traditional birth attendants during labour as
the nearest health centre could be many kilometres away. While the midwives can be highly skilled
they are often not fully aware of hygiene issues or how to detect complications. An ACTIONAID
community health worker has provided training for the attendants in Kalinger Union Council so they
can incorporate new methods with their traditional skills.
</ul>
<hr>

<p><b><a href="../cause/coca1/tradition.html">Building on tradition</a></b><br>
The village elders in rural Pakistan are used to making the decisions, so when building a new water
supply scheme affects everyone, how do others get a say?
</font>

<!--footer-->
<p><hr>
