<head>
<title> GHANA</title>
<!!keys: >
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#000066" vlink="#FF6600">
<font face="arial, helvetica">
<a href="../info/index.html"><img src="../pix/logo-t.gif" width=96 height=41 hspace=10
vspace=2 border=0 align=right></a>
<h6 align=left>The material that follows has been provided by <a
href="../info/index.html">ACTIONAID</a></h6><br clear=right>
<br>

<h2 align=center> GHANA</h2>
<p align=center>
<img src="../pix/ghana.jpg" hspace=5 vspace=2 width=414 height=267 alt="Map of Ghana">
</p>
<hr>

<b>Key National Statistics</b>

<p>Population	18 million

<p>Population growth rate	3% a year

<p>Under-five child mortality	170
(deaths per 1,000 live births)

<p>Rural population with 	35%
access to safe water

<p>Adult literacy rate	61%
<br clear=left>
<p><hr>
<h3>Programme Overview </h3>

<p>ACTIONAID began working in Ghana in 1990 and, through work in two development areas, is now
reaching a population of more than 45,000 people. Addressing food security is the main focus of
activity in
both areas. 

<p>Families rely on small-scale farming for their survival and are at the mercy of erratic rainfall
and
pestilence problems. Severe food shortages can occur, leaving farmers with no seed left to plant for
the
following season. By providing seed on credit, developing grain banks, and improving composting and
soil
and water conservation,  ACTIONAID is helping farmers to improve their crop yields. Better access to
health care, clean water and education are also fundamental to improving the quality of life here.

<h3>Examples of ACTIONAID's work in Ghana</h3>
<b>ACTIONAID has:</b>

<p><ul><li>established a community based monitoring system to give early warning of food shortages.
By
checking food prices and availability in the markets every fortnight, watching for seasonal migration
to
the south in search of work and checking on attendance at schools, village development workers can
identify the earliest signs of food shortage. 

<p>ACTIONAID can then assist, for example, with community food distribution before the escalating
crisis
demands large scale emergency relief.

<p><li>provided low-interest seed loans in Sapeliga where erratic rains and crop pests often mean
there is
no surplus of seed for the next planting season. Over 90 per cent of farmers who have taken loans of
sorghum and groundnut have repaid their loans on time.

<p><li>been directly involved in peace discussions in northern Ghana, working with all parties to
seek a
resolution to ongoing problems. Ethnic conflict in 1994 and continuing insecurity in the region have
had an
impact on ACTIONAID programmes.

<p><li>In 1996 a new urban programme is to begin helping poor communities in Tamale in northern
Ghana.
</ul>
<hr>

<p><b><a href="../cause/coca1/taboos.html">Talking taboos </a></b>
The villagers of Ayakoliga, Ghana, talk about the traditions and taboos that govern their lives and
the
threat of modern ways, including those of ACTIONAID
</font>

<!--footer-->
<p><hr>
