<html>
<header>
<title>Development Co-operation Review -- European Community</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H3><center><img src="../images/eu.jpg"><p></a>
Development Co-operation Review Series:<br>European Community<br>
<i>OECD Development Assistance Committee</i><p></h3>
<h5>(Summary of Development Co-operation Review Series, Number ?, 1995)<br>
For a copy of the full report, please contact OECD Publications, 2 rue Andr&#233; Pascal, 75775 Paris cedex 16, France
<br>
Home Page: <a href="http://www.oecd.org/dac/index.htm" target="_top">http://www.oecd.org/dac/index.htm</a></h5>
</center><p>
<hr>
<h4>This Report</h4>
The OECD Development Assistance Committee (DAC) conducts periodic reviews to improve the individual and collective development co-operation efforts of its members.
<p>
The peer review is prepared by the Secretariat and involves staff from development agencies in other DAC member countries. A draft report is prepared by the Secretariat and it forms the basis for a review meeting with the member.
<p>
This publication contains the conclusions as agreed by DAC following the review meeting on 19 September 1995, as well as the report prepared by the Secretariat team.
<p>
<h4>Main Points</h4>
The European Commission (EC) of the European Union is a large and unique multilateral donor with distinctive and ambitious development cooperation goals. At the same time, the EC is also charged to promote coordination among its Member States. Although each Member State has its own development cooperation programme, the Maastricht Treaty specifically envisions a common development policy to be complmented by those of the Member States. The Union is also pledged to take account of its agreed development objectives in the full range of its policies that are likely to affect developing countries.
<p>
The Commission's large aid programme is growing faster than the national programmes of its Member States. By 1994, over 17 per cent of total EU Member States' overseas development assistance was channelled through the EC making it the second largest multilateral donor after the World Bank. With the amount of Member State aid passing through the Commission projected to continue growing, the effectiveness of EC aid is crucial to the overall European effort.
<p>
<h4>Main Points</h4>
Since the last DAC review in 1991, the Commission has made significant progress in several areas. It has introduced project cycle management and the logical framework for project designs, expanded staff training, upgraded its evaluation programme, improved its staffing, promoted a culture of greater transparency and accountability, and strengthened its analytic capacity.
<p>
In its earlier review, the DAC suggested that the EC might benefit from some organisational streamlining and general simplification. However, the organisational structure remains complex as is to be expected from an organisation that aims to group together all the Commission's bilateral external relations in one structure. It is now a major and conscious policy of the EC to strengthen internal coordination, cooperation, and sharing of experience.
<p>
Despite these welcome improvements, the DAC suggests that the Commission still needs to strengthen its capabilities to plan, manage, and implement its new generation of projects. These require a high level of skilled dialogue with recipient countries and patient nurturing of local ownership, particpation, and local ownership. Finally, the DAC suggested that the Commission consider creating a single evaluation unit to encompass all the development activities of the EU, instead of having several units as at present.
<p>
<h4>Further Information</h4>
To get a copy of the report, please contact OECD Publications, 2 rue Andr&#233; Pascal, 75775 Paris cedex 16, France<p>
<HR>
