<html>
<HEADER>
<TITLE>EU Development Council 'Comitology'</TITLE>
</HEADER>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<H2><center><img src="../images/eu.jpg"><p></a>
EU Development Council 'Comitology' </h2>
<h4>Full text of an article from <i>EURO-CIDSE News Bulletin</i><br>January/February 1996</h4>
</center>
<hr>
<h3>Contents:</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#wha">What is Comitology?</a>
<li><a href="#sco">The Scope of Comitology</a>
<li><a href="#iss">The Issues and the Views of the Institutions</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#par">The Parliament</a>
<li><a href="#com">The Commission</a>
<li><a href="#cou">The Council</a>
</ul>
<li><a href="#ngo">Some NGO Perspectives</a>
</ul>
<hr>
<b>On 20 December 1995, the EU Development Council met, under the Presidency of Jos Luis Decenta Balleester, Spanish Secretary of State for International Co-operation and Latin America.  Included on the Council's agenda was discussion of a number of proposed regulations providing legal bases for the implementation of existing EU budget lines.  In discussing these proposed regulations, the Council became enmeshed in a lengthy - and in two cases inconclusive - debate on 'comitology' (comitologie, in French).  Since the proposals under discussion - co-financing, decentralised co-operation, rehabilitation, South Africa, humanitarian aid, food aid and security, refugees - all concern the NGO community, EURO-CIDSE embarked on a crash course on this somewhat esoteric (if not arcane) institutional procedure.  We are grateful for all those in the European institutions - Council, Commission, European Parliament - who gave unstintingly of their time and patience as unpaid tutors.  We are particularly indebted to  The European Parliament, Second Edition by Francis Jacobs, Richard Corbett and Michael Shackleton  for its introduction to this issue.  In this initial article, we try to explain (as simply as the subject allows), what is comitology, what is its scope, why does it matter and what are the views of the European Institutions, and an NGO perspective on the budget lines under question.</b>
<p>
<A NAME="wha"><h3>What is Comitology?</h3></a>

Comitology is essentially "Eurospeak" for the variety of committees and procedures utilised in implementing EU legislation.  Whilst most Community legislation provides for the Commission , as the executive arm of the European Community, to implement, execute and adapt its provisions, over the years the Council has subordinated  Commission powers to the scrutiny and approval of committees comprised of national civil servants of the EU Member States.  In essence, therefore, is a question of how the executive powers of the Commission are circumscribed by Member States.  Since the European Parliament, as a democratically elected body, also sees a role for itself, which we deal with below, this has been an issue of some controversy and will certainly be on the agenda of the 1996 Inter-Governmental Conference which will open in Turin on March 29.
<p>
The issue is further complicated by the fact that there are three types of committee under the comitology procedure (originating from a Council Decision of 13 July 1987 laying down the procedures for the exercise of implementing powers conferred on the Commission - Official Journal of the European Communities of July 18 1987) :
<ul>
<li>Type 1. This is an advisory Committee. The Commission submits to the committee a draft of the measures to be taken and the Committee delivers an opinion.  The Commission then takes a decision taking into "the utmost account of the opinion delivered by the Committee".
<p>
<li>Type 2. This is a management Committee.  If a qualified majority within the Committee is opposed to the Commission's proposals, then either a) the Com-mission may delay the application of its decision for up to one month; or b) the Commission shall delay the application of its decision for up to three months.  Within these deadlines, the Council, by qualified majority, may take a different decision .
<p>
<li>Type 3. This is a regulatory Committee.  If the Commis-sion is not supported by a qualified majority (i.e. a blocking minority) in the Committee, the matter is referred to Council for a decision within three months.  If the Council fails to adopt a position then a) the proposed measures shall be adopted by the Com-mission or b) the Commission shall adopt its proposal unless a simple majority in Council votes against it, in which case no decision os taken (i.e. back to the drawing board).
<p></ul>
An additional complication is the process involving the three European institutions for determining the comitology procedure.  Under the Co-Decision Procedure, the Parliament has more power and the comitology procedure is governed by an interim  modus vivendi on comitology adopted on 19 December 1994.  However, the budget lines we are dealing with here fall under the Co-operation Procedure  (which governs development co-operation under the Maastricht Treaty) under which the Parliament has less power and the procedure is government by the Plumb-Delors agreement (an exchange of letters between the then President of the European Parliament of 11 December 1987 and the then President of the Commission of 14 March 1988 and which essentially establishes rules/guidelines for notifying Parliament of draft implementing measures).   Under the Co-operation procedure, the Parliament gives a first reading of the Commission proposal.  The matter then goes to Council.  Once Council has adopted a Common Position, the proposed regulation goes back to Parliament for a second reading.  The Parliament must, within three months, approve, reject or amend (with an absolute majority of 314 votes) the Council Position. The Commission then examines the Council's Common Position and Parliament's amendments and presents a revised proposal to the Council.  The Commission is not obliged to accept Parliament's amendments, but Parliament can threaten to reject the Common Position if they are not taken into account and the legislation will fall.  The Council can overrule the Parliament's rejection - but only if the Council is unanimous and with the agreement of the Commission.  
<p>
The Commission could seek a compromise with the Council, such as agreeing to the use of a II committee instead of a IIIa committee.  If the Commission, however, maintains its position (for example to have no committee with regard to co-financing), with the support of at least one Member State and the Parliament, then in the Council's Second Reading, the Member States have three months to approve by qualified majority or amend with unanimity.  If Council does neither, the proposal falls.   
<p>
<A NAME="sco"><h3>The scope of comitology</h3></a>

In 1995, in response to action taken by the Parliament in the exercise of its proper budgetary powers (to which we will return), the Commission produced a document Budget 1995 Comitologie, the size of two telephone directories.   These documents were analyzed - in what can only be described as a Herculean task - by Terry Wynn MEP (UK, Socialist Group) in a report of 25 July 1995 and which gave rise to a Parliamentary resolution on this issue.  His report states :
<p>
<i>	"1,918 pages in the two volumes and the addendum describe the activities of 424 committees that prepared 4679 "acts" in total during 1994 - either in the form of decisions (199), opinions (4193) or absence of opinions (287).  The sectors on which these committees work cover almost all areas in the Community budget.  It is not always clear how the distinction between decisions and opinions is made, given that 60 of the 199 decisions were made by consultative committees.  The activities of these committees cost 17.98 MECUS, or an average of about 3,480 ECUs per "act", or about 42,400 ECUs per Committee.
<p>
	"Based on the cases where committee type is specified (all under A-2510), the largest proportion are consultative committees (178 Type 1), although 7 further cases are mixed Type 1 and 2 or Type 1 and 3 committees.  Nevertheless, 72 are management committees of Type 2 (20 Type 2b) and 84 are regulatory committees of Type 3 (19 Type 3b with safeguard powers for the Council)."</i>
<p>
In two later paragraphs, Terry Wynn's report goes on to say :
<p>
<i>	"Agriculture is the sector with the most committees (79), followed by external relations (50), customs and indirect taxation (47), environment, nuclear safety and civil protection (43) employment, industrial relations and social affairs, and industry (both 30), fisheries (20), education, professional training and youth (12) statistics (11), energy (10) consumer affairs (8), telecommunications and information policy (7).
<p>
	"Agriculture is also the sector that accounts for the largest number of "acts" : 61% of all "acts" emanate from the agricultural committees.  Strangely, the order of the number of "acts" does not then follow closely that of the numbers of committee in each sector.  The industry committees were responsible for 409 "acts", employment, industrial relations and social affairs for 324, development with four committees for 221 "acts", customs and indirect taxation for 193, external relations 129."</i>>
<p>
The four development committees cited above comprise :
<ul>
<li>The EDF Committee which covers the 70 ACP countries of the Lom Convention (it should be noted in this regard that, pending budgetisation of the EDF - called for by the Commission and the Parliament - the EDF remains an intergovernmental affair).
<li>The ALA Committee which covers Asia and Latin America
<li>The MED Committee which covers the Middle East and North African countries
<li>The Food Aid Committee which covers food aid.
</ul>
The three regional committees (EDF, ALA and MED) have been described to us by everyone we have spoken to as Type 3a committees.  And certainly this is the case for the ALA and the MED Committees, according to the Budget 1995 (Official Journal of the European Communities L 369 of 31 December 1994).  Interestingly, this same official journal lists the EDF committee as a Type 1 committee i.e. advisory.  Food Aid, for its part, has operated, albeit without a legal base, under a Type 2 b Committee.
<p>
There are six pages in the 1,918 page tomes devoted to DG VIII, Development.  The lists give a 1 or 2 line 'object of the act' e.g. Rwanda - humanitarian aid for the population of Rwanda; Ethiopia - social rehabilitation programme; Chad - support for structural adjustment - general import programme.  Adjacent (although we have found gaps in the information) to each act is the committee decision.  There are 3 choices : A (for avis or opinion); a (for absence d'avis, or no opinion), and D for decision.  In every case of the four development committees there is an A.  There is no information on the nature of this opinion.
<p>
<A NAME="iss"><h3>The issues and the views of the Institutions</h3></a>

The issues involved in comitology fall into two distinct categories.  The first, and most important, category is essentially political and involves issues of democratic control, transparency, oversight and accountability.  The second can be summarised as cumbersome bureaucratic delays (or bureaucratic Bumbledom).  These may not only impinge on the timely intervention of EU assistance and add to the heavy administrative burden of the Commission but must also impact on the think-tank/policy formulation aspects of Commission work which can provide a vital tool for/important impetus to EU development policy formulation, coherence, and co-ordination. 
<p>
<A NAME="par"><h4>The Parliament</h4></a>

The Parliament's view on comitology is clear - it is not happy with the current procedures (although it tends to accept Type 1 committees, tolerates at a pinch Type 2 committees and is totally opposed to Type 3 committees).  In his introduction to his report for the Budgets Committee, Terry Wynn states :
<p>
<i>	"The problems raised by comitology are not recent.  All governments devolve executive responsibilities onto committees which may advise, decide or simply deliberate.  The members of such committees are, as a rule, not elected and are generally appointed by the government in power - the executive.
<p>
	"Elected legislators have overseen the actions of these committees often with scepticism.  First, the committees meet in secret and maintain secrecy over the decisions that are taken by them or over the advice that they proffer to the government minister concerned; second, the members of the committees are not elected by often are chosen by the government to which they give advice; thirdly, the elected representatives have felt that some decisions taken in such committees have changed the sense of the legislators (as they interpret that).  From this derives the charge that these committees may subvert the legislative process, being unelected and almost always meeting in secret and therefore not being subject to oversight of the budgetary and legislative authority."</i>
<p>
The 2 volume tomes mentioned above were as a result of the decision in Parliament's budgetary resolutions of 27 October 1994 and 15 December 1994 to place in reserve 90% of the proposed funding for budget lines A-2510 and A-2511 (the budget lines covering the activities of the committees) pending information from the Commission on the decisions and other acts during 1994 by the committees.  On 2 February 1995 the Commission produced its two volume summary and subsequent decisions (the last of which on 10 July 1995) agreed to the transfer of the funds out of reserve.  In the 1996 Budgetary procedure, the Parliament has placed 50% of the proposed allocation in reserve.  
<p>
Introducing his report to the Parliament plenary session in October 1995, Terry Wynn stated :
<p>
<i>	"The reason for this action is the concern of the Budget Committee that the budgetary and legislative competencies of Parliament may be infringed whenever the Council and the Commission take such decisions through the comitology procedure.  The Commission says - and we welcome its commitment - that the Union should now be more democratic, transparent, accountable and accessible.  Comitology is none of these."</i>
<p>
In producing his report, the rapporteur sought and received the opinions of the Parliamentary Committees on Agriculture and Rural Development; Research, Technological Development and Energy; Legal Affairs and Citizens' Rights; Social Affairs and Employment; Regional Policy;  Culture, Youth, Education and the Media; Development and Co-operation; Institutional Affairs; and Fisheries.  All had their own critical comments to make : the uneven quality of information supplied, internal information in the Commission on the activities of these committees seems partial and not centralised, points to inconsistencies and lack of oversight etc. etc.
<p>
In his written opinion to the Committee on Budgets, Umberto Scapagnini MEP (Italy, UPE Group) and Chairman of the  Committee on Research, Technological Development and Energy, stated that the two volumes produced by the Committee represent :
<p>
<i>	"a first attempt to shed some light on comitology procedures in the Commission.  As such, for most of the committees whose work is "described", it represents little more than a single candle burning in the darkness."</i>
<p.
Arguing the need for greater democratic control and accountability, he cited one example which we found particularly pertinent :
<p>
<i>	"To take one instructive example, the proposed Commission directive on infant formula and follow-up milks revealed certain flaws in this process.  Since this proposal was deemed to be an implementing measure within the framework of an existing Council Directive, it did not require Parliamentary approval, just that of the expert committee.  However, details of the proposal were brought to the Environment Committee's attention not as a result of the Plumb-Delors agreement - but by a pressure group which had obtained a leaked copy.  Parliament subsequently adopted a resolution which prompted a revision of the proposal.  Our own experience in the Research Committee is that we seem to have very few comitology documents provided to us via the mechanisms established by the Plumb-Delors Agreement."</i>
<p>
The Parliament's consequent resolution of 26 October 1995 reflects the criticisms outlined above and includes the following paragraphs :
<ul>
<li>Recommends that a timetable is set at the end of which all executive committees set up under Union legislation would meet as a rule in public, unless a specific duly-motivated decision is taken to the contrary and published in good time, and that the dates and times and places of these meetings be published in time to allow those who wish to attend to do so;
<li>Recommends also that the members of these committees register their interests in a public record, that is regularly updated;
<li>Supports the systematic addition, in the comitology paragraph of legislative proposals establishing committees, of the following text : <i>The committee shall meet as a rule in public, unless a specific duly motivated decision is taken to the contrary and published in good time,  It shall publish agendas two weeks in advance of its meetings.  It shall publish minutes of its meetings.  It shall establish a public register of declarations of interest by its members."</i>
<li>In the meantime requests that the principles agreed in the modus vivendi be generalised to all legislative procedures and that the information be forwarded in good time without exception.  to this effect, proposes to place in reserve in the 1996 budget the funding foreseen for the committee activities and requests the Commission to provide information on the activities of the committees before the transfer request is considered. 
</ul><p>
<A NAME="com"><h4>The Commission</h4></a>

In the Parliamentary debate on the Wynn report in October 1995, Commissioner Erkki Antero Liikanen, Commissioner for the Budget, thanked him for his report and stated :
<p>
<i>	"Lastly, with regard to the report by Mr. Wynn on the question of information concerning committees, I recognise the serious concerns of Parliament in this area.  The Commission shares the objectives of transparency, effectiveness and appropriate interinstitutional co-operation.  The Commission provides regular information on the activitires of the executive committees in its annual report and in the budgetary procedure.  It will continue to do so, as requested.  furthermore, the Commission has quickly provided substantial additional information, which was rather broad in the 1995 budgetary procedure.  It is ready to do so again in 1996.  We may want to reflect on the most suitable form and context - I think you concur with this remark.
<p>
	"The Commission is fully committed to the application of modus vivendi agreed in December 1994.  It is willing to review its proper functioning, but it may be useful to have some more experience with such a new procedure.
<p>
	"With regard to the substantial changes concerning the information on the executive committees called for in the Wynn report, the Commission will take a position before the end of the year.  It will have to examine what improvements are possible in the current legel framework.  Other changes may require modifications of the Treaty which could be a result of the intergovernmental conference...."</i>
<p>
Commissioner Liikanen's speech was followed up in a letter of 21 December 1995 from David Williamson, Secretary General for the European Commission to Enrico Vinci, Secretary General of the European Parliament.  We reproduce the bulk of this letter here (leaving out only the introductory paragraph and the standard concluding sentences) :
<p>
<i>" Une note sur le fonctionnement des comit&#233;s en 1995 sera transmise au Parlement europ&#233;en dans les meilleurs d&#233;lais, et au plus tard au cours du premier semestre 1996.  L'information sera plus synth&#233;tique que celle donn&#233;e en 1995 et fournira un bilan d'ensemble.  Elle permettra notamment de distinguer entre les diff&#233;rents types de comit&#233;s, leurs fonctions et leur apport &#224; la gestion des politiques communautaires.
<p>
"La Commission a &#233;galement l'intention de re&#233;diter le r&#233;pertoire des comit&#233;s, publi&#233; dans le pass&#233; sous la forme d'un suppl&#233;ment au bulletin de l'Union europ&#233;enne : cette publication constituera un pas important vers une plus grande transparence et une meilleure connaissance des comit&#233;s.  Elle sera, bien entendu, mise Une note sur le fonctionnement des comit&#233;s en 1995 sera transmise au Parlement europ&#233;en.
<p>
"Ces mesures seront rendues possibles gr&#226;ce au renforcement et &#224; la modernisation progressive de la coordination interne au sein de la Commission.  Ce renforcement et cette modernisation ne doivent cependant pas faire oublier la n&#233;cessit&#233; d'une gestion d&#233;centralis&#233;e, qui tient &#224; la fonction m&#234;me frd comit&#233;s.  Ceux-ci ne constituent en effet pas un bloc, mais doivent r&#233;pondre aux exigences propres et sp&#233;cifiques de chacune des politiques communautaires.

"D'autres mesures pourraient &#233;galement &#234;tre envisag&#233;es.  C'est ainsi que la Commission examinera de facon pragmatique et modul&#233;e les voies permettant une information plus concr&#232;te et continue du Parlement europ&#233;en, par exemple au travers de ses commissions.  Il faudra en tout cas &#233;viter toute surcharge administrative et respecter les crit&#232;res de rapidit&#233; et d'efficacit&#233; qui s'imposent.

"La Commission veillera aussi &#224; ce que le flux des documents transmis au titre du "modus vivendi" ou de l'accord Plumb-Delors soit r&#233;gulier et demeure toujours conforme &#224; l'esprit de ces accords.

"Je voudrais enfin attirer votre attention sur le fait que certains des point figurant dans la r&#233;solution n'impliquent pas la seule Commission.  Je me r&#233;fère, par exemple, aux demandes du Parlement europ&#233;en concernant la publicit&#233; des r&#233;unions des comit&#233;s et le registre d'int&#233;r&#234;ts de leurs membres, qui visent des mati&#232;res o&#249; les responsabilit&#233;s sont partag&#233;es avec les Etats membres.  En tout &#233;tat de cause, la Commission pourrait soulever certains d ces points aupr&#232;s des instances du Conseil.
<p>
"Ces aspects mis&#224; part, pour les questions relevant de sa responsabilit&#233;, la Commission consid&#232;re que les mesures &#224; prendre suite &#224; la r&#233;solution WYNN devraient permettre de r&#233;pondre aux attentes du Parlement en mati&#232;re de simplification et de transparence accrue, tout en continuant &#224; garantir la bonne collaboration entre la Commission et les administrations nationales."</i>
<p>
In other words, and without being too unkind, the Commission will do what is can to simplify, to synthesise and make more accessible information on the workings of committees under the comitology procedures, but can do little on its own about the central issue of the Wynn report - the question of democratic accountability and control.
<p>
From speaking to a number of officials within the Commission, the bureaucratic procedures which accompany the comitology procedure (and in general, the more stringent the committee, the more bureaucratic the procedure) and which strain already overstretched resources e.g. having to produce documents in 11 languages and seven weeks before a committee meeting in some cases.
<p>
<A NAME="cou"><h4>The Council</h4></a>

The position of the Council seems less straightforward - as the lengthy debate during the December 20 Development Council indicates.  But we begin by quoting from the Report of the Reflection Group for the Intergovernmental Conference of December 5th 1995.  This Council Reflection Group, chaired by Spanish Secretary of State for Relations with the European Union, Carlos Westendorp , presented its report to the Madrid Summit of 15-16 December 1995 and the Summit "considers that the guidelines distilled within the Group, following a thorough analysis of the internal and external challenges facing the Union and the possible responses, constitute a sound basis for the work of the Conference."  It should be stressed that this substantial document covers all aspects to be dealt with during the IGC and committee procedure only rates a few paragraphs but which are, nevertheless, worth quoting.  
<p>
<i>Powers of execution (committee procedure)
	<p>
127.  On this subject, which the interinstitutional "modus vivendi" of 20 December 1994 identified as one to be dealt with by the Conference, there are the following positions :
<ul>
<li>Those in favour of a hierarchy of acts resolve this issue by assigning full power to the Commission, subject to control by the Council and the European Parliament.
<p>
<li>Those opposed to granting executive power to the Commission because they believe it would disturb the balance between the institutions are willing to consider simplified procedures which would not undermine the Council's executive functions.
<p>
<li>There is a compromise proposal for a single procedure under which it would be up to the Commission, in consultation with national experts, to decide on implementing measures under the supervision of the Council and the EP, which could cancel the measures and request the application of normal legislative procedures.  At least one member pointed out that opposition by a minority of States should be sufficient to reject any implementing measure.
</ul>
128.  In any case, a large majority in the Group is in favour of simplifying the present committee procedure, which is already complicated and confused and will not survive beyond the next enlargement.  The need to improve the quality of the rules adopted under these procedures was also emphasised.
<p>
In any event, revision of the 1987 Decision on committee procedure does not require reform of the Treaty and therefore consideration must be given to the improvements which can be introduced before the Conference.  In this context, one member has suggested the idea of introducing a standard set of internal rules of procedure to apply to all committees.</i>
<p>
The last two paragraphs are particularly important in the light of the discussions at the 20 December Council meeting.  
<p>
<h4>The December 20 Council Discussions</h4>

As stated in the introduction to this article, the Council discussed the refugees regulation, food aid and security regulation, humanitarian aid regulation (ECHO), South Africa regulation, rehabilitation regulation, co-financing regulation and decentralised co-operation regulation.  Whilst there are significant differences of opinion in terms of comitology with regard to these regulations, it is fair to say that there is a general tendency in Council to go for Type 3a committees.  In discussing this issue with Council sources, three principal arguments emerge :
<ul>
<li>the standardisation of committee pro-cedures and to bring them in line with the three regional committees (EDF, ALA and MED);

<li>the desire of Member States to co-ordinate their activities more closely and this includes financing decisions;

<li>the desire to have a greater say in major policy decisions.  Two examples were cited : a) the decision of the Commission to suspend development aid to Rwanda following the Kibeho massacre  -  decision which at least some in Council were not in agreement; b) that, of the humanitarian aid to Latin America, 80% went to Cuba.  In addition, it is argued, that the new EU Member States are significantly altering their aid patterns, due to their adherence to the EU, and consequently want a greater say in policy decisions.
</ul>
With regard to the individual regulations discussed, the results of the Council were as follows :
<p>
<h4>Refugees</h4>
	
Awaiting Parliament's views on this regulation but the tendency is towards an ALA Committee procedure (Type 3a).
<p>
<h4>Food Aid & Security	</h4>

The Commission has reached a Common Position on this regulation.  For actions above 2 MECUs, the Commission will be assisted by a Type 2b committee (as is the practice at present).
<p>
<h4>Humanitarian Aid</h4>

The Council has approved a Common Position by a qualified majority (with Denmark, Finland and the Netherlands voting against on the grounds that they wanted a tougher comitology procedure - Type 3a).  This common position is a complex and sui generis mix of comitology procedure.  In so far as it has been explained to EURO-CIDSE by Council sources, this involves a) a Type 1 committee for annual guidelines of the programme and for evaluation and management;  b) a Type 2b committee for global plans or expensive and ongoing crisis situations; c) a Type 3a committee for sensitive issues, irrespective of the amount of money involved, such as where there is a question of the military protection of humanitarian aid supplies or where ECHO intervenes directly; d) an urgency procedure where the Commission can decide alone in cases of urgency (defined in the Common Position) for an amount up to 10 MECU.  For amounts up to 2 MECU, the Commission decides (and informs the Member States through the 14 Point Telex reporting system).  Where the amount is in excess of 2 MECU, the Commission must inform the Member States in writing within 48 hours and account for its decision at the committee's next meeting, in particular giving the reasons for its use of the emergency procedure.  Any extension of the particular action needs to go back to the Type 2b committee.
<p>
<h4>South Africa (EPRD)	</h4>

Although no Common Position document is to date available, the Council unanimously agreed that this budget line will be governed by a Type 3a committee.
<p>
<h4>Rehabilitation</h4>

The Common Position states that the Commission shall be assisted "by the relevant geographically determined committee" i.e. EDF, MED, ALA or Type 3a committee for grants of more than 2 MECU.  At the same time, the Commission shall inform the Committee of decisions under 2 MECU not later than 1 week before the decision is taken.  (The Commission can also overrun, without seeking the opinion of the Committee, for an amount less or equal to 20% of the initial financing decision.  If the additional commitment is less than 4 MECU, the Commission shall inform the Committee.  If it is more than 4 MECU. but less than 20%, the Committee's opinion shall be sought).
<p>
<h4>Co-Financing with NGOs</h4>

The Council was unable to reach a Common Position on the comitology issue.  The Commission, supported by Belgium and Luxembourg wants to maintain the current practice of having no committee.  We understand that Germany, the Netherlands, UK and Finland would like a Type 3a.  We understand further that the then Spanish Presidency argued for a Type 2b committee.  We have no information on the position of other member states.  This issue will again be discussed by Council on May 28.  
<p>
<h4>Decentralised Cooperation</h4>

As with the Co-financing Budget line, there was disagreement within Council on the comitology issue, with some  Member States arguing for a Type 3a committee.

<p>
<A NAME="ngo"><h3>Some NGO Perspectives</h3></a>

EURO-CIDSE has tried to tackle this issue in some depth since we are convinced, as Terry Wynn cogently argues, that there are fundamental issues at stake - how can we argue for the promotion  of human rights, democracy and good governance when it comes to development co-operation, if we do not ensure it in our own community, our own European Union.  It is also important that NGOs are not dismissed as simply defending their own turf - we are, of course, but the issue is much broader than that and cannot simply be confined to the kind of horizontal standardisation which the Council appears to favour.
<p>
Before looking individually at the budget lines in question, three preliminary remarks can be made :
<ul>
<li>standardisation is by no means synonymous with simplification (as the Council Reflection Group suggests), especially when the standard is the most stringent type of committee and which, in the Parliament's view, makes the Commission's task of implementing legislation unnecessarily lengthy, complicated and cumbersome.  
<p>
<li>the co-ordination of Member States' activities is both a laudable and a necessary objective.  However, the establishment of a committee will not per se bring this about unless a genuine exchange of information and increased collaboration is part of its terms of reference.  The experience of committees to date seems in general that Member States are well apprised of Commission activity but that this largely remains a one-way street.
<p>
<li>the desire to have a greater say in policy is quite understandable, particularly as the EU and its budget continues to grow.  If we take but one example, that of humanitarian aid, its expenditure has increased from around 100 MECU at the beginning of the decade and the Iraqi crisis to 765 MECU last year.  But the question remains whether the current committee structure (which tends to be project/programme oriented) of national civil servants is best suited to such policy discussions or whether it assists in the process of democratic accountability, co-decision making and interinstitutional co-operation.
</ul><p>
With regard to individual budget lines, we would offer the following comments :
<p>
With regard to Humanitarian Aid (ECHO) and the Rehabilitation regulations :
<ul>
<li>The ECHO procedure seems extraordinarily complicated, particularly since NGOs regard all of ECHO's work, including short term rehabilitation which is part of its mandate as urgent.
<p>
<li>ECHO deals with an enormous volume of work.  In 1995 ECHO dealt with  205 decisions.  For example, if there is an outbreak of civil strife in country x (with attendant refugee problems, outbreaks of disease etc.) ECHO goes to Council for a decision, indicating the types of actions it envisages and proposing a global amount e.g. 10 MECU.  Out of those decisions, in 1995, there emerged between 12,000 and 15,000 contracts.  This volume of work and its urgent nature argue for the most simplified procedures possible.
<p>
<li>In this regard, the fine print of whatever procedures are finally put in place are critical - and these internal regulations are determined by the committee(s) itself once the Parliament has given the regulation its second reading and once the Council has ratified it.  Questions such as the number of languages documents have to be produced in, written procedures/consultations, length of time to take decisions (e.g. within 48 hours or longer) become literally critical in the life-or-death situations with which ECHO is sadly all too frequently confronted.
<p>
<li>The NGO community has some experience with rehabilitation under a Type 3a committee.( in this case the EDF Committee).  It will be recalled that, for a number of years the European NGO community (EURO-CIDSE, the EU-NGDO Liaison Committee, Caritas Europa, EUROSTEP, EURONAID and APRODEV) had long campaigned for special Community measures for rehabilitation, particularly in Africa.  The campaign had both short term and long term objectives : a) to ensure immediate recovery programme for Africa's agriculture and infrastructure modelled in the special EC food aid programmes for Africa in 1991 and 1992; b) to secure a permanent financial instrument i.e. the establishment of a specific rehabilitation budget line.  This campaign came to political fruition in 1993 when a) the May 1993 Development Council launched a fast-track Special Initiative for African Recovery with an immediate allocation of 100 MECU; b) at the instigation of Commission and with strong support from the Parliament, a rehabilitation budget line was introduced into the 1994 EU Budget.  In mid June 1993, Commissioner Marin called together the European NGO networks cited above to implement, through their NGO members, the Council's Special Initiative.  Without going into too much detail (and in any event there is a detailed NGO evaluation of this Special Initiative which is available from EURO-CIDSE) and leaving aside that it was never our intention to create an NGO facility but rather to help African states in crises, by the end of September 1993, 330 projects had been submitted to the Commission in the five countries designated by the Commission (Angola, Mozambique, Somalia, Eritrea and Ethiopia) for a total value of 170,961,738 ECU of which 142,580,524 ECU was requested from the Commission.  In September-November 1994, having decided that to continue to speak of a Special Initiative served no useful purpose, we conducted a survey of the results.  The response rate, despite the frustration level among the NGO community, was 53%.  By November 1994, of the 195 projects known through the survey, 17 had received Commission funding, with a further 5 awaiting funds and 16 waiting to sign contracts.  Whilst our evaluation examines the complex of reasons for the dismal failure of the implementation of this Special Initiative, one of the reasons was undoubtedly the comitology procedure: <i>"Implementation of the Council's decision was made difficult by the inherent contradiction between its commitment to a fast track, urgent and flexible response and the directive to use EDF funds in accordance with existing procedures.."</i>
</ul>
<p>
With regard to food aid and food security, we would highlight the following :
<ul>
<li>This food aid budget line has been operating under a Type 2b committee for quite some time and, in general, NGOs feel that this Committee has functioned well, largely due to the flexibility and confidence on all sides.  But Committees can change and reliance on existing good will is not necessarily the best basis for case law.  Potentially, a Type 2b committee could be a source of blockages and delays.
<p>
<li>This question is particularly important if/when a food emergency arises since the bulk of emergency food aid provision rest with the food aid division in DG VIII and not within ECHO.  In 1995, ECHO had an allocation of 33.6 MECU for emergency food aid (with a likely 87 MECU in 1996).  The food aid division had an allocation of 591.9 MECU in 1995 (with a likely 540.9 MECU in 1996).  
</ul><p>
With regard to the Co-financing Budget Line Regulation, we would offer the following reflections :
<ul>
<li>The Co-financing Budget Line has operated successfully for 20 years without any Member States Committee.  And indeed NGO demand exceeds EC supply.  And here we would cite the old adage "if it isn't broken, don't fix it".  We recognise  and appreciate that this budget line has grown considerably, from its modest experimental period in 1976 of 2.5 MECU to 174 MECU in 1995 (and a decreased 162.5 MECU in 1996, despite the adherence of new Member States).  And we would not underestimate the value of this budget line - particularly in terms of impact of the lives of people in developing countries where much can be done with  relatively small amounts of money.   Nevertheless it does rather pale into insignificance compared to 40.82 BECU allocated to agriculture in the EU 86.525 BECU budget.
<p>
<li>The decrease in the Parliament's allocation to this budget line - the first since the budget line's inception - is in recognition that the NGO division in the Commission simply cannot cope with the volume of work, as evidenced by the underspending in 1995 on this budget line.
<p>
<li>Some ballpark figures illustrate this volume.  In 1995 the NGO Division processed approximately 1,200 projects of which some 800 were financed.  This figure does not include all the contacts and meetings with NGOs regarding pre-discussions on possible projects.  And, of course, there is follow up of projects - financial reports, interim reports, final reports etc. and this involves some 3,000 or so projects. (And this figure does not include the 2-3,000 projects currently financed under the block grant scheme.)  The NGO division has some 1,000 NGOs on its list, some 600 of whom they deal with annually.  For development projects and development education combined there is a total of 12 staff supervised by Amedeo Brusasco and Cesar Granda, with Bernard Ryelandt, of course, as Head of Division (and who currently has also 2 temporary staff - one till the end of February and the other till the end of April).
<p>
<li>The chronic problem of understa-ffing is not new.   Luciano Vecchi (Italy, Socialist) drew attention to this problem in January 1992 (subsequently reflected in the Parliament's resolution of May of that year) 
<p>
"A second major problem posed for the operation and potential expansion of co-financed measures results from the inadequate complement of staff to deal with NGOs at Commission DV VIII, a numerical shortfall which makes the job in hand more difficult for the admittedly very highly qualified and efficient personnel now employed.  Given that the offices responsible for dealing with NGOs (already burdened with an enormous workload) will also be called upon to an increasing extent to attend to decentralized cooperation operations under the Fourth Lom Convention, it appears that existing staff strength needs to be boosted substantially.
<p>
"Finally, in the light of nearly four year's experience with the new rules on co-financing, it might be appropriate to begin discussions on what improvements could be made, both to the procedure for considering projects (without detracting from the Commission's essential supervisory responsibilities and the criteria of good repute and sound management as far as NGOs are concerned) and with regard to extending the far less cumbersome system of global donations."</i>
<p>
Since this report was written (when the Co-financing budget line was 110 MECU), 1 additional staff member was added in 1995.  But, at the same time, due to Council decision, the co-financing budget line lost the mini-budget line which allowed 1 MECU out of the overall funds for the recruitment of staff and equipment.  At the same time, the proposed revision of the general guidelines - and the NGO community is in agreement on an extended block grant system/framework agreements - has still to take place.
<p>
<li> Council sources stress that, in pressing for a Committee (with 13 of the Member States in favour of some type of comitology procedure), they have absolutely no intention of discussing individual projects and hence there will be a proposal that projects under 1 MECU (or 2 MECU in the case of NGO consortia) would be part of the provisions.  And this is eminently sensible and welcome but we would seriously question the ceiling levels in the light of the remarks above regarding the general revision.
<p>
<li>On the other hand, Council sources stress that they would like to have a say in policy formulation/guidelines through, say, an annual meeting.  Beyond the general guidelines for the co-financing budget line, the development  priorities set by Council and the remarks added to the Budget, it is difficult to envisage how such a steering committee would operate in practice bearing in mind the following considerations : a) the Commission's role is essentially reactive - responding to requests submitted to it by a large number and wide range of European NGOs; b) for their part, European NGOs react to the needs expressed by their partners c) NGOs see development as a process and therefore an essentially long term commitment.  We outlined current development thinking at some length in EURO-CIDSE's submission to the Commission (in December 1992) on the revision of the general guidelines and argued for a whole new approach to co-operation with NGOs "in line with the thinking on man and woman at the centre of development policy, protagonists in a complex development process which is part of a global framework of North-South interdependence.  The current General Conditions suggest a simplistic project approach, easily quantifiable, and with people in developing countries as mere beneficiaries of aid from the North." d) NGOs bring their own money to the table.  The Vecchi report cited above stated that for every ECU spent by the Community," NGOs manage to invest a total of ECU 2.5, thus acting as an effective 'multiplier' of Community resources; "  This is not to argue against policy discussions involving the Member States.  Rather, it is to argue for a different formula to the comitology procedures and which involves other parties, such as the European Parliament, and, in particular, the NGOs.  It is also to stress that NGOs are not merely sub-contractors - cheap delivery systems for EU policy (and thus responding to this or that shift in policy towards this or that geographical area or sector or even, God forbid, discussions of whether NGOs from this or that European Member States are getting their fair share of the co-financing cake) but legitimate stakeholders in any policy debate in this context.
<p>
<li> It is also useful here to recall the experience of the South Africa Budget Line (or ESP as it was then termed).  This budget line operated under a Type 1 Committee structure.  Whilst we recognise all the specificity, uniqueness, political sensitivity of this particular budget line, it was, until the emergence of the new democratic South Africa, a budget line which operated exclusively through NGOs.  And whilst every effort was made by the Commission, the South African partners (of which there were only four) and representatives of their European NGO counterparts to ensure the smooth running of this 'advisory' committee, our experience was not a very positive one.  Indeed, less than a year after the programme began operations, the South African partners publicly suspended (in April 1987) their participation in the ESP because of undue political interference from the Member States.  On a more recent note, the Commission, using a firm of external evaluators, has commissioned an evaluation of the Special Programme from its inception in 1986 to the present.  Whilst this evaluation is currently in the process of being finalised, its initial findings regarding 'lessons learned' suggest that the most important lesson to be learned from the ESP is that key ingredients, even the sine qua non, for a successful project are ownership, dedication, and community involvement where applicable.  The ESP was successful because it was reactive rather than top-down.  It empowered organisations financially to carry out activities that from their perspective were crucial to move South Africa towards democracy and prosperity.  No amount of planning by even the most professional and concerned development expert, expatriate or national could replace that collective experience.  Whilst efforts were made at the outset to ensure the programme operated in a special way, in some fundamental aspects, the ordinary routines as regards the formal approval of contracts, payments etc. pertained.  Combined with the large number of parties involved in the process, battles over turf, and understaffing at all levels, the administration of the programme became a nightmare for everyone involved.  When this became apparent, the reaction on the part of the Commission was to seek to reshape the programme to fit the internal administrative constraints rather than the other way round.  An alternative to squeezing the South Africa programme into the standard Lom type mould would have been to radically decentralise formal decision making, by providing block or endowment grants to appropriate South African intermediaries, while strengthening the substantive and financial monitoring of the programme.
</ul><p>
With regard to the South Africa regulation, we have yet to see a common position, we have little to add to other remarks made above, except to say that, if the intention is to bring South Africa in line with EDF procedures, then the new South African government has our sympathy (and speaking as an organisation which ploughed its way through the post-Fiji study, conducted by Price Waterhouse in November 1992, Study on the Causes of Delay in the Implementation of Financial and Technical Cooperation.

<p>
Finally, a word about decentralised co-operation..  Why a budget line with an allocation of 5 MECU in 1995 and 6 MECU in 1996 - and designed to foster experimental and innovative local activities to promote this approach to development - needs a committee of any description is quite beyond our understanding.
<p>
In conclusion, we quote again from Umberto Scapagnini MEP :
<p>
<i>	"In the USA, the Federal Advisory Committee Act of 1972 obliges all expert advisory committees which advise US Executive Agencies (such as the Environment Protection Agency or the Food and Drug Administration) to meet in public, to publish their agendas in advance, and to publish minutes, with the usual exemptions for national security issues.  The US system is designed to achieve the kind of openness and transparency which ensures that pressure groups, concerned individuals, representatives of industry - the list is endless - make sure that politicians know what is going on in expert committees."</i>
<p>
Does the European Union deserve any less?

<p>
<h3><a href="eurocid.htm">Return</a> to EURO-CIDSE Page</h3>
</ul>
<p>
<hr>
