</DOCHDR>
<html>
<header>
<title>Development Cooperation Advisory Structures in Europe</title>
</header>
<hr>
<h3><center><IMG SRC  = "../images/eu.jpg" border=1><p>
Cooperation of Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy:<br> A Survey in 17
European Countries<p> <i>Possibilities for Cooperation of Advisory Structures for Development
Cooperation Policy in seventeen
European Countries</i></h3></center>
This information is drawn from the report of a survey (1993-1994) carried out by the European Centre
for Development Policy Management (ECDPM) on behalf of the National Advisory Council for
Development Cooperation (NAR) in the Netherlands.
<p> 
<IMG align=left SRC  = "../images/nar.jpg" border=1> 
<h5>Source: Kooij, A. and R. Mevis. 1994. <i>Cooperation of Advisory Structures for Development
Cooperation Policy: A Survey in Seventeen European Countries.</i> The Hague: National Advisory
Council for Development Cooperation. Copies of the report are available from: NAR Secretariat,
Ministry of Foreign Affairs, P.O. Box 20061, 2500 EB The Hague, the Netherlands.
</h5>
<hr>
<h3>Contents:</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#trends">Organisation of European Development Cooperation</a>
<li><a href="#ins">Institutional Framework</a>
<li><a href="#adv">Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</a>
<li><a href="#poss">Possibilities for Cooperation in Europe</a>
<li>Acronyms can be checked by clicking on <a href="../../ecdpm/acro.htm"><IMG align=top SRC =
"../images/acro.jpg"></a>
</ul><p>

<hr><a name="org">
This chapter summarises in very broad terms the main characteristics and trends that can be observed
in the
description of development cooperation policies and administrative structures as the main environment
in which
advisory institutions have to operate. Secondly, the various advisory boards or councils encountered
are
summarised in several categories, and discussed per category. Third, an overview is given of
possibilities for
cooperation between these institutions. The choice between given alternatives and/or realisation of
these
possibilities, depends very much on the outcome of the subsequent discussions on this report. Within
the current
changing  circumstances, the observations that are made here are mainly points for discussion rather
than
recommendations.
<p>
<hr><a name="trends"><h3>Characteristics and Trends in Policies and Administrative
Structures</h3></a>
<p>
The main characteristic that can be observed from the 17 country reports is their wide range of
variations in all
relevant aspects. A number of these differences dates back to historical situations, from which several
countries are
presently emerging (Portugal, Spain, Austria). All countries have to deal with a current changing
international
political situation that brings new problems and focal points for international cooperation to the fore:
environmental degradation, conflicts and peacekeeping, aid to the Central and Eastern European
Countries (CEEC)
and the New Independent States (NIS) of the former Soviet Union and reception of immigrants.
Moreover nearly all
donor countries face domestic economic constraints. Regardless of old or new policies, focal points,
a too familiar
ghost keeps haunting developing countries: poverty.
<p>
The main differences between the 17 European countries can be observed in the following areas:
<ul>
<li>general aid objectives and their historical background;
<li>the balance between numbers of officially stated objectives and priorities,  available means and
actual
disbursements;
<li>aid targets as well as the actual disbursed volume of aid;
<li>the composition of aid such as emergency aid, and commercial orientation;
<li>instruments and channels such as multi- and bilateral ratio, and channelling through NGOs;
<li>the level of detail to which general objectives are operationalised into separate sector- and country
guidelines,
policies for cross-cutting issues such as WID and the environment;
<li>the forms of political responsibility for development cooperation, policy coordinating authority,
and the
administrative organisation of aid;
<li>aid procedures, including those for evaluation and feedback;
<li>the importance that is attached to policy dialogue with recipient countries and the responsibilities
that are
shared with them, which are strongly related to the decentralisation of implementation;
<li>the number of documents on general policies, White Papers, Strategies, country and sector
policies, and
evaluations in which official policies are described, published and made available to the public. 
</ul>
<p>
Regardless of their present type of development cooperation policy and their actual modes of
implementation, all
donor countries have to find a new coherence, both within the framework of development cooperation
policy as
well as between development policy and other policy areas, notably foreign, domestic and economic
affairs. At the
same time they have to find a new balance between stated objectives and required means. All countries
are in
different stages of this re-orientation process. In a number of countries these changes have led to
administrative re-organisations. The main points of difference are summarised below.
<p>
As far as can be observed from government Strategies, White papers and general Policy Papers, in 11
countries
major policy changes can seen to have taken place over the past four years, that will be continued
during the
coming years, in Denmark, Spain, Ireland, the Netherlands, Norway, Austria, Portugal, Finland,
Sweden, UK and
Switzerland. In 8 of the 11 countries these major policy changes are directly related to efforts for the
integration of
new tasks into 'traditional' areas of development cooperation, in Denmark, Ireland, the Netherlands,
Norway,
Finland, Sweden, UK and Switzerland. In this process the integration of Agenda 21 has advanced
farthest. In 3 of
the 11 countries adjustments are, till now, mainly related to surpassing historical constraints (in Spain,
Austria,
Portugal, and to a certain extent in Italy). In a majority of the 11 countries, major policy changes were
accompanied
by re-organisations in the aid administration. In 3 countries no major policy changes could be observed
(in
Germany, France, Luxembourg), while in another 2 countries only administrative changes were, or
are,
implemented (in Belgium, Italy). The situation in Greece is largely unknown. 
<p>
Apparently in a number of countries budget cuts are implemented without major changes in policy.
In the majority
of the 17 countries, decentralisation of aid implementation - for instance: policy dialogue and the
sharing of
responsibilities with developing countries - as a central feature of administering aid can be observed.
In at least 2
countries relationships with development countries are entered into on a basis of mutual responsibility
for each
other's development. The Netherlands and Switzerland established relations in which recipient
countries, for
instance advice on measures for the realisation of the donor country's national goals for sustainable
development. 
<p>
In Denmark, Ireland, the Netherlands, Norway, Austria, Finland, Sweden, the UK and Switzerland
White Papers,
Strategies and comprehensive Policy Papers on development cooperation in the 1990s, including an
emphasis on
the integration of Agenda 21 and sustainable development have been written in the last three years,
in addition to
the usual Annual Plans, Annual Reports and Explanations on the Budgets that some countries
produce. Studies on
Agenda 21 include both consequences for developing countries and for development cooperation, as
well as the
consequences of sustainable development for donor countries. In particular in Denmark, Ireland, the
Netherlands,
Norway, Finland, the United Kingdom and Switzerland the sustainable development issue has been
integrated in
cooperation policies, and is linked to their own national environmental plans. 
<p>
<hr><a name="ins"><h3>Institutional Framework</h3>

In 11 countries a Minister or a State Secretary is responsible for development cooperation (Belgium,
Denmark,
Germany, Ireland, the Netherlands, Norway, Austria, Portugal, Finland, Sweden, UK). In 6 of these
11 countries
the Minister is a full member of the Cabinet. To compare: in 1992 out of the 20 member states of the
DAC 8 had a
Minister of  Development Cooperation that held a full Cabinet position. Allocations of responsibilities
and
coordinating authorities vary greatly. In these 11 countries there is a separate form of governmental
organisation for
policy formulation and implementation of official development cooperation, or for parts of it. In most
cases the
responsible directorates are located within the Ministry of Foreign Affairs. In 2 of the 11 countries
implementing
agencies are located outside the administration (Norway, Sweden). In the majority of countries
development
cooperation is distributed over several ministries, agencies and institutions. Some are still traditionally
structured,
some organised on the basis of new concepts and tasks. Internal and external coordination of policy
formulation
and implementation is difficult and time consuming. In the majority of countries the government aid
organisation
has been re-organised several times, initiated mostly by changes in the domestic political situation and
in a few
cases as a direct consequence of changes in the content of development cooperation policies.
<p>
Since 1980/81, and more significantly since 1989, ODA volumes in nearly all of the 17 countries have
decreased.
In 1992/93 the ODA GNP ratio of 12 countries was below the international target of 0.7 per cent and
the ratios of 4
countries were above this target (1 unknown). In 1990 ODA of 11 of the 17 countries (1 unknown)
was already
below the average of the EU member states of 0.51 per cent of GNP. In 11 countries budget cuts are
projected for
the years after 1993, in 4 countries none are planned (Denmark, Ireland, Luxembourg, Austria), and
in 2 countries
plans are unknown (Greece and Portugal). Costs for peacekeeping, for aid to the CEECs and the NIS,
for the
reception of immigrants and refugees have been kept mainly outside ODA. Nevertheless the need for
a re-ordering
of all 'external assistance costs' is growing, while the discussion for an up-date of the familiar definition
of ODA
continues. At the same time the call for more attention to domestic economic interests within
development
cooperation policies becomes louder. Multilateral contributions to the EU, UN- and World Bank
institutions grew
fastest. These contributions are likely to continue to increase, at the expense of bilateral aid to
developing
countries, in a time of constant or decreasing total aid budgets. Paraphrasing a question posed by the
Finnish
NGOs, one could ask: 'What is there left to defend Europe's ODA?' 
<p>
Concluding: 17 European countries are searching for new forms of coherence and coordination of new
policies and
instruments, in changing circumstances, still supported by the public, and with apparently less funds. 
<p>
<hr><a name="adv"><h3>Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</h3></a>
<p>
Advisory Councils and other advisory structures vary as widely as the above summarised policy and
administrative
environment. This paragraph describes some general characteristics, and elaborates successively
mandate and actual
functioning, size and membership, independence, and subject areas covered. The description cannot
be complete in
all detail, since for some countries (notably Greece) and on some points data are lacking; for instance
on the
subjects discussed by councils that mainly have an internal advising function within the Ministry of
Development
Cooperation. Finally, some general observations are made. Figures elaborated in this survey point to
general
indications and directions of observed developments and trends. 
<p>
In this survey several types of Advisory Structures and Mechanisms are described. These are 'Formal
Advisory
Institutions'. Advisory Councils for Development Cooperation that are installed by the Government
and that have
the explicit mandate to advise the Government, through one of its Ministers, on matters of
development cooperation
policy. Not taking into account other characteristics, such as actual functions, procedures, right of
initiative.
'Policy' is defined here as general development policy excluding specific policies for sectors or
countries. A
Council is classified in this category when at least its mandate permits it to advise on general policy
questions; in
practice it may also cover other areas, for instance a Council may comment on annual reports or
contribute to the
specification of the budget. These include the institutions described under the second paragraphs
headed 'Formal
Advisory Institutions'. In these countries other organisations, structures and mechanisms that might
contribute to or
influence advising on development cooperation policy, are described in the third paragraphs, 'Other
Actors'. They
are not covered in the following summary. 
<p>
In countries where no such Formal Advisory Institution for policy advice exists, all advisory activities
are described
in the second paragraphs of the country descriptions, headed 'Advisory Structures and Mechanisms'. 
<p>
For completeness sake, attention in the country reports has been given to commercial consultancy
services for
implementation of development activities that may influence general development policy. However,
these activities
are excluded from the following summary. This leads to the observation that in the majority of the 17
countries
more policy advisory activities are carried out than the objective of this survey allows to describe.
Formal Advisory
Councils are only one group of several producers of policy advice.
<p>
<h3>Table I: An overview of Formal Advisory Institutions and their structure or status</h3>
<p>
8 formal advisory institutions (board and/or council) in:
<ol>
<li>Denmark,  since 1971 (a Board and a Council)
<li>Germany, since 1963 (a Scientific Council)
<li>Ireland, since 1994 (first Council installed in 1979 )
<li>Italy, since 1987
<li>The Netherlands, snce 1964, (to be abolished in 1997)
<li>Austria, since 1974
<li>Finland, since 1992 (first Council installed in 1979)
<li>Switzerland, since 1976
</ol>
<p>
1 Board of a limited mandate, in:
<ol>
<li>Sweden, since 1965 (a separate Council is installed for each aid agency)
</ol>
<p>
In 2 countries Councils are about to be installed:
<ol>
<li>Spain, planned by the government
<li>Portugal, requested by groups in society
</ol>
<p>
2 Councils have been abolished in:
<ol>
<li>Belgium, since 1962 (abolished in 1985, although not officially )
<li>Norway, since 1968(abolished in 1989)
</ol>
<p>
In 2 countries policy advisory work is carried out by other institutions or influenced by other
mechanisms:
<ol>
<li>France - many renowned research institutes and other organisations
<li>UK - many renowned research institutes, some government owned
</ol>
<p>
in 1 country no formal advisory institutions and/or other institutes are known:
<ol>
<li>Luxembourg
</ol>
<p>
in 1 country the advisory situation is unknown:
<ol>
<li>Greece - no Council, the contribution of research institutes is unknown
</ol>
<p>
In the 11 countries where a Minister or State Secretary is responsible for development cooperation
policy, 6 have
an Advisory Council, in Denmark, Germany, Ireland, the Netherlands, Austria, Finland. In 4 of the
11 countries
there is no formal Council, in Belgium (defunct), Norway (abolished), Portugal (requested) and the
UK. In Sweden
several Boards exist, one per aid agency. Sweden is not included in the following description, unless
explicitly
mentioned. Two countries without a Minister or State Secretary of Development Cooperation have
an Advisory
Council, Italy and Switzerland. 
<p>
All 8 Advisory Councils were installed - finally or for the first time - in the same period in which
legislation on
development cooperation was passed and the first governmental administrative institutions were
created, in the
1960s and 1970s. A period, when official development cooperation policy had to be elaborated, and
its support
base -NGOs and voluntary organisations - had to be enlarged in the donor countries. In the
Scandinavian countries,
where a clear distinction exists between relatively small Ministries for policy formulation and larger
agencies for
implementation, a Board as well as a Council for the implementing Agency were established. The
Board (Styrelse)
can be considered a Steering Committee, and the Council (Radet) a Consultative Committee. In
Sweden this is still
the function of the boards at SIDA and the other implementing agencies, BITS, SAREC and
SWEDECORP. One
of the functions of the, now defunct, Belgian Council, certainly was to strengthen the independent
position of the
newly created agency AGCD.
<p>
Generally speaking, the Advisory Councils observed in this survey may be divided into two broad
categories,
according to their official mandates and actual functions:
<ul>
<li>Councils with a primarily consultative function, in Denmark, Italy, Austria, and Finland. The
Council in these
countries serves to inform the administration, as well as Council members and their networks. All 4
Councils meet
in the presence of the Minister or her/his representatives. In Austria the Minister convenes and chairs
the Council's
meetings. Since, among others, Parliamentarians are also Council members (except in Italy),
consensus can be
reached before parliamentary debates take place. None of these Councils publishes results, since these
results are
for internal use only. In practice there are more variations in actual activities. Denmark's Council also
comments on
projects before they are sent to Parliament; the clear intermediating role of Finland's KESU between
Government
and pressure groups in society has been described earlier. In Italy the Council comments on the annual
report on
development cooperation, and in the 1970s the Austrian Council elaborated Austria's Law on
Development
Cooperation into Guidelines for cooperation.
<p>
<li>Councils with mainly an advisory function, in Germany, Ireland, the Netherlands, and
Switzerland. These
Councils firstly advise the Government on general development cooperation policy, on their own
initiative or on the
governments request. Also here distinctions are not clear cut. In Germany the Minister may attend
discussions of
the Beirat, while in the Netherlands the Minister only discusses written recommendations in a special
meeting with
the Council and is officially obliged to respond in writing to the Council and to Parliament. In
Switzerland the
Council also comments on government policy documents before they are sent to Parliament, and meets
in the
presence of SDC officials. In this category, the now defunct Belgian Council might be classified, since
its first task
was to advise the Government on policy formulation. But in addition the Minister was obliged to ask
the Belgian
Council's advice on his annual report on development cooperation, on policy options and on project
proposals of
NGOs.
</ul>
<p>
Judging from the apparent change in composition of the Dutch Council's membership over the years),
one might
conclude that changes in the principal function of one and the same Council occur; in this example a
change from a
primarily consultative to a mainly advising function.
<p>
It can be observed that the actual realisation of a mandate very much depends on the position and
initiatives of a
Council's members. Secondly, a Council actually combines the function of 'consultative committee'
and that of
'advisory council'. The last observation is supported by the fact that actual Council membership is
based both on
expertise and representation. A construction which might influence the technical contents of
recommendations and
reports, and the speed with which they are produced. 
<p>
Of the 8 Councils, 3 Councils have a membership of less than 20 persons (Ireland, Finland - the
smallest Council
with 10 members - and Switzerland). The German Council has 25 members, while 4 countries have
Councils with
45 members or more: in Denmark (the largest Council with 75 members), Italy, the Netherlands and
Austria.
SIDA's Board in Sweden has 14 members and the Belgian Council used to have 14 and later 35
members. Small or
large, actual representativity of Councils' membership is high, even in Councils of which the members
are
appointed on criteria of expertise and personal capacities. For instance in the Netherlands, the NAR
membership is
based on expertise, but should also include as many sections of Dutch society as possible.
<p>
The Councils in Denmark, Austria and Switzerland have the greatest variety in membership
composition, followed
by (Belgium), Italy, and Finland, then by Ireland and the Netherlands. The German Council has the
most
homogeneous composition and purest scientific character. Trade unions and the business community
tend to be
underrepresented. Councils with a primarily consultative function, include members from the official
development
cooperation administration in (Belgium), Denmark, Italy, Austria and Finland. In Denmark Council
meetings may
also be attended by the press. Three of these Councils also have Parliamentarians among their
members, in
Denmark, Austria and Finland. This underlines their consultative function. In the Netherlands official
contacts on
behalf of the Council with members of Parliament are currently maintained by the Presidium of the
Council, and
have an informative function about the general position of the Council only. Except for the Council
in Austria, the
other 7 Councils have the right of initiative. They select subjects for discussion and write
recommendations. They
bring matters of their choice to the attention of the Minister. 
<p>
Five Councils have their own secretariat that is located in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs. These are
the two
'consultative councils' in Denmark and Finland, and the three 'advisory councils' in Ireland, the
Netherlands and
Switzerland. The secretaries are officials of the Ministry except in Ireland where the Secretary is
directly contracted
by the Council. Secretaries of the former Finnish Councils were sometimes located outside the
Ministry. 
<p>

In Germany the Council can be contacted through the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and in Austria
through the
Federal Chancellery. As far as is known the Secretariats of the Councils in Denmark, the Netherlands,
Finland and
Switzerland are located in the Policy Planning Unit of the development cooperation administration
within the
MFA. Details of feedback procedures of Councils' discussions and reports to- or through these Units
are unknown,
except for the Netherlands. Generally speaking, they vary greatly, according to the appreciation by
Ministers of the
results of the Council's activities. The fate of the now defunct Belgium Council is a point in case.  
<p>
Councils in Ireland and the Netherlands have their own budgets, provided by the Ministry of Foreign
Affairs. The
Councils in Germany and Finland have to submit a funding request for each activity to the Ministry.
In the
Netherlands and in Finland,  Councils may have research conducted on their behalf and organise
conferences and
seminars for a wider public. This was also the case with the Belgian Council. In Germany the Ministry
sometimes
decides to publish the reports of the Council. In the Netherlands reports by the Council are always
published (in
several languages). The Irish Council can do so in consultation with the Ministry. Working procedures
of the
Councils seem to be farthest elaborated and formalised in the Netherlands.
<p>
From the foregoing it can be observed that Councils in Germany, Ireland, the Netherlands and Finland
have the
most independent relation with their respective Governments, followed by Denmark, Italy,
Switzerland, and last,
Austria. Evidently, this observation does not take into account the variations that doubtless occur,
based on
personal initiatives.         
<p>
Policy areas and subjects that are and were covered by Councils are difficult to describe, since only
three Councils
have the means to publish results of their work. The Netherlands' Council publishes its
recommendations and other
studies; the German Council publishes some of its results. Publications of the present Irish Council
are not yet
known. In most countries results of discussions are for internal use only. However, subject-areas that
were and are treated, are amongst others:
<ol>
<li>General development cooperation policy: WID, migrants and refugees, development cooperation
in the 1990s,
public support for development cooperation, industrial and agriculture development, comments on
reports of
international organisations such as DAC, UNDP and World Bank. Agenda 21 after UNCED 1992
appears to be the
most frequently studied and discussed issue in the past few years. Current agenda's of several Councils
include
discussions on the coming UN Worldconference on Population, the UN Worldconference on Women
and on the
World Social Summit. Although broad in their analyses, these studies are oriented towards the
formulation of
national positions for those occasions.<p>
<li>Specific areas and issues include: comments on annual reports, budgets, project proposals,
specific policy papers, national aid instruments and channels for aid, procedures and guidelines;
</ol>
<p>
Apparently in only one country, Finland, the Council has contributed directly to the Government's
most recent
Strategy Paper (1993), 'Finland's Development Cooperation in the 1990s'. While Agenda 21 is both
on the agenda
of several Governments and on the agenda of several Councils, it seems doubtful whether the two have
actually
met.
<p>
<h3>Further Observations</h3>
<p>
From the foregoing summary a number of very tentative observations can be made.
<ul>
<li>Regardless of their actual consultative or advisory functions, Councils appear to have been most
influential in
the period when development cooperation was yet unexplored and expertise had to be built up. In
several countries
Councils were abolished when the administration had acquired expertise, when support for
development activities
was secured, and when advice could be bought through less complicated procedures from consultants,
specialised
institutes and NGOs. However, current international circumstances appear to create similar
opportunities for
Councils, as in the 1960s and 1970s. The current changes in international relations, again create areas
where new
policies can be explored. Globalisation and regionalisation processes have consequences for: financial
systems,
sustainable development in the traditional 'recipient' and 'donor' countries, technology and
environment, social and
economic reforms, economic development and human rights, security, arms and conflict, economic
dualism,
government policies and private enterprise, population, contents of development cooperation policy
and foreign
policy, etc. Leaving the smaller and more traditional issues, Councils could concentrate on the
coherence of these
policy areas. They could fulfil again an intermediating task between Governments, policy makers, and
scientific
communities as well as related sections of society. 
<p>
<li>The world anno 1994 probably requires a consistent shift of perspective in all activities that
concern relations
between groups of people. The international perspective could replace the traditional national one, in
which the
point of departure could be shared responsibilities with developing countries. This required change
of perspective
might be of the same importance, as was the transition from a colonial order to a cooperation structure,
to which
councils and other advisory or consultative structures and mechanisms have contributed in the past.
<p>
<li>The degree of 'Euro-content' of Councils' activities could certainly be raised. Not only as far as
the number of
activities on specific European issues is concerned, but firstly by the inclusion of the European
dimension in each
study and recommendation. 
<p>
<li>These changes could be facilitated by a number of practical measures, to be derived from the
above described
experiences:
<ul>
<li>the acquisition of a relative independent position appears to enhance a Council's productivity;
<li>a minimum amount of formally regulated procedures, amongst others for operating, feedback
mechanisms, and
secretarial support, is required;
<li>publication of results, studies and recommendations is probably a conditio sine qua non for
participating
effectively in policy debates;
<li>enlarging the accessibility of studies and reports through translations into relevant languages is
an obvious
measure in 'our global village';
<li>inclusion of relevant domestic expertise, as well as expertise from the South, and from 'Brussels'
supports an
international and European approach and quality;
<li>the consultative function could be more clearly separated from the advisory function. Why not
delegate the first
function to the existing 'Committees for Development Education', already concentrate in some
countries on
development cooperation  nd sustainable development? They also are changing their perspective;
<li>a budget would create more possibilities for councils to organise seminars, workshops and have
research
conducted and establish contacts;
<li>Secretariats could integrate the international and European dimension in their work by allocating
some of their
time to these activities, if only by maintaining international contacts;
<li>secretariats could organise meetings with representatives from the EC and other relevant
international
institutions and with partner Councils.
<li>Councils appear to have been established on the initiative of Governments, and seem to have gone
up and down
with administrative reforms. They could find ways to create their own, scientific base of support in
their societies
and through international contacts. For instance, contacts by Councils as a whole or by the Secretariats
could be
institutionalised with research communities and institutes, and international data-bases could be used. 
<li>Networking experiences of NGOs and Universities could be used here. Besides the
EC-NGO-Liaison
Committee and the numerous other NGO-networks, one could mention the 'Joint Planning Committee'
between
NGOs and Governments that was established in 1993 in Paris. Also, the cooperation between the
Evaluation Units
for Development Cooperation from several donor countries could be instructive. Within and without
the DAC,
several of these Units conduct joint evaluations, for instance of the World Food Programme, the EU-
Food Aid
Programme, the Regional Development Banks and a planned evaluation of the EDF.
<li>A flexible model such as the Finnish Council might enhance the topicality of a Council's work.
The KESU in
Finland is installed for a limited period and receives a specific mandate for each new term. 
</ul></ul>
<p>
A short remark should be made about the situation in France and the UK on the one hand and in Spain
and
Portugal on the other. In the first two countries numerous 'other advisory structures and mechanisms'
are present in
many broad as well as specific areas, without an apparent need to create more formalised advisory
institutions for
development cooperation. In Spain and Portugal, perhaps supplemented by Belgium, there is a wish
- from different
quarters though - to organise the available expertise for development cooperation, into some sort of
advisory or
consultative structure. Institutions in both groups of countries may profit from the here described
experiences,
when they want to decide upon their course for further cooperation in this area. 
<p>
<hr><a name="poss"><h3>Possibilities for Cooperation in Europe</h3></a>
<p>
The EC has shown interest in the efforts of several Councils to establish some form of cooperation
between
advisory councils for development cooperation policy. Representatives of the EC attended the 1991
Workshop in
the Hague and in June and December 1993 DG VIII organised two one day meetings on Coherence
of EU-Development Cooperation Policies, that were also attended by representatives of several of the
here mentioned
institutions. However, the DG VIII focuses on ad hoc cooperation with a group of individual experts
for policy
development in specific areas, rather than on establishing more structured or organised forms of
cooperation.
Notwithstanding this difference in focus, contacts and cooperation with the EC should be maintained,
and
approaches should be developed that connect with the European level of policy formulation. 
<p>
Recent EU-related discussions include several useful suggestions for the direction of any future
cooperation
between advisory structures in Europe. With regard to general approaches, inclusion of global issues
and broad
approaches are stressed. For instance, Bossuyt, Laporte and Brigaldino argue, in their discussion of
complementarity, that the EC should limit itself to those areas where it has an added value, such as
macro-economic approaches, policy coordination, or performing the role of think tank. The present
preoccupation with the
implementation of projects should be left to other actors, according to the authors. Faber also stresses
the need for
the study of coherence between areas such as development cooperation, agriculture, trade, environment
and
monetary policies, effectiveness and evaluation of EC policy instruments, on the basis of the
development
cooperation paragraph of the Treaty of Maastricht (art. 130 u). He proposes that the EC introduces
a coherence test.
Broad topics and the coherence between them are mentioned, such as trade, SAP's, good governance,
human rights,
population, Africa, and migration. A report on the position of the Netherlands' Social Economic
Council (SER) in
Europe, also argues that activities of the Council directed towards 'Brussels' should not loose
themselves in short-term details, but should concentrate on fundamental points and main issues.
<p>
In addition to raising the degree of the 'Euro-content' of studies and recommendations by choosing
subjects of
European importance (including studies on the consequences of European measures for Member
States), and by
including the European dimension in reports directed to national Governments, contacts with relevant
institutions
could be helpful. Direct contacts could be established by Councils and their Secretariats with relevant
EC
departments and European umbrella organisations and networks of scientists, researchers and NGOs.
The EC-NGO-Liaison Committee and EADI have already been mentioned, but also contacts with
institutes such as
ECDPM in Maastricht and the North-South Institute in Portugal can be useful.
<p>
As yet there is no 'European Advisory Council for Development Cooperation Policy' , comparable to
the advisory
Social Economic Committee (SEC), that was installed by the Treaty of Rome. An input by advisory
Councils and
other advisory institutions for development cooperation policy into the 'Brussels information
processing
machinery', can contribute to the coherence and coordination of EU development cooperation policy
and to that of
its Member States. However, without a careful pragmatic approach, such a network might be more
of a hindrance
than an asset for effective cooperation. The SEC appears to feel the need for a number of measures for
strengthening its functioning. These measures seem to be related to the above mentioned points with
regard to
national Councils: strengthening independence, institutionalisation of working procedures, clear
criteria for
membership and required and relevant expertise.
<p>
Information on the (former) cooperation of the Councils of Denmark, Norway, Finland and Sweden
in the 'Nordic
Council' is not conclusive about the actual reason for stopping this cooperation. Perhaps, minds were
too 'like
minded', thereby excluding interesting topics for discussion, or it could not operate independently
enough in order
to be sufficiently creative.  
<p>
The foregoing summary does not generate one exclusive route to one form of cooperation between
advisory
structures in Europe. Depending on the choice of goals, long-term and mid-term, several ways are
open, probably
parallel to each other. The original idea for cooperation pre-supposed the existence of more or less
identical, and
also quite structured advisory councils for development cooperation policy. This 'ideal type' apparently
does not
exist. The 8 - 9 described Councils vary greatly on most essential aspects. In addition, in some
countries any form
of advisory structure is clearly absent. Whatever form any future cooperation will take, it has to take
into account
this variety, at least as a point of departure.
<p>
Theoretically two routes for strengthening European Cooperation could be followed.
<p>
Route I starts with building a structure for cooperation. This approach seems futile and will not create
any
participation. What could it have to offer? The discussions and interviews during this survey did not
find any
enthusiasm for this route. Route II takes as a starting point a pragmatic form of cooperation between
interested
members of councils and other institutions in Europe, which may create in mid-term a network for
practical
cooperation and, in long-term some form of more structured cooperation, if need be. People
interviewed appear
interested in such a, carefully managed, approach. It could start with a relative small nucleus of people
that are
prepared, and have the practical possibilities, to invest in building up cooperation and enlarge the
number of
contacts, gradually.
<p>
The interest for cooperation of people spoken to in 14 countries during this survey, is felt through all
Councils and
institutions. Roughly speaking, people in half of the number of countries visited are prepared to be
involved from
the start in one way or the other. The other half, which is certainly interested, would rather like to wait
for further
developments first. Both groups acknowledge the relevance of cooperation, both for their national and
for their
international functioning. These attitudes support a choice for Route II. Finally, one should be aware
that
cooperation, at least for the time being, actually should be established on commitments of individuals,
since no
Council, or Council member, has a 'European mandate'. 
<p>
In addition to these suggestions, the following practical points of action for enhancing cooperation can
be
proposed. 
<p>
The Council in Germany is prepared to organise a workshop to discuss 1) the results of this survey,
second, 2) a
draft for a joint paper, and 3) possible further steps for cooperation. This workshop might be held later
in 1994
when Germany chairs the EU.
<p>
Cooperation could be initiated by producing joint reports on subjects of common interest. Cooperation
should
produce something of interest to all parties concerned. Members of the Council of Germany, the NAR
of the
Netherlands, the ODI in the UK and the ELO in Portugal expressed their interest and willingness to
prepare a draft
paper for joint discussion. The German Council would be prepared to coordinate matters and produce
a first set-up
for the draft of the joint paper.
<p>
Collection and exchange of information could contribute to the coordination of activities, as well as
to establish
and maintain contacts. A definite interest was expressed in such an exchange. Information might
include subject
areas of work, agenda's, coming reports, events and publications, as well as (changing) procedures.
This report
could serve as a basis. Generally speaking, the information that could be collected during the survey,
consists
mostly of documents that are published by Governments and institutes. It gives little exchangeable
information on
the functioning of advisory Councils and institutes. The majority of the latter type of information was
acquired
during interviews and from internal documents. In fact, policy recommendations were only received
from the
Councils of the Netherlands and Germany. 
<p>
A practical continuation of the present cooperation during this survey, could be the preparation of an
up-dated
edition of this report within the next year.
<p>
Observing the experiences during the survey in the past year, it appears that these efforts need the
regular support
of some sort of focal point, that may function as a liaison between the participants. And, at this stage,
some
encouragement might be needed. An internationally composed steering committee of interested people
could be
installed to coordinate and initiate activities, at however low profile it should operate.
<p>
As indicated in the beginning of this part of the report, the further course of cooperation depends first
and foremost
on the decisions that will be taken by the participants in the coming discussions. The collected material
seems more
than sufficient. 
<p>
<HR>
