<html>
<header>
<title>The Comparative Effectiveness and the Coordination Efforts of EU Donors</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H3><center><IMG SRC  = "../images/eu.jpg"><p>
The Comparative Effectiveness and the Coordination Efforts<br>of EU Donors
<br>
<i>Werner Gocht, Adrian Hewitt, and Paul Hoebink</i></h3></center><br>
<h5><IMG align=left SRC  = "../images/nar.jpg" border=1>Source: Gocht, W., A. Hewitt, and P. Hoebink. 1994. <i>The Comparative Effectiveness and the Coordination Efforts of EU Donors</i>.<br> The Hague: National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation.<br>The report is available from the NAR Secretariat, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, P.O. Box 20061, 2500 EB The Hague, the Netherlands<br>(e-mail: <a href="mailto:nar-dgis@dgis.minbuza.nl"> nar-dgis@dgis.minbuza.nl</a>).
<p>
</h5><p>
<hr>
This paper is the product of a workshop held in Feldafing, Germany, on 11 November 1994 under the auspices of the Wissenschaftlicher Beirat and with the support of the Federal Ministry for Economic Cooperation. 
<p>
Given the massive changes confronting aid donors, it is important that the decision-takers among the donors grasp the nettle not only of policy reform but also of procedural reform. They should set in motion a process whereby Europe's development assistance can be provided not just coherently, but on the basis of donor comparative advantage. This may not mean easing the European Commission out of its role as "seventeenth donor" but it will require a clearer, more logical and ultimately a more politically sensible division of responsibilities in aid supply between the Member States
and the Commission.
<p>
How should the objective of assessing the strengths of the existing European donors' aid delivery systems and advising on the means for achieving coordination be accomplished? Five methods (not mutually exclusive) are advanced:
<p>
<ol>
<li>In the first, the Development Council has selected four sectors in which EU donors will work more closely at sectoral policy and country levels.
<li>The second, more iterative and practical approach, is for the donors to coordinate (with assistance from the Commission) their aid through a pilot scheme in six recipient countries.
<li>The third approach, promoted by the Dutch DGIS aims to coordinate and improve EU aid by setting up an external evaluation of the European Development Fund. 
<li>The fourth approach is to apply strict competitive performance criteria to aid policies and aid administrations and for those that do not reach the standards to be eliminated.
<li>the fifth approach, and the one recommended by the workshop, is for the various research institutes to carry out a study of the comparative effectiveness of European and Member States' aid, and their aid management systems.
</ol>
The authors conclude by suggesting that efforts to make European aid more effective must be based on a joint approach insted of the current parallel approaches. This requires a sustained intensification of the role played by the European Commission in development cooperation, as well as improved coordination of bilateral development policy, harmonised methods of administrative procedures, the establishment of common rules, and enhanced efforts to ensure parliamentary monitoring of development cooperation at all levels.
<p>
<hr>
<H6><IMG ALIGN=middle
SRC="../images/nar.jpg"> <i>Updated on October 18,
1995</i><br>

