</DOCHDR>
<html>
<header>
<title>The Comparative Effectiveness and the Evaluation Efforts of EU Donors</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H3><center><IMG SRC  = "../images/eu.jpg"><p>
The Comparative Effectiveness and the Evaluation Efforts<br>of EU Donors
<br>
<i>Paul Hoebink</i></h3></center>
<br>
<h5><IMG align=left SRC  = "../images/nar.jpg" border=1> Source: Hoebink, P. 1995. <i>The Comparative Effectiveness and the Evaluation Efforts of EU Donors</i>.<br> The Hague: National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation.<br>The report is available from the NAR Secretariat, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, P.O. Box 20061, 2500 EB The Hague, the Netherlands.<br>(e-mail: <a href="mailto:nar-dgis@dgis.minbuza.nl"> nar-dgis@dgis.minbuza.nl</a>).
<p>
</h5><p>
<hr>

CONTENTS
</ul>
<li><A HREF="#int">Introduction</A>
<li><A HREF="#eff">Effectiveness</a>
<li><A HREF="#eva">Evaluation by European Donors</a>
<li><A HREF="#con">The Context of Evaluation</a>
<li><A HREF="#end">Conclusions</a>
<li>Additional annexes and a literature list are available in the
printed version
</ul>

<A NAME="int"><hr><h3>Introduction</h3></A>

There are many factors that influence aid effectiveness. They
range from policies of the aid-receiving country to donor
motives and bureaucratic procedures. Foreign aid is probably
the most evaluated branch of government in EU member countries. But although evaluation is part of the common management techniques of most donors and thousands of projects are
as such evaluated, still large parts of aid effectiveness, of
successes and failures of aid-programs and -projects, and
especially of the impact of development aid are unknown. It is
therefore difficult to formulate generalizations on this
subject and even more so to do this in a comparative way. Up
till now evaluations and studies on the effects of foreign aid
do not provide adequate enough data to come to firm and unambiguous conclusions other than expert judgements. Still we
will try in this paper to come to some conclusions on aid
effectiveness on basis of the existing scientific literature
and of a comparison of recent evaluations of European donors.
Based on this material we will also give an overview of
evaluation practices and suggestions for the improvement of
evaluation research by European donors.
<p>

<A NAME="eff"><hr><h3>Effectiveness </h3></A>

The number of evaluations of official aid might well reach the
number of 15.000. Included in that number though are appraisals and monitoring reports. The number of ex-post
evaluations is much lower, but still must run into the
thousands. Most donors evaluate large parts of their project
portfolio. One should think it might be easy with such a large
quantity of research material at hand to come to general
conclusions and to give an answer to the question 'Does aid
work?'. In fact answers are given to that question as well by
donor agencies as by special task forces. Studies and publica-
tions, most of them by evaluation units of donor agencies,
that try to do so, seem, though to use first and for all
'rules of the thumb' rather than scientific or controlled
methods of research. But also in scientific literature it easy
to find statements as:
<p>
'The misuse of aid has been repeatedly substantiated in many
books and articles, and it is not intended to dwell on it
here... In many ways, the official aid agencies have really
lost their way. They continue to use the old formulae and
procedures, as in the past, but with less and less conviction.
Get any aid official over a beer in the 1990s, and he will
soon be questioning the effectiveness of what he is doing in
Africa.' (McCarthy, 1994:179, 216)
<p>
This might be partly true, but then it is very difficult to
discover this many books and articles in the author's bibli-
ography, because not even one title that would substantiate
his argument is given.
<p>
In donors' documents it is easy to find data that prove the
contrary. In the Annual Review of the Operations Evaluations
Department of the World Bank one could read year after year
that three quarters of the projects evaluated achieved overall
satisfactory results. The percentages were lower in Sub Sahara
Africa and particularly in East Africa, but in general the
large majority of projects performed as planned. In the
nineties though results deteriorated and more than one third
was rated as unsatisfactory. This led to the so-called Wapen-
hans-report, its critique on the functioning of the Bank and
proposals for organizational reforms. In recent German annual
reports on evaluation it was stated that about 30% of the
evaluations gave positive results for the projects evaluated,
40% mixed results and about a quarter of the projects per-
formed unsatisfactory. In the only Dutch report out of 1984
giving an overview of about 150 evaluations by the evaluation
unit since its formation, the unit concluded, but the results
had to be handled with care that: 15% of the projects per-
formed very satisfactory, 35% reasonably satisfactory, 19%
more or less satisfactory, 20% rather unsatisfactory, 8% very
unsatisfactory and on 3% no judgement was possible.
<p>
Although sometimes this kind of results are presented with
great care and warnings against over-interpretation are given,
one should look at them with at least as much doubt as the
certainty with which the reports are generally presented.
Evaluation methods used, the quality of researchers, the
length of field research among other make evaluation results
incomparable in most of the cases. Riddell concluded:
<p>
'To date, aid evaluation has been a very blunt and inadequate
tool with which it is difficult to construct firm and in-
contestable conclusions: in many cases there is simply insuf-
ficient evidence available, in others the evidence is too
ambiguous... In short, both critics and supporters of aid
appear to have been far too eager to draw general conclusions
about aid's performance than the evidence available would
justify.' (Riddell, 1987: 184, 188)
<p>
One could say that seven years later this is still true. Of
course the number of evaluations executed has risen, the body
of knowledge has grown, but also now these firm and incontest-
able conclusions can not been drawn in an objective, scien-
tific, or say non-partisan way. It is definitely now easier to
say which things, projects or programmes, go wrong or which
instruments have a high failure-rate, but large fields of
aid's impact are still unknown. This is particularly true for
the impact of aid-projects and -programmes on poverty al-
leviation or on the poorest strata in society. Also here
Riddell concluded:
<p>
'Of the evaluation material that does exist, much does not
consider this impact (on the poor, p.h.) explicitly or at
all.' (Riddell, 1987: 194)
<p>
And also here the situation has changed little. It seems thus
wise to dwell on some issues where more evidence is available.
<p>
Too often the reasons for aid-failure or for low aid effec-
tiveness in compilations of evaluations, country- or sector-
evaluation studies by donor-organizations are laid at the aid-
receiving side: government policies and institutional barriers
in developing countries are seen as the cause for unsatisfac-
tory project-outcomes. It is certainly true that endogenous
factors have a heavy impact on project-outcomes. A sound
macro-economic policy might be the most mentioned and most
influential factor here, but for projects in a lot of sectors
other factors might be of more influence. A lack of institu-
tional capacity to design and monitor projects often leads to
blue-print planning and inadequate and too optimistic project
designs, many times fuelled by commercial interests. Lopsided
power structures might make a failure of every poverty
oriented project in a given region or country. It is remark-
able how little the unequal distribution of power or f.e.
clientele politics are used as an explanatory factor for low
aid effectiveness. In this sense the evaluation-exercise is
often depoliticized.
<p>
Without propagating a self-castigating exercise, one could
conclude out of many evaluation reports that donors only
seldomly make their own decision-making processes and bureau-
cratic procedures an integral part of evaluation and impact-
measurement. The Nordic countries and the Netherlands are
here, partly, the exceptions. The influence, though, of power
relations and of bureaucratic procedures and structures within
the donor-country on aid effectiveness is large. Political and
commercial interests do influence country-choice, project-
choice and technology-choice. Studies of aid effectiveness
indicate that the number of failed or partly failed projects
rises when other than purely developmental motives play an
important role. When political/strategic or eco-
nomic/commercial motives overrule the motive that foreign aid
should first and foremost bring economic, social and human
development, aid-projects and -programs clearly show more
deficiencies. Donors with a greater emphasis in their programs
on commercial and strategic goals seem to be comparatively
less effective and have relatively more failures. The end of
the Cold War might have diminished donors' political and
strategic considerations in the provision of aid in most
regions of the world. One can imagine that they will continue
to play an important role in the Middle East and to a lesser
extent in Central America, but in general they will be more at
the background. Economic and commercial interests still dis-
tort aid programs. In its latest annual report the Development
Assistance Committee (DAC) of the OECD states:
<p>
'The practice of making a certain amount or specific types of
aid funding conditional on procurement in the donor country is
one which has long raised concerns about the quality and
sustainability of the aid provided.'
<p>
On the costs incurred DAC especially mentions:
<p>
'The interest in the provision of goods and services may give
impetus to project designs that do not correspond well with
recipients' priorities for sustainable development and the
inputs may be priced well above prevailing market levels.'
<p>
These commercial interests often bring with them: blue-print
planning, an over-emphasis on hard-ware, a technological bias
and difficulties in standardization, less value for money and
complications in aid-management within recipient countries.
Regardless of the absorption capacity of aid-receiving
countries, driven also by the budgetary or institutional needs
to spend money, donors in many cases push their projects into
aid-receiving countries. As such, one of the reasons that aid
effectiveness is clearly lower in Africa (R.Cassen, 1985;
T.Killick, 1990) could be that aid-projects and -activities
are more donor-driven in African than in other developing
countries.
<p>
When aid does not work, most of the time it appears that the
mistakes were made right in the beginning: superficial iden-
tification and appraisal, blue-print or inadequate project-
design and wrong choice of technology, appraisal distorted by
bureaucratic or commercial interests are among the most common
mistakes. When the project or program is merely identified, it
already often seems difficult to stop the 'financing train'.
Budget pressures, the need to invest aid-money and an emphasis
on loan approval clearly diminish the quality of appraisal.
One could conclude here that investment in the pre-project-
phase pays itself off easily. Donor agencies should be able
and ready to invest more in the identification and appraisal-
phases. Once planned and in execution project-implementation
is often rather inflexible. Donor's procedures often don't
allow changes in the lay-out of projects or programmes, only
after time-consuming bureaucratic procedures. To improve aid
effectiveness it seems clearly necessary for donors to be more
flexible and to let changes to be incorporated in project-
plans during the implementation phase.
<p>
Aid effectiveness is heavily affected by the recipient-coun-
try's policies and its social and institutional environment.
Wrong macro-economic policies, especially wrong price-
policies, and policies that favour the rich and/or the urban
population, make projects easily less cost-effective or set to
fail from the beginning. The several country-studies of
Sweden, the Netherlands and the World Bank give ample prove
here. But one should add that these studies should be treated
as 'cases' or 'examples'. At first because the researchers'
capabilities and attitudes, as well as their focus or terms of
reference do play a role in their final judgements on aid
effectiveness. Secondly because research methods differ and
are not all of the same quality. Thirdly because these
evaluation studies don't, yet, allow for a comparative
judgement. Several country-studies f.e. are made of Tanzania
with quite negative results on aid-delivery in this country,
but these studies can't lead us to the sort of statements
politicians seem to like, that aid effectiveness in Kenya must
be 'better' or 'worse', or that all aid to so-called socialist
countries a waste.
<p>
'Ownership', reflecting the extent to which a project or
program emanated from the recipient country itself, is the new
buzz-word here. It is believed that a high degree of aid
receiver's ownership and a low or absent imposition from
abroad improve project performance. This could be related with
the correlation between absorption-capacity and aid-perform-
ance: weak institutions and limited planning capacity, or a
limited will to planning of the recipient country, give aid-
project and -programs that are introduced or imposed from
abroad a better chance to be implemented, but a limited chance
of success. Lower aid effectiveness in Africa, compared to
Asia, might be the best proof for the fact that a low absorp-
tion-capacity finds its causes in a low level of overall
development, and for the low extent of local ownership and
consequently low project performance. This implies that donors
should invest more in institutional development and the plan-
ning capacity of the recipient country. Especially technical
aid  should be used more to this effect: to train, especially
in Africa, a new generation of planners who adhere to demo-
cratic procedures and principles of participation. It implies
also that donors and practitioners should pay more than lip-
service to 'participation'. 'Local ownership' in itself, by
definition, should imply that participation of the affected
social groups or classes in planning and project design is
assured. More democratic structures, a higher accountability
and transparency of decision-making in aid-receiving countries
in this way should lead to a higher degree of aid effective-
ness.
<p>

<A NAME="eva"><hr><h3>Evaluation by European Donors</h3></A>

Before entering into some general issues of aid evaluation, we
will try to give a short overview of the evaluation work by
the EU member states and other European donors. Most of them
started with evaluations in the second half of the seventies
or in the eighties. Work done by USAID and the World Bank was
in most cases the example. Some countries have several
evaluation units in all the executing agencies or ministries,
but where the execution of aid programmes is centralized in an
agency or ministry there is mostly only one evaluation unit.
Most evaluation units are small and amounts spent on
evaluation research is limited, confined to less than 0,35%
and in most cases less than 0,10% of ODA (see also Table 1).
<p>
<A HREF="../no/no.htm">Norway</a> has a small, three professionals large, evaluation
unit, placed in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, i.e. outside
the aid-agency NORAD, of two persons dealing with external
evaluations. It spends about 0,12% of ODA on evaluations (see
table). Since 1986 it published three to nine evaluation
reports per year. Some of these evaluations deal with
projects, most with sector reports or multilateral aid
studies. Furthermore ten, quite voluminous but quite superfi-
cial and little critical, country studies were published
between 1985 and 1990, most of them executed by the
Chr.Michelsen Institute. Apart from that 40 to 50 project
reviews are made by the country desks. Country studies and
external evaluations are free to get for the interested audi-
ence.
<p>
Evaluations made by the evaluation unit were dedicated to
specific projects and special programmes, as well as to dif-
ferent aid channels, from multilateral agencies (f.e. UNESCO,
UNIFEM) to private organizations. Most of the times field
research is rather short and linked, especially in the case of
import-support, more to macro-economic aspects. Several
studies are almost entirely based on file-studies and inter-
views with officials.
<p>
One Norwegian evaluation report was dedicated to the learning
effects of evaluations and reviews. It concluded that there
was a gap between the evaluation system and policy oriented
studies. In the evaluation studies aid delivery was more
addressed than impact and policy issues. Evaluation reports
seemed, according to the report, to serve the purpose of
control and management more than the purpose of feed back.
<p>
<A HREF="../se/se.htm">Sweden</a> has since 1972 an evaluation unit, that is placed
inside the Swedish International Development Agency with four
professional staff members. Expenditure on the work of the
unit is some 0,07% of ODA. It carries out some 20 evaluations
a year (on some 300 ongoing projects) and publishes about four
to five, as well project as thematic, studies a year.
Evaluation results are public and easy to come by. The
evaluations are the more traditional type of project
evaluations, with rather short field-visits, limited to aid-
delivery, with no aid-receiving country involvement in the
evaluation, etcetera. They therefore better should be called
project-reviews. Only recently some more thematic evaluations,
f.e. on import support, were done.
<p>
The 1992 management reform, implying a shift in responsibility
for aid implementation to the aid-receiving countries, meant
also a shift in emphasis of evaluations to more non-project
impact-studies and thematic studies. At this moment a special
Secretariat, directly under the Minister, is involved in a
major review of the overall Swedish international cooperation
programme. In the course of this exercise country-studies and
case-studies of macro-economic impact were made. Already nine
main reports and more than twenty sectoral and thematic
studies were written. The final report will be published in
1995.
<p>
<A HREF="../fi/fi.htm">Finland</a> restored its evaluation unit in 1993, placed within
the policy coordination unit of the agency. Its three
evaluation officers coordinate the internal evaluations done
by FINNIDA and hire mainly external, often foreign, consul-
tants for thematic evaluations or evaluations of aid-
instruments. Recently f.e. NGO-activities and the investment-
support programme were evaluated and together with BMZ and
CIDA an evaluation of UNFPA was made. Short field research is
part of most of the studies. In the 1980s about 60 project
evaluations were done, now the number of evaluations is about
20 a year. The unit has about 0,22% of Finnish ODA at its
disposal for evaluations.
<p>
<A HREF="../dk/dk.htm">Denmark</a> has an independent evaluation unit since 1982, that
gained more autonomy since the reorganization of DANIDA in
1991. Its staff consists of four evaluation officers. A rather
large amount of ODA, 0,33% is reserved for this evaluation
research. The number of evaluations was quite high in the
eighties up to 31 in a year, but most evaluations were mere
project evaluations then. Since 1988 about 8 to 9 evaluation
studies were done. They are public and can be easily attained
by interested researchers. 
<p>
Evaluations became more thematic since 1988 than before.
Multilateral aid was already for a long time part of the
surveys, but a major evaluation on 11 agencies in four
countries was published in 1991. Sectoral evaluations included
f.e. electrification, public telephone, grain storage and
drinking water projects. The unit did also organize a more
procedural evaluation of NGO-aid. Nearly all evaluations are
executed by external consultants. By methodological quality
and by time reserved for field research several of the
evaluation studies distinct themselves from most of other
donors' work in this field.
<p>
Participation of local authorities and researchers in
evaluations is limited. A shift to more impact-studies was
proposed two years ago. Feed back mechanisms seem to be first
and for all informal, but the writing of follow-up memorandums
is part of the unit's job.
<p>
The <A HREF="../gb/gb.htm">United Kingdom's</a> evaluation department was formed in 1980
It has six officers and publishes about fifteen reports a
year, some of them are published by the institutes that
contracted the research. About 0,06% of ODA is spent on evalu-
ations. These studies are normally released to the public. In
the beginning evaluation was project-oriented, but there are
more thematic, sectoral and cross-country studies now. The
content of the reports is rather mixed. Most reports deal with
the review of projects, but there are also summaries of
evaluations by other donors, summaries of evaluations of
similar projects, etcetera. Also the volume ranges from five
pages to more than 150. Focus in the evaluations is generally
on financial and economic analysis. Field-research is short
and superficial, impact-analysis nearly absent. 
<p>
Apart from these evaluations the totally independent National
Audit Office undertakes irregular studies on aid-programmes
and -projects. Recently it has published reports on water and
irrigation projects and the environment, emergency relief and
the Pergau Hydro-Electric Project in Malaysia. For this short
research visits to (some of) the countries involved are also
made. The evaluation is not purely on financial regulations
but also impact analysis may be part of it.
<p>
The administration has tried to assure feedback of evaluations
by demanding reference to former evaluations in the submis-
sions for new projects. To reach this relevant evaluation
reports are disseminated at the time officials are planning
new projects. Other feedback instruments seem to have low
priority.
<p>
In <A HREF="../nl/nl.htm">the Netherlands</A> individual project evaluations are dealt
with by the country desks. The evaluation unit, 'Inspection
Development Cooperation in the Field' (IOV), with a staff of
10 professionals undertakes larger studies of most of the time
two or even three years with several field studies. The
'inspectors' themselves are responsible for the final reports
and write most of it themselves. External expertise is hired
for field research and often also for the whole exercise. The
evaluations deal with special programmes and aid-instruments
or are country studies. Two to four, quite voluminous reports
are published each year and disseminated free of charge to the
interested audience. The unit is semi-independent within the
Ministry of Foreign Affairs. 0,06% of Dutch ODA is spent on
IOV-evaluations.
<p>
Local government institutions and researchers play only a
limited role in the evaluations. Field research is rather
short and sometimes superficial. In general the evaluations
are more directed at improving aid-management and aid-delivery
than at measuring aid-impact. Project officers are part of the
'reference group' which advises on methodology and approach. A
critique is that therefore major points of critique are
omitted or final reports are undone of sharp comments. In 1993
an 'Inspection'-report was published dealing with (internal)
evaluation and monitoring. It was quite critical on the
quality of and methodological aspects of evaluations and
concluded that aid/receiving organizations played only a
limited role in evaluations and that the feedback on policy
formulation of these internal evaluations/project reviews was
nearly absent, because structures to feed the institutional
memory were missing.
<p>
In <A HREF="../de/de.htm">Germany</a> about 50 evaluations per year are executed, mostly
by external experts. The unit with four professionals produced
about 750 reports since 1976. About 0,2% of ODA is spent on
evaluation by the ministry and the executing agencies for
technical and financial aid, of which about two thirds by the
evaluation unit. The unit functions more or less as a coor-
dinating and technical support unit for evaluation. 
<p>
Most of the evaluations are project reviews with limited
research time. Two to six cross-project sectoral or thematic
evaluations (Querschnittsanalysen) are made every year. In
recent years f.e. drinking water projects, fertilizer fac-
tories, special energy projects, small industries, women in
development were subject of such analyses. Furthermore
sometimes file-studies or literature-studies on aid-
instruments or developmental themes are published (f.e. cul-
ture and development, sustainability). 
<p>
Yearly reports are made in which general overviews of
evaluation results are given. The main accent is on project
and sectoral studies. No country studies are made up till now.
Feed back mechanisms seem still poor at the moment.
<p>
The several executing agencies and ministries of the
government of <A HREF="../fr/fr.htm">France</a> have their own evaluation units. Most of
the times their evaluations are combined with auditing. The
unit within the Ministry for Cooperation has a number of five
professional staff members and a budget of 0,15% of ODA. It
carries out thematic and country studies, respectively  about
six and two a year. Since these reports are classified, only
out of excerpts a limited view on the exercise could be ob-
tained. The accent is on project evaluations; critical but
without a broad range would be the main characteristic of
evaluation research here. The unit of Caisse Fran&#162;aise de
D&#233;veloppement evaluates about 15 projects a year and also
the Treasury of the Ministry of Economics has a two staff
members unit which carries out 15 to 20 of these evaluations.
Most of these are project reviews and also these are clas-
sified and for internal use only.
<p>
Since a reorganization of its aid-agency, ABOS, in 1992 <A HREF="../be/be.htm">Belgium</a> also has a separate evaluation unit. The Belgium unit
dealt before with research, organization and evaluations. The
new unit has two professionals and a head only for evaluation.
It carries out only a limited number of project evaluations,
project reviews (8-10 per year) that have a restricted circulation. Feed-back mechanisms are still underdeveloped. Only
0,05 percent of ODA is spent on evaluation.
<p>
The evaluation-unit of the European Union was reorganized in
1992 after a very critical report on EU evaluation activities
by the former head of the evaluation unit of ODA and after
continuous critical comments on EC-aid by the European
Auditors and the European Parliament. As a consequence of new
evaluation policies the number of professional staff was
brought to 10. Accent is on project evaluations. The number of
project evaluations reaches the hundred. The quality is not
high, since clear references on methodology are often lacking
and main topics are restricted to technicalities. This is
mainly due to limited field research and reliance on a pool of
researchers of varying qualities. Recently also thematic
cross-sectoral studies were introduced, as well as country
studies, until this moment only directed at technical aid.
Yearly reports on aid evaluations are published.
<p>
Ireland, Portugal and Italy don't have separate evaluation
units. Evaluation is done only sporadically. Ireland has a
Audit and Evaluation Unit though that carried out a first
country-study in 1993 in Lesotho. Until then a very limited
number of project evaluations was executed. The main accent is
on project reviews. Portugal is preparing rules for
evaluations. Also Austria's evaluation capacity is still
limited; a restricted number of mainly mid-term project
reviews/evaluations are carried out up till now.
<p>
Summing up one could conclude that in the northern European
countries the evaluation-function in aid agencies and/or
ministries is  better developed than in southern European
countries (Belgium belonging here to the southern European
part). But also in the northern donors' evaluation work some
easy improvements could be made. The quality of evaluations,
as far as it could be analyzed from the about 90 reports that
were studied for this paper, leaves us with an even more mixed
picture. In terms of the range of subjects and aid-channels,
time spent on field research, methodological accountability
etcetera the Danish reports show the best quality; Finland and
the Netherlands coming next. Most evaluation research by the
other donors is mere project-reviewing with poor reference to
criteria and research methods used. Feed-back mechanisms seem
to have been ameliorated in recent times, but also here
definite improvements could be made especially in the field of
enhancing the learning capacities of the organizations.
<p>

<A NAME="con"><hr><h3>The Context of Evaluation</h3></A>

Evaluation is one of the most important tools to improve aid
effectiveness. One can conclude from the above that too many
donors still have limited or no evaluative capacity, no clear
procedures or guidelines concerning the impartiality and
independence of evaluations, no programming of evaluations, no
or little rules for reporting and dissemination of evaluation-
studies and no structures for follow-up. This leads to the
conclusion that donors take the 'Principles for Evaluation of
Development Assistance' of the DAC (1992) until now not very
seriously.
<p>
Most evaluations by European donors could be better called
project reviews. Limited research time and especially limited
field research makes it impossible for the evaluators to come
further than discussions with authorities and project staff
and an obligatory visit to the 'field'. Given these limited
possibilities measuring results and measuring impact,
especially in complex projects or programmes, seems therefore
impossible, especially when the evaluators want to go beyond
the aid delivery systems themselves.
<p>
Furthermore, evaluation by donor agencies is currently still
too much donor-centred. The aid-relationship in itself implies
inequality, but too often only lip-service is paid to catch-
words as 'partnership in evaluation' and 'participation in
evaluation'. Also in many aid-receiving countries there is no
open climate for impartial and objective evaluation. Still,
donors should make more efforts to involve local scientists
and experts in evaluation and direct their technical aid more
to capacity-building for monitoring and evaluation activities.
Some developing countries, especially in South Asia, have a
long standing tradition in evaluation. Although data on the
quality of their research is lacking, donors should at least
be ready to study the possibilities for a more narrow
cooperation and trying to integrate these developing country
evaluation experts in their own research.
<p>
Evaluation at the moment is too much directed at project-
performance and the improvement of effectiveness on that
level. In that sense, evaluation is too often only a manage-
ment-tool instead of an instrument to enhance the learning
capacities and institutional memory of the aid-organizations
or -agencies. Too often results of evaluations do not go
beyond the desks of the country-officers and the field-
missions involved. Evaluation of EC, Norwegian and Dutch
evaluation-, monitoring- and feed-back-systems led to very
critical comments on the quality of evaluation-research and -
reporting, especially also on the methodological issues, and
on the lacking of feed-back mechanisms.
<p>
More creativity is needed to come to new and more advanced
evaluation techniques with the right mix of quantitative and
qualitative methods. Until now participation of target-groups
in evaluation just seems to be a catchword in official
documents, but is sparsely effectuated. Most evaluation is
done by rapid appraisal in which only local staff and local
officials are involved or interviewed. Donors should, at the
risk of not getting the material they hope for, experiment
with other techniques: self-evaluation also with quantitative
criteria; participation by means of group interviews or group-
evaluations; investing more in long time, even repetitive or
time series, research, etcetera. 
<p>
Most donors have difficulties with integrating their
evaluation results in new country- or sectoral policies. An
open discussion on evaluation results could give an input to
institutional learning and integration in future policies.
Donors should therefore look for ways to disseminate their
evaluation reports to a broader audience. Accountability to
the general or interested public in the donor-countries should
be attained by openness and a wide dissemination of evaluation
material. Too often donors run their 'aid-business' like a
secret service and not as a government-activity which involves
tax-payers' money.
<p>
There is, in general a lot of pressure from parliament,
political parties and interest groups to have more indications
that 'aid does work'. Although many questions regarding
overall aid effectiveness and the impact of foreign aid in
general remain, evaluation though should not in the first
place be used to legitimize the 'aid-business' or to assure
future public support for development cooperation. The public
debate in the donor-countries on the quality of aid is of
great importance to redirect donor-policies, but the first
role evaluation has to play is to improve future aid policy,
aid programs and projects by improving feed back mechanisms
and learning capacities. This also because it seems impossible
to gather in the end enough data to come with clear and un-
questionable conclusions on the impact of development aid. One
of the aspects of the 'Does aid work?'-discussion, though,
should be taken more into account and more underlined; i.e.
the general impact of aid-programs and projects on poverty
alleviation and economic and human development in general
still gets to little attention compared with the progress and
efficiency of a specific project. Evaluation is often, still
too much a project-oriented management-tool. Impact-
measurement, therefore, should be a central focus of evalu-
ations in the coming years. 
<p>
Out of the material collected for this paper one can conclude
also that it seems far easier to come with and gather infor-
mation on the ineffectiveness of aid or to demonstrate aid-
failure than to show aid effectiveness. For critical resear-
chers it is always possible to find objectives that are not
attained, actions that were not cost-effective or target-group
interests that were damaged by project-activities. To learn
lessons in another way, it might be useful to undertake a
critical study on aid-successes and analyze the economical,
socio-political and institutional factors that contributed to
these successes and to a higher aid effectiveness.
<p>
<A NAME="end"><hr><h3>Conclusions</h3></A>

It is still impossible to come with generalized statements on
aid effectiveness and even more so to come to a comparison on
effectiveness of the several European donors. Evaluation has
up till now been a rather blunt instrument, mainly also
because most evaluation research does not go 'deep', stays
away from impact measurement and the quality of it is often
low and in each case of varying level, partly due to time and
budgetary constraints. Only a few donors, f.e. Denmark at
first and then also Finland and the Netherlands, have reached
good or satisfactory levels of evaluation research. A more
creative approach is needed. Furthermore evaluation research
and evaluation results, in most European countries, should be
discussed more in public, through a wider dissemination of
reports, also to ameliorate feed-back mechanisms and to en-
hance the learning capacities of donors' institutions.
<p>
<hr>
