<HEAD>
<title>An Exemplary Partnership: The Development Policy of the European Union</title>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<H3><CENTER><IMG SRC ="../images/acp.jpg"> <IMG SRC  = "../images/eu.jpg"></H3>
<H3>An Exemplary Partnership:<br>The Development Policy of the European Union<p>
<I>Hildegard Lingnau</I></H3>
<H4>Full text of an article from <I>D+C Development and Cooperation<BR>
</I>No. 2, March-April 1994: pages 24-26</h4>
<a href="../index_uf.htm">EUFORIC Page</a><br></CENTER>

<HR><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/dse.gif"><h5> D+C is published
by the Deutsche Stiftung f&uuml;r Internationale Entwicklung.
Subscriptions and further information are available from: The
Editor, E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, Postfach 10 08 01,
D-60008 Frankfurt, Germany. Tel: +49 69 7501-4366, Fax: +49 69
7501-4855. </H5>
<HR>
<P
<B>The Maastricht Treaty for the first time puts the development
policy of the European Union on a firm legal basis. It requires
coordination with the development policies of the member states
and coherence with other union policies. Since the expenditure
of the EU and the member states together make up 40 per cent of
the funds allocated worldwide, the further development of European
development cooperation assumes considerable importance.</B>
<P>
The European development policy grew out of the need not to cut
off from their &quot;mother countries&quot; the areas dependent
on the European colonial states through the formation of the European
Economic Community in 1958. The &quot;association&quot; provided
by the Treaties of Rome in principle gave goods from the associated
countries customs free access to the EEC. As a complement to this
the European Development Fund (EDF) was set up which to this day
is financed directly by the member states(and not out of the EU
budget). After the association partners gained their independence
in the early 60s, continuation of the special relationship was
agreed, first in the Yaound&eacute; Convention (1963 and 1969)
and, after Britain's accession to the EEC in 1973, in the Lom&eacute;
Conventions (from 1975). The cooperation practised under these
agreements with meanwhile 69 African, Caribbean and Pacific (ACP)
states represents the core of the EU development policy and is
regarded internationally as the model for North-South cooperation.
The positive assessment of the Lom&eacute; cooperation rests on
the following characteristics:
<P>
<ul>
<li><B>Contract nature: </B>The agreement lays down in a form
binding on both sides both the joint aims of the cooperation and
the rights and duties of the contracting parties.
<li><B>Durability: </B>The agreements run for several years
(hitherto five, since Lom&eacute; IV 10 years), making cooperation
calculable.
<li><B>Supranationality: </B>As agreements between regions
they overcome bilateralism and make possible a certain independence
of national interests.
<li><B>Continuous dialogue: </B>Negotiation, planning, programming
and control of the development cooperation are done by bodies
with equal representation: the ACP-EU Council of Ministers, the
ACP-EU Committee of Ambassadors and the Joint Assembly.
<li><B>Broad cooperation approach: </B>Beside the usual projects
and programmes of financial and technical cooperation the  Lom&eacute;
Convention encompasses trading  advantages, commodity policy measures
 (STABEX, SYSMIN) and since Lom&eacute; IV  measures to support
structural adjustment  efforts.
<li><B>High grant proportion: </B>The grant  element of the
sixth EDF amounted to 75 per  cent. Since Lom&eacute; IV, with
the exception of the  European Investment Bank (EIB), all loans
 given are non repayable. The grant element of  the present EDF
is 92 per cent.
<li><B>Above average benefits for the least  developed countries
</B>(LDC): 40 per cent of  the Official Development Aid disbursements
of  the EU go to LDCs compared with an average  of 25 per cent
of the corresponding share of  all OECD countries.</ul>
<P>
Parallel to the Lom&eacute; Convention the EC over  time took
on additional development policy  tasks. The food aid in the beginning
was not  very development oriented but simply grew  out of the
surplus production of the European  Community.
<P>
Another regional focus of the EC  development policy became cooperation
with  Mediterranean countries that are not in the EU.  On the
basis of the &quot;Global approach to  Mediterranean policy&quot;
cooperation  agreements of indefinite duration were  reached with
individual countries in the  1970s. Budget funds and EIB loans
are made  available within the framework of finance  protocols,
each of five years duration. As a  &quot;strategic response&quot;
to the economic and  demographic development in the  Mediterranean
region the EC in the early 90s  formulated a &quot;new Mediterranean
policy&quot;  providing for intensified cooperation.
<P>

<table border=1 cellpadding=8>
<caption><b>Table 1: Quantitative trends</b> (net disbursements in US$ million)</caption>
<tr><td><td><B>1973-75</B><td><B>1978-80</B><td><B>1985</B><td><B>1989</B><td><B>1990</B><td><B>1991</B>
<tr><td>ODA<td>565<td>1132<td>1150<td>2690<td>2862<td>3818
<tr><td>Bilateral ODA<td>448<td>970<td>1407<td>2437<td>2618<td>3594
<tr><td>1. Grants<td>441<td>808<td>1387<td>2403<td>2551<td>3513
<tr><td>2. Loans<td>47<td>162<td>20<td>70<td>67<td>81
<tr><td>Multilateral ODA (only grants)<td>77<td>162<td>103<td>217<td>244<td>224
<tr><td>Source: DAC/OECD
</tr></table>
<p>
<table border=1 cellpadding=8>
<caption><b>Table 2: Regional distribution</b> (gross disbursements)</caption>
<tr><td><td><B>1975/76</B><td><B>1980/81</B><td><B>1990/91</B>
<tr><td>Sub-Saharan Africa<td>59.6%<td>60.3%<td>58.2%
<tr><td>South Asia<td>20.8%<td>16.9%<td>7.2%
<tr><td>Other Asian countries and Pacific<td>1.9%<td>4.8%<td>4.9%
<tr><td>Near and Middle East/North Africa/South Europe<td>12.3%<td>11.7%<td>19.6%
<tr><td>Latin America and Caribbean<td>5.4%<td>6.3%<td>10.1%
<tr><td><td>100.0%<td>100.0%<td>100.0%
<tr><td>Source: DAC/OECD
</tr></table>
<p>
Although cooperation with further  developing countries was expanded,
it fell far  short of the countries' expectations (see  Table
2). Cooperation agreements were  reached especially in the 80s
with a great  many countries and regional organisations of  Asia
and Latin America but they do not include  pledges of financial
aid. Funds annually made  available by the EU &quot;autonomously&quot;
from the  budget, i.e. without a contractual basis, are  reserved
especially for the poorest  developing countries.
<P>
Cooperation with eastern Europe began in  the late 80s. The association
and &quot;Europe&quot;  agreements concluded in 1988 and 1989
first  with Poland and Hungary, then with all  countries of eastern
Europe and the former  Soviet Union, offer a legal framework for
 cooperation and trade. In addition, within the  framework of
the PHARE and TACIS technical  aid programmes funds are made available
 which taken together will considerably  exceed those set aside
by the 7th EDF for the  69 ACP states.
<P>
EU development policy assumes an  altogether new dimension in
the context of  growing europeanisation. The treaty on  European
Union decided in Maastricht in 1991  for the first time encodes
development policy  as a sector of policy in its own right (Title
 XVII, Article 130uy). The treaty demands a  development policy
coordinated between the  member states and the EU and coherent
with  other fields of policy. The coordination command (Art. 130x)
raises hope for  administrative simplifications, synergy gains,
 reduction in bilateral dependencies and  possibly the abandonment
of supply tying.
<P>
Systematisation and improved coordination  is planned at following
levels:
<P>
<ul>
<li>Policy coordination (elaboration of joint  sectoral and
regional concepts which are also  binding for the bilateral development
policies);
<li>operational coordination (sectoral and  country specific);
<li>coordinated cooperation with other bilateral  and multilateral
donors and in international  bodies;
<li>coherence (coordination of development  policy with other
EU policies).</ul>
<P>
How the coherence command, which is  also laid down in Article
130v of the  Maastricht Treaty, is to be met is still unclear.
 The council of the development ministers  charged the Commission
in November 1992 to  elaborate proposals by November 1993 on 
how the effects of other EU policies on  developing countries
can be systematically  monitored. Approaches to this might be
<P>
<ul>
<li>that the Commission proposals of all general  directorates
would have to be countersigned  by the General Directorate (GD)
I and/or GD  Vll,
<li>that all EU directives would have to show the  impact of
the measures on developing  countries, analogous to the obligatory
&quot;fiches  financiers&quot; in which financial effects are
 outlined.</ul>
<P>
<B>Aims</B>
<P>
The aims to which the Treaty on European  Union (Article 130u)
obligates the EU  development policy are
<P>
<ul>
<li>sustainable economic and social  development of the developing
countries,  especially the most disadvantaged ones,
<li>harmonious, gradual integration of the  developing countries
into the world economy,
<li>fighting poverty in the developing countries,
<li>further development and strengthening of  democracy and
the rule of law,
<li>observance of human rights and  fundamental freedoms.</ul>
<P>
In a concept paper presented by the  Commission in 1992, adopted
only as a  &quot;declaration&quot; rather than the usual &quot;decision&quot;
 by the Council <a href="#1">(1)</a>, the aims are operationalised.  Accordingly,
sustainable and economic  development is to be achieved by &quot;a
 consistent drive to liberalise domestic  economic activity&quot;.
Sustainability is not defined  more closely and generally the
outcome of the  United Nations Conference on Environment  and
Development (UNCED, Rio de Janeiro  1992) is not taken into account.
Positive,on the  other hand, is that the &quot;Horizon 2000&quot;
paper  suggests complementing the economic criteria  of allocation
of development cooperation  inputs with efficiency criteria and
calls for a  solidarity pact between Africa and the Union.
<P>
<B>Scale of EU aid</B>
<P>
In financial volume the development  cooperation of the EU is
about the same as  that of a medium donor. The expenditures of
 the EU listed in Table 1 comprise  approximately equal parts
of expenditures  from the EDF (Lom&eacute; cooperation) and from
the  EU budget.
<P>
The Maastricht Treaty reaffirms the 0.7 per  cent aid target of
the member states and the  EU (Articles 130 u Paragraph 3) which
 currently only few member states reach and  the EU as a whole
does not. With regard to  the development cooperation funds controlled
 by the Commission, no increases are to be  expected in the near
future; the 1993 budget  allocations for development cooperation
were  11 per cent lower than those of 1992 and  there is little
likelihood that the 8th EDF will  show increments of the nominally
50 per cent  that have been usual.
<P>
The importance of EU development aid  nonetheless becomes clear
when one adds  up the expenditures of the EU and the member  states,
which are to be increasingly  harmonised. With a share of 40 per
cent of  the ODA given worldwide, the EU is then by far  the biggest
donor, followed by Japan and the  USA with 17 per cent each.
<P>
<B>Organisation</B>
<P>
Depending on whether it is EU development  cooperation or cooperation
under the EC-ACP  Lom&eacute; Convention various institutions,
powers  and procedures are involved in the EU  development policy.
The major players in both  cases are the`member states which decide
 on EU development policy in the Council and in  the committees.
The &quot;Development Council&quot;  (the development ministers
of the 12 member  states) convenes twice a year and makes the
 fundamental decisions about the development  policy of the EU.
In the six committees in  which the member states are represented
at  working level the projects and programmes of  the EU are approved
by qualified majority.
<P>
The Commission, comprising the  commissioners and the general
directorates,  forms the executive. Its key functions  comprise
the right to propose, the elaboration  of strategies and concepts
and the  implementation of EU development policy.
<P>
Responsible for the development  cooperation are Commissioner
Manuel Marin  (responsible since 1993 for the development  cooperation
with all developing countries) and  the general directorates I
and VII. General  Directorate I (&quot;Foreign Relations&quot;)
in addition to  general foreign policy is responsible for  North-South
relations, Mediterranean policy  and relations to Asia and Latin
America; the  General Directorate Vl11 (&quot;Development&quot;)
for  the Lom&eacute; cooperation. In addition the GD VII  administers
food aid for all regions, immediate  aid and co funding of NGO
projects.
<P>
In contrast to most bilateral donors the EU  has no implementing
organisations of its own;  implementation of projects and programmes
is  contracted out to consulting firms and  nongovernmental organisations.
In the  developing countries the &quot;Delegate&quot;  represents
the EU in all development  cooperation matters.
<P>
Of little importance in the area of  development cooperation is
the European  Parliament which has no lawmaking power.  In the
Lom&eacute; cooperation sector it may merely  ratify the convention
and in the communal  development cooperation it may merely set
 down the budget framework. The main  controlling function is
exercised by the  European Audit Office which draws up annual reports
about the development policy of the EU.
<P>
Although the EU's development cooperation  has always had and
continues to have flaws,  overall appraisal has to be positive.
It has  brought forth original instruments (export  earnings stabilisation,
promotion of regional  cooperation, etc.) and exemplary procedures
 (institutionalised dialogue, contractual pledges  of development
cooperation) which were  developed further in the light of the
 experiences and insights of three  development decades.
<P>
The biggest flaw in EU development policy  is the unequal treatment
of the various  regions of developing countries. As  development
policies will be conducted jointly  in the EU, it will be important
to &quot;globalise&quot;  development policy, i. e. to transfer
the Lom&eacute;  experience to the development cooperation  with
Asia, Latin America and the  Mediterranean developing countries.
<P>
<B>Outlook</B>
<P>
The 7th EDF ends on 28 February 1995.  Before negotiations on
replenishment of EDF 8  start in 1994 the contracting parties
will have  to name the regulations of the agreement they  want
worked over. Everything indicates that  the EU and the member
states are taking the  half time appraisal of Lom&eacute; IV seriously.
Now  that the &quot;Father of the Lom&eacute; treaties&quot;,
Dieter  Frisch, has left as general director for  development,
the responsible Commissioner  Marin has announced a&quot;modernisation&quot;
of the  Lom&eacute; cooperation. One can presumably take  that
to mean that the allocation of funds is to  be made flexible and
that overall the  development cooperation is to be made more 
conditional. If &quot;modernisation&quot; leads to more  emphasis
to observance of human rights,  reduction of military spending
and &quot;good  governance&quot;  as the Council declared in 
November 1992  this has to be welcomed  and is in fact long overdue.
But if greater  emphasis on these aspects primarily serves  as
a pretext to legitimise cutting development  aid, the credibility
of the EU will be at stake.  How could the EU demand far reaching
 adjustment efforts from the developing  countries without even
coming close to  fulfillment of its own promises  reaching the
 0.7 per cent target, more  environmentally friendly methods of
 production, etc.? The dialogue structures of  the Lom&eacute;
cooperation shouldn't be  circumvented but, on the contrary, used
more. 
<P>
<B>Note:</B>
<P>
<a name=1></a>1. A Development Policy for the Year 2000, s. D+C 1/93, pp. 8-11
<P>
