<html>
<header>
<title>Lom&#233; Review Heightens ACP Concerns</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H2><center><A HREF = "../index.html"><img src="../images/logo.gif"></a><p>
Lom&#233; Review Heightens ACP Concerns</h2>
<p>
<h4>Full text of an article from the <i>ECDPM Programme Highlights 1995</i>: page
4</h4>
</center>
<hr>
Under the Lom&#233; Convention, the European Union provides the most generous
preferential access to markets offered anywhere in the world. It's also one of the largest aid
programmes in the world. Its days seem to be numbered.
<p>
Questions were being asked before the mid-term review of Lom&#233; IV began late last
year. But the quibbling that took place during the review, changes which were made to the
pact, and the decision of EU Member States not to increase funding to ACP countries in real
terms underscore the fact that major innovations must be made if there is to be a Lom&#233;
V.
<p>
Few concessions were made to the ACP side during the re-appraisal of the 20-year-old
Convention, an aid and trade package between Europe and 70 sub-Saharan African,
Caribbean and Pacific (ACP) countries including 40 of the world's poorest nations. Although
Europe agreed to some compromises after the funding deal was finalised, many from ACP
countries expressed disappointment about the outcome of the review. 
<p>
<h3>ACP Disappointed and Relieved</h3>
"Of course we're disappointed. It's not adequate," former Zambian ambassador Kapembe
Nsingo said of the funding package. "Given the accession of the new members (Finland,
Sweden and Austria), they should have augmented the total envelope."
<p>
Disappointment was coupled with relief, however, since at certain points during the
negotiations ACP countries were uncertain whether the review would produce any kind of
agreement.
<p>
"At one point ... it did look as though we were not going to have a conclusion to the matter
and, furthermore, hanging over it was the threat of substantial reductions in the envelope,"
noted Carl Greenidge, interim Secretary General of the ACP Group in Brussels and ECDPM
Board Member. "We were relieved and most appreciative of the contributions of EU
countries, especially France, to getting the matter resolved."
<p>
Over the coming five years, ACP countries will receive 14.965 billion ECU from Europe;
this is a 23.3 percent increase over funding during the first protocol (1990-95). Of this
amount, Member States contributed 12.8 billion ECU (compared with 10.9 billion ECU
under the first protocol). This may sound impressive on first glance. In real terms, however,
it represents a drop in aid.
<p>
That disappointed ACP countries, which hoped for 15.8 billion ECU, mainly to improve
processing, marketing, transformation and distribution of produce so that ACP states can hold
their own in a competitive EU market.
<p>
As Greenidge pointed out, however, the ACP is in a weak bartering position because Europe
now has a surplus in the commodities provided by the group. Furthermore, with the end of
the Cold War, the priorities of Western Europe in general and Germany in particular have
changed. 
<p>
<h3>More Control for the EU</h3>
Although the overriding concern for ACP countries is the level of Lom&#233; funding, they
also are worried about Europe's effort to exert more leverage and control over its partners.
But, as Greenidge acknowledged, "The group is relatively clear on the question of
conditionality; some degree of conditionality is inevitable."
<p>
The shift towards greater European control is manifested in changes to the Convention. These
cause many to question whether Lom&#233; is still a unique partnership, or just another aid
programme where the donor sits in the driver's seat.
<p>
The review, itself opposed by the ACP states, occurred because Europe wants to see more
value for its money. It decided that the best way to achieve this was to link the allocation of
funds more closely to performance. Countries which perform well - according to European
standards, though no one is quite sure how performance will be evaluated - will receive more
money.
<p>
Also, instead of granting a fixed amount of money for a five-year period and giving
recipients a relatively free hand in using the funds, entitlements will be for three years and
recipients must absorb 70 percent of the total funds that have been allocated. If the recipient
fails to do so, the funds may be re-allocated. Although some ACP countries argue that this
condition abrogates the basic principles of partnership, Greenidge disagrees.
<p>
The condition doesn't nullify the partnership, he said. "It leaves in the hands of the
Commission - and, more specifically, the desk officers of the Commission - an undesirable
degree of discretion in the allocation of funds," he explained. "But the matter of
implementation has been raised with the Community and hopefully during the initial period
we will be able to agree what objective criteria will be used in this phasing of disbursements
and determining whether a second disbursement is appropriate."
<p>
<h3>Greater Emphasis on EU Priorities</h3>
Some ACP countries also believe that Europe is linking performance too closely with
political issues such as human rights. Indeed, one of the most significant changes made
during the review was the introduction of a human rights "suspension clause" in Article 366
of the Convention. This states that if any of the essential human rights specified in Article
5 are violated, development aid can be suspended partially or completely. However, as a
concession to the ACP, the EU agreed that this can only happen after a joint ACP-EU
consultation and decision-making process.
<p>
Another change is that the Commission will now take greater responsibility in preparing
projects. It will appraise projects single-handedly but will collaborate with recipients to draft
project proposals (in the past, recipient countries did this themselves). Not unexpectedly, this
is also a concern of the ACP countries.
<p>
"We are not opposed to them looking at projects, but it concerns us that the Commission will
only fund projects it looks favourably on," Greenidge said, adding: "There is a tendency in
some situations to pursue projects in which it has an interest."
<p>
During the review, the EU signalled that it would begin to press harder for ACP countries
to take note of donor priorities when seeking funds. Among the areas identified as needing
particular attention are education, health and training, which Commission officials believe
are central to the economic development of ACP countries. The issue is sensitive, and ACP
countries have resisted what they see as EU efforts to dictate aid policy.
<p>
Nevertheless, by the end of the mid-term review, ACP countries decided that it was not
unreasonable for the Convention to reflect the priorities of both themselves and Europe.
"That is the way [the document] is worded," said Greenidge. "At the end of the day, the
group has been able to have the proposals modified in a way that is more tolerable than the
original proposals would have been. The package wasn't thrust down our throat; it's
something we have negotiated."
<p>
</h5>
<hr>
