<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>A Singular Regional  Pact</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<H3><CENTER><IMG SRC = "../images/eu.jpg"></H3>
<H3>A Singular Regional  Pact<br>The Future of  Lom&eacute; Cooperation<p>
<I>Hildegard Lingnau</I></H3>
<H4>Full text of an article from <I>D+C Development and Cooperation<BR>
</I>No. 5, September-October 1995: pages 8-12</h4>
<a href="../index_uf.htm">EUFORIC Page</a><br></CENTER>

<hr><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/dse.gif"><br><h5> D+C is published
by the Deutsche Stiftung f&uuml;r Internationale Entwicklung.
Subscriptions and further information are available from: The
Editor, E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, Postfach 10 08 01,
D-60008 Frankfurt, Germany. Tel: +49 69 7501-4366, Fax: +49 69
7501-4855. </H5>
<HR>
<P>
<B>European development  policy grew from the need  not to cut off
the former  colonies from their  &quot;mother countries&quot;
 through the formation of  the European Economic  Community. The
 &quot;association&quot; provided by  the Treaties of Rome  primarily
enable the duty  free access of goods  from the associated  countries
to the European  Union (EU).  Complementarily the first  European
Development  Fund (EDF) was set up; it  is still funded directly
by  the member states (not  from the EU budget).</B>
<P>
After the associated partners achieved their independence in the
early 60s, continuation of the special relationships was agreed
first in the conventions of Yaound&eacute; (1963 and 1969) and
after Great Britain's accession to the EC (1973) in the conventions
of Lom&eacute; prom 1975). The cooperation practised within the
framework of these agreements with by now 70 African, Pacific
and Caribbean (ACP) states represents the core of EU development
assistance and is regarded internationally as a model for North-South
cooperation.
<P>
The positive assessment of the Lom&eacute; cooperation is based
especially on the following characteristics:
<P>
<ul>
<li>Treaty character: The agreements bindingly lay down the
joint aims of the cooperation as well as the rights and obligations
of both contracting sides.
<P>
<li>Durability: The agreements have terms of several years
(in the past five, since Lom&eacute; IV 10 years), allowing calculable
cooperation.
<P>
<li>Supranationality: As agreements between regions, they overcome
bilateralism and give a measure of independence from national
convetousness.
<P>
<li>Ongoing dialogue: Negotiation, planning, programming and
control of development cooperation happen in bodies with parity
representation  the ACPEU Council of Ministers, the ACPEU Committee
of Ambassadors and the Joint Assembly.
<P>
<li>Broad cooperation approach: In addition to the usual projects
and programmes of financial and technical cooperation, the Lom&eacute;
cooperation encompasses trade advantages, commodity policy measures
(Stabex, Sysmin) and since Lom&eacute; IV also measures to support
structural adjustment efforts.
<P>
<li>High grant element: The grant element of the 6th EDF amounted
to 75 %. Because only nonrepayable grants are given, since Lom&eacute;
IV, with the exception of loans made by the European Investment
Bank (EIB), the grant element of the 7th EDF is 92 %.
<P>
<li>Above-average consideration for the least developed countries
(LDCs): 40 % of the disbursements of Official Development Assistance
(ODA) of the EU goes to LDCs, whereas the corresponding average
proportion of all OECD donors amounts to merely 25 %. But the
high LDC proportion must be seen less as a pluspoint than as a
structural deficit of European-African cooperation  it is no coincidence
that most of the former European colonies remained least developed
countries!</ul>
<P>
The mid-term review of the current Lom&eacute; IV Convention, completed
in early 1995, has prompted more fundamental debates and further-reaching
changes than earlier new negotiations of the agreement. For example,
EU and ACP states have agreed on inclusion of a democracy clause
in addition to the human rights clause, to the introduction of
&quot;special appropriations for Incentive building&quot; for
measures in areas the EU holds to be especially important (sustainable
development, private enterprise, environment policy, institutional
reforms) as well as intensification of the &quot;decentralized
cooperation&quot;, i. e. cooperation with semi or non-statal players.
In addition, the possibility was opened of stopping development
cooperation in case of human rights violations and bad governance,
the joint administration of funds was limited, and phased disbursements
and changed financing modalities for various instruments were
agreed (Stabex, structural adjustment financing, rehabilitation
measures).
<P>
Thus in respect of development cooperation procedures and instruments
Lom&eacute; cooperation is up to date. But in a more comprehensive
development policy sense much remains to be desired, especially
in regard to trade policy. The &quot;free trade&quot; striven
for was never achieved. The remaining trade policy advantages
of the ACP states vis-&agrave;-vis other developing countries are
increasingly being hollowed out by the general liberalisation
of world trade and the EU's foreign trade.
<P>
<B>Cooperation with other development regions</B>
<P>
The second regional focal area of EU development cooperation has
become cooperation with Mediterranean countries that are not members
of the EU (MTC). On the
basis of the &quot;Global Approach to Mediterranean Policy&quot;
worked out in 1972, cooperation agreements with open ended terms
were reached in the 1970s with individual countries. Budget funds
and EIB loans are made available within the framework of finance
protocols with terms of five years each. As a &quot;strategic
response&quot; to economic and demographic development and the
ecological threat in the Mediterranean region, the EU designed
a &quot;new Mediterranean policy&quot; in the early 90s aimed
at intensifying cooperation. There has been discussion since 1994
about a new &quot;Euro-Mediterranean partnership&quot; whose major
components are to be the &quot;Euro-Mediterranean Economic Area&quot;
(EMEA) and a &quot;Euro-Mediterranean Zone of Political Stability
and Security&quot; (analogous to the Conference on Security and
Cooperation on Europe, CSCE). Although cooperation with additional
developing countries was expanded, it remained far short of their
expectations, especially in regard to trade. Cooperation agreements
were entered with a large number of countries and regional organisations
of Asia and Latin America, especially in the 1980s. But they include
no pledges of financial aid. The funds made available &quot;autonomously&quot;
by the EU, i. e. funds annually taken from the budget without
a contractual basis, are reserved mainly for the poorest developing
countries of these regions. Nor will the proposals submitted by
the Commission at the end of 1994 on future relations with the
Mercosur of Latin America as well as Mexico and Chile and the
&quot;new Asia strategy&quot; change much in the relative low
ranking of these developing regions in the EU's development cooperation.
Rather, the agreements take account of the grown importance of
Latin America and Asia for foreign policy and trade.
<P>
Cooperation with east Europe began in the late 80s. The agreements
reached first with Poland (1988) and Hungary (1989), then with
all east European countries and the former USSR from 1990 to 1992,
provide a legal framework for cooperation and trade.
<P>
<center>
<table border=1 cellpadding=8>
<caption><B>Development aid of EU (Net disbursements in million US $)</B></caption>
<tr><td><td> 1973-75<td> 1978-80<td> 1990<td> 1991<td> 1992<td> 1993
<tr><td>ODA<td> 565 <td>1132 <td>2862<td> 3818<td> 4426<td> 3948
<tr><td>Bilateral ODA <td>448<td> 970<td> 2618 <td>3594<td> 4156 <td>3637
<tr><td>1. Grants<td>441<td> 808<td>2551 <td>3513 <td>4140 <td>3437
<tr><td>2. Loans <td>47<td> 162<td> 67<td> 81 <td>17 <td>200
<tr><td>Multilateral ODA<td> 77<td> 162 <td>244<td> 224 <td>306<td> 311</tr></table>
Source: DAC/OECD</center>
<P>
The shift in foreign and development policy priorities towards
the Mediterranean region and east Europe will increase further
in the years ahead. For the five-year term 1995-1999 the ACP states
received more than 13 billion ecus, central and east Europe 6,7
billion, the southern Mediterranean seabord countries 4,6 billion
and all Asian and Latin American countries together also 4,6 billion.
In content, an increasing convergence is discernible in all regional
development policies of the EU. Conceptual innovations (environment
and structural adjustment policy, promotion of democracy and human
rights, etc.) developed in the context of cooperation with a region
of developing countries, are being successively integrated in
the development cooperation with other developing regions.
<P>
<B>European development policy after Maastricht</B>
<P>
EU development cooperation policy receives a new dimension in
the context of
increasing Europeanisation. In the treaty on European Union adopted
in Maastricht in 1991 development cooperation policy is codified
for the first time as an area of policy in its own right (Title
XVII, Article 130uy). The treaty demands a development policy
that is complementary, coordinated between member states and the
Commission and coherent with other areas of policy. The
coordination demand (Art. 1 30x) gives rise to hope for administrative
simplifications, synergy and efficiency gains, reduction of bilateral
dependencies and possibly the abandonment of supply tying.
<P>
The Maastricht Treaty on European Union (Article 1 30u) commits
the development cooperation of the EU to &quot;foster&quot;:
<P>
<ul>
<li>the sustainable economic and social development of developing
countries, and particularly the most disadvantaged among them,
<P>
<li>the smooth and gradual integration of developing countries
into the world economy,
<P>
<li>the campaign against poverty in developing countries,
<P>
<li>the observance of human rights and fundamental freedoms,
and developing and consolidating democracy and the rule of law.</ul>
<P>
In a concept paper submitted by the Commission and adopted by
the Council as a &quot;Declaration&quot; rather than the usual
&quot;Resolution&quot;, the socalled &quot;Horizon 2000 Paper&quot;,
the aims are operationalised. Accordingly sustainable economic
and social development is to be reached by &quot;consistent liberalisation
of the economy&quot;. No precise definition is made of sustainability,
however, just as generally the outcome of the UN Conference on
Environment and Development (UNCED, Rio 1992) is left out of EU
considerations. Positive in the &quot;Horizon 2000 Paper&quot;
is that for the first time performance criteria are demanded to
complement the economic criteria for the allocation of EU aid,
and a solidarity treaty between Africa and the community is suggested.
<P>
<B>European development cooperation</B>
<P>
In its financial volume the development cooperation of the Commission
compares with that of a medium-size donor. The development cooperation
disbursements comprise about equally disbursements from the European
Development Fund (EDF, Lom&eacute; cooperation) and the budget
of the EU (see table).
<P>
The Maastricht treaty again reaffirms the 0,7 percent target of
the member states and the EU (see Art. 13u Para. 3) which, however,
few member states reach. In regard to the development cooperation
funds administered by the Commission, no significant increases
are to be expected in the foreseeable time, in fact disbursements
dropped in 1993 below the level of 1991.
<P>
How much greater the value of European development policy could
be overall if it were better coordinated becomes plain when one
looks at the disbursements of the Commission and the member states
together. With a share of more than 50 percent of the ODA given
worldwide the EU is then by far the biggest donor, followed by
the USA and Japan (1992) with 17 percent each.
<P>
Although the development cooperation of the EU remains flawed,
overall it must be positively assessed, however. It has brought
forth original instruments, especially within the framework of
the Lom&eacute; cooperation (export earnings stabilisation, fostership
of regional cooperation) and procedures of a model character (institutionalised
dialogue, contractual assurance of aid disbursements) which in
line with the findings and experiences of three development decades
were developed further. Just like most other bilateral donors,
the development cooperation of the EU must be accused of having
supported and stabilized for many years little development oriented
and sometimes even criminal regimes (&quot;collective clientelism&quot;).
It speaks in favour of the development policy of the EU that as
one of the first it began already in the 1980s to stop development
cooperation in especially bad cases and is trying actively with
socalled &quot;positive measures&quot; to promote respect for
human rights.
<P>
The biggest flaw of the EU's development cooperation is the unequal
treatment of the various regions of developing countries. As development
policies are Europeanised it will be important to &quot;globalize&quot;
the development policy of the EU, i. e. to &quot;Lom&eacute;ize&quot;
the development cooperation with Asia, Latin America and the MTC.
In these processes it will be important to introduce the dialogue and cooperation procedures as well as individual
instruments of the Lom&eacute; cooperation into the development
cooperation with the other regions of Third World countries (without
abandoning the financial emphases in favour especially of African
LDCs) and to develop and implement an appropriate &quot;global
policy&quot; coherent with trade and foreign policies.
<P>
<B>On the future of the Lom&eacute; cooperation</B>
<P>
The midterm review of Lom&eacute; IV has again shown the ability
of the contracting parties to engage in dialogue and of the Lom&eacute;
Convention to be developed further. Despite this, there are increasing
demands for ending the special relationships with the ACP states,
regarded increasingly as uninteresting in foreign policy and trade
terms. Commissioner Pinheiro has announced a &quot;radical reappraisal&quot;
of the Lom&eacute; cooperation for the near future. If this leads
to
<P>
<ul>
<li>the Lom&eacute; instruments being differentiated by development
status of the relevant respective recipient countries,
<P>
<li>other LDCs being given support as good and comprehensive
as that given the ACP states and above all
<P>
<li>the newly democratically legitimated development oriented
governments being given substantial support and aid being withdrawn
from criminal and corrupt regimes this is only to be welcomed
and lone overdue. But if these demands aim at letting the Lom&eacute;
Convention, the only meaningful North-South development pact,
run out and justifying the reduction of development cooperation
contributions, the credibility of the EU is at risk and development policy will be thrown back to square one. How can the North,
how can the EU demand far-reaching adjustment efforts from developing
countries without ever coming close to honouring their own pledges
(0,7 % target, environment-compatible production and living patterns,
etc.)? How should &quot;global policy&quot; be practised if not
as a dialogue between partners and in cooperation with all participants?
<P>
It is now more important than ever not to lever out the dialogue
and cooperation structures developed within the framework of the
Lom&eacute; Convention, but, on the contrary, to use them more
intensively and to expand this type of cooperation to other regions
of developing countries. EspecialIy in this regard the Lom&eacute;
cooperation is model for North-South cooperation. 
<p>
<HR>
<H6><I>Updated on November 15, 1996<BR>
