<title>Treaty of Rome</title>

<h1>Treaty establishing the European Community<br>
as Amended by Subsequent Treaties</h1>

<a href="3title17.txt">Title XVII.</a> Development Cooperation (Arts.
130u-y)</ul></blockquote>
<a href="part4.txt">Part Four.</a> Association of the Overseas Countries and
Territories (Arts. 131-6)<p>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT17-B14-46</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA007-000067-B043-397</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.ecdpm.org:80/euforic/dandc/95e_eur.htm 193.128.6.150 19970222012341 text/html 14233
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Sat, 22 Feb 1997 01:23:28 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.5
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Tue, 26 Nov 1996 10:52:04 GMT
Content-length: 14058
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>20 Years DeveIopment Cooperation</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<H3><CENTER><IMG SRC = "../images/eu.jpg"></H3>
<H3>20 Years Development Cooperation<br>The History of the Lom&eacute; Conventions<p>
<I>European Commission</I></H3>
<H4>Full text of an article from <I>D+C Development and Cooperation<BR>
</I>No. 5, September-October 1995: pages 13-15</h4>
<a href="../index_uf.htm">EUFORIC Page</a><br></CENTER>

<hr><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/dse.gif"><br><h5> D+C is published
by the Deutsche Stiftung f&uuml;r Internationale Entwicklung.
Subscriptions and further information are available from: The
Editor, E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, Postfach 10 08 01,
D-60008 Frankfurt, Germany. Tel: +49 69 7501-4366, Fax: +49 69
7501-4855. </H5>
<HR>
<P>
<B>Among the major principles of cooperation between the Community
and the ACP countries are acceptance of the sovereignty of the
partners and the design of projects in a dialogue of partners
with equal rights. Trade advantages are secure and predictable.</B>
<P>
Many former colonies achieved their independence in the 1960s.
The European Community perceived a duty to place trade and cooperation
with these states on new contractual foundations.
<P>
In 1964 it entered the first treaty of Yaounde with 17 African
states and Madagascar. Five years later followed the second Yaounde
Convention with a development budget of 843 million ecu. When
Denmark, Ireland and the United Kingdom joined the EC in 1973
there was agreement also to integrate their former colonies in
the joint trade and development policy. Apart from this historic
obligation, the cooperation between Europe and African, Caribbean
and Pacific states (ACP) was also driven by efforts to intensify
the North-South dialogue and promote the underdeveloped trade relations
among the ACP states.
<P>
<B>Lom&eacute; I</B>
<P>
A landmark in the cooperation of the European Community with the
ACP states is the Lom&eacute; Convention I signed on 28 February
1975. It made a major contribution to a new international economic
order. Special attention was given to the least developed countries.
For them Lom&eacute; I for the first time laid down precise regulations
in respect of the volume of aid and the acceleration of aid allocations.
Lom&eacute; I defined 24 of the 46 signatory states as least developed
countries. Five years later, in Lom&eacute; II, 35 countries were
so categorised, in Lom&eacute; III finally it was 43.
<P>
<B>Lom&eacute; II</B>
<P>
The number of Convention partners rose to 57 in Lom&eacute; II.
The European Community also modified the elements of its aid concept
and laid down certain focal areas.
<P>
<ul>
<li>Lom&eacute; II increasingly concentrated its technical
and financial aid on rural areas. The speed of approval and tying
of EDF grants slowed down. From these experiences the Community
drew conclusions for the Lom&eacute; III agreement and its support
instruments, signed in 1986.
<P>
<li>Africa was helped more than the Caribbean and Pacific states.
In Lom&eacute; I and 11 more than 70 per cent of the funds went
to West and East Africa. Aid for island and landlocked states
was also improved because they are especially disadvantaged by
geography.</ul>
<P>
<B>Lom&eacute; III</B>
<P>
The Lom&eacute; III Convention entered in 1986 increased the range
of ACP treaty partners by nine to 66 states. Lom&eacute; III ran
from 1985 to 1990 and disbursed 7.4 billion ecu in aid. The agreement
started a new trend:
<P>
<ul>
<li>More strongly than in the 70s the Community oriented itself
to focal aid sectors. In close exchange of views with each ACP
state one or two sectors were chosen for assistance. More emphasis
than under Lom&eacute; II was placed on rural development and
food security.
<P>
<li>In the infrastructure promotion sector the Lom&eacute;
aid shifted increasingly to projects serving the maintenance of
existing facilities (e.g. roads). This was because many of the
ACP states already possessed complete infrastructures, e.g. in
the transport sector. </ul>
<P>
Cultural cooperation was included in the agreement as a new field.
In 1986 the partners founded the ACPEEC Foundation in Brussels.
It receives funds from the European Development Fund and supports
studies, research and exchange projects in the cultural field
to advance intercultural dialogue.
<P>
<B>Lom&eacute; IV</B>
<P>
The most important innovation of the Lom&eacute; IV agreement,
which at the same time serves to consolidate successful policy,
is the extension of the term of the  agreement from five to 10
years. That means Lom&eacute; IV will run until the year 2000.
<P>
A big advance was also the increase of funds from 8.5 billion
ecu (Lom&eacute; III) to 12 billion ecu in the finance protocol
from 1990 to 1995. This not only took account of the devaluation
of money and the development of Gross National Product in the
Community, it was in fact a substantial increase in funding.
<P>
Lom&eacute; IV pays special attention to the debt problem of the
ACP states, even though the European Union is their smallest creditor,
which excludes it from directly influencing their debt status.
Many countries are already having to pay back more to the donor
countries than they received as support. Hence the Lom&eacute;
IV agreement contains measures to address the debt problem:
<P>
<ul>
<li> Almost all aid given (except that of the European Investment
Bank) is non-repayable.
<P>
<li>Loans became substantially cheaper. Interest of EIB loans
will in future be three to five per cent, instead of five to eight
per cent up to now.
<P>
<li>The European Union gives the ACP states finance-technical
aid, e.g. in debt management.</ul>
<P>
Into this context belongs the introduction of structural adjustment
aid which supports the economic recovery of the ACP states. This
aid is given in addition to the classical longterm development
projects.
<P>
Some completely new areas have been brought into the agreement:
<P>
<ul>
<li>Population pressure especially in Africa is increasingly
impeding development. Hence the agreement provides for population
policy measures: expansion of statistical services, information
and education campaigns. (For the first time the agree, ment also
contains a reference to voluntary family planning.)
<P>
<li>Promotion of the services sector.
<P>
<li>The importance of environmental protection is upgraded.
A special article on it bans the transport of toxic waste and
radioactive waste to the ACP states.
<P>
<li>Strengthening the private sector. Investments are protected
and promoted primarily with liable capital.</ul>
<P>
The development policy under Lom&eacute; IV increasingly supports
democratisation processes and respect for human rights. With funds
from the 7th EDF the EU supports young democracies in the ACP
states. Examples: In 1994 Mozambique received 13 million ecu to
buy materials for impending elections. The EU also supported the
organization of elections in Togo and Tanzania.
<P>
<B>European development policy in the 90s</B>
<P>
Meanwhile the world economy is undergoing important shifts in
emphases. An outstanding role is played by the results of the
GATT negotiations. The more trade barriers are removed worldwide,
the smaller the gain from the largely duty-free access of the ACP
states to the European internal market. Some ACP states are sceptical
whether they will be able to keep their already problematical
positions in the world market.
<P>
A second change concerns east Europe. More intensive EU relations
to the reforming states of east Europe have eased access to the
Single Market on the scale desired. In view of this, some ACP
states as early as 1990 voiced concern that the least developed
among them could fall even further behind. The European Union
must in future address these concerns and attempt solutions.
<P>
A third essential change for the development policy of the Union
arises from democratisation in South Africa. The responsible Commission
member Joao de Deus Pinheiro assigns to South Africa a key role
in the development policy of the European Union for the ACP states.
<P>
In the cooperation with the ACP states he intends consistently
to follow the maxims of his predecessor, Manuel Marin, and to
tie the allocation of aid to observance of human rights and democratisation.
The Commission is considering increasingly disbursing aid funds
in instalments and more strictly tying them to efficiency criteria.
<P>
<B>Development policy guidelines</B>
<P>
The European Commission continues to place special emphasis on
efficiency and transparency in implementing EU aid programmes.
<P>
Joao de Deus Pinheiro in March underlined his guidelines to representatives
of private European development organisations:
<P>
<ul>
<li>Governments should try to put in place fair competition
conditions for private enterprise. Their control activity in private
business decisions should be reduced to a minimum.
<P>
<li>The major foundation for a functioning market economy is
a viable capital market.
<P>
<li>Stronger growth of investments from home and abroad is
urgently needed.</ul>
<P>
<B>The future of ACP-EU cooperation</B>
<P>
In December 1994, the South African minister for trade and industry,
Trevor Manuel, took part for the first time in the joint ACP-EU
talks in Brussels. Manuel emphasised that his country felt more
comfortable surrounded by developing countries than in a club
of industrial countries.
<P>
South Africa is economically much stronger than the ACP states.
But its national economy is dependent on the export of mining
products and its industry is not internationally competitive.
The great majority of its black population, even after the end
of racial segregation, live in poverty.
<P>
Even before apartheid went, the European Union worked towards
political changes in South Africa. It stood by the victims of
racial segregation through international aid agencies. The EU
supports the democratisation process in two ways:
<P>
<ul>
<li>The Union promoted the April 1994 elections which made
Nelson Mandela president by helping with preparations and observation.
<P>
<li>The Union is aiding the transition to a democratic society
with a cooperation agreement. An interim agreement was signed
in October 1994 and approved by the Council in December. At the
same time negotiations began about comprehensive and longterm
relations.</ul>
<P>
In March 1995 the Council decided to take on guarantees for EIB
loans for projects in South Africa. At the same time it mandated
the Commission to negotiate further agreements with South Africa.
The EU is following a twopronged approach here:
<P>
<ul>
<li>A protocol added to the Lom&eacute; Convention will lay
down the conditions for South Africa's accession. The decision
on it will be made by the ACP-EU Council of Ministers. South Africa
will participate in all cooperations as laid down in the second
part of the Convention. For everything going beyond that (e.g.
Stabex and Sysmin) South Africa's special situation has to be taken into account.
<P>
<li>In addition the Union seeks a trade and cooperation agreement
with Sauth Africa. Its longterm aim is establishment of a free
trade zone.</ul>
<P>
The Commission will make available another 500 million ecu for
the years 1996 to 1999 in the framework of the European Programme
for Reconstruction and Development (EPRD).
<P>
South Africa's inclusion in the Lom&eacute; Convention primarily
is to serve the interests of the ACP states. In the view of the
European Commission South Africa could become the &quot;powerhouse&quot;
of the ACP states' development in its region and beyond.
<P>
<B>Perspectives of joint development policy</B>
<P>
The framework conditions for the cooperation between ACP states
and the European Union have changed. A meaningful partnership
must take that into account and adjust. Some areas in which modifications
will be needed are already becoming apparent.
<P>
<B>Trade. </B>Experience has shown that easing trade alone is
not enough to develop the ACP states. Rather, their export industry
has to become competitive. That requires the instruments of the
Lom&eacute; Convention to be expanded so as to stimulate investment
in the ACP states, support the private sector and so strengthen
competitiveness. 
<P>
<B>Politics. </B>Regional conflicts have proved the decisive impediment
to successful development of the ACP states. The agreement of
Lom&eacute; and the Treaty of Maastricht (strengthening joint
foreign and security policy of EU members) will make for more
effective policy in future to be able to address such conflicts
by diplomatic means. 
<P>
The Lom&eacute; Convention after 2000: The developing countries
have so far been perceived as a homogeneous group whose problems
could be solved with a few &quot;patent medicines&quot;. In reality,
country-specific problems and needs will have to be considered
more strongly.
<P>
It is also necessary to improve the interaction and coordination
of the various instruments. It is the only way to achieve highest
efficiency. In the view of the Commission, bilateral development
aid is a necessary complement, but it can never replace a multilateral
agreement like the Convention of Lom&eacute;. 
<p>
<HR>
