<html>
<HEADER>
<TITLE>ACP SECRETARIAT</TITLE>
</HEADER>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<pre>

</pre><center><A HREF="index.html"><img src="images/acp.jpg"></A></center>
<P>
<H4 align=center>General Secretariat of the Africa, Caribbean and Pacific Group of States<br>
Secr&#233;tariat g&#233;n&#233;ral du groupe des Etats d'Afrique, des Cara&#239;bes, et du Pacifique</H4>

<center>Mr Ngandu Peter MAGANDE<br>CURRICULUM VITAE, October 1996</center>
<hr>
Mr Ngandu Peter MAGANDE, 49, from Zambia is the Secretary General of the 70 African, Caribbean and Pacific (ACP) Group of States with its Secretariat based in Brussels, Belgium.  He was elected by the ACP Council of Ministers in Apia, Western Samoa in June, 1996 and took office on 16th July, 1996.
<P>
Mr Magande was born on 5th July, 1947, at Namaila in the agricultural district of Mazabuka in Zambia.  He attended Namaila, Chikankata and Munali Schools before entering the University of Zambia in Lusaka, where he obtained a Bachelor of Arts degree in Economics and Mathematics in 1970.  In January, 1971, he joined the Zambian Civil Service as an Economist.
<P>
In 1972, Mr Magande won a Ford Foundation scholarship to attend Makerere University in Kampala, Uganda, where a new post-graduate programme in agricultural economics was being established.  Mr Magande earned a Master of Science degree in 1974 and went back home to resume duties in the public service.  He rose through the ranks and served as Director of Planning  in Agriculture and Director of Budget in Finance.  In 1983, he was appointed Permanent Secretary and served in the Ministries of Commerce/Trade/Industry, Local Government, Agriculture and National Commission for Development Planning.
<P>
In 1986, Mr Magande was seconded to the parastatal sector where he served as Managing Director of the Lima Bank, and the Zambia National Commercial Bank, Executive Director with the Industrial Development Corporation (INDECO) and finally as Group Executive Director in the Zambia Industrial and Mining Corporation (ZIMCO).  On retirement from the public service in 1994, Mr Magande was taken on by the Zambian Government as a Technical Assistance Consultant funded by the African Development Bank to coordinate a project on active private sector participation in the agricultural sector.
<P>
During his service, Mr Magande participated in negotiations including those with IFAD and the World Bank.  He attended and chaired national, regional and international meetings and seminars.  He was chairman and board member of many private and public companies.  He has extensively travelled in Asia, the Americas, Europe and within Africa.  Within the crowded work schedule, Mr Magande found time to engage in large-scale commercial farming and in civic society activities.  At the time of his election to the ACP position, he was Chairman of the Economics Association of Zambia.
<P>
Mr Magande is married to Joyce and they have three daughters, two sons and two grand-daughters.  The new Secretary General likes gardening, swimming, playing chess and watching sports.



<p>
<center><h4><a href="index.html">La page ACP</a> / <a href="index.html">ACP Home Page</a></h4></center>
<p>
