</DOCHDR>
<HEADER>
<TITLE>Linking Relief and Development</TITLE>
</HEADER>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<H2><center><img src="images/aprodev.jpg"><p></a>
Linking Relief and Development</h2>
<h4>Full text of an article from <i>APRODEV Bulletin</i><br>April 1996: pages 10-12<p></h4>
</center>
<hr>
<p>
In December 1995, the Commission finished its internal discussion
document on "Linking Relief, Rehabilitation and Development". It
has subsequently been discussed with experts from the academic
world, the Member States and the NGOs. A revised document, taking
account of comments made, is now going through a consultation
process within the Commission. The aim of the discussions could be
a Resolution or a Common Position by the Council of Ministers,
meeting in May. In the meantime, the Commission has decided to test
the new approach in its dealings with Liberia, Angola, Somalia,
Haiti and the Great Lakes region.
<p>
The issue of linking relief and development is on the EU agenda
because: "During 1995, important decisions on long-term development
cooperation relationships have been taken: negotiations on the
Lom&#233; IV Mid Term Review..., a new EU-Mediterranean policy...,
periodic conferences with Latin American (San Jos&#233; and Rio
groups) countries,... and new framework agreements with Asian
countries (Vietnam, Cambodia, Laos).... At the same time, a series
of legal bases/draft regulations have been proposed, regarding a
number of instruments ranging from short-term relief and
rehabilitation to longer-term development." This has led the
Commission to realise that better coordination between all these
instruments was called for. Key words are: complementarity,
coherence and efficiency. The aim being the strengthening of
linkages between the various fields of activity.
<p>
<h3>Linkages</h3>
<p>
The paper starts from the assumption that: "better 'development'
can reduce the need for emergency relief; better 'relief' can
contribute to development; and better 'rehabilitation' can ease the
transition between the two." It says that "the explicit aim of
humanitarian aid is to save the lives of victims of emergency
situations... Although in such situations, the long-term
perspective must come second to saving life, it is nevertheless
extremely important to keep sight of the longer-term view. Indeed,
the short-term and long-term perspective can sometimes be
conflictive."
<p>
According to the discussion document, there are two main ways to
deal with this conflict: improved awareness of the impact of
humanitarian actions and organisational coordination. "A solid
long-term perspective of relief operations can only be assured if
a clear impact analysis is made before relief actions are
implemented." There is a need for country-specific impact analyses.
<p>
The Commission has not managed to apply the proposed "holistic"
approach to the document, which breathes the spirit of a
"continuum" approach. It says that rehabilitation and
reconstruction primarily concern the re-establishment of rule of
law and political dialogue, and that rehabilitation efforts should
be of limited duration, not aiming for restoration but rather for
the resumption of development.
<p>
In the section about development, the terms "Risk" and
"Vulnerability" play an important role. The Community should take
vulnerabilities into account in programming its assistance. This is
then illustrated for two fields: food security and health. 
A fourth section deals with man-made emergencies. "Conflict
prevention should be an intrinsic element of development
cooperation policy.... A policy of crisis prevention should
adequately combine political, economic, legal, military, social and
environmental stabilisation measures. The challenge lies in the
mobilisation of efforts, their coordination and their direction
towards a common goal." According to the document, EU policies
should be captured in an overall policy framework, aiming at
"structural stability" i.e. "sustainable economic development,
democracy and respect for human rights, viable political
structures, healthy social and environmental conditions, with the
capacity to manage change without resort to violence."
<p>
The paper therefore concludes that:
<ul>
<li>"The approach to the economic, political and social development
of developing countries should be more holistic than is the case
until now." The EU has a need for strategic planning policies, set
out in global policy frameworks that need to be developed. These
frameworks need to describe vulnerabilities and set out the
linkages between conflict prevention, development planning,
rehabilitation, relief and disaster preparedness for each country
and region.
<li>More attention should be paid on coordination, between donors
as well as internally between different Commission services.
Internal EU coordination could be improved by the creation of
country Task Forces, consisting of officials from departments
dealing with relief, rehabilitation, development and political
relations.
<li>Political analysis capacity must be enhanced. The EU
Delegations in-country will play a more important role in this
respect. "Country-specific relief impact studies" and
"rehabilitation planning strategies"  must be developed, and
"disaster preparedness programmes should be given increased
prominence."
</ul>
<p>
<h3>NGO comments</h3>

The Commission discussion document is one of many papers recently
published on this issue. NGOs welcome the document as it is a
genuine effort to translate the insights from the debate into
workable recommendations for the EU organisational lay-out. At the
same time, the Commission's text needs strengthening on several
points, as was pointed out by the NGOs who participated in the 23
February meeting. 
<p>
Most importantly, the text presented in February made little
reference to the importance of the societies the EU aid is meant to
assist. There is no clear commitment to investing in civil society
in those countries. While mention is made of vulnerabilities, the
document takes no account of the capacities that are available in
the countries concerned. This makes the document too theoretical,
as it lacks direction from the people that are most closely
affected by EU policies. If the Union is able to change its
management culture in such a way that its aid policies are defined
to a large degree by the people it strives to  aid, then that would
be a major step forward. There should be much clearer reference to
the pivotal role played by local organisations.
<p>
In this context, it needs to be said that the first draft did not
take account of the gender issues: in trying to develop new models,
the document missed out on the importance of analysing the
structures that make certain groups more vulnerable, or place
others in key positions. Assistance is fundamentally a dialogue
with people. International aid often ignores existing coping
mechanisms and structures, forgetting the human aspect of
development.
<p>
Thirdly, in defining humanitarian aid as "saving lives" rather than
"saving lives and livelihoods", and by insisting on the limited
duration of rehabilitation efforts, the Commission keeps the
separation between the two fields of activity alive. NGOs pointed
out that international donors should define their humanitarian aid
efforts in such a way that they focus on development from the
start: Programming relief for development. In other words, making
development principles an integral part - the aim - of relief and
rehabilitation.
<p>
<h3>Conflict Prevention</h3>
<p>
The document makes reference to the need for greater efforts in the
field of conflict prevention. The Commission is presently defining
its strategy towards the prevention of conflicts in Africa as well.
The approach the Commission is advocating is that, without having
to change financial arrangements or the division of competencies,
the EU could achieve much more than at present, simply by targeting
its existing assistance programmes more firmly towards the
"structural stability" of countries.
<p>
According to the Commission, the basic condition for such "targeted
assistance" is the enhancement of political analysis of root causes
of conflict. At present, the EU's capacity to fully assess the
power relations, historic backgrounds and the existence of
effective mechanisms for peaceful conciliation of different
interests are not sufficient. It is also argued that the EU needs
to focus more on closing the gap between early warning and
preventive action.
<p>
APRODEV is of the opinion that, at present, in the debate about
conflict prevention too little attention is paid to the role of
local civil society and for the bottom-up approaches to conflict
management and conflict prevention. The top-down approach, with its
stress on international military and diplomatic intervention is
necessary, but overlooks the contribution that small-scale, grass-
roots organisation can have on the growth of a climate of peace,
respect for human rights and non-violent ways of dealing with
conflict.
<p>
Furthermore, the EU has to realise the delicacy of being involved
in conflict prevention. It could be argued that many of the
conflicts in Africa today, are at least partly due to policies
promoted and followed by EU Member States. EU trade policies,
WB/IMF/EU Structural Adjustment programmes and the foreign policies
of the individual member states play a role that cannot be over-
emphasised. This is particularly relevant when mention is made of
increasing the EU's capacity to analyse the root causes of
conflict. The crucial question is who will do this analysis and
with what theoretical reference frame, as the reference frame of
the researcher largely determines the result of the research.
Also, there is the confusion about the term "Conflict Prevention".
In reality it is the prevention of violent conflict that is our
concern. Conflict is a normal aspect of any society. The issue is
to find ways and means of dealing with them in a non-violent way:
"conflict transformation" or "conflict management".
<p>
<center><a href="index.html">APRODEV Home Page</a> / <a href="../euforic/index_uf.htm">La page EUFORIC / <a href="../euforic/index_uf.htm">EUFORIC Home Page</a>
</center>
<p>
<hr>
