<html><head><title>NI Issue 267 - Hunger: The Facts</title><!!keys: New Internationalist+hunger></head><body><img width=100 height=88 src="ni_pix/nilogo.gif"><br><i>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="NIinfo.html">  New Internationalist</a></i><hr><center><h1>HUNGER - THE FACTS </h1><p>
<h5>(A SAMPLE OF FACTS FROM THE VISUAL CENTRE SPREAD OF THE MAGAZINE)</h5><p>
<font size=+1><i>The world produces more than enough food to feed its entire
population. Yet an estimated 35,000 people die of hunger each
day in the Majority World. The <b>NI </b>examines the gap between the
hungry and the greedy.</i></font></center><hr><p><h3>EATING MONEY</h3>

Richer countries can choose: they have ample access to food and
are less dependent on agriculture. The US is the world's second
largest producer of cereals and meat and comes third in fruit
and vegetable production - yet agriculture accounts for only
2.3% of its GDP. European Union countries import twice as many
agricultural products from the Majority World as they export to
them.1 Poorer countries have little or no choice (see map).<p><ul><ul>SHARE OF AGRICULTURE IN GROSS DOMESTIC PRODUCT<font size=-2>[2]</font><p></ul></ul>
<img width=453  height=264 src="ni_pix/nimap267.gif"><h3>THE SCALE OF IT</h3>

The number of hungry people has actually fallen in recent years,
despite overall population increases - though the numbers in
Africa and Latin America have increased. But nearly 800 million
people still face persistent, everyday hunger. Much larger
numbers suffer from malnutrition and seasonal or temporary
hunger. <p><ul><ul>NUMBER OF UNDERNOURISHED PEOPLE IN MILLIONS<font size=-2>[3]</font>
<p><pre>
		1970            1990

Asia		762		540

Africa	 	94		175

Latin America	53		58 

Middle East	32		12

Total		941		785</pre></ul></ul><p><h3>FEAST AND FAMINE</h3>

The rich world has a glut of excess food and obese citizens: in
the US about a third of the population is overweight - $33
billion is spent each year in attempts to lose weight. In the
poor world millions subsist on an amount of food that is simply
inadequate for good health. An estimated 190 million children
under the age of five are chronically malnourished.<font size=-2>[4]</font><p><pre><ul><ul><b>The feast</b>
Countries with highest daily supply of calories per head as % of requirements* 1988-90 
Ireland			157

Greece			151

Belgium 		149

Bulgaria 		148

France 			143

Spain			141

Italy			139

United States		138

Hungary 		137

Singapore		136

_________

Aotearoa/New Zealand 	131

United Kingdom		130

South Africa		128

Australia		124<p><b>The famine</b>
Countries with lowest daily supply of calories per head as % of requirements* 1988-90

Afghanistan 		72

Chad			73

Ethiopia		73

Mozambique		77

Angola			80

Somalia			81

Central African Rep	82

Rwanda			82

Sierra Leone		83

Burundi			84

Bolivia			84</pre></ul></ul><p>
Shocking as they may be, these figures are only averages. There
are hungry people in rich countries and those who can afford
more than they need in poorer ones which makes the contrast
between greed and need even more dramatic<p>
<i>*An adequate adult calorie intake is between 2,350 and 2,600
calories per day, depending on climate and kinds of work
performed.</i><p><center><img width=250  height=235 src="ni_pix/nicartoon267.gif"></center><p>
<hr><font size=-1>Sources: 1 Bertrand Delpeuch, Seed and Surplus, CIIR/Farmers
Link, London 1994. 2 The World Bank, World Development Report
1993. 3 Bread for the World Institute, Hunger 1995: Causes of
Hunger, Silver Spring, 1994. 4 UNICEF, State of the World's
Children 1995. </font><p><i>Every month the centre spread of the <b>New Internationalist
</b>collects together the key facts about the subject of the month.</i>
