<html><head><title>British ODA - Aid for the former Yugoslavia</title><!!keys: ODA></head><body><img src="oda_pix/oda_logo.gif"><br><i>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="oda_info.html">  Overseas Development Administration</a></i><hr><center><h2>UK BILATERAL HUMANITARIAN AID FOR THE FORMER YUGOSLAVIA</h2></center><h3>GENERAL</h3>Britain is the third largest donor of humanitarian aid to the former Yugoslavia and through the Overseas Development Administration (ODA) has contributed over £271 million so far in aid:  £136 million bilaterally and £135 million through the European Community (EC).  In addition, the RAF has taken part in the currently discontinued Sarajevo airlift and the Foreign and Commonwealth Office and Ministry of Defence contributions to the UN Protection Force (UNPROFOR) amount to £280 million.<p> Need is greatest in central Bosnia, where most of the fighting has taken place and around 2.7 million people are at risk.  The British bilateral aid programme aims to alleviate some of this suffering, by getting food and medical relief into the country and assisting with infrastructure and utilities works.<p>The ODA's bilateral aid consists of:<p><h3>DISTRIBUTION OF RELIEF</h3>An ODA fleet of over 30 British trucks, plus drivers and support staff, is operating as the largest contributor to the UNHCR road delivery operation, running convoys to Sarajevo and other areas, when possible.  The fleet plays a vital role in the delivery of relief supplies, particularly during suspensions of the airlift. Working from bases in Zagreb, Zenica and Metkovic, the ODA civilian drivers have braved shelling and gunfire to get aid through to central Bosnia and UN-protected areas.  So far over 2,060 ODA convoys have delivered over 152,000 tonnes of supplies. The ODA also manages a vehicle workshop at Metkovic for UNHCR which is one of the main centres for distribution operations to central Bosnia, including Sarajevo.<p>The ODA operated an Ilyushin-76 aircraft from Ancona in Italy as part of the UNHCR airlift to Sarajevo.  It delivered over 15,000 tonnes in over 450 flights.<p><h3>POWER</h3>The ODA is undertaking a £13.0 million programme to restore basic electricity supplies in central Bosnia.  ODA engineers have made vital repairs to power stations and transmission lines and maintained coal output to fire the power stations to provide electricity for local communities.  Maintaining power supplies has been made difficult by fighting and deliberate blocking of essential spare parts for repair work.<p><h3>DIRECT SUPPLIES</h3>The ODA has provided supplies such as winter stoves for the RedÊCross, sleeping bags, Land-Rovers - including armoured LandRovers for Sarajevo - and warehouse equipment.<p> High protein biscuits worth more than £6 million have been donated to the World Food Programme's supplementary feeding plan which targets particularly vulnerable groups such as small children, pregnant women and the elderly.<p><h3>EXPERTS AND TECHNICIANS</h3>Nearly £4 million has been spent on experts for UNHCR including:<ul><li>radio operators, convoy fitters, telecommunications experts and logisticians working for UNHCR throughout Bosnia and Croatia;<li>interpreters for the relief experts and road convoys.</ul><h3>EMERGENCY ENGINEERING UNIT (EEU)</h3>Originally part of the European Union Task Force, the EEU has been an independent programme since August 1993 and employs 46 engineers, technicians and support staff.  The unit has completed over 500 infrastructure and public utilities repair projects, from district heating systems and bridge repairs, to vehicle maintenance, refuse collection services and even stray dog catching.<p><h3>SARAJEVO GAS PROJECT</h3>War damage to gas pipes and home-made heating installations in Sarajevo have resulted in over 60,000 homes that are vulnerable to gas explosions.  The ODA has a team of gas engineers with specialist equipment repairing the system and training local staff.<p><h3>MEDICAL SUPPLIES AND HEALTH CARE</h3>The ODA is the largest donor in the medical sector, contributing £15 million in medical aid, including over £7 million in medical supplies, £3 million in experts and £3 million in grants to medical NGOs. Among the experts have been trauma specialists, brain surgeons, plastic surgeons, pediatricians, nurses, hospital engineers and logisticians.  For the rehabilitation of Sarajevo's health service and two main hospitals, the ODA funded 'Operation Phoenix', a health programme that provided visiting teams of up to 15 specialists at a time for emergency work and in areas like reconstructive plastic surgery, training and health service management.<p>The ODA has also funded the emergency evacuation of urgent medical cases.  ODA's substantial programme of medical aid within Bosnia remains the priority.  The ODA also gives assistance for local pharmaceutical production and packaging.<p>  <h3>WINTER SHELTER</h3>Winter shelter has been provided in central Bosnia for up to 20,000 refugees at a cost of £2.5 million.  An ODA team identified where help could best be provided and the vitally needed shelter and sanitation facilities were constructed in and around Zenica.  In addition ODA is funding NGOs such as ScottishÊEuropean Aid who are providing roofing tiles to assist with the repair of damaged homes.<p><h3>NGO PROJECTS</h3>The ODA sponsors the work of many non-governmental organisations like Oxfam, Save the Children and Marie Stopes International in social programmes such as trauma counselling, winter clothes distribution and family tracing.  Smaller specialist agencies, like War Child and Feed the Children, are also funded to run projects such as mobile bakeries and orphanage repairs.<p><h3>MACEDONIA</h3>£4 million has been spent on emergency assistance to Macedonia of which about £1.7 million has been provided for medical supplies urgently needed by the Ministry of Health.  For example, existing stocks of insulin were virtually exhausted in the Republic.<p><h3>AIRDROPS</h3>£600,000 for food supplies as the UK's contribution to the USAF airdrop operation.<p>  <h3>SUPPORT FOR EUROPEAN UNION INITIATIVES</h3>The ODA has also organised and supported several EU initiatives:<ul><li>   taking the lead in establishing and heading the EU Task        Force;<li>	providing thirteen British EU task force engineers to repair vital public utilities, including water supplies, district heating and sanitation in central Bosnia;  <li>	funding the Dame Warburton investigation into rape and other abuses against women. The ODA is the major EU contributor to the women's support groups and counselling programme run by Marie Stopes International (MSI), and the reproductive health care programme implemented by WHO and MSI;<li>	repairing a major bridge between the east and west sides of Mostar;<li>	providing specialists to the European Union Administration of Mostar to repair infrastructure;<li>	providing financial and technical assistance for the WEU policing initiative in Mostar.</ul><p><h3>RECONSTRUCTION</h3>In March 1994, a joint UK/US mission of 20 experts carried out an assessment of Sarajevo's infrastructure and social services. Full reconstruction will depend firstly on a sustained peace and then substantial financial support from the international community. <p>The ODA committed £5 million to the rehabilitation of several sectors identified as priorities by the mission.  These include: the health service, electrical power, gas supplies, central heating, hygiene and waste disposal, public transportation and rail transport.<p><h3>REFUGEE CAMP - TUZLA</h3>The ODA has reacted swiftly to the current crisis in Tuzla, where the refugees from Srebrenica have gathered.  We have made available to UNHCR all our resources and manpower currently in the former Yugoslavia, to be used as they think best.<p>We have also contributed over £300,000 in grants towards Oxfam's and the British Red Cross' emergency relief programmes in the Tuzla refugee camp.<p><h3>AID STATISTICS</h3>Bilateral allocations consist of:<p><pre>Cash Grants to UN Organisations	             	         £34.50mCash Grant to IOM for refugee transport- for up to 1000 detainees and families			 £ 0.50mWinter Shelter - building rehabilitation                 £ 2.50mto accomodate 20,000 peoplePower supplies - maintaining coal production and         £13.00m repairing power stations						Direct supplies - vehicles, stores,                      £ 1.50msleeping bags, etc							Experts - logisticians, radio operators,                 £ 6.0mmanagers, etc - includes satellite communicationscostsSarajevo Airlift                                         £ 3.50mRoad convoys - 50 plus trucks and support                £27.50mstaff - includes warehouse operationsMedical assistance - supplies, doctors and               £19.60memergency and family evacuations - includesemergency aid to Macedonia			     						Grants to non-governmental organisations                 £ 9.90m-  Red Cross, Oxfam, etc						Agricultural support - seeds for central                  £ 0.60m Bosnia									Contribution to US air drops - 364,000 meals,ration packs, high nutrition biscuits, etc		 £ 0.60mEU initiatives - EU task force engineers,                £ 2.70mWarburton mission, rape and women's supportcounselling, EU administration of Mostar, etc	UK/US Initiative in Sarajevo                             £ 5.50mEmergency Engineering Unit - Central Bosnia              £ 8.10m						</pre>(Also contributed £6.5m worth of high nutrition biscuits not included in these figures because donated from MAFF surplus stock)<p>TOTAL BILATERAL ASSISTANCE - 					£136.00m<br>							                                                    UK SHARE OF EU AID - 					 	     £135.00m<p><h3>TOTAL UK ASSISTANCE  -                		    £271.00m</h3><hr>©Copyright: ODA, July 1995<hr><a href="index.html"><img src="oda_pix/oda_logo2.gif"> ODA Home Page</a> <hr></body></html>					                                        
