<!--This file created 5/9/96 3:21 pm by Claris Home Page version 1.0b1--><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE>Kurds use crisis to demand more from United States</TITLE>   <X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=89 BOTTOM=478 LEFT=11 RIGHT=535></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><P><IMG SRC="ot_pix/ot_logo.gif" WIDTH=165 HEIGHT=59X-SAS-UseImageWidth X-SAS-UseImageHeight ALIGN=bottom><IMGSRC="ot_pix/ot_line.gif" WIDTH=581 HEIGHT=5 X-SAS-UseImageWidthX-SAS-UseImageHeight ALIGN=bottom></P><H1>Kurds use crisis to demand more from United States</H1><P>By JOHN WEST</P><P>LONDON, September 5 - The United States may be involved in a tensestand-off with Saddam Hussein once again but for the two Kurdishfactions whose feuding sparked the conflict there is a definiteupside - the world is once more looking at Kurdistan.</P><P>This is the picture that has emerged from two live Internetdiscussions run by OutThere news service with officials from thePatriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) and the Kurdistan Democratic Party(KDP) over the last two days. </P><P>President Bill Clinton's decision to launch cruise missile attacksand extend a "no-fly zone" in the south of Iraq has enraged largeparts of the Arab world and made many of Washington's partners suchas France and Russia uncomfortable.</P><P>But among both Iraqi Kurdish parties, it has encouraged calls formore intervention. Despite their feuding, both parties have much thesame demands: they want the West, which gave them limited autonomyfrom the Baghdad government in 1991 by establishing a no-fly zoneover their mountainous area of northern Iraq, to go further and takeaction to ensure that the Kurds are free of Saddam Hussein forever.</P><P>"We are not disturbed at all by what happened," said<A HREF="kdp.html">Burhan Jaf of the KDP</A>, the party whichenlisted Saddam Hussein's help to oust the rival PUK from the city ofArbil on Saturday and so sparked this week's American strikes. "Wecontributed to bringing the Kurdish situation to the world again," hesaid. "The KDP felt that the Iranian threat has been neglected by ourWestern allies, and we are tired of regional intervention in ouraffairs, and yet there is no Western response to that."</P><P>For <A HREF="puk.html">Sarbast Hussain of the PUK</A>, similarly,a week at the top of the world's foreign affairs agenda was just thestart. Asked by Internet user Starr Baroth if he agreed withClinton's strikes, he replied: "As one step a a series of steps, yes.But I believe there are other measures to follow... Kurdistan needsdefence weapons against tanks and armoured vehicles, not necessarilyWestern personnel, but hardware, or a more determined signal toSaddam - such as expanding the no-fly zone further south, lifting thesanctions against the Kurdish people to allow them to import thetools that let them rebuild the infrastructure in the country."</P><P>Both sides said they were keen to take part in U.S.-sponsoredtalks, announced by State Department officials on Tuesday. They hadjust started to meet in the U.S. embassy in London last week when theoffensive by the KDP and the Iraqi army on Arbil happened.</P><P>Burhan Jaf said that the rival Kurdish parties agreed on manypolitical issues. Asked whether he supported Hussain's call for theno-fly zone to be extended south to the 34th parallel and for the UNsanctions on Iraq to be lifted for the Kurds, he said: "Yes, I agree.I would add that we agree on many points, it's just unfortunate thatwe fight each other."</P><P>During two hours of discussions on the Internet, the officialsalso faced close questioning by users from Turkey, the United Statesand elsewhere on the relations of their two parties with Iran and theanti-Turkish Kurdistan Worker's Party (PKK), and their own disputesover money and power-sharing arrangements.</P><P>For fuller details, please see our edited transcripts of thediscussion with <A HREF="puk.html">Sarbast Hussein</A> and<A HREF="kdp.html">Burhan Jaf.</A></P><P><B><HR></B></P><P ALIGN=CENTER>Reporting by John West. Production by Paul Eedle.</P><P ALIGN=CENTER>About <A HREF="ot_info.html">OutThere.</A></P><P ALIGN=CENTER>Please<A HREF="mailto:75714.1042@compuserve.com, johnwest@logos.cy.net">tellus what you think</A> of OutThere. What issues and events would youlike us to cover?</P><P><FONT SIZE=4><HR><IMG SRC="ot_pix/arrow.gif" WIDTH=91 HEIGHT=19X-SAS-UseImageWidth X-SAS-UseImageHeightALIGN=left></FONT><A HREF="http://www.oneworld.org/news/index.html">Back</A>to OneWorld News Service</P><P>&nbsp;</P></BODY></HTML>
