<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT17-B14-95</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA007-000070-B002-133</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.ecdpm.org:80/acpsec/address.htm 193.128.6.150 19970222020131 text/html 13559
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Sat, 22 Feb 1997 02:01:15 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.5
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Fri, 10 Jan 1997 15:00:20 GMT
Content-length: 13384
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Address by Mr. Carl B. Greenidge</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<pre>

</pre><center><A HREF="index.html"><img src="images/acp.jpg"></A></center>
<P>

<CENTER><H3>Address by Mr. Carl B. Greenidge<BR>
Deputy Secretary General of the ACP Group<BR>
at the <A HREF="../liaison/ln17e.htm">1996 General Assembly for European NGOs</A><BR>
Brussels, 18-19 April 1996</H3></CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
Distinguished Guests,
<P>
President Agostinho Jardin Gonzales,
<P>
Honourable Commissioner,
<P>
Ladies and Gentlemen,
<P>
It is a profound honour for me to have the opportunity to address
members of this 22nd General Assembly of the Liaison Committee
of Development NGOs to the E.U. It is also a great pleasure for
me to be able to start by congratulating this Forum for the continuing
interest it and its constituents have shown in the evolution of
ACP-EU relations over the years and in the assiduous and tenacious
manner in which it has worked on this issue and collaborated in
the struggle to negotiate and implement a better and more effective
Convention of Lome.
<P>
The work of NGOs is especially important and welcome in a world
which could be aptly portrayed by Albert Camus' observation that
&quot;too many people have decided to do without generosity in
order to practice charity&quot;. How fitting that quip is in the
world of development aid today.
<P>
Being specially appreciative of the work of the NGOs I am heartened,
although not surprised, to find that the programme for the meeting
includes a Workshop on the Future of the Lome Convention. That
debate is one of many being conducted among and between the Lome
partners. Some of these debates also concern the IGC which will
set the scene for much of Europe's future policies.
<P>
In this regard, I wish to commend the Liaison Committee of European
NGOs for the analysis and recommendations conveyed in the Position
Paper which it presented to the Reflection Group.
<P>
Our own work on the Future of Lome in this area is at a very preliminary
stage but several factors can already command a general consensus.
<P>
The Convention, in spite of its weaknesses, has been of great
benefit to ACP States. They would have been considerably worse
off without it. The financial transfers  and Commodity Protocols
constitute the most obvious testimonies to this assertion.
<P>
In response to a number of changing trends within Europe and elsewhere,
some elements of the Convention will have to be modified after
the year 2000. The Group recognises this and is prepared to contribute
to helping to fashion and implement pertinent modifications which
will help to keep the Convention &quot;alive&quot;.
<P>
Having said that, it also needs to be observed that the ACP Group
is not of the view that the Convention has to be radically re-written
or reconceived. Since there have been assessments of implementation
and constraints to implementation the future Agreement should
adequately reflect these as should the workings of the Institutions
and Organs of the Convention.
<P>
Liberalisation and globalization per se need to be supported by
resources to ACP countries because without it those States with
inadequate infrastructure, low educational levels, inappropriate
technology and limited managerial capacity will find themselves
increasingly marginalised. Poor countries attempting to cope with
liberalised market conditions need to be supported with adequate
levels of aid, technical assistance, improved market access and
debt relief.
<P>
The tendency to declining levels of official aid flows runs contrary
to this imperative. Coherence between aid policy and liberalisation
conditionalities is necessary if inequalities are not to be a
by-product of policies.
<P>
The need for additional aid for those countries such as net food
importers, which are likely to be losers as a result of the Uruguay
Round was recognised in the final report of the GATT. However,
the proposed modality for addressing the problem is far from satisfactory.
One cannot help feeling in this context that Bagehot was right
when he observed that, &quot;poverty is an anomaly to rich people.
It is very difficult to make out why people who want dinner don't
ring the bell&quot;.
<P>
The priorities of the ACP, the  like international trends, will
be changing too. In the light of African experiences since the
1980s there is a growing pre-occupation with food security and
political stability. Mr Chairman, the policies of some EU States
and some of the policies embraced by the EU as members of some
multi-lateral financial institutions have contributed to both
of the foregoing problems.
<P>
And yet in other spheres and at the Community level there has
been a commitment to food security and political stability in
ACP States. There is, in other words, a lack of coherence in some
policies. It is necessary to ensure that development policies
are not always require to give way to strategic and foreign policy
considerations as well as defence industry needs.
<P>
Mr Chairman, the position paper to which I have already made reference
dealt quite appropriately with the problem of human rights and
democracy. I would only wish to endorse the need for the Lome
partners to consider and agree on clear criteria concerning breaches
and consistent rules for tackling those countries infringing the
accepted standards. The rules should seek not merely to penalise
States but to facilitate movement along the broad and complicated,
spectrum of practices representing acceptable behaviour.
<P>
It has been said that &quot;creditors have better memories than
debtors&quot;. When we look at the debate on external indebtedness
it is hard not to conclude that this is the main reason for international
failure to resolve the problem of indebtedness of least developed
countries. In this regard, it is instructive to juxtapose the
EU treatment of debt during the course of the recent Mid-Term
Review of the Lome Convention alongside the plight of ACP debtors
as portrayed by the IBRD/IMF. In the course of the latter's analysis
of debtors they identified 20 States which have unsustainable
or near unsustainable debt burdens. Of those 20 countries classified
as heavily indebted poor countries with such burdens only 2 were
non-ACP.  18 of the 20 countries with unsustainable or nearly
unsustainable debt burdens were ACP States.
<P>
This, I might add, should be considered against a background in
which Africa alone undertook some 8,000 rescheduling between 1980
and 1992.
<P>
Mr Chairman, I believe it was William Blake who contended that,
&quot;one law for the lion and the ox is oppression&quot;. The
weak or specially disadvantaged need, in other words, appropriate
programmes, even in the case of debt.
<P>
Mr Chairman, Ladies and Gentlemen, the ACP Group recognises the
significance of two related factors in the process of development,
namely the import of investment in trade and growth and the imperative
of competitiveness in international markets. Some ACP countries
have been able to identify and exploit  niche markets and new
product lines thereby expanding their share of trade with the
E.U. This success has enabled some ACP countries to embark on
the diversification of their economies.
<P>
That economic diversification depends on further investment if
it is to be sustainable. If investment in many of our countries
is to be expanded significantly and rapidly foreign, savings will
need to be attracted so as to supplement domestic savings. However,
Europe's investment in ACP has tended to be problematic because
it is generally :
<P>
 i) very narrowly concentrated by country;
<P>
 ii) and by sector and in this regard usually focuses on the supply
of raw materials such a soil; and is
<P>
 iii) not attracted to the production of manufactured and processed
goods especially if they are directed at the EU market.
<P>
This brings us back to the issue of coherence : at one level in
the Convention there is a very wide range of  instruments for
facilitating investment; at the private level there is concentration
of investment, which further accentuates differentiation among
the poor countries. Yet EU policy is supposed to have a poverty
focus.
<P>
At the same time some States are seeking to reclaim aid policies
for national governments. Many national aid policies are increasingly
concerned to channel aid to regions and countries where trade
(meaning export) prospects are greatest and where returns on investment
is most lucrative.
<P>
Again the result is to channel resources to the few areas where
resources are already flowing and to further marginalise those
without.
<P>
It would seem then, Mr Chairman, that these are six of the areas
in which improvements can be effected in EU policies so as to
be of benefit to ACP States.
<P>
We hope that with the support and understanding of the NGOs the
importance of these points can be brought to bear on the EU so
that the necessary changes can be effected.
<P>
Like the famous beer adverstisement, NGOs are in a position &quot;to
reach parts which others cannot reach&quot;. We have had over
the last 20 years dramatic evidence not only of how effective
NGOs can be in both informing and influencing public opinion in
donor countries but in dragging unwilling governments to fashion
and implement policies. The best examples have been in the field
of humanitarian aid and disaster relief.
<P>
That capacity of the NGOs to influence opinion in donor countries
is to date employed in only a limited way to influence opinion
on aid ideology. The potential is there to help stem the tide
of so-called aid fatigue.
<P>
Mr Chairman, latterly the role and significance of NGOs have enjoyed
an enormous boost as a result of new thinking in aid ideology.
The latter recognises the virtue of other partners in civil society
and places great weight on the desirability of NGOs as a channel
for assistance to developing countries. This trend, which almost
constitutes euphoria, is evident if one looks at the financial
resources flowing to NGOs. In recent years NGOs involved in international
emergency relief  received some us $ 8 b. Annually. Through these
NGOs, funds were channeled to some 300 million victims. In 1995
relief agencies bought more than 7,000 vehicles and chartered
over 500 ships and 1,000 aircraft. In 1995, there were an estimated
165 NGOs attempting to operate in Kigali alone. When one realises
just how much political power such resources places in the hands
of a few hundred individuals it is sobering. Few commercial enterprises
have control over such a large quantum of resources.
<P>
Yet, in the words of World Aid, &quot;few business of this size
are run as incoherently&quot;.
<P>
NGOs therefore need to put their houses in order. Chaotic rivalry,
lack of coordination, the absence of enforceable rules and supervision,
all threaten their viability.
<P>
I do not propose to dilate on these problems or pitfalls here
Mr Chairman; many are well-known especially after the dramatic
events surrounding the  case of Rwanda. Suffice it for me to urge
that NGOs seek to bear in mind the following points. I trust that
you will not find these observations presumptious, Mr Chairman,
they are intended to facilitate good organisational relations
:
<P>
 i) NGOs are not substitutes for governments. If conflict with
recipient governments is to be avoided and tensions minimised
there is virtue in recognising a division of labour between NGOs
and governments. That division of labour should be informed by
the fact that governments have a mandate to an electorate or a
constituency other than that of the ngo, in the recipient country;
<P>
 ii) NGO &quot;agendas&quot; should be generally non-political
and politically non-partisan in sensitive situations or those
characterised by conflict so that their activities may be most
effective;
<P>
 iii) NGOs should not try to manage their activities without respecting
some basic principles about organisational management  including
the deployment of  qualified/experienced/appropriate human resources.
If they are to survive  the euphoria phase therefore they should
avoid biting off more than they can chew however tempting the
prospect of more responsibilities and easy resources may be. Be
modest in your ambitions.
<P>
Mr Chairman, Honourable Commissioner, Ladies and Gentlemen, please
allow me in closing to once more express my sincere wishes for
fruitful deliberations during the 22nd General Assembly.
<P>
I thank you.
<P>
<HR>
<h3><a href="index.html">ACP Group / Groupe ACP Home Page</a>
