</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Development Assistance Without Grants</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<H3><CENTER><IMG SRC = "../images/handshke.jpg"></H3>
<H3>Development Assistance Without Grants:<BR>
A radical proposal to counter vested interests<p>
<I>Hans Gert Braun</I></H3>
<H4>Full text of an article from <I>D+C Development and Cooperation<BR>
</I>No. 4, July-August 1994: pages 24 - 25</h4>
<a href="../index_uf.htm">EUFORIC Page</a><br></CENTER>
<hr><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/dse.gif"><br> D+C is published
by the Deutsche Stiftung f&uuml;r Internationale Entwicklung.
Subscriptions and further information are available from: The
Editor, E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, Postfach 10 08 01,
D-60008 Frankfurt, Germany. Tel: +49 69 7501-4366, Fax: +49 69
7501-4855. </H5>
<HR>
<P>
<B>The development aid budget of the Federal Republic of Germany
was to be frozen at the 1993 level of 8.4 billion DM for 1994
and 1995, and now has been cut even further. Many are protesting
this decision, pointing out that the promise was made, and reconfirmed
by Chancellor Kohl at UNCED in Rio, to reach the 0.7 per cent
goal in the near future. For others, the stagnation of German
development assistance is a reason to reevaluate the quality rather
than the quantity of contributions. As a result, they demand greater
effectiveness and efficiency.</B> 
<P>
It is not my intention to reflect on ways to improve the planning,
management, and monitoring of Technical and Financial Cooperation
projects. l want to address this topic in a much more radical
way
<P>
<B>1. The grant element</B> 
<P>
All current discussions leave one cornerstone of development cooperation
untouched: The &quot;grant element&quot;. This is almost inevitable,
since the grant element is the development aid component which
the Development Assistance Committee (DAC) of the OECD recognizes
and registers statistically (and not the gross contributions).
All forms of development cooperation that operate successfully
with only small subsidies were in a statistical sense not particularly
attractive, since they did not accelerate the cash outflow, the
&quot;resource transfer&quot;. The Federal Ministry for Economic
Cooperation defines grant element as &quot;. . . the difference
between outright subsidy and transactions at market terms (assuming
a market interest rate of 10%). In the case of a nonrepayable
loan the &quot;grant element&quot; is 100% per cent; a 40year
loan bearing an interest rate of 0.75% per cent and including
a 10year grace period, has a grant element of 80.86% per cent;
a loan at 2% per cent interest and 30 year maturity with a 10year
grace period has a grant element of 66.14% per cent.&quot;
<P>
The average grant element of German development cooperation in
1990 amounted to 85.9% per cent. The DAC average is 86 per cent.
The term &quot;grant element&quot; infers that at the respective
percentage levels, development cooperation funds have the character
of donations. The justification for these donations is their alleged
positive impact on development.
<P>
The obvious questions are:
<UL>
<LI>Would it be possible to achieve a positive impact on development
with a substantially smaller grant element? Or:
<LI>Could a reduction of the grant element possibly have a greater
impact on development at the same development cooperation funding
level?
</UL>

<P>
<B>2. Revolving funds</B> 
<P>
Revolving funds do not provide grants but guarantee that (at the
very least) their capital is preserved. Consequently, they use
their capital only to make loans, or to invest it in shares. Since
the loans are repaid, and the stocks and bonds earn dividends
and interest, and are sold when necessary, the fund principal
is preserved and fund management expenses are covered. The IFC
(International Finance Corporation of the World Bank group) the
DEG (German Investment and Development Corporation), and other
similar institutes are such revolving funds (in the abstract sense).
They provide financing according to market principles. Therefore,
they must consider profitability; their fund capital is preserved,
and it revolves.
<P>
Since they operate according to private industry practices, the
grant element of their contributions is zero, or close to zero.
It is not completely zero because their profit margin does not
come close to capital market interest levels in Germany and the
OECD countries. Insofar, it may be argued that their promotion
includes a 35% per cent grant element. But even that is still
far below the grant element percentage of Financial (FC) and Technical
Cooperation (TC).
<P>
At this point, the argument may be made that TC and FC projects
frequently still have enough problems despite their large grant
element and would not stand a chance without their high donations.
Consequently, these projects could not be successful without a
grant element. However, this is the weakest point of the argument.
<P>
It is undisputed that both IFC and DEG have a positive impact
on development. The DEG came to this conclusion after a comprehensive
evaluation of its portfolio. The results of its evaluation were
made public. In its publication, the DEG demonstrates that its
promotion of private industry helps make private enterprise profitable
and therefore viable in the long term; private enterprise provides
employment and thereby creates income; its foreign exchange balance
is positive; it imports technological and managerial knowhow;
it diversifies the economic structure of the specific country,
and contributes to an improvement of the infrastructure. In addition,
it voluntarily though not necessarily unselfishly provides important
social services for its employees and thus functions as a model
for private industry in the respective countries. All this is
accomplished with an (almost) zero grant element.
<P>
Would this not suggest that German and international development
cooperation should shift much more heavily toward this form of
development assistance ,toward the instrument of &quot;revolving
funds&quot;? Why does the Federal Government continue to implement
TC and FC measures which cannot be &quot;successful&quot; without
a large grant element? Is it a fact that projects with a large
grant element have a greater proven and measurable effect on development
than those which are financed without grants? The author is not
aware of any such evidence.
<P>
Even if this were the case, would it not be wiser for the Federal
Republic and other &quot;donors&quot;, particularly in times of
tight budgets (but also in other times) to concentrate on instruments
that can operate without grant elements on a constantly revolving
basis? After all, &quot;to revolve&quot; means that the same amount
of money can positively affect development not just once, but
many times.
<P>
Another important aspect should not be overlooked: Outright as
well as partial grants have been known to very rapidly lead to
wanton use of scarce resources, to state consumption and unproductive
investments, to corruption and mismanagement and finally to indebtedness.
Market conditions, on the other hand, have a healthy disciplinary
effect.
<P>
<B>3. Guarantee Funds</B> 
<P>
The &quot;revolving&quot; concept can be further enhanced or optimized
if the fund's capital is not revolved, but used exclusively as
collateral to guarantee the loans of commercial banks.
<P>
The private Swiss foundation FUNDES (Foundation for Sustainable
Development in Latin America) is based on this concept. It has
established joint ventures with local FUNDES foundations in nine
Latin American countries. Its target group are small enterprises
with up to 50 employees, which do not have access to commercial
credits because of their lack of collateral. The FUNDES guarantee,
which is issued by the local foundation after it has evaluated
the project, is fully accepted as collateral by the local banks.
FUNDES foundations can issue guarantees up to a quintuple of their
capital. To ensure that these guarantees are not called, the FUNDES
foundations also provide management consulting services for their
clientele.
<P>
In 1992, 1120 small entrepreneurs obtained commercial loans with
the help of FUNDES guarantees. The credit volume was 1.6 million
US $; the average loan amount was US $10,000. FUNDES (Switzerland)
as well as the national foundations are funded with contributions
from private industry in Europe and Latin America. The guarantee
business itself is self sustaining: Actual defaults are very low
0.8% per cent. These defaults as well as current operating expenses
for fund management are offset by income from guarantee fees.
Of course, the guarantee capital also earns investment interest.
<P>
From a development standpoint, the following aspects are important:
<UL>
<LI>The grant element is practically zero; guarantees are &quot;fully
paid for&quot; by the fees charged.
<LI>The guarantee fund instrument has the important advantage
that it strengthens the local financial sector without disturbing
it. There is no intervention in the local process of savings formation
and loan disbursements.
</UL>

<P>
<B>4. Fund capitalization sets limits</B> 
<P>
The development of the FUNDES foundations demonstrates that the
expansion potential of this instrument whose development successes
need not be enumerated is limited by only one factor: The capitalization
of the guarantee funds. The same holds true for the IFC and DEG.
Therefore it is not at all surprising that the IFC, which increased
its loan volume in the last ten years from about 200 million US$
to 2 billion US$ and had great difficulty of late in raising additional
capital, now openly considers increasing it through higher investment
profits.
<P>
<B>Worker in a DEG supported company producing safety valves in
Bombay, India</B> 
<P>
It would also not come as a surprise if the DEG, whose business
plan called for an increase of its guarantee volume from about
300 million DM to approximately 1 billion DM in the 1990s and
which has been stagnating for years at a guarantee level of about
350 million DM due to capital shortages, would follow the IFC
example to replenish its capital. It would not be surprising at
all, but it certainly would be a big mistake for German development
policy, since the quality of development promotion would definitely
suffer at the IFC as well as the DEG.
<P>
Bundestag member Ingrid Walz has proposed that governments of
developing countries be allowed to make debt service payments
in their own currency, rather than have their debts forgiven,
and to use these counterpart funds to establish venture capital
funds denominated in the local currency. These funds could then
sponsor small entrepreneurs who only need local financing anyhow
<P>
This proposal concurs with the concepts of this article. Such
counterpart funds could function either as revolving or as guarantee
funds. All the above mentioned institutions FUNDES, IFC, and DEG
could easily manage such counterpart funds to promote the private
economy
<P>
5. <B>Restructuring of development cooperation </B>
<P>
Why is there no radical restructuring of development cooperation
to make increased use of revolving and guarantee funds? Why is
the totally inadequate 0.7 per cent goal conjured up again and
again? Why is more and more economic cooperation demanded, when
the main problem of present development assistance is after all,
to find worthy objects, promising projects?
<P>
Most likely, opponents will be quick to argue that private promotion
through revolving and guarantee funds will soon reach the limits
of its absorption capacity also, and that DEG, IFC, and FUNDES
will very soon encounter &quot;marketing problems&quot;. The response
is: Let's try it. Contrary to TC projects, which have a grant
element of 100 per cent such an experiment would not cost anything;
the principal, as has been shown, will be preserved. What are
the real reasons for the opposition to a radical restructuring
of development assistance in the direction of capital preservation?
The first reason is the 0.7 per cent goal and the concept of resource
transfer The second reason is the development assistance administration
establishment a system of entrenched turfs. Every budget director
in the government administration jealously guards his &quot;pot&quot;.
Every &quot;implementation organization&quot; fights for its share
of the development budget. The consulting industry has an ever
watchful eye on the vestibules of political decision making, on
party councils, and on parliamentary committees to find out whether
there is even the slightest mention of structural changes and
always demands, through its lobbyists, that the 0.7% per cent
goal be reached sooner, rather than later.
<P>
Dr. Hans Gert Braun is Professor for Economics at the University
of Stuttgart and Director and Chief Economic Advisor at the DEG
in Cologne The above article expresses his personal views.
<p>
<HR>
<H6><I>Updated on August 9, 1996<BR>
