<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The End of Technical Cooperation</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<H3><CENTER><IMG SRC = "../images/handshke.jpg"></H3>
<H3>The end of technical cooperation:<BR> Or just a change in concept?<p>
Klaus von Mitzlaff and Andrea Vermehren</H3>

<H4>Full text of an article from <I>D+C Development and Cooperation
<BR>
</I>No. 3, May-June 1994: pages 23 - 25</h4>
<a href="../index_uf.htm">EUFORIC Page</a><br></CENTER>

<hr><IMG align=left SRC = "../images/dse.gif"><br> D+C is published
by the Deutsche Stiftung f&uuml;r Internationale Entwicklung.
Subscriptions and further information are available from: The
Editor, E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, Postfach 10 08 01,
D-60008 Frankfurt, Germany. Tel: +49 69 7501-4366, Fax: +49 69
7501-4855. </H5>
<HR>

<P>
Worldwide discussion on the ineffectiveness of Technical Cooperation
(TC) has led to the decision to hold a conference, on the initiative
of the OECD, the World Bank and UNDP, on the subject of &quot;Improving
the Effectiveness of Technical Cooperation in the 90's&quot;.
The conference takes place in June 1994 in Paris. Two staff members
of the German Agency for Technical Cooperation (GTZ) take up the
discussion.
<P>
The three so far most important contributions to the discussion
came from the OECD, UNDP and the World Bank. In response to criticism,
the OECD published its &quot;Principles for effective aid&quot;
in 1992. For UNDP, Elliot Berg took a critical look at TC, particularly
in Africa, in &quot;Rethinking Technical Cooperation&quot;, 1992.
In a wellreceived speech in May 1993 (&quot;Capacity building
the missing link in African development&quot;), Edward Jaycox
of the World Bank urged that, rather than sending out experts,
priority be given to the training of local development planners
and managers.
<P>
<B>An evaluation of TC criticism</B> 
<P>
The criticism of TC is on the whole under | standable in view
of the inadequacy of development aid faced with powerful security,
economic and political interests both in the North and in the
South. The hopes placed in development cooperation, however, were
often unrealistic and exaggerated. The sometimes oversimplified
criticism does not do justice, either to the complexity of problems
facing development support in Africa, or to the diversity of reasons
for failure which would require a more differentiated analysis.
<P>
In Germany, unlike other donor countries, Technical and Financial
Cooperation (FC) not only developed along different lines from
the outset, but also within separate organisations: the German
Agency for Technical Cooperation (GTZ) and the Reconstruction
Loan Corporation (KfW). This meant that TC in Germany was never
subordinate to FC, i.e. an accompanying or preparatory factor,
but was always able to concentrate on 'capacity building' in the
wider sense, that is, on increased efficacy through training and
further training programmes and the establishment and capacitation
of organisations, networks and selfhelp structures.
<P>
Following decolonisation, the new states were lacking in vital
historical, ethnic, economic and institutional requirements for
'nation building'. A broad variety of public services was, therefore,
supposed to improve the legitimacy of the new states in the eyes
of the population. Development Cooperation was used for the setting
up of government facilities whose economic and social coherence
or longterm stability was often insufficiently verified. It thus
shares the responsibility for the structural crisis in the partner
countries and within DC itself.
<P>
During the 80s, the severe worsening of the situation in many
partner countries made it clear that the welfare state concept
was unrealistic, particularly for the poorer countries. Structural
adjustment programmes designed to overcome the crises showed and
show insufficient effect. One consequence of the crisis, augmented
by structural adjustment, was a capacity decrease of the governmental
partners, which led to a rethinking of previously stateoriented
bi- and multilateral DC. In many countries, DC is now confronted
by a situation in which
<UL>
<LI>structural adjustment programmes have sometimes intentionally
weakened the state instead of underpinning its more vital functions;
<LI>at present neither sufficient financing nor the political
strength is available for the implementation of an urgently needed
basic redistribution of political capacities between a competent,
administrative state and a pluralistic array of organisations
for social development, and,
<LI>as long as the above remains unattained, DC serves nothing
more than the extension of an unacceptable situation, rather than
employing its potential for the furtherance of social change.
</UL>

<P>
The above problems apply to a greater or lesser degree to all
developing countries and to the transition states of eastern Europe,
particularly with reference to the participation of the population
in decisionmaking processes.
<P>
<B>Modern TC in changed circumstances</B> 
<P>
In future, it can no longer be the task of TC to ensure the prolongation
of unsustainable structures simply because these are needed at
the time for the securing of public services. Rather it is a question
of fulfilling the (historically and culturally determined) essential
tasks of the state. TC should support governmental partners in
the search for their new role. Where the state sets limits, complementary
nongovernmental structures and organisations must be set up, the
establishment and assistance of which should also be a task for
TC.
<P>
A form of TC with a sociopolitical function as described above
does not indiscriminately transfer a certain model, rather it
looks for adequate solutions together with the partner. It advises
its governmental partners in particular to admit and support giving
more participation and decisionmaking power to nongovernmental
structures. Capacity building, apart from being the training of
political management as favoured by the World Bank and UNDP, is
then the enabling of broad sections of the population to take
part in decisionmaking processes relevant to their own lives and
resources. It is in the balance between governmental and nongovernmental
fields that TC faces its main new challenge.
<P>
The greater the opportunities for a majority of people to participate
in the process of their own development, the more evident it becomes
that TC operates in a context of power and related interests.
This is where the political function of modern TC becomes important
and where it can use its potential in favour of participation,
pluralism and the reduction of poverty. TC as the promotion of
social diversification can only be said to have been successful
once the pluralist network can support itself without outside
aid.
<P>
<B>New concepts within the GTZ</B> 
<P>
New concepts and mechanisms have been developed within the GTZ
according to the perception of conditions and the changed role
of the GTZ as described above. They will be introduced in the
following as possible answers to the deficits of TC. The adaptation
of each to the structures of the society in question forms an
important aspect.
<P>
1. <B>Analysis of the interests of various participants:</B> 
<P>
TC projects are embedded in a multifarious system of development
problems, processes and interests, which necessitates a sensitive
analysis of the interests of various participants as well as the
use of relevant instruments (participant analysis, conflict management).
<P>
2. <B>Assignment of participants' roles:</B> 
<P>
Before beginning a project, the GTZ and the partner establish
which tasks for the attainment of project targets can be taken
on by target groups themselves, by NGOs or by private companies
instead of governmental bodies, and how decentralisation and private
enterprise management can relieve public and parastatal institutions.
<P>
3. <B>Promotion of pluralism on an institutional level:</B> 
<P>
Programmatic concepts are ideal here (rather than isolated projects).
The German side no longer aims to serve all regions and sectors,
but prefers to identify focal points in order to achieve synergetic
effects by working on different levels. 4. <B>Inclusion of NGOs:
</B>An increasingly important element of TC is the inclusion of
qualified NGOs with grassroots legitimisation as project partners.
The cooperation with NGOs from the developing countries as mediators
is at the same time a step towards lessening structural poverty.
<P>
5. <B>Transfer of adapted technology and knowhow:</B> 
<P>
The combination of local and external knowhow can often result
in a creative synthesis knowledge adapted to the problem in question.
A major undertaking for TC is to continue the development and
communication of new, adapted forms of technological development.
<P>
6. <B>Realistic planning through counselling of partners: </B>
<P>
One of the main points of criticism in evaluations is the overambitious
planning resulting in an unrealistic assessment of project targets.
The GTZ has therefore developed a mechanism known as the &quot;open
orientation phase&quot;. Should a partner government's project
application fail to clarify project concept and executing agencies
the GTZ offers a period of planning counselling with partner and
target groups.
<P>
7. <B>Project Cycle Management:</B> 
<P>
The GTZ has broadened participatory planing methods to form an
integral concept known as &quot;Project Cycle Management&quot;
(PCM). This includes the usual participatory, target oriented
project planning, a monitoring and evaluation system for every
project and further adjustable management mechanisms. Of increasing
importance for TC measures are participatory assessment and evaluation
methods (e.g. Rapid Rural Appraisal and Participatory Poverty
Assessment).
<P>
<B>a. Use of local knowledge:</B> 
<P>
Many local professionals nowadays have the necessary qualifications
to find the required solutions to problems themselves. In addition,
they have important knowledge of local institutions and their
interests. The GTZ now employs some 5,000 local staff. For some
time now, it has regularly used local experts in survey and evaluation
phases and trains local consultings in various fields.
<P>
9. <B>Support of key political figures:</B> 
<P>
A central problem of TC in Africa remains the departure of qualified
professionals from key public positions. The need to find a solution
to this problem is of utmost urgency wherever duties cannot be
transferred but the remuneration for the duties in question is
inadequate. This is particularly true of highranking civil servants
in decisionmaking positions. Direct, limited support for individuals
in such positions should be taken into consideration as a temporary
solution.
<P>
10. <B>Use of various TC instruments for appropriate problem solutions:
</B>
<P>
The GTZ supports development processes in almost 100 countries
with various development histories and various solutionfinding
capacities. The role of the experts and their professional profile
has been enlarged. In countries where solutionfinding capabilities
are already relatively high, external experts are needed as specialists
in the transfer and development of knowhow. In countries or situations
with relatively low problem solving capacities, the experts can
also act as agents in social change.
<P>
<B>Summary</B> 
<P>
Capacity building, in the broader sense described in the above,
remains the top priority for TC. In the next few years, competent,
politically sensitive, communicative and enthusiastic international
experts as well as the professional capacities and the experience
of development organisations will remain a necessity wherever
relevant solutions cannot be found in the pages of international
sales catalogues.
<P>
Countries in which the conditions for successful FC private enterprise
structures and acceptable public framework conditions are not
(yet) given, should nevertheless be allowed access to TC. Indeed,
herein lies a major challenge for TC in its sociopolitical role
for the development of pluralism and democracy.
<P>
Solution concepts drafted in the above cannot of course be initiated
immediately and in all situations. The notions and ideals, both
of decisionmakers on both sides and of many project workers, are
still characterised by the principles of the TC of the 70s and
80s. Concepts and mechanisms are for the most part in alignment
with the &quot;DAC Principles for Effective Aid&quot;, some go
beyond that.
<P>
The TC Conference planned for June will have to show whether the
international donor community, including such multilateral organisations
as the World Bank, the United Nations and the European Union,
cannot only agree on the guidelines laid down in the DAC Principles,
but can also pledge themselves to their implementation. In view
of the global shortage of resources for TC, their coordinated
and thus economic use has to be given priority over personal or
national interests. This would be the first serious step towards
a new generation of Technical cooperation. <HR>

<H6><I>Updated on August 13, 1996<BR>
</I>This article is made available on EUFORIC by kind permission
of the publishers - E+Z Entwicklung und Zusammenarbeit, Postfach
10 08 01, D-60008 Frankfurt, Germany. Tel: +49 69 7501-4366, Fax:
+49 69 7501-4855.<BR>
