<HTML>
<HEADER>
<TITLE>The Future of EU-ACP Relations Beyond the Lom&#233; IV Convention</TITLE>
</HEADER>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<center><IMG ALT="Lom&#233; 2000" SRC  = "../images/2000.jpg"></a><p>
<h3>The Future of EU-ACP Relations Beyond the Lom&#233; IV Convention<br>
ECDPM Conference, Maastricht, 12-14 June 1996</h3>
Instruments of Financial and Technical Cooperation:<br>Synthesis of Working Group Discussions
<p><a HREF = "top3_gb.htm">Comment on the Issues Raised Here</a></CENTER>
<P>
<hr><a HREF = "top3s_fr.htm"><img align=middle src="../images/fr.gif"></a> Ce materiel est aussi disponible en fran&#231;ais
<hr>
<P>
A wide variety of issues have been addressed by the participants
in the Working Group. We limit ourselves here to a selection of
interesting conclusions.
<P>
<B>1. Simplify management of Lom&eacute; instruments</B>
<P>
Lom&eacute; is endowed with a wide variety of instruments of financial
and technical cooperation. In theory, this diversity should allow
for much flexibility in adapting the support to specific country
needs. In practice however, great difficulties arise in using
this package of instruments in the most effective and coherent
way.
<P>
In the view of the working group there is nothing wrong with the
broad package of Lom&eacute; instruments for financial and technical
cooperation. Rather than abolishing instruments, they should be
simplified to ensure a better management by both the recipient
and the Commission. In recent years, the Post-Fiji study has already
pointed to major weaknesses in the implementation of Lom&eacute;
resources. Particularly in small and with capacity poorly endowed
ACP countries, the system does not work in practice. In many cases
this has led to an increasing weight of individuals (e.g. European
technical advisors) who are exercising a high amount of discretion
in deploying the EDF. Although discretion may favour some, it
was also seen as one of the real weaknesses of the system. 
<P>
<B>2. NIP must remain cornerstone of Lom&eacute; instruments</B>
<P>
In spite of the rapid increase of non-programmable resources in
recent years, a number of participants felt that the NIP should
remain central to all Lom&eacute; instruments. It is the instrument
&quot;par excellence&quot; of policy dialogue.  Programming remains
important since it ensures predictability, flexibility a relatively
low degree of conditionality and a match between demand and supply.
Others, however, criticised the &quot;obsessive attention&quot;
being paid to programming to mainly satisfy requirements of bureaucracy.
The programming process could be improved to ensure more cohesion
between all instruments. The practical value and effectiveness
of the NIP depends to a large extent of the way it has been integrated
in a global development vision of the ACP country. In the future
the basis for programming should be enlarged by sharing the NIP
with private sector and NGO's. The example was given of C&ocirc;te
d'Ivoire were a National Committee for the Management of the NIP
(&quot;Comit&eacute; National de gestion du PIN&quot;), comprising
private sector and civil society actors, has been created. It
was also stressed that coherence between NIP and RIP should be
strengthened and, even more importantly that both should not contradict
each other.
<P>
<B>3. Controversies about phased programming/incentive allocations</B>
<P>
The recent innovations in the use of financial and technical cooperation
(e.g. phased programming, incentive allocations) aroused considerable
controversy. In general it was felt that these innovations will
undermine the positive features of the Lom&eacute; programming
exercise (e.g. previsibility of funds, autonomy of the recipient
government,..). If the system would have worked adequately, these
innovations would not have been necessary. Participants mentioned
a number of risks involved with these new approaches:
<P>
* increase of leverage of the Commission on the policy dialogue;
<P>
* lack of transparancy on how the second tranche will be decided.
Adequate criteria have not yet been established;
<P>
* risk that ACP partners would be inclined to submit 'easy' short-term
projects (quick spending approach) instead of qualitative long-term
sustainable projects in order to ensure eligibility for the second
tranche; 
<P>
* increase of management problems at both sides. 
<P>
Standardised appraoches should be avoided to explain the underutilisation
of EDF funds by ACP countries. For each country one should try
to identify the main reasons for this (political problems? capacity
problems? at the ACP side, or at the level of DG VIII or at the
level of the delegation?, etc...). The working group also felt
that more work should be invested in measuring 'performance' of
ACP countries. In any case this should not be done by defining
purely quantitative targets (e.g. disbursement levels) but  qualitative
ones (e.g.economic reform, good governance, etc..).
<P>
<B>4. Differentiated approaches in the management of Lom&eacute;
instruments</B>
<P>
While co-decision (i.e joint programming of Lom&eacute; resources)
was seen as a prerequisite for effective cooperation, co-management
of aid programmes at the level of implementation was not considered
desirable. Experiences with the actual system of co-management
have been rather dissapointing with considerable delays caused
to a large extent by a lack of clear division of roles and responsibilities.
 To overcome these bottlenecks the group has proposed a differentiated
approach. In ACP states that are unable (because of political
or capacity problems) to manage Lom&eacute; resources well, a
larger degree of interventionism from the EC in various stages
of the project cycle could be justified. If the problem is purely
one of absorptive capacity (e.g. small Pacific islands), the provision
of institutional support that may help to create the necessary
conditions for effective implementation of the development programmes
by the ACP country, is considered necessary. In any case this
should be done in the framework of local administrative structures
and not through the creation of special management units or excessive
use of TC. In countries where the relations between the EU and
central government are flawed because of political reasons, decentralised
cooperation may be indicated. 
<P>
In another (and growing) group of ACP countries where the dialogue
is good and where trust exists, the working group strongly advocated
the principle that ACP countries should be responsible for managing
EDF funds on their own (&quot;full management&quot;). This could
also imply that instruments can be adapted to the provision of
direct budgetary support, with limited programming. It has been
strongly emphasised that, in a similar vein as the World Bank,
criteria should be developed for distinguishing different categories
of ACP countries for which different types of instruments can
be deployed (e.g. well governed countries, reforming countries,
countries in crisis,..)
<P>
<B>5. Coherent and integrated use of instruments</B>
<P>
Both programmable and non-programmable intruments retain their
validity. However, some concern was expressed over the increasing
weight of non-programmable instruments over the programmable instruments.
The integrated use of both types of instruments will depend to
a very large extent from a variety of country specific factors.
<P>
Some examples were given of well integrated use of both programmable
and non-programmable Lom&eacute; instruments (e.g. Ethiopia, Guyana,
C&ocirc;te d'Ivoire etc..).  Key ingredients for a well integrated
approach to Lom&eacute; resources included:
<P>
* ownership based on large inputs in fashioning the package by
the ACP country. In this respect it was clearly said that &quot;pushes
from the donor cannot make a difference. Only the ACP country
can make the difference&quot;;
<P>
* the institutional environment in the ACP country. The example
was given of C&ocirc;te d'Ivoire where coherence between various
instruments has significantly improved since the Prime Minister
coordinates EDF instruments as well as World Bank resources;
<P>
* absorption capacity. The example was given of some Pacific countries
were this was totally lacking;
<P>
* the quality of dialogue between the ACP government and the EU.
If there is a good &quot;entente between the trio&quot; (desk
officer, delegate, NAO) everything is possible.
<P>
<B>6. Direct support to non-state actors?</B>
<P>
The Working group fully recognised the validity of non-state actors
in Lom&eacute;. New requirements will need new instruments but
the working group strongly warned not to do this in an improvised
manner. A number of warnings were issued:
<P>
* do not go by doctrines. During thirty five years of development
cooperation we have been confronted with too many of these (e.g.
in the past central government planning doctrine, now decentralised
cooperation);
<P>
* look at multi-faceted aspects: With whom do you work : How do
you measure the representativity and legitimacy of non elected,
self appointed entities? How should these be made accountable?
<P>
To overcome the potential risks of working directly with these
new actors in development, the group proposed a three step approach:
<P>
* the EU must first have a strategy towards these non-state actors
that has been discussed with the ACP governments.
<P>
* second, a 'constituency analysis' with disaggregation of non-state
actors should be made (&quot;a who is who in civil society&quot;,
business and non-profit organisations with risk and opportunity
analysis). It is therefore important to check accountability and
to guarantee transparancy of non-state actors. ( e.g. care should
be taken that Northern NGO's do not 'hijack' EU funds that should
be provided to local NGO's.).
<P>
* third, mechanisms should be established for accessing and managing
Lom&eacute; funds by non-state actors. In this context a proposal
was formulated to create a special fund for the management of
decentralised cooperation through which all EU aid for non- state
actors would be tranferred 
<P>
<B>7. New instruments for conflict prevention and ensuring coherence</B>
<P>
The Group did not see any fundamental reason to equip future Lom&eacute;
Conventions with new conflict prevention instruments. Prior to
conflict outbreaks, existing institutions (Joint Assembly) could
play a useful role. Delegations could also be more pro-active.
But it was felt that other fora (such as OUA, UN) were more indicated
to deal with these issues. It was also strongly advocated to have
a stronger role of the EU in multilateral debt relief facility
which is hindring to a large extent the room of manoeuvre of ACP
governments.
<P>
<hr>
<H6><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="../images/logo.gif"> <i>Updated on July 4, 1996</i><br>
