<html>
<header>
<title>Clarifying Concepts as a Prelude to Action</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H3><center><img src="../images/dpmf.jpg"><p></a>
Clarifying Concepts as a Prelude to Action</h3>
by <i>Rogerio Pinto</i>
<p>
Full text of an article from <i>DPMN Bulletin, 2(3) December 1994: pages 6 - 7</i>
</center>
<hr>
<h3>Commitment, Ownership and Participation</h3>

The World Bank, along with most other donor agencies, now stresses the importance of country
commitment and ownership as critical to improving the quality of its project portfolio. But there
is a widespread failure to distinguish clearly between these two terms and thus a danger that the
processes required to achieve greater commitment and ownership will be less effective than
anticipated. The two are, of course, related concepts. But the difference between them needs to
be recognised as a basis for action.
<p>
Commitment to a project is associated with the intent of the leadership while ownership is
associated with the hands-on involvement (participation) of the rank-and-file who will have a
more direct effect on implementation activities.
<p>
<h4>Commitment</h4>

In the context of project preparation and implementation, commitment extracted from the
political leadership in borrowing countries is achieved through high-level consultation and
exchanges. It takes the form of declarations or enunciations of intent by the government. It may
also be reflected in policy acts or governmental statements.
<p>
But while commitment entails willingness to contribute to achieving outcomes by holding others
accountable for its outcome, it does not necessarily ensure ownership, nor respons- ibility for the
project.
<p>
<h4>Ownership</h4>

Where there is ownership of a project the owners will feel responsible and will care about
outcomes. If the outcome of the project is successful, owners will gain; if it is not successful,
owners will lose. Thus ownership goes beyond mere commitment. While commitment is
articulated in a declaratory manner, ownership is achieved through intensive interaction between
owners and the project.
<p>
All too often, donors incorrectly assume that where there is commitment at the highest level,
ownership by the rank-and-file will follow almost automatically. However, if it is accepted that
ownership is a higher order of involvement than commitment and that it needs to be achieved
rather than simply declared, then the need for participation in project preparation becomes more
evident.

<p>
<h4>Participation</h4>

Participation is, therefore, the means to ensure ownership of a project. It brings project
preparation closer to the people, in and outside of government, who determine the outcome of
implementation.
<p>
The importance of commitment is that it allows the project preparation process to get underway
leading to project approval. But it does not ensure project implementation. This requires that
preparation is undertaken in a participatory way, resulting in ownership.
<p>
In other words, you can have commitment without responsible ownership, but you cannot have
responsible ownership without commitment.
<p>
<h3>Institutional Environment Assessment</h3>

The process of Institutional Environment Assessment (IEA) has been developed in the World
Bank as a diagnostic procedure conducted by African governments as preparation for their civil
service reform programmes. However, the process has the potential for wider application to all
project activities.
<p>
IEAs build on commitment at the highest level but are designed to ensure ownership by all
concerned. Accordingly, the IEA provides a participatory process for project preparation
involving both senior and mid-level government officials. It creates opportunities for full
understanding of project objectives as well as for the shaping of these objectives.
<p>
The starting point for a participatory process designed to achieve ownership is to engage mid-level actors in diagnostic activities. This is a central objective of an IEA workshop which allows
these actors and other rank-and-file officials to be mobilised for the collection and analysis of
information on the environment to be targeted by a project. Thus the participants are brought in
at the ground level of project preparation and genuinely contribute to the shaping of the project.
While participation is very beneficial for ownership and improved project implementation, it
bears a cost. Participation increases expectations and projects can become more complex.
Furthermore, there is a need to keep participating players involved in project preparation which
entails a longer and therefore more costly process.
<p>
Participation involves donors working with officials and not merely with the political leadership
which gave its initial commitment to a project. But it is with this leadership that the World Bank
and most other donor officials typically interact. By following the IEA procedure, donors are
required to examine their own internal project cycle procedures so as to ensure that the costs and
benefits of ownership of project preparation are fully internalised by borrowers. 
<p>
The World Bank is currently introducing changes in its review procedures to streamline the
project cycle and make it more consistent with borrower participation, leading to genuine
ownership of projects.
<p>
<h4>An IEA in Practice</h4>

An IEA was conducted in The Gambia in the context of preparation of a Sector Adjustment
Loan. Both commitment and ownership were, to a large extent, achieved. Senior officials have
consistently demonstrated a high level of commitment and mid-level managers have continued
to be involved in project preparation activities to ensure ownership. It can be expected that both
commitment and ownership will be maintained throughout the project's implementation.
<p>
<HR>
