<header>
<title>Cooperation in Policy Reform</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H3><center><img src="../images/dpmf.jpg"><p></a>
Cooperation in Policy Reform</h3>
by <i>Derrick Brinkerhoff</i>
<p>
Full text of an article from <i>DPMN Bulletin, 2(3) December 1994: pages 8 - 9</i>
</center>
<hr>
<h3>Background</h3>
Cooperation between donor agencies and the poorer developing countries has become an area
increasingly characterised by dissatisfaction and disillusionment on both sides. Donors look at
cooperation and observe weak commitment to reform, feeble institutions, failed or partial
implementation, and limited results for the funds expended. Countries, from their perspective,
see cumbersome procedures for accountability, lack of flexibility, ambitious timetables and
targets, imposed technical solutions, and little sympathy for political realities. 
<p>
At no time in the past, however, have the needs of the developing world been greater, nor the
resources available from the industrial countries to deal with these needs scarcer. Furthermore
the post-Cold War era has introduced a new set of interests and players into the development
assistance equation, which is having a strong impact on the partnership between donors and
recipients. Adding even further complexity is the increasing recognition that many of the
problems facing our world are global and interconnected. No-one disagrees that development
cooperation needs to become more effective and efficient, the critical question is how to do it.
<p>
Obviously, there is no simple solution and this short essay does not purport to have one. The
problems of cooperation for development are multi-faceted and complex, and we need to
continue to search for the right questions as well as the answers. What is offered here is a process
perspective on policy reform and some suggestions on how that perspective can contribute to
improved donor-country cooperation in policy implementation.
<p>
<h3>Policy Reform as a Process</h3>

Many analysts have pointed out that a key factor in the difficulties with donor-country
cooperation for policy reform is a flawed perception of the policy process itself. Technocrats in
the international financial institutions and in developing country finance and/or planning
ministries have tended to view the policy process as mechanical and linear rather than political
and interactive.
<p>
This linear view places a premium on 'first-best' technical prescriptions, and the preparation of
detailed plans that follow predetermined steps once the decision to move ahead has been
negotiated. These steps then become the basis for releasing funds, judging success, and
determining accountability. When problems arise, remedies are sought by refining the technical
content of the policies and programmes and/or in seeking to build technical and analytic
capacity. The primacy of the technical fix is reinforced by the officially apolitical stance of
multilateral donors, as laid out in their charters, and by recipient governments' concerns for
sovereignty.
<p>
Experience has shown, though, that the policy process is at least as political as technical (if not
more so), and is multi-directional and highly interactive. Besides technical analysis and
prescription, the policy process calls for consensus-building, participation of key stakeholders,
compromise, contingency planning, and flexibility. Instead of identifying ideal solutions a priori,
the process perspective highlights the importance of iteratively developing 'second or third-best'
answers that stakeholders can agree on over the life of the policy. When problems are
encountered, addressing them turns on shared analysis and joint action, both inside and outside
of government, and on building strategic planning and management capacity along with technical
skills. In the liberalising political environment of many developing countries, the ability of
donors and/or governments to impose technical fixes for economic reform is vastly reduced.
<p>
Adopting an interactive process view of policy reform changes the nature of donor-country
partnership, moving it from an emphasis on conditionality to an emphasis on mutuality. This
change implies new opportunities and responsibilities for both partners. On the donor side, it
means assuring that policies and programmes have real constituencies along with the capacity
to begin to implement them. This implies greater selectivity in interventions, wider participation
in discussions of potential programmes intents and actions, more attention to specifying clear and
agreed-upon goals, and a willingness to suspend or withhold assistance if the constraints are too
binding.
<p>
On the country side, it implies governments being more responsible and accountable for
outcomes, not just to donors but to their own citizens, building broad constituencies for change,
and actively managing implementation to achieve results creatively, not just going through the
motions to reach targets. On both sides, a mutual partnership for development cooperation
indicates a more extended time horizon for reaching goals, which puts a premium on monitoring,
feedback, and adaptation.
<p>
<h3>Capacity-building for Policy Reform</h3>

The United States Agency for International Development (USAID) has supported technical
assistance and applied research over the past four years in the provision and refinement of
approaches and tools to help developing country policy-makers and implementors become more
strategic in designing and carrying out policy reforms.
<p>
The Implementing Policy Change project (IPC) has worked with governments, the private sector,
and NGO's in more than a dozen countries on various aspects of policy management. IPC uses
a process framework for strategic management that includes several steps: 
<ul>
<li>agreeing on a strategic process for developing a policy implementation strategy;
<li>mapping the policy situation, including analysis of political and operating environments,
policy content, and stakeholder expectations and resources;
<li>identifying key strategic issues;
<li>designing an implementation strategy;
<li>designing and applying a process to monitor progress and make ongoing adjustments.
</ul>
<p>
Helping developing country managers to understand and apply this framework and its
accompanying tools has contributed to building stronger local ownership for policy changes.
Furthermore, it has increased the capacity to respond to accountability requirements from donors.
An example illustrates one case of how strategic management capacity-building has taken place. 
<p>
<h3>A Case Study -- Zambia</h3>

In Zambia, IPC was asked to help set up a Policy Analysis and Coordination Division (PAC),
located in the Cabinet Office. PAC's mission is to serve the Cabinet with advice on policy
decisions and help the Cabinet to implement its decisions. PAC and a reformed Cabinet Office
are intended to contribute to the Zambian Government's effort to become more performance-driven and client-responsive.
<p>
Zambia is implementing a World Bank-IMF structural adjustment programme, which imposes
tight budgetary targets. Among the problems in meeting those targets is that sectoral ministries
frequently present proposals to the Cabinet requiring extra-budgetary expenditure. Without a
mechanism to review priorities and communicate them effectively, the Cabinet was poorly
equipped to deal with these requests and its decisions were often ignored, thereby creating
accountability problems with Zambia's donors. The IPC was intended to be this mechanism.
<p>
The IPC team worked with the Cabinet Secretary and the Cabinet Office, talking with them
about their vision of government and what was hampering its realisation. Jointly terms of
reference and an organisation chart for PAC were drafted. These were refined in discussions and
ultimately approved by the Secretary and the President. One month later, the formation of the
division was officially announced. 
<p>
PAC's four principal responsibilities are: to review proposals submitted to the Cabinet; to prepare
the minutes of Cabinet meetings; to monitor the implementation of decisions taken by Cabinet;
and to facilitate implementation of those decisions.
<p>
A workshop for PAC staff and the other senior Cabinet Office staff was held. To detail PAC's
tasks and explore relationships between PAC and the rest of the Cabinet Office. First we helped
participants conduct a stakeholder analysis, asking: Who are PAC's key stakeholders? Who is
interested in what PAC will do? Whom should PAC serve? Who might oppose PAC's activities?
What resources can the stakeholders mobilise for or against PAC? Then we helped the
participants to prepare an action plan to implement PAC's four areas of responsibility. We
conducted two more workshops with the Permanent Secretaries of line ministries. These
workshops presented PAC's mission and action plan, and addressed how PAC and the line
ministries could work together effectively. 
<p>
Once PAC had been operating for a year, gradually introducing new procedures, a workshop for
the Cabinet to review PAC's performance was held. It explored the Cabinet's expectations of
PAC, and discussed innovative ways the Cabinet might conduct its business. IPC continues to
work with PAC staff to set up systems to monitor PAC's performance and the impact of Cabinet
policy decisions.
<p>
While it is too early to assess the institutionali- sation of this strategic management approach,
some progress has been made in increasing the Zambian government's capacity to implement its
structural adjustment programme. The rambling Cabinet meetings of a year ago, which often
lasted till midnight and even then failed to resolve issues, have been replaced by far less
contentious meetings that finish before lunch. The government task force on structural
adjustment now sends its recommendations to the Cabinet so that important but difficult
decisions can receive its collective support, rather than be rejected by ministers who were never
consulted. Line ministries now hold daily informal consultations with Cabinet Office staff during
the preparation of policy proposals, and this has increased efficiency in making decisions on
those proposals.
<p>
<HR>
