<HTML>
<HEADER>
<TITLE>The Future of EU-ACP Relations Beyond the Lom&#233; IV Convention</TITLE>
</HEADER>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<center><IMG ALT="Lom&#233; 2000" SRC  = "../images/2000.jpg"></a><p>
<h3>The Future of EU-ACP Relations Beyond the Lom&#233; IV Convention<br>
ECDPM Conference, Maastricht, 12-14 June 1996</h3>
New Principles and Forms of Partnership:<br>Synthesis of Working Group Discussions
<p><a HREF = "top4_gb.htm">Comment on the Issues Raised Here</a></CENTER>
<P>
<hr><a HREF = "top4s_fr.htm"><img align=middle src="../images/fr.gif"></a> Ce materiel est aussi disponible en fran&#231;ais
<hr>
<P>
The group worked through the four sessions as they were detailed
in the annotated agenda.
<P>
<B>I The historical and conceptual background to the notion of
Partnership</B>
<P>
The first (thorny) question to be considered by the Group was
the definition of partnership and the appropriateness of using
this term to describe the Lom&eacute; relationship.
<P>
<I><B>1. Diagnosis of the erosion of partnership</B></I>
<P>
The participants appeared to agree on the diagnosis of the erosion
of partnership during the 20 years of the Convention. 3 <U>politicohistorical</U>
interpretations were presented:
<P>
* The first is based on the concept of a pendulum motion, according
to which the relationship has shifted from one extreme  in which
responsibility was vested in ACP partners  to the opposite extreme
of paternalism. The danger highlighted by this approach was a
tendency by the EU to take over from its partners under the guise
of achieving greater efficiency.
<P>
* The second interpretation focused on the evolution of Articles
4 and 5 of the Convention, which requires a compromise between
ACP priorities and those of European Union development policy.
Certainly the objectives of the Maastricht Treaty referred to
in Article 4, which are of a universal nature, are not in conflict
with ACP interests. However, in order to avoid friction, particularly
in the political sphere  human rights/democratisation (c.f. Niger)
 mechanisms need  to be found which will ensure compatibility
of priorities while preserving the prerogatives of the ACP side.

<P>
* The third interpretation stressed the intrinsically political
nature of the original partnership: in order to preserve the partnership,
it is necessary to find a political raison d'&ecirc;tre for the
relationship.
<P>
<I><B>2. Partnership and the lack of cohesion within the ACP and
EU groups</B></I>
<P>
The lack of cohesion within the two sides of the partnership was
identified as one of the causes for the ineffectiveness of Lom&eacute;
co-operation and a manifestation of the erosion of partnership:
<P>
On the ACP side, the group was considered by some to be too large,
even though very categorical positions were taken to defend the
integrity if not of the entire group at least of its three component
parts. The aim of the latter approach is to preserve a political
weight against Europe: there is a certain intraACP solidarity
even in the absence of concrete common interests shared by the
3 component parts. Several options were considered: differentiation
within the group in matters of trade in particular, extension
to include other Least Developed Countries, the creation of free
trade areas with certain subgroups. The option of regionalization
of the Convention on the basis of the present regional groups
was greeted with great reserve: the groupings of countries within
the ACP are far from definite or firmly rooted.
<P>
On the European side, two lacunas were emphasised, relating to
co-ordination between the EU donors and to the coherence between
EU commitments under the Lom&eacute; Convention and the other
policies which it is pursuing (including the integration of the
Bretton Woods requirements in the implementation of Lom&eacute;).
With regard to the first aspect, a path was indicated: using strategy
documents (documents studying the lessons of the past and future
trends in the countries and regions with which the EU is co-operating)
in order to achieve better co-ordination of European policies
and substantially involve the partner countries in the discussion.
<P>
<I><B>3. Partnership, Solidarity or Common Interests?</B></I>
<P>
The adequacy of the term partnership to describe Lom&eacute; co-operation
was the subject of lively discussion.
<P>
The starting point was the erosion of this partnership: some thought
it should be revitalised and that the term should be retained;
others thought it essential to stop sticking on a label devoid
of meaning and to consider the motivation for co-operation: solidarity
and common interests. The legitimacy of these two terms was discussed:
the first requires that the effectiveness of the aid should be
clear to the European contributors and entails the danger of drifting
into the untenable concept of  'charity'. The second is more difficult
to determine, with the exception of the wellknown negative interdependencies.
It was noted that interest in co-operation was a particular rather
than a common interest, each party co-operating because it has
an interest in doing so (generally not shared by the other party):
an example of this is the particular interest of the EU in the
return of aid (tied aid, contracts, employment in Europe) and
in market and investment opportunities (the interests of Japanese
and American investors were underlined).
<P>
The impression which emerged was that if partnership is  limited
to financial and technical co-operation, the term is inadequate,
as the relationship is one of assistance and the interest of the
parties is measured according to the balance of an equation of
costs and benefits. According to one of the participants, it is
necessary to reintroduce a more global political connotation,
a  &quot;joint project&quot;. The dimension of reciprocity of
rights and obligations should be enhanced.
<P>
<B>II New political principles of partnership</B>
<P>
The discussion at the second session was mainly concerned with
the political dialogue, the political foundations of the relationship,
and also with the relationship between partnership and development.
<P>
<I><B>1. Political aspects of partnership</B></I>
<P>
The Group considered a number of questions, in particular the
rationale for the politicisation of the Convention and the themes
to be discussed within the framework of a political dialogue between
adults. The question of good governance and democracy was considered
from the point of view of implementation.
<P>
<I> The politicisation of the Lom&eacute; Convention</I>
<P>
It is interesting to note an apparent contradiction in the discussion.
On the one hand, during the first session, there was an intervention
stressing the erosion of the political nature of partnership;
this was not contradicted. During the second session, on the other
hand, everyone agreed that there was a politicisation of the Convention
due to the strengthening of the human rights and democracy clauses
and the institution of the political dialogue. This contradiction
is outweighed by the fact that the politicisation of the Convention
is felt to have been a political dictate imposed on one party
by the other, rather than a political agreement negotiated between
equal partners. The politicisation of the Convention is an inevitable
phenomenon, bearing in mind the increasing politicisation of one
of the two partners, the European Union, and the changes which
have taken place on the international stage. The problem is to
get the ACP side to accept this politicisation, introducing a
change in the nature of the relationship and including themes
important to the ACP countries. 
<P>
<I> Partnership and political dialogue</I>
<P>
The keywords running through this discussion were  'frankness'
(according to D. Frisch  it should be possible to say things to
one other even if they are 'unpleasant') and mutual commitments.
Partnership is them transformed from a relationship between a
donor and a recipient into an adult relationship based on a contract
imposing obligations on both sides. The political dialogue should
make it possible to identify the common interests and objectives
and also the roles of the two parties. Partnership should also
include themes which go beyond development co-operation i.e. questions
such as security, prevention and resolution of conflicts. Political
dialogue should in fact be reinforced and made more obvious to
public opinion.
<P>
<I><B>2. Partnership and development</B></I>
<P>
Co-operation under Lom&eacute; is primarily about development
co-operation. The relationship between political partnership and
development was discussed at length focusing on: the 'benefits'
of development, planning of development and the interaction with
the donors, the establishment of criteria for good governance,
how to break with the culture of automatic allocation.
<P>
<I> Are the 'benefits' of development shared?</I>
<P>
The aspect of benefit to the Europeans as a result of development
co-operation was discussed by a number of ACP participants, who
called for studies to be carried out on this point. Reserves were
expressed on the European side, stressing that statistical analyses
entail the risk of a higher rate of return being indicated in
certain countries and in particular the risk of a return unequally
distributed between the various member states of the EU, thus
reinforcing nationalist attitudes with regard to European aid.

<P>
 <I>Partnership and development strategies</I>
<P>
A plea was made both by someone from the nongovernmental sphereand
by an ACP public representative in favour of implementing national
or regional development strategies. In order for development co-operation
to take place on a basis of partnership, it is necessary for the
donors to intervene in support of national strategies; however,
planning has acquired, in recent years, a negative connotation,
pushing ACP governments to think in terms of structural adjustment
deadlines and neglect longterm development due to lack of time
and resources. Support from the EU in the conception and implementation
of strategies (including politically in relation to other donors)
would be necessary and appreciated. A call was also made for the
concentration of development co-operation.
<P>
 <I>Flexibility and partnership</I>
<P>
The question of how to break with the 'entitlement culture' while
at the same time avoiding the dictates of the donor was of course
a controversial matter. Programming is in fact a guarantee that
a strategy exists and it also provides the predictability necessary
for the countries. Two questions were considered: What are the
criteria for the allocation of aid? What are the criteria for
performance? On the first question, the option to 'start from
zero' and to allocate aid according to objective criteria was
contested. Two criteria should be used: first the needs of the
country (national allocation and poverty criterion. The 'acquis'
of the Maastricht Treaty  Article 130 U  were quoted in this connection)
and subsequently assignment on merit.
<P>
The judgement of  'merit' should not be based on a quantitative
absorption capacity but rather on the commitment of the country
to pursue a course of good management of its affairs. The question
of democracy was approached with some caution, particularly by
the European side. On the ACP side the commitment in favour of
democracy was very strong and emphasised two requirements: the
necessity for sustainable democratisation, based on the 'ownership'
of this principle by the people, and the necessity of receiving
support from the European partners in what was called a  'longdistance
race'.  Good governance seemed to be a more acceptable and more
quantifiable concept. However, although the Group agreed on the
fact that evaluation of the performance of  'governance' should
be carried out collectively in accordance with objective criteria,
these criteria were not established and it was recommended that
policy research centres should consider the question.
<P>
<B>III Partnership and management of development co-operation</B>
<P>
On the theme of the management of development co-operation, the
starting points for the discussion were the observation that there
is a certain sluggishness in the system of comanagement, that
there is a lack of transparency and that a state and institutional
monopoly of the Convention is no longer desirable. Nonetheless,
it is necessary to ensure that efficiency  seen as a faster flow
of spending on aid  does not take precedence over partnership
and longterm development.
<P>
 <I>Partnership and participation by other actors in society</I>
<P>
It is no longer the generally accepted view that partnership is
something involving only the EU and governments: partnership should
also be seen in relation to representatives of civil society and
the private sector. It is necessary to involve and consult representatives
of the social and economic sphere: pleas were made for a more
open attitude on the part of the delegations in the field and
reinforcement of the capacities of co-ordinating NGOs. However,
implementation of this participation has to contend with various
obstacles: the sovereignty of states in their internal organisation,
although the International Convention against Desertification
(Article 21), which enjoins the signatories to involve economic
and social actors, was presented as an option for the revision
of Lom&eacute;; the representativeness and thus the accountability
of the actors chosen; the danger of the collapse of development
strategies pursued by the state, public bodies, civil society
groupings or economic operators. 
<P>
 <I>Partnership and programming</I>
<P>
Two recommendations were made in this connection: First of all
a very strong plea was made to safeguard national programming
and the national allocation of funds (NIP): indeed the existence
of national programmes provides a management framework which remains
extremely useful and requires a mediumterm strategy to be drawn
up, even if it only concerns EDF funds. The predictability of
the funds allocated, or at least part of them (phased allocation)
is highly important. Secondly, a call was made for the democratisation
of programming by opening it up to other actors in development.
Such an exercise would permit better allocation of priorities
(through consultation with operators who know the requirements
and constraints in the field) and greater transparency: the operators
thus involved are in a better position to check the implementation
of the priorities agreed on with the national government.
<P>
 <I>Partnership and joint management</I>
<P>
Again in relation to opening up the Convention to other actors,
joint management of the funds (within the framework of NIP) by
the central authorities and other actors (associations and NGOs,
private sector, decentralised public bodies) was proposed. One
option would be to place certain funds, where State presence is
essential, under joint management and to leave other funds entirely
to the private sector, public bodies, social representatives,
limiting the role of the State to the essential role of checking
the results. 
<P>
 <I>Flexibility and performance</I>
<P>
The system of comanagement by the ACP countries and the European
Union is extremely sluggish and bureaucratic. Placing management
of aid in the hands of the donor would imply a major step backwards
in the partnership. Co-management should therefore be maintained
as it is but it should be made more flexible: there is at the
present moment a surfeit of administration which is absorbing
most of the time and resources the ACP governments. The option
preferred by the Group was to link good performance on the part
of the beneficiary of the aid to increased responsibility acquired
through progressive budgeting of the aid. This means that if a
country manages its affairs well, the Community funds can be fed
directly into its national budget. A system of this kind, founded
on mutual trust, assumes the existence of a real dialogue on the
policies followed by the country benefiting from the aid, so that
it is possible to check that the aid is being well used. 
<P>
 <I>'De-bureaucratisation' and simplification of aid</I>
<P>
This can be achieved by more delegation in the field, by the progressive
introduction of aid budgeting (see above) and by a simplification
of existing procedures. This simplification could be effected
not only in respect of Community aid but also in the case of bilateral
aid from member states of the European Union.
<P>
 <I>Followup and evaluation</I>
<P>
As an indispensable corollary to a system based on greater responsibility
of the partners, there should be a more careful followup of activities
undertaken and a joint evaluation of the impact achieved: this
is essential in order for both the donor and the receiving state
to be accountable to their people regarding how the resources
have been used.
<P>
<B>IV European responsibilities in a new partnership</B>
<P>
It was agreed without discussion that greater coherence is needed
between the EU development policy and other common policies. The
debate concentrated on two elements: the role of the ACP group
in protecting the interests of its members in international bodies,
and the support expected from the European Union. The Debt issue
was stressed most particularly.
<P>
 <I>The protection of ACP interests on the international stage:
a responsibility of the group...</I>
<P>
The lack of an international dimension within the ACP group was
strongly regretted: the group seems to exist only in relation
to the ECU 14.6 billion from the Convention. The policies and
constraints which weigh on the ACP countries are decided in Washington
and in Geneva. The group should organise and mobilise itself in
order to protect its interests in these places.
<P>
<I> ... that should be supported by its European partners</I>
<P>
Partnership will be an empty concept if the European part of the
equation (i.e. the European Commission and the 15 Member States)
does not demonstrate solidarity with its ACP partners in the defence
of their interests and of common points of view in the Bretton
Woods institutions and the WTO. Indeed the EU is a heavy weight
in these fora: 50% of ODA, greatest chunk of votes in the financial
institutions, first trade block. The case of Structural Adjustment
was put forward: the Europeans should use their leverage to put
forward their views on structural adjustment in the Bretton Woods
institutions and to implement them in the bilateral policies of
the Member States. 
<P>
<I> The debt issue</I>
<P>
The case of debt was singled out in the discussions. As a matter
of fact, as long as this issue is not solved, the development
of ACP countries is compromised. The support of the EU has been
requested in this respect: although EDF does not increase the
debt of the ACP, the latter do expect the European Commission
to put the issue on the agenda of the Member States in particular.
This case exemplifies a major challenge to the solidity of the
ACP-EU relation: that of the integration of structural development
problems in the partnership. 
<P>
<hr>
