<header>
<title>Partnership in Agricultural Research</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H3><center><img src="../images/dpmf.jpg"><p></a>
Partnership in Agricultural Research</h3>
by <i>Steven Tabor</i>
<p>
Full text of an article from <i>DPMN Bulletin, 2(3) December 1994: pages 12 - 13</i>
</center>
<hr>
<h3>The Historical Background</h3>
The development and diffusion of new technologies is perhaps the single most important source
of long-term growth in low-income agrarian societies. Helping developing economies reach their
full technological potential is one of the reasons why donors have historically provided aid to
agricultural research. The fact that the majority of the world's poor reside in rural areas and
depend on agriculture for their main source of livelihood are other factors explaining this
commitment to agricultural research. 
<p>
Over the past four decades, donors have invested heavily in building agricultural research
capacity. During the 1950's and 1960's, aid was mainly used to train scientists and to equip
national research systems. In retrospect, this can be considered the 'bricks-and-mortar' heyday
of international assistance to agricultural research. During these years, spending on agricultural
research increased by close to 9% per year and the numbers of trained scientists rose by almost
12% each year.
<p>
In the 1980's, the emphasis in development assistance to agricultural research shifted in two
important respects.
<p>
First, the development agenda shifted from building institutional capacity and resolving
structural constraints to growth, to 'getting policies right'. That policy reform was long overdue,
and that governments caught in the vice of balance of payments disequilibrium had little choice
but to use aid to stabilise financial markets, cannot be contested. At the same time, however, this
contributed to a diversion of aid resources away from agricultural development in general, and
in many countries, from agricultural research in particular. As a result, growth in research
spending slowed while development of scientific manpower continued at a relatively brisk pace.
Many agricultural research systems began to be plagued by severe financial imbalances,
characterised by considerable physical and human-capital capacity, but with inadequate
operational resources to utilise it.
<p>
Second, aid terms hardened (in a qualitative sense) during the 1980's. Aid projects to agricultural
research began to demand more emphasis on environmental sustainability, women-in-development and participation of non-governmental organisations. As the policy dialogue began
to touch on matters of public sector management, agricultural research projects were used as a
means of fostering private-sector development and reforming technology policies. Increasingly,
research aid projects became centred on changing processes, be it institutional management,
policy direction or the technology environment, rather than investment in tangible assets. 
<p>
As funding for agricultural research began to stagnate, it became clear that past investments were
not financially sustainable, or at least could not be sustained at a reasonable level by
governments mired in fiscal crisis. The degree to which expensive investments in agricultural
research facilities and trained personnel became grossly under-utilised contributed to a sense of
cynicism and resentment on the part of aid donors and recipients alike. But at the same time, the
need for new technologies to address rural poverty and meet developing country food needs
remained largely unchanged.
<p>
<H3>Some Lessons from Experience</h3>

Three lessons stand out from this brief summary of aid experience for agricultural research.
<p>
First, development assistance will be biased towards the public sector, to new investments and
to activities that can be tackled within a relatively modest time-frame.
<p>
Second, development priorities will shift, and as they do, countries face the risk that high-cost
investments cannot be sustained. 
<p>
And third, donor spending priorities are far more subject to change than are the underlying
development problems and challenges faced by recipient countries.
<p>
<h3>Implications for Country-donor Partnership</h3>

How then can country-donor partnerships be forged to make an effective and long-lasting
contribution to economic growth and development? Many measures have been proposed which
would change the ground rules under which aid is negotiated or implemented. Leaders of donor
agencies have suggested, for example, a halt to technical assistance to Africa, creation of new
institutions to manage policy dialogue, and increased attention to project design and supervision.
While some of these measures might improve aid effectiveness, one can question whether they
would in fact result in a meaningful change to the aid environment as a whole.
<p>
It may well be that the aid environment is far more resistant to change than aid insiders would
like. As in all long-standing, bureau- cratic systems, forces in favour of inertia are strong indeed.
If the aid environment is not likely to change very much, or will change in ways beyond the
control and foresight of both donors and recipients, then the appropriate partnership strategy
would be for all parties concerned to learn from past experience and adjust to an evolving aid
climate.
<p>
Aid recipients and donors alike would be best advised to forge strategic, time-bound,
partnerships to tackle particular tasks. That long-term relationships might evolve would be more
a product of serendipity than of deliberate policy. In such cases, the best partnership solution
would arise when aid donors and recipients try to match financing requirements, priorities, aid
utilisation capacity and implementation strengths. Some of these different attributes, upon which
partnerships could be forged, are shown in the table below.
<p>
<center>                         
<TABLE BORDER=1 CELLPADDING=8>

<tr><th></th><th>Criteria on Which Partnership can be Forged</th><th></th></tr>
<tr><th></th><th>Donor Attributes</th><th>Recipient Attributes</th>
<tr><th>Financing supply/demand</th><th>Short-term or long-term<br>
Multilateral, bilateral or consortium<br>Loan, credit, grant or debt forgiveness</th><th>Balance of payments support or investment<br>Scale of the undertaking<br>Development level and perceived aid value</th>
</tr>
<tr><th>Aid priorities</th><th>Part one country agenda<br>Tied versus untied aid</th><th>Country policy and objectives<br>Sectoral investment strategies</th>
</tr>
<tr><th>Aid utilisation capacity</th><th>Aid 'due diligence' mandate<br>Perception of 'urgency'<br>Donor staff quality<br>Sustainability probability<br>Regulatory requirements</th><th>Governance standards<br>External environment and political importance<br>Ministry capacity to programme aid<br>Fiscal and environmental situation<br>Administrative abilities
</th>
</tr>
<tr><th>Aid implementation processes</th><th>Donor managed<br>Donor-driven reporting and evaluation<br>Project agreement as a binding contract<br>External supervision</th><th>Country managed<br>Country-driven reporting and evaluation<br>Project agreement as a starting point<br>Best staff used to implement or mobilise aid</th>
</tr>
</table>
</center>
<p>
If a good fit can be found between a country's needs and a donor's assistance instruments, then
a partnership should be forged. In many cases the fit between aid-agency and recipient nation
attributes will be far from perfect. In these cases, the objective becomes one of searching for
satisfactory partnerships, directing those partnerships to tackle particular tasks, assessing and
remoulding such partnerships as both donor mandates and country requirements evolve.
Flexibility in forming and redefining partnerships may be the best-fit for countries, and their
donor partners, as the aid climate evolves in the 1990's. 
<p>
<HR>
