<html>
<header>
<title>Partnership in Development Cooperation</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H3><center><img src="../images/dpmf.jpg"><p></a>
Partnership in Development Cooperation -- Selected Readings</h3>
<p>
From <i>DPMN Bulletin, 2(3) December 1994: page 14</i>
<p></center>
<hr>
Berg, E.J. 1993. Rethinking technical cooperation: Reforms for capacity-building in Africa. New York: United
Nations Development Programme.
<ul>
Reviews technical cooperation effectiveness and criticises its limited impact on local capacity building. Suggests that
donor agencies should find ways to support local capacity and institutions.
</ul>
<p>
Bossuyt, J. et al. 1992. New avenues for technical cooperation in Africa. Maastricht: European Centre for
Development Policy Management.
<ul>
Proposes an agenda to change technical cooperation in Africa. Using case experience from four countries - Burundi,
Cameroon, Malawi and Tanzania - the authors point to a number of promising avenues in the continuing search for
effective modes of aid delivery. Focussed on possible actions by African governments and donors, it assesses how
current reform efforts can be used to build and sustain capacity for aid management in recipient countries.
</ul>
<p>
Development Assistance Committee. 1992. DAC principles for effective aid. Paris: OECD.
<ul>
Compilation of aid 'best practice' for use primarily by donor agencies. Considers project appraisal and the need for partnership,
presents new orientations for technical cooperation, and outlines some principles for evaluating development assistance. Covers
the whole process of aid programming and implementation, from appraisal and policy dialogue with recipient countries through
to procurement and evaluation of results.
</ul>
<p>
Donors to African Education. 1994. Improving the implementation of education projects in Africa through ownership.
Paris: DAE.
<ul>
Reports on discussions between high-level education officials from Africa and education specialists from the donor community.
Particularly interesting for the report of a closed session in which African ministers of education reviewed ownership and
partnership in education projects.
</ul>
<p>
Lele, U. 1991. Aid to African agriculture: Lessons from two decades of donors' experience. Baltimore: Johns
Hopkins University Press. 
<ul>
This study on aid to African agriculture shows that donors are part of the problem. The form in which aid is given, the
large number of donor agencies, the limited human and institutional capacity in Africa, and the lack of institutional
memory and know-how in donor agencies make its absorption more difficult than it should be. 
</ul>
<p>
Price Waterhouse. 1992. Study of the causes of delay in the implementation of financial and technical
cooperation. London: Price Waterhouse.
<ul>
Examines the causes of delay in implementing aid delivered under the Convention of Lom&#233;. Stresses that the
nature of the partnership envisaged under the Convention requires that effective local capacity be developed if the
funds are to be fully utilised.
</ul>
<p>
Wapenhans, W. 1992. Effective implementation: Key to development impact. Washington, DC: World Bank.
<ul>
Reviews World Bank portfolio performance and criticises the Bank for paying more attention to conditions for approval
of projects than to the requirements for successful implementation. 
</ul>

<p>
