<html>
<header>
<title>Weaknesses and Arrogance in Development Cooperation</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H3><center><img src="../images/dpmf.jpg"><p></a>
Weaknesses and Arrogance in Development Cooperation</h3>
by <i>Jos&#233; Filipe Fonseca</i>
<p>
Full text of an article from <i>DPMN Bulletin, 2(3) December 1994: page 4</i>
</center>
<hr>
<h3>Both Partners Need to Reform</h3>

Responsibility for the disappointments of both donors and recipient countries with the
effectiveness of development assistance must be shared between the two partners. Neither should
point fingers of criticism at the other without examining its own processes, institutions and
behaviour. Two problems encountered in implementing a true partnership are of particular
importance. First, are the pervasive weaknesses in recipient countries. Second, is the widespread
arrogance in the behaviour of donors.
<p>
<h4>Recipient Countries</h4>

When I speak of weaknesses, I am not only referring to the obvious economic and technological
weaknesses of African countries. These are, of course, important. But there are others which
have more bearing on the type of relationships which exist between North and South. These are
the institutional weaknesses in our countries, particularly in respect of the rules by which society
functions at all levels.
<p>
These institutional weaknesses are primarily the result of a lack of real willingness to improve
organisations and management in depth. They are found in relationships with other countries,
including donors, but also in respect of internal matters. Without the fundamental willingness
to take appropriate action, all other factors become secondary.
<p>
Perhaps more important still is the fact that these institutional weaknesses necessarily lead to the
moral weakness of those who are in positions of responsibility in society. The very people who
are called by their countries to manage the cooperative development process and to improve this
process, frequently have a vested interest in maintaining the status quo.
<p>
These institutional weaknesses are themselves the basic reason why African countries need ever-increasing amounts of donor assistance to achieve their objectives of growth and poverty
alleviation. For they result in wasted resources and a situation in which domestic resources are
never sufficient for almost everything we do.
<p>
<h4>Donor Countries</h4>

The arrogance of financial donors is not a rare phenomenon. All Africans who have had to
negotiate or execute a project know how weighty a factor this is. Of course, not all donors are
arrogant. People behave in many ways and this is true of field representatives and other officials
of donor organisations. Nevertheless the experience in Africa at all levels is too widespread to
be ignored.
<p>
Certainly the partnership relationship and the effectiveness of external assistance at the project
level would have been far better if, right from the start, donors had the modesty to listen to what
others had to say; if they were not so convinced that only they had the right ideas and the right
solutions to all problems.
<p>
What makes this arrogance worse is that donors equally assert that responsibility for the success
or failure of a project resides entirely with the recipient government and agency. Thus, future
financial liabilities stemming from donor assistance are entirely with the borrower. Moreover,
sanctions are imposed by the donor if these liabilities are not met in full.
<p>
There are no corresponding sanctions which can be imposed by the borrower on the lender, even
if the latter is at fault in project design or implementation. I have never heard of a country being
compensated (for example, by exemption from debts incurred in a project) because a donor has
urged a country to make inappropriate choices or has not correctly executed its duties under a
loan agreement.
<p>
<h3>Deciding to Take Action is as Important as What Action to Take</h3>

It is easy to be pessimistic when looking back at the persistent unwillingness or inability of
donors and African governments to address the problems that lie at the heart of their failure to
generate an effective partnership relationship. Certainly to eliminate the arrogance of the former
and the weaknesses of the latter will be a complicated and long term process. But I think we can
succeed if only we can decide to begin.
<p>
<HR>
