<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>PAF6</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Klaus Hoefsloot">
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<P>
<CENTER><IMG align=middle src="../euforic/images/eustep.jpg"></CENTER>
<CENTER>
<H3>PAF PROACTIVE FILE<BR>
Regular News Update From Eurostep No. 6 Friday 22 March 1996 </CENTER>
</H3>

<P>
<CENTER>
<H4>EUROSTEP<BR>
115 Rue St&eacute;vin, B-1000 Brussels, Belgium<BR>
Tel.: (32)-2-2311659 / Fax: (32)-2-2303780<BR>
E-mail: <A href="mailto:eurostep@knooppunt.be">eurostep@knooppunt.be</A></CENTER>
</H4>
<HR>

<P>
<B>1 NIGERIA ISOLATED AT ACP/EU JOINT ASSEMBLY </B>
<P>
Members of ACP and European Union parliaments have today adopted
a very strong resolution against Nigeria at this weeks Joint Assembly
meetings which started on Monday in Windhoek, Namibia.  The resolution
was put forward by the EP group earlier in the week.  The wording
is much stronger than a resolution put forward by the ACP group.
 After an acrimonious debate on the issue on Wednesday, Nigeria
had threatened to pull out of the ACP alltogether.  They also
demanded that the vote on the European resolution be conducted
by secret ballot, and that it should also be a split vote.  This
means that the votes cast by the ACP and EU groups are counted
seperately.  Simon Stocker, Director of Eurostep, is at the Windhoek
meetings and has sent us a report on this morning's vote
<P>
&quot;Of the 49 ACP votes counted 30 were in favour, 13 were against.
 There were 5 abstentions and one spoilt paper.  Of the 56 EP
votes, 52 were in favour, 3 were against with one abstention .
. . This is the first time that there has been a secret ballot&quot;
<P>
According to Simon, the vote is important because so often in
the past the ACP representatives have tended to vote as a block
on difficult issues.  Under considerable pressure, Nigeria has
announced that it will allow a United Nations Special Mission,
to visit Nigeria from 27 March.  The Mission had previously been
turned down by the Nigerian authorities.  It has two major objectives
- 
<P>
i) to investigate the trial and execution of Ken Saro-Wiwa and
eight other minority rights leaders and consider whether the procedures
which were followed meet minimum standards of justice as laid
down by international legislation on human rights.
<P>
ii) to report on the plans of the military regime for a return
to democratic rule
<P>
The Mission will have three members
<P>
 Atsu Kofi Amega Former Foreign Minister, President of the Supreme
Court of Togo
<P>
 Justin B S Malmath Member of the National Human Rights Commission
of India
<P>
 John Pace  Chief of Legislation and Prevention of Discrimination
Branch at the Centre     for Human Rights.
<P>
<B>2 OTHER NEWS FROM WINDHOEK</B>
<P>
The Windhoek meetings close today.  One of the subjects for discussion
was the future of the Lom&eacute; Convention beyond the year 2000.
 There is a general feeling that the convention needs a fundamental
overhaul.  The President in Office of the ACP Council, Mr. Z&eacute;phirin
Diabre (Burkina Faso's Minister for Economic Affairs) appealed
to the ACP states to give priority to the development of trade,
and also to increase the effectiveness of aid, which could involve
a speeding up of present procedures.  He also called for a new
initiative to be taken with regard to the continuing debt problems
and suggested that this should be a topic for discussion at the
meeting of ACP Finance Ministers in June.  
<P>
Since it is very early in the process of negotiating the successor
to the Lom&eacute; Convention this Joint Assembly will serve as
a forum for initial discussion rather than a concrete statement
of intention.
<P>
<B>3 RWANDA EVALUATION OF THE CRISIS</B>
<P>
Danida has published a 600 page evaluation of the Rwanda crisis.
 The report looks at the crisis as a whole, including issues of
conflict prevention, the humanitarian response, and the political
response.  There is also an in depth look at the performance of
the many NGOs that rushed to the scene after April 1994.  Copies
of the report are available (free of charge) from Beck Distribution,
fax number + 45 4675 3222.
<P>
<B>4 RWANDA GOVERNMENT LOOKS AGAIN AT NGOs</B>
<P>
Following the expulsion of NGOs from Rwanda in December of last
year, the Rwandan Government, with the cooperation of UNDP, started
an evaluation of all NGO activities.  The evaluation is being
carried out by a team which includes a representative from the
steering committee of NGOs in Rwanda.  We do not know when the
report from the evaluation will be published but it is expected
to be soon (APRODEV, Lutheran World Federation).
<P>
The Rwandan Prime Minister will be visiting Brussels next week.
 A meeting has been arranged in the European Parliament at 11.00
am on 27th March.  The meeting is open to the public.
<P>
<B>5 DUTCH VOTE TO BAN LAND MINES</B>
<P>
Yesterday the Dutch Foreign Minister voted to ban the export of
Anti Personnel mines from Holland.  Since the Defense Minister
had already announced on March 11th that the Dutch armed forces
will no longer use APMs and will destroy existing stocks, this
amounts to an effective cessation of land mine production in the
Netherlands because there are no remaining legal outlets.  Therefore
Holland becomes the 23rd country in the world to have legislated
against the production of land mines.  The growing international
move against these weapons on humanitarian grounds has recently
led the United States to announce a fundamental review of the
use and stockpile of mines by american armed forces.
<P>
<B>6 WOMEN IN DEVELOPMENT WIDE ANNUAL CONFERENCE</B>
<P>
WIDE has announced that this year's annual conference will take
place between Thursday 30 May and 2 June at the Gustav-Stressman
Institut in Bonn, Germany.   Information from Monika Loffler at
the Gustav-Stressman Institut fax + 49 228 8107198.
<P>
<B>7 ASIA FOLLOW UP TO THE SUMMIT</B>
<P>
There will be a Joint Assembly of Parliamentarians from Asian
countries and the European Parliament in Strasbourg on April 18th.
 This follows the recent summit of Asian and European leaders
in Bangkok.  The conclusions from that meeting have now been published
and are available from the Eurostep secretariat.
<P>
<B>8 RWANDA MEMORIAL DAY</B>
<P>
Preparations are under way in Brussels for the commemoration of
the second anniversary of the plane crash which, on April 7th
1994, killed the Presidents of both Rwanda and Burundi and signalled
the beginning of the genocide in Rwanda.  A group of Rwandan nationals,
with support from Oxfam Belgium and other NGOs, has organised
a series of workshops on March 30th with discussions on rehabilitation,
the role of the churches, the role of the media, justice etc...
 The group will also mount an exhibition with videos for two weeks
from the 30 March.  The highlight of the campaign will be a torchlit
march from the Place Royale to the Palais de Justice at 7.30 pm
on April 7th.
<P>
We reproduce here the Oxfam summary of the Danida report &quot;The
International Response to Genocide: Lessons from, the Rwanda Experience&quot;
<P>
A The international community failed to recognise and address
numerous indications of impending genocide.  By not imposing strict
human rights conditionality on aid and failing to enforce and
arms embargo, the international community reinforced a perception
of disinterest and allowed the militarisation of the conflict.
 The narrow scope, inadequate support and slow deployment of the
UNAMIR mission again reinforced this perception as well as rendered
the mission ineffective.  Regional governments and the OAU were
under utilised, despite the fact that non regional actors had
proves either incapable or disinterested in translating early
warning to action.  The study criticises the absence of unit within
the UN to analyse information and translate it into options for
action.  It also criticises the inability of the UN to respond
effectively to early warning signals when a partisan interest
is not involved.
<P>
B The study concludes that the international community's response
to the refugee crisis before April 1994 was weak but commends
the large scale humanitarian response that ultimately did take
place after April.  Its criticism of the response include uncoordinated
operations, uneven funding, and poor contingency planning and
preparedness.  The study concludes that there is a need for a
greater link between foreign policy and humanitarian assistance;
more formal and effective mechanisms to ensure professional standards
among NGOs and a strong capacity at the centre to provide leadership
and overall coordination
<P>
C An effective shift from humanitarian aid to assistance for the
reconstruction of Rwanda has not taken place.  Donors have been
slow to comply with the assistance for national recovery that
they pledged in January 1995.  In fact, according to UNDP, only
1/3 of the pledged funds had been disbursed by September 1995.
 Weak areas pointed out by the study include insufficient concern
for survivors of the genocide vis a vis the refugee population,
problems with the distribution of seeds, tools, and food aid in
general, and failure to give women special treatment as a vulnerable
group.  Slow disbursement of Round Table funds, refugees fear
of reprisals, and government perceptions of the camps as a threat
have constrained the repatriation of refugees.  The study concludes
that in order to address these problems, an effective judicial
system must be put in place, the physical security of the refugees
and survivors must be ensured, and rapid economic growth in agriculture
and small business sectors must be promoted.  Because of the historical
and cultural context of the situation, a regional solution to
the crisis should be sought.
<P>
Based on the conclusion of these studies the evaluation makes
over 23 recommendations.  Sole overlap with our lobbying objectives
on Rwanda and UN reform.  They include -
<UL>
<LI>The development of a comprehensive unit for analysis of early
warning of conflict under the office of the General Secretary
<LI>Established procedures for the Rapid Deployment of UN peace-keeping
troops and the rapid response capabilities of peace-keepers from
regional organisations
<LI>Enforcement of international arms embargoes
<LI>Regional participation in preventive diplomacy and peace-keeping
<LI>Setting aside of resources for contingency planning in relief
operations
<LI>Consolidation of one mechanism in the emergency response functions
of major UN humanitarian operations
<LI>Compliance with the rule of law and observance of fundamental
human rights principles with close monitoring of government abuses
<LI>Support for government efforts to establish and promulgate
guilt and punishment for the participants in the genocide
<LI>Instituted consultations and procedures to allow for the rapid
availability of flexible resources for assistance
<LI>Expanded support for the justice system and law enforcement
by developing a systematic approach to assisting the reconstruction
of the justice system and by strengthening the International Criminal
Tribunal through an adequate budget and delegated authority.
<LI>Integrated UN leadership and line of command between headquarters
and the field
<LI>A regional framework for a solution to the crisis.
</UL>

<P>
<HR>

