<HEAD>

<TITLE>PAF7</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Klaus Hoefsloot">
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<P>
<CENTER><IMG align=middle src="../euforic/images/eustep.jpg"></CENTER>
<CENTER>
<H3>PAF PROACTIVE FILE<BR>
Regular News Update From Eurostep No. 7 Friday 29 March 1996</CENTER>
</H3>

<P>
<CENTER>
<H4>EUROSTEP<BR>
115 Rue St&eacute;vin, B-1000 Brussels, Belgium<BR>
Tel.: (32)-2-2311659 / Fax: (32)-2-2303780<BR>
E-mail: <A href="mailto:eurostep@knooppunt.be">eurostep@knooppunt.be</A></CENTER>
</H4>
<HR>

<P>
<B>1 INTERGOVERNMENTAL CONFERENCE</B>
<P>
The Intergovernmental Conference (IGC) gets under way in Turin
today.  Whilst the discussions are purely preliminary, and will
probably be dominated by the issue of qualified majority voting,
(with british cows appearing in the background) several organisations
have nevertheless rushed to publish position papers before the
proceedings begin.  Amnesty International has called on the EU
to accede to the European Convention on Human Rights as a legal
entitiy in it's own right.  The Fourth World Committee echoes
this idea and also wants a Charter on Fundamental Social Rights
to be included in any new treaty.  The Fourth World Committee
appeals to the IGC to lay down the legal foundations enabling
the Union to complement measures taken byMember states in the
fight against poverty.  They propose that representatives of the
poor be invited onto the EU Economic and Social Committee.  Finally,
they call for a genuine policy for a global fight against poverty
and exclusion.  They want to see the European Commission committed
to analysing the economic and social impact of its policies on
the poorest.
<P>
After much complaining the European Parliament has been invited
by the Council to send a delegation to the IGC meetings.  In Turin
today the EP is represented by it's President and two MEPs.  At
subsequent meetings there will be a larger delegation of MEPs,
who will be able to meet with the Council of Ministers prior to
IGC meetings to discuss items on the agenda.  Written positions
can also be put forward by the European Parliament.  This therefore
creates a mechanism for NGOs (through contacts with the relevant
MEPs) to impact on the IGC process.  The focus for this in Brussels
will be the Parliament's Committee on Intstitutional Affairs.
 It will also be important for NGOs to lobby at the national level.
<P>
<B>2 FOLLOW UP FROM ACP/EU JOINT ASSEMBLY</B>
<P>
Last weeks PAF did not give full news on the events in Windhoek.
 We should take the opportunity to mention the other discussions
which took place.
<P>
<B>EU action on refugees</B>
<P>
The joint assembly adopted a report by MEP Luciano VECCHI which
invites the ACP/EU Council of Ministers to undertake a general
revision of the policy concerning refugees and displaced persons,
reconstruction and rehabilitation measures.  The Assembly was
concerned by an idea being contemplated in the EU Council to adopt
a restricitive interpretation of the legal concepts of &quot;political
refugee&quot; and &quot;refugee&quot;.  There was support for
the regional approach to the resoultion of refugee crises and
therefore for the idea of a regional conference on peace, security
and development in the Great Lakes region under the aegis of the
UN and the OAU.  More specifially on Rwanda, the Assembly noted
with concern that large scale refugee intimidation was being perpetrated
by ex-government of Rwanda and interahamwe forces responsible
for the genocide in Rwanda.  The assembly guaranteed that it will
give its full support to the new EU special envoy, Mr Aldo Ajello.
<P>
<B>Sugar</B>
<P>
The joint assembly asked for a gurantee from the EU that sugar
would not be targetted by free trade arrangements.  The Union
was asked to take account of socio-economic factors when setting
the price for ACP sugar.
<P>
<B>Cocoa</B>
<P>
There were fears for the future of the cocoa market.  The joint
assembly called on the EU to explicitly ban the use of vegetable
fats rather than cocoa butter in the manufacture of products bearing
the name chocolate.  The European Commission was called on to
find a solution so that the three Member states that benefit from
a derogation from the rule (Denmark, Ireland, United Kingdom)
could gradually adapt to the Community rules.
<P>
<B>Bananas</B>
<P>
The joint assembly appealed to the EU to keep the quota for ACP
bananas at 30% of EU consumption (it was reduced to 26% two weeks
ago).  It also called on the Union to take steps to monitor social
conditions linked to banana production by multi nationals, especially
in South America, and to prevent imports when these conditions
are notoriously inhuman.
<P>
<B>Other trade issues</B>
<P>
The assembly recommended that that ACP governments set up a joint
and permanent pressure group to defeat their interests within
the WTO.  The Council and Commission were urged to improve the
trading position of ACP countries by being more flexible on rules
of origin, widening preferences giving acess to EU agricultural
markets, and allowing easier access for technology, licences and
patents when these correspond to a country's development plans.
 The assembly also called for a special committee to investigate
the extent of dumping of EU agricultural products and a process
to bring about an end to this practice.
<P>
<B>3 FAO REGIONAL CONFERENCE FOR EUROPE</B>
<P>
The FAO is inviting organisations as observers to it's Regional
Conference for Europe which is being held in Tel Aviv, Israel
between 29 April and 3 May.  The conference will mark a step along
the way to the World Food Summit in November this year at FAO
headquaters in Rome.  The regional conference in Tel Aviv will
be given draft versions of the policy document and plan of action
that will be considered at the summit.  For more information contact
The Conference Secretary, FAO Regional Office for Europe, FAO
Headquarters, 00100 Roma.  Fax - + 39 6 5225 5634.
<P>
<B>4 FOLLOW UP TO THE SOCIAL SUMMIT</B>
<P>
&quot;Social Watch&quot; is launched today at a special meeting
in Brussels to follow up on the Social Summit.  A further organ
forum for follow was identified by the UN Economic and Social
Committee at its meeting of June 1995 when ECOSOC designated the
UN Commission for Social Development as the official UN body for
follow up and implementation of the outcomes of the World Summit
for Social Development.  In pursuit of this designation the UN
Commission for Social Development is to convene a special session
to discuss its mandate with other interested parties.  Novib is
preparing a position paper.  They will attend the meeting with
a number of southern partners and in collaboration with Oxfam
International in preparation for this meeting, which will take
place between 21 and 30 May 1996 in New York.   The responsible
person at Novib is Caroline Wildeman.
<P>
<B>5 NIGERIA</B>
<P>
We have been receiving information concerning a campaign being
organised in USA by the Washington Office on Africa (WOA) who
describe themselves as &quot;a not for profit church, trade union
and civil rights group supported organisation that works with
Congress&quot;.  They are calling for a US ban on imports of Nigerian
oil, and are encouraging people to write letters to various influential
figures in the US.  They can be contacted on the internet - woa@igc.apc.org./rg
<P>
<HR>

<P>
