<P><BR></P>

<H1>April 1996 Newsletter</H1>

<P>Welcome to the first edition of  'Short Cuts,' a new electronic publication

aimed at keeping you in touch with our efforts to link British schools with

their counterparts in poorer countries. 

</P>

<P>Interaid is the brain-child of Nick Short, a lecturer at Reading University,

whose long-standing interest in computer technology and its social and economic

impact, led him to recognise the potential of using the Internet to link young

people around the world.  After much research, Interaid was launched succesfully

on March 11th, 1996, with the intention of giving children the opportunity to

share information and learn more about different cultures and lifestyles. 

</P>

<P>

As an educational device, Interaid's concept of  the global school is

compelling. In countries where access  to new research, scientific data and

academic expertise is often hampered by financial problems, the global school,

with its walled-garden facility is of great value.   This has been  illustrated

sharply by the speed and enthusiasm with which schools in South Africa, Jamaica

and India have expressed their interest in our plans.  However, the merits of

Interaid's international, electronic network go far beyond than the transfer of

educational material from North to South. 

</P>

<P>For too long, the people of develping nations have been told what is good

for them and had &quot;improvement&quot; schemes imposed upon them, often with

the minimum of consultation.   Their countries are home to legions of &quot;advisers&quot;

and &quot;consultants&quot; who though well-meaning, are sometimes viewed as

prolonging a culture of dependency that has poorer countries looking to the

continents of Europe and North America for support.  We at Interaid do not

intend to follow this well-worn development path. We seek to create a true

relationship between school-children the world over, so that a meaningful

dialogue can take place.  Where once children from Southampton to Soweto, sought

understanding in books, encyclopaedias and atlases, our global school intiative

will enable them to explore cultural diversity, to asks questions about national

lifestyles and receive answers by lively, interactive means.

</P>

<P>

Interaid's global school will develop into a rich, well-spring of academic and

cultural information from which young people around the world will be able to

draw 24 hours a day.  Of course, we recognise the size of this bold undertaking.

</P>

<P>Over the last two decades, the sheer pace and scale of computer development

has added significantly to the South's technology deficit. This alone makes a

nonsense of the argument that certain regions of the world can afford to stand

aside blithely from such advances.  The people of poorer nations certainly give

no indication of wishing so to do. They want the modern technological skills

that can improve their nations, as any visitor to such countries can testify. 

It is our wish to assist this demand in a manner which is both sustainable and

responsible.  

</P>

<P><BR></P>

<H2>WHY INTERAID?  - By Nick Short 

</H2>

<P>In the past 10 years, information technology has had an enormous impact on

society in the developed countries of the world. Today everything from

commercial enterprises to academic institutes have become dependent on the

efficiency of computers.   Whilst there have been some negative repercussions,

there can be little doubt that the &quot;computer revolution&quot; has affected

people's lives to an extent comparable to that of  the 18th century's Industrial

revolution. 

</P>

<P>The developing countries of the world have lagged far behind the wealthy

nations in their adoption of this new technology. This is due to a limited

access to computers, the lack of training in their use and the problems of

adapting Western technology to Third World needs among other factors.   The

consequence has been that many such countries are at risk of being left behind

in this new revolution placing them at an even greater disadvantage in their

struggle to keep pace with Western development and maintain their global

influence. 

</P>

<P>INTERAID intends to address the unbalanced share of information technology

by channeling resources from computer users in the North to assist the people of

the South to develop similar skills.  

</P>

<P>Training software developed at the University of Reading will be sold in

Europe and the United States to fund Interaid projects in developing countries. 

 This &quot;Robin Hood&quot; approach provides the a win-win approach which will

benefit both existing computer users in the North world whilst encouraging new

users in the South. 

</P>

<P>To focus the limited resources of INTERAID we have decided initially to

concentrate on providing secondary schools in British Commonwealth countries

with the latest computer technology. All participating schools will be linked up

via the Internet to a secure walled garden where school children and their

teachers can communicate with each other around the world.   This will provide

the children of today with the technology that they will need for the coming

century. We also hope that by improving communication between countries we will

help to foster a climate of international understanding and cooperation. </P>   

 

<HR>

