<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Dangerous weekend in Derry</TITLE>
   <X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=90 BOTTOM=480 LEFT=12 RIGHT=545>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<P></P>

<P></P>

<H1>Danger for peace looms in Derry</H1>

<P>By JOHN WEST</P>

<P>DERRY/LONDONDERRY, AUGUST 9 - This is a dangerous weekend for the
failing peace process in Northern Ireland. Long negotiations have
failed to defuse a crisis over Saturday's planned march by the
Apprentice Boys Association, which commemorates a crucial victory by
Protestant colonists over Irish Catholics 300 years ago. Catholics
have decided to hold their own march on Friday night.</P>

<P>Leaders and politicians from both sides of Northern Ireland's
religious divide are warning that in the present tense atmophere, a
confrontation in <A HREF="ot_town.html">Londonderry - or Derry</A> as
its majority Catholic population knows it - could reignite full-scale
sectarian fighting.</P>

<P>The British government has banned all public processions on a
section of Londonderry's 17th-century town walls overlooking the
Catholic Bogside area where the Apprentice Boys had been demanding to
march. Security forces have put up razor wire and metal sheeting to
close the stretch of walls.</P>

<P>Orange marchers<B><FONT SIZE=1>R</FONT><FONT SIZE=2>ight: Loyalist
marchers: a piping band in the Whiterock Parade, Belfast. Photograph
by John West.</FONT></B></P>

<P>"We're in the majority here in Derry and we have to stand up for
the Nationalist community in the whole of Northern Ireland,"
<A HREF="ot_views.html">Margaret Gallagher</A>, a teacher who was
elected to the Bogside Residents' Association when it was formed last
year, told OutThere after the <A HREF="ot_watershed.html">decision to
go ahead</A> with the Nationalist march on Friday. "We should show
that we can stand up for what we believe in without being threatened
by anyone and without threatening anyone."</P>

<P>The mood in the loyalist Protestant camp is grimmer. "The people
here are down, it's bad for our side, you know?"
<A HREF="ot_views.html">Alexander Trotter</A>, a middle-aged welder,
commented bitterly. "The English don't want us, they think we're a
headache. The Free State (the Republic of Ireland) doesn't want us,
we're too much trouble."</P>

<P><A HREF="ot_sinnfein.html">Martin McGuiness</A>, deputy head of
Sinn Fein, the political wing of the Irish Republican Army (IRA),
urged Nationalists in Derry to remain "calm, peaceful, dignified and
disciplined".</P>

<P>The Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, Sir Patrick Mayhew,
issued the ban on Wednesday night after days of talks failed to
produce a "local agreement" between the Apprentice Boys and the
Bogside Residents Association. It prohibits all processions and open
air meetings on the section of Londonderry's walls overlooking the
Bogside from now until the end of August.</P>

<P>Mayhew angered and dismayed nationalists last month when he
refused to intervene in a crisis over a loyalist march in Portadown.
The Royal Ulster Constabulary (RUC) first banned the march and
blocked the road, but then gave way after some of the worst street
violence since Northern Irelands "Troubles" erupted in 1969. The
<A HREF="ot_troubles.html">long years of political violence</A> began
after a similar dispute over an Apprentice Boys parade in
Londonderry.</P>

<P>Mayhew said: "My purpose in making this order is to assist the RUC
in its task of preserving public order and protecting the community
over the coming days, and is not intended to favour any side in the
current dispute ." He added: "In the event of local agreement being
reached before 10 August, the order will be rescinded."</P>

<P>The Apprentice Boys march is the last major parade of the Orange
marching season, which for Northern Ireland's Unionist majority is
vital reaffirmation that the victories of their ancestors are still
revered and that the province is still part of the United Kingdom.
</P>

<P>But for many Catholics, marches by Orange orders loyal to the
British Queen and the Union Jack affront their sense of Irish
nationalism and increasingly in recent years they have organised to
oppose them.</P>

<P>No Surrender mural<B><FONT SIZE=2>Left: The loyalist slogan, seen here on a
wall on the Shankill Road in Belfast, was born in the siege of
Londonderry in 1689. Photograph by John West.</FONT></B></P>

<P>In Derry, local MP John Hume has chaired at least five extensive
meetings between the Bogside Residents' Association and the
Apprentice Boys in the past week. The latest round of talks collapsed
on Wednesday.</P>

<P>It is not clear whether or when the two groups may meet
face-to-face again. Relations between them have deteriorated, with
Apprentice Boys' Governor Alistair Simpson calling the leader of the
Bogside Residents Association, Donncha MacNiallais, 'dictatorial'.
</P>

<P>To an outsider the actual dispute might now seem insignificant.
</P>

<P>The Apprentice Boys had agreed to allow only 250 of the thousands
of marchers who will be in Londonderry to parade along the 150-metre
section of the city wall that directly overlooks the Bogside. The
Nationalist negotiators were demanding that the number should be cut
to just 13 - one for each of the original Protestant Apprentice Boys
who closed the gates of the city to the army of the deposed Catholic
King James II in 1689, an action which began the bloody three-month
siege of Derry and gave birth to what is still the rallying cry of
Unionism, "No surrender".</P>

<P>The two sides were also arguing about whether marchers could carry
banners and play piped music on the disputed section of the walls.
</P>

<P>In the politically charged atmosphere of Northern Ireland, even
the words used to describe the negotiating process have become an
issue. The Bogside Residents Association have been arguing that the
Apprentice Boys should agree to the general principle of seeking
consent from residents of areas they plan to march through. But the
Apprentice Boys are objecting to the use of terms like 'consent',
which they feel implies they do not have a right to march peacefully
in their own city. Instead, they say they could agree to the idea of
reaching 'consensus' over the march.</P>

<P>The <A HREF="ot_ceasefire.html">breakdown of a ceasefire</A> by
paramilitary groups and the week-long stand-off over last month's
march in Portadown have made many people here worried that conflict
in Londonderry could escalate into a full-scale return of political
violence.</P>

<P>The parade in Portadown turned into a major confrontation when
police originally blocked the Orangemen's march through a Catholic
area.</P>

<P>Thousands of Unionists gathered at the small town, and Protestant
areas of Belfast rioted for five nights running. Dozens of Catholics
living in majority Protestant areas were terrorised out of their
homes.</P>

<P>Eventually, police chief Sir Hugh Annesley changed his mind and
allowed the march to go ahead, which created enormous anger in the
nationalist community and damaged carefully nurtured relations
between Britain and the Irish government in Dublin.</P>

<P>Both the Apprentice Boys and the Bogside Residents have made
well-publicised appeals in the past few days to supporters from
outside Londonderry to come and show their support.</P>

<P>Irish-Americans, too, have become involved. Bill Quinn, a leading
member of the Noraid nationalist fund-raising group, addressed a
public gathering in Enniskillen on Monday, saying he and 40 other
members of the organisation fully backed opposition to the Orange
marches. Quinn, from Kansas City, is leading a fact-finding mission
by the group to Northern Ireland.</P>

<P>The prospect of a rogue loyalist paramiliary unit with no
commitment to the ceasefire declared in 1994 has also loomed in the
last week. The Ulster Volunteer Force, the most formidable of the
Loyalist paramilitary groups, expelled seven men from its mid-Ulster
brigade after they publicly insulted leaders of the Progressive
Unionist Party, the group's political wing.</P>

<P>The Portadown unit - led by a notorious figure known as 'King Rat'
- has been questioned by police over last month's killing of a
Catholic taxi driver.</P>

<P>Now that they are officially at large, the question is whether
they will feel free to strike Catholic targets, or even if the UVF
leadership will try to preempt them to stop them seizing the
initiative within the loyalist community.</P>

<P>The IRA announced in February after a huge bomb in London that it
was ending the ceasefire it began in August 1994. But it has been
careful so far not to launch any attacks in Northern Ireland itself.
Ordinary people in the province relished the months of peace, when
military patrols disappeared from the streets, tourism boomed, and
outside investment began to flow into the economy.</P>

<P>In a further ominous move, a lobby group has been petitioning the
RUC not to equip police with plastic bullets this weekend. The
police, who were equipped with them during last month's unrest over
Portadown, have replied that they actually save life by dealing with
'serious public disorder' in a non-lethal way.</P>

<P><HR><A HREF="index.html">OutThere logoBack</A> to
OutThere home page</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
