<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Derry report live from the streets</TITLE>
   <X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=42 BOTTOM=478 LEFT=4 RIGHT=626>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<P></P>

<H1>OutThere on the streets of Derry after the Apprentice Boys' march
</H1>

<P><FONT SIZE=4>Here is an edited transcript of OutThere's live chat
session on the Net on the night of Saturday 10 August 1996:</FONT>
</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle, OutThere news service:</B> Welcome to OutThere's
live chat with correspondent John West, on the street in the centre
of Derry at the end of a tense day when thousands of Protestant
Apprentice Boys marched through the largely-Catholic city to
commemorate victory over a Catholic army 300 years ago.</P>

<P>Over to John to set the scene...</P>

<P><B>John West:</B> It's now Saturday night in the city of
Derry/Londonderry in Northern Ireland and, thankfully, no blood has
been spilt over today's march by Protestants in the city. Here in the
Diamond, inside the picturesque 17th century walls of the old town,
the streets throng with Orangemen drinking in pubs and a fresh breeze
blowing up from the River Foyle blows the litter of thousands of
marchers along the road.</P>

<P>Neither side of this divided city could be said to be happy. The
Protestants - in a minority here but a majority in Northern Ireland
as a whole - feel bitterly disappointed that the British government
stopped them marching along the length of Derry's walls, which are
steeped in a history in which they take great pride. For them, it is
one more sign that they are still 'under siege' - from the Catholic
Nationalist community who want to leave Britain.</P>

<P>But down on the Bogside, a few hundred yards from here beneath the
city walls, many Nationalists feel that the issues are still
unresolved. They resent the fact that the town was effectively
blocked off to them throughout the day, although they represent some
75 percent of the town's population. They also resent what they see
as the arrogance of the Apprentice Boys and the Orangemen in refusing
to come to an agreement with them.</P>

<P>There may yet be trouble tonight. At least some gangs of
Protestant youths are almost bound to be on the rampage along these
streets, and among their favourite victims are journalists - so watch
out! Protestant leaders have enigmatically spoken of 'walking the
walls at a time of their own choice'. There's an outside chance that
could mean storming the barricades tonight. But it could have been a
lot worse. Both sides had talked cataclysmically of today as being a
possible flashpoint that could plunge Northern Ireland back into
full-scale blood on the streets.</P>

<P>So far, that hasn't happened and I sit in the Diamond, with a pint
of Guinness for good measure, waiting to hear from you.</P>

<P>...But just hang on a second, there's too much drunk angry
shouting coming this way. I'm moving right now...</P>

<P><B>Saira Shah:</B> Hope he's not getting nutted.</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> Me too.</P>

<P>(John West logs off the live chat session)</P>

<P><B>Saira Shah: </B>Oops</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> This proves we were definitely live from the
street.</P>

<P>(John West logs back onto the live chat session)</P>

<P><B>John West</B>: waves but discreetly, trying not to attract too
much drunk Orange attention</P>

<P><B>Saira Shah:</B> So what's been going on?</P>

<P><B>John West:</B> I just pegged it from the Diamond down to
Shipquay Street. Someone just came to tell me there are two busloads
of Orangemen shouting and throwing bottles down at 'the Gaelics'...
while about 20 'Gaelics' are shouting back at them.</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> Do the people in the centre of Derry know that
there have been some clashes elsewhere - I've just heard on the radio
that there's a standoff in the village of Dunloy.</P>

<P><B>John West:</B> Yes, they know... FIVE RUC vans storming up the
street, STORMING. They must be heading towards the drunken Orangemen.
</P>

<P><B>Saira Shah:</B> How far away are the Orangemen?</P>

<P><B>John West:</B> We're talking unruly teenagers, as far as I've
seen. They must be gathering up the HQ of the Apprentice Boys, which
is about 300 yards from here. I still think there's unlikely to be
any large scale trouble here tonight.</P>

<P><B>Saira Shah:</B> So - do you think this proves that stamping
down hard on the marchers is the way to stop the kind of aggro we saw
after Drumcree?</P>

<P><B>John West:</B> I'm not sure about that. Drumcree was Drumcree
and Derry is Derry. One thing I've realised since getting here two
days ago is that the whacking Catholic majority here really makes all
the difference to the dynamics of the situation. The Orangemen
weren't going to stand off here in Derry because they simply
couldn't, whereas Portadown is smack in the middle of the Protestant
heartland. To answer your question, Saira, I'd say the government
could certainly try cracking down on them more than they have done in
the past but they really have to assess each situation on its own
merits...</P>

<P><B>John West:</B> There's now a little conversational knot around
this laptop - two Catholics and an English photographer. The
Catholics want to know who we think is in the right and who's in the
wrong.</P>

<P><B>Saira Shah:</B> Let's hear one of them talk to us.</P>

<P><B>Paddy:</B> My name is Paddy, I'm 33 years of age. I've two
babies, a boy and a girl. One's 14 and one's 11.</P>

<P>John West asks what Paddy thinks about today.</P>

<P><B>Paddy:</B> It's up to the government. I believe that the
Orangemen should be able to walk on the walls. They defended the
place in 1689.</P>

<P><B>Saira Shah: </B>What numbers are reasonable?</P>

<P><B>Paddy:</B> 13 (the number of the original Apprentice Boys who
shut the city's gates against the advancing Catholic army in 1689).
</P>

<P><B>Saira Shah:</B> And when does a march become a provocation?
</P>

<P><B>Paddy:</B> When it's marching through an area where the
marchers are not welcome. They DID march, just not along the walls
over the Bogside... but the centre of town has seen 10,000 Orangemen
today.</P>

<P><B>Saira Shah:</B> Do you think there is trouble to come?</P>

<P><B>Paddy:</B> No, not between the two communities here in Derry
because Sinn Fein don't want trouble.</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> Do you think peace is possible? Do the two
sides really want it?</P>

<P><B>Paddy:</B> No, most definitely not. They've ruled us for too
long, the Unionists.</P>

<P><B>Saira Shah: </B>Do you think there is any LONG-TERM solution to
the marching season? Or will it always have to be thrashed out on an
individual basis?</P>

<P><B>Paddy:</B> I don't know, but there has to be parity of esteem.
</P>

<P><B>John West:</B> Paddy was arrested and tortured as a teenager.
Paddy wants to know what you all think and he's just off home so make
it fast.</P>

<P><B>Saira Shah:</B> I'm trying to understand it all, specifically
the marches. Intellectually, I understand the reasons and rationale
of why it's considered important. But I still can't really grasp it
emotionally.</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> I think it's hard for British people who aren't
from Ireland to understand the depth of passion.</P>

<P><B>Paddy:</B> It's hundreds of years of history.</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> I mean my ancestors were Welshmen who were
occupied by Edward the First but I don't feel that means much to me
now. In Ireland, it's different.</P>

<P><B>Paddy:</B> When you have to go through three generations like
in my family, and none of us had a job and we all lived in the same
house, and them Protestants wouldn't give us the vote. And my Dad was
in the British army, too, in the Enniskillen Fusiliers, he was in
Palestine.</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> I take your point - history means so much when
there is present-day discrimination.</P>

<P><B>Paddy:</B> I'm 33 and I've never had a job. I left school in
1979 and have NEVER had a job. I had no education. You see, when I
started secondary school it was 1973 and it was hard core then from
'73 to '75. You weren't really educated, you were trying to move guns
around and bombs around rather than going to school. That was
expected of you. I regret that now for my children but not for
myself.</P>

<P>(Paddy and his wife leave. A young man has come up.)</P>

<P><B>George:</B> I want to be known as George. I'm 17. That's not my
real name.</P>

<P><B>John West:</B> Ask George a question, he's unemployed, lives in
the Bogside, spent tonight walking about and in and out of bars...
George doesn't want to be known as George any more, wants to be known
as Toss, which is his real nickname. So, questions for Toss?</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> Do you think there'll be a settlement in your
lifetime?</P>

<P><B>Toss: </B>(Thinks about it for a second) Aye, because if Sinn
Fein get to sit down with that John Major there'll be peace.</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> Do you think the IRA should agree to a
ceasefire to make it possible for Sinn Fein to talk to Major?</P>

<P><B>Toss: </B>Those two men from the UVF (Protestant paramilitary
group) went to talk with your man Major. So why not Sinn Fein?</P>

<P><HR><A HREF="index.html">OutThere logoBack</A> to
OutThere home page</P>
</BODY>
</HTML>
