<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Attwood: Unionist values must be accommodated</TITLE>
   <X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=90 BOTTOM=480 LEFT=12 RIGHT=542>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<P></P>

<H1>Nationalist councillor: Unionist values must be accommodated
</H1>

<P><FONT SIZE=4>Here is an edited transcript of OutThere's interview
with Belfast City councillor Alex Attwood on Sunday 10 August
1996.</FONT></P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle, OutThere news service:</B> Welcome to the first of
two live OutThere interviews this evening on prospects for peace in
Northern Ireland. With OutThere correspondent John West in
Revelations cyber cafe in the centre of Belfast is Alex Attwood,
member of Belfast City Council for the Social Democratic and Labour
Party, the mainstream Nationalist party in Northern Ireland.</P>

<P>Mr Attwood has represented the Upper Falls area on Belfast City
Council since 1985 and ran the 1987 general election campaign of the
SDLP's Member of Parliament for West Belfast, Joe Hendron. He works
as a lawyer, and his legal skills have helped to steer the SDLP
through the complex procedural wrangles that dominated the first
sessions of all-party talks on the future of Northern Ireland.</P>

<P>First question - A month ago, Northern Ireland erupted in violence
when police rerouted a Protestant parade in Portadown. Yesterday, the
Apprentice Boys' parade passed off peacefully in Londonderry, even
though police closed off part of its route. Why such a different
outcome?</P>

<P><B>Alex Attwood:</B> First, because there was a process of
dialogue in Derry which created a better atmosphere than in
Portadown. Second, the British Government adopted a different
approach in banning marches from part of the parade route, which
defused some problems though encouraged others. Third, the hype and
attention on Derry and the very serious threat that the situation
presented in Derry made virtually everybody attempt to pull back from
an even more serious situation than on 12th July.</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> Is there any way to build on this improvement
in the atmosphere?</P>

<P><B>Alex Attwood:</B> Yes. The process of dialogue between marching
orders and protest groups needs to be expanded and developed. The
British government need to take serious control of the issue by
reviewing the law on marching, encouraging principles that would
govern march routes. There should be a commission on cultural
celebration of all the traditions and a better method of resolution
of disputed marches. In addition, there is an endless range of
political initiatives that must be taken immediately to defuse the
very deep-seated community tensions.</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> The problem seemed to be in Derry that the
government had to take control because the marching order and the
local groups couldn't reach agreement. Is it practical to think that
'local agreements' can be reached in future?</P>

<P><B>Alex Attwood:</B> There is no alternative unless there is an
annual rerun of conflicts over routes, increasing the number of areas
and the potential for catastrophe... There has to be an improvement
in the overall atmosphere otherwise if it's not marching, it will be
another issue - policing, human rights, or something else.</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> A question from someone nicknamed Dual in the
Revelations cafe - What are the SDLP going to do to avoid
confrontation on a similar or worse scale than that which we have
witnessed? Will the next 10 months be used fruitfully; will attempts
be made to enable discussion without so much argument about
rudimentary issues such as George Mitchell (US Senator appointed to
chair all-party peace talks)?</P>

<P><B>Alex Attwood:</B> First, we will continue to maximise the
opportunities of the current talks process, moving beyond procedural
issues, getting into negotiations on a comprehensive agenda, which is
negotiations on all the relationships in this island and between
these islands which are at the heart of the conflict. We will
encourage local initiatives as (SDLP leader) John Hume valiantly
demonstrated in Derry to resolve marching and other justice issues.
Most critically, we will hold the line as always against extremism,
both political and paramilitary.</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> But there has been a blockage in the peace
process in the last few weeks - what has caused the problem, in your
view, and how can it be unblocked?</P>

<P><B>Alex Attwood:</B> The primary reason for the blockage is that
people and parties will not engage in dialogue on local issues and
broader issues, and when they do engage, they are not serious or
genuine. In the absence of proper structured creative dialogue, you
end up with a stand-off on a disputed march route or at the talks
table. However, the blockages reflect people's and parties' concerns
about their community and their future, and also reflect the refusal
of too many to accept change, to encourage equality, and to take
risks for peace.</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> It looks as if there is a need for confidence
building measures. Do you have any suggestions of what could be done
to build confidence in practical ways immediately?</P>

<P><B>Alex Attwood:</B> Yes. The British government, who surrendered
to threat and terror in July, have a primary responsibility to accept
publicly the crisis that the Nationalist community is now
experiencing. Secondly, rather than slavishly defending the RUC
(Royal Ulster Constabulary), they should acknowledge that the RUC's
contribution to this crisis is profound. Thirdly, they should move
the talks process forward urgently from the 9th September by showing
leadership on the issue of decommissioning, by accepting that
decommissioning can only be dealt with in parallel to the
negotiations NOT in advance, and should fully adopt the Mitchell
proposals. The British government with the Irish government must
prevail on all the parties to accept the comprehensive agenda of the
talks, that everything is on the table and must be addressed to
secure agreement, including constitutional issues such as the future
constitutional position of the north of Ireland.</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> This connects to a question that Dual would
like to ask - Does Mr Attwood agree that the Dublin Government has a
place in securing a lasting agreement between both sides?</P>

<P><B>Alex Attwood:</B> Yes, the Dublin government is essential. As a
Nationalist, I identify with the rest of the island, I wish to share
in the life of the rest of the island. That requires political,
institutional and symbolic links between the north and the south of
the island.</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> Question from Saira Shah - you've laid out what
the British government can do, what should the nationalist community
do as well?</P>

<P><B>Alex Attwood:</B> First, we must repeat that the Unionist
community has an equal and full place on this island, that what they
value - the British way of life, the loyalty to the crown, the
commitment to the British union - must be accommodated in any future
agreement. Second, while we state that the Irish people have the
right to self-determination exercised by referendum on the island,
north and south, we also accept the principle of consent, which is
that any future constitutional change must be with the consent of the
people of Northern Ireland.</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> Someone nicknamed TineBeag from Dublin asks -
Do you think that a solution satisfactory to nationalists could
involve Northern Ireland staying within the UK but with greater links
to the Republic of Ireland?</P>

<P><B>Alex Attwood:</B> What we wish to see is an agreed Ireland with
institutions of government which have the allegiance of all the
people. Now, what an agreed Ireland would look like is what is agreed
between the governments and the parties and endorsed by the people.
My strong preference is that the most durable basis for peace and
prosperity is the reunification of our country but realistically what
the Unionist parties will agree to may fall somewhat short of our
preference.</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> Dual asks - Does Mr Attwood know that those in
the South want a United Ireland? What do they think about sharing
their growing prosperity?</P>

<P><B>Alex Attwood:</B> My sense from being in Dublin regularly and
from my parental ties to Cork City, where they were born and bred, is
that the people in the south want peace, that they know that peace
will need political and institutional changes, that in that context,
the opportunities for economic growth throughout the island are
immense and that peace and political agreement can bring economic
advantage to all and not loss to the south.</P>

<P>I want to say another thing. A united Ireland is one political
model which MIGHT secure agreement and the one I am personally
committed to but an AGREED Ireland may have many political forms best
suited for our political conditions.</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> What would you say has been the significance of
this past weekend's events for the Nationalist community in Northern
Ireland?</P>

<P><B>Alex Attwood:</B> First, the Nationalist community
instinctively knew that we all had to step back from the brink, that
a rerun of the stand-off, the terror and the threat before and after
Drumcree would be too much for peace and the political process.
Second, the Nationalist community committed itself to the principle
of dialogue over marching, and over everything else, and this is a
very important anchor in the political process. Third, the crisis and
lack of confidence in the state has NOT declined but there is a
stability, generally, that didn't exist even a week ago.</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle: </B>TineBeag asks - Economically, do you think that
given the large (3 billion pound odd) subsidy Great Britain pumps
into Northern Ireland that nationalists might be inclined to vote for
a continuation of the UK for economic reasons, e.g. the much lower
tax rates?</P>

<P><B>Alex Attwood:</B> Well, we would prefer that whatever political
agreement emerges, it is underpinned by financial and social
guarantees from the British and Irish governments, from Europe, from
private monies invested, particularly from America, and critically,
there is a sustained attack on social need and the historic
inequality in jobs and justice, because after 25 years a male
Catholic adult is 2.2 times more likely to be unemployed than a
Protestant male adult and that equally the economic disadvantage of
many Protestants is equal to that of their Catholic neighbours .
Ultimately, as the ceasefire period proved, the opportunities of
tourist jobs, U.S. investment, special European packages, and
increased cross-border trade suggest political agreement can bring
economic advantage on a broad scale to those in greatest need.</P>

<P>Your readers might like to know that within the last four weeks
the foundations were laid for Belfast's Hilton hotel, symbolically
putting our city on the map.</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> Final question from Saira Shah - Do you think
the new stability you mentioned will last for any length of time?
</P>

<P><B>Alex Attwood:</B> Northern Ireland people have immense
resilience and defiance. That's why Belfast did not become a Bosnia.
Something in the make-up of its people pulled them back from the
excesses of open civil conflict. With that human resource comes
stability in the face of all threat and terror and that will endure
now also. Change and agreement may come very slowly but a return to
25 years of violence and disorder seems not likely because the
community does not believe there is any advantage to war and refuses
to live with the consequences of war.</P>

<P><HR><A HREF="index.html">OutThere logoBack</A> to
OutThere home page</P>
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
