<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Maginnis: Nationalists talk at us and about us but not to
   us</TITLE>
   <X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=42 BOTTOM=477 LEFT=4 RIGHT=534>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<P></P>

<H1>Ulster Unionist MP: Nationalists talk at us and about us but not
to us</H1>

<P><FONT SIZE=4>Here is an edited transcript of OutThere's interview
with Ulster Unionist MP Ken Maginnis on Sunday 10 August 1996.</FONT>
</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle, OutThere news service:</B> Welcome to OutThere's
second live interview this evening on prospects for peace in Northern
Ireland. In the hot seat in Revelations cyber cafe in the centre of
Belfast with OutThere correspondent John West is Ken Maginnis, MP for
Fermanagh and South Tyrone and spokesman on security matters for the
Ulster Unionist Party.</P>

<P>Mr Maginnis has been MP for Fermanagh and South Tyrone since 1983.
Once a teacher, he also served for several years as a volunteer
policeman and a part-time officer in the Ulster Defence Regiment of
the British Army. He's been described as the "liberal voice of
Unionism" but also as a "Prophet of Doom" who never believed that the
ceasefire announced by the IRA in 1994 would last.</P>

<P>First question - A month ago, Northern Ireland erupted in violence
when police rerouted a Protestant parade in Portadown. Yesterday, the
Apprentice Boys' parade passed off peacefully in Londonderry, even
though police closed off part of its route. Why such a different
outcome?</P>

<P><B>Ken Maginnis:</B> The community has gained some experience from
the Drumcree, that is the Portadown, events. In Portadown, the parade
that was taking place substituted for seven parades that used to take
place there and the Garvaghy Road route was previously agreed as a
compromise. For the Orangemen to be told that they could ONLY parade
in what amounted to their own ghetto areas was a contradiction of the
very thing that Nationalists had demonstrated for 27 years before, in
1969. In Londonderry, however, because of IRA activity for 25 years,
the parade route along the wall had been closed. It was only opened
again last year and so it became a reasonable compromise, if somewhat
unwelcome, that part of the route should be abandoned until the whole
question of parade rights was sorted out</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> Is there some way to build on this outcome to
reinvigorate the wider peace process in Northern Ireland?</P>

<P><B>Ken Maginnis:</B> The important thing that society as a whole
has got to realise is that driving each tradition strictly into its
own ghetto area is going to create fear and distrust, the very diet
on which terrorism feeds. Therefore, the resolution to the parades
issue must be one where both traditions can have free access to
traditional and main arterial routes rather than what is happening at
present. A difference can be made and indeed should be made between
traditional parades which have a degree of pageantry attached and
political parades. The political parades should be confined to areas
where there is significant political support but those which have
traditional aspects should be able to continue unimpeded along
traditional routes and particularly arterial highways.</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> Do you think it was right that the government
took responsibility for the route of the parades in Londonderry,
rather than leaving it to the police as at Drumcree?</P>

<P><B>Ken Maginnis:</B> I believe the ideal solution would be a
predetermination as to what is generally acceptable, that parades
should be registered and that the size and nature be carefully
defined. Then the police will only have the task of applying the law
in terms of behaviour and general decorum. They should certainly not
be required to make operational decisions which have significant
political undertones. The government's forthcoming enquiry into this
matter will decide how contentious issues are to be resolved.</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> A question from someone nicknamed Dual in the
Revelations cafe - Does Mr Maginnis agree that the only way to secure
a real lasting peace is for all the Unionist representatives at all
levels to be in immediate and direct dialogue with Gerry Adams and
Sinn Fein regardless of their obvious association (with the IRA)? If
not, who will the Unionists talk to?</P>

<P><B>Ken Maginnis:</B> The Ulster Unionist party has been in talks
with every constitutional, political party in Northern Ireland, with
the Irish government and obviously with our own government. We have
talked in London, in Belfast and in Dublin. We have been members of
every elected body over the past 75 years and have played a
significant part in trying to reach a compromise and agreement.</P>

<P>It has been Nationalist parties which have traditionally boycotted
the democratic process and we see an example of this in the
reluctance of the SDLP to play a full part in the current political
talks process. They have been selective in participating in the
actual negotiations without giving whole-hearted support to the
debating chamber. In fact they have now withdrawn from that chamber.
To ask Unionists under these circumstances to consider entering into
dialogue with IRA/Sinn Fein is to ask too much. These are the people
who promised a ceasefire but who without any forewarning exploded a
bomb at Canary Wharf on 9 February last... That despite the fact that
our government had talked to them at official level, at junior
minister level and at cabinet level; despite the fact that the Irish
government had released terrorist prisoners; despite the fact that
President Clinton had facilitated Gerry Adams in the United States.
What is the point in Unionists compromising on democracy by entering
into talks with those who cannot be depended upon to honour a promise
made even to the President of the United States?</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> Question now from someone nicknamed TineBeag in
Dublin - Do you think different rules should apply to parades which
campaign against the other's community's beliefs, e.g. an Orange
Order march and those that merely celebrate their own, e.g. a Church
of Ireland march?</P>

<P><B>Ken Maginnis:</B> I consider the Orange order, the Royal Black
Preceptory, the Ancient Order of Hibernians, the Irish National
Forresters, and the Apprentice Boys as religious/cultural
organisations. These should be treated as 'traditional'. I was
suggesting that purely political parades should be judged on the
nature of the issue about which they are organised. For example a
political parade which demonstrates against the closure of a hospital
would normally be cross-community and would present no difficulty,
whereas one which demonstrated against the rights of a Gaelic club to
fly the Irish tricolour or one which demonstrated against the RUC
would be controversial, and would need to be carefully considered in
terms of how where and when it would take place.</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> Looking more widely, what do you think is
needed to unblock the peace process now?</P>

<P><B>Ken Maginnis:</B> It is often overlooked that more than 80
percent of society in Northern Ireland functions normally. It is
among this greater number of people that there needs to be more
positive activity to support constitutional political initiatives. It
is particularly disappointing that so many decent people who would
never approve of guns and bombs have been attracted by the blatantly
sectarian activities of Sinn Fein/IRA. In the Ormeau Road, Portadown,
and other areas of Northern Ireland, the terrorist who knows he
cannot win a military campaign is capitalising on the baser sectarian
instincts of some people. It is imperative that these folk recognise
the danger and draw back from such confrontation before it is too
late.</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> What measures can you as the Ulster Unionist
Party take to encourage "positive activity" across the sectarian
divide?</P>

<P><B>Ken Maginnis:</B> You can only break down barriers when those
on the other side are content that that should happen. For my entire
political life, I have been travelling throughout the WHOLE of
Ireland to universities, rotary clubs, chambers of commerce,
basically wherever I'm asked to speak to people from the other
tradition. Often I've wondered whether I am merely entertainment or
being tolerated as a token Unionist or if there is a genuine desire
to try to understand the Unionist point of view. The last few weeks
have left me with grave doubts. I'm quite disheartened but like my
colleagues, I will continue to communicate with those from the
nationalist tradition in the hope that this will ultimately bear
fruit. Already, in the 1992 talks process, Ulster Unionists put
proposals on the table which would involve Nationalists
(constitutional) at every level within a Northern Ireland
administration. We went to Dublin to negotiate with the Irish
government, we proposed a Bill of Rights, but each of these efforts
was ignored by John Hume's SDLP and the Irish government, which
responded by seeking to do a deal with our own government behind the
backs of Unionists.</P>

<P>To summarise, these people have shown that they will talk AT us
and ABOUT us but are unwilling to talk MEANINGFULLY TO us.</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> Dual asks - Does Mr Maginnis agree that the
more recent extreme activity has been caused by the exclusion of Sinn
Fein? Have these people lost their constitutional right by voting for
Sinn Fein?</P>

<P><B>Ken Maginnis:</B> That question is the same as suggesting that
the victim of a serious crime is more responsible than the person who
actually committed the offence. Sinn Fein have been told that they
can enter the democratic process, when they are prepared to accept
the responsibilities that go with this. It's not a question of anyone
excluding Sinn Fein but one where they against the wishes of both
governments and all constitutional political parties insist on
excluding themselves. They have only to indicate their willingness to
abide by the same peaceful means as other political parties within
the process, and they can be admitted but obviously, one of the first
things that will then be required is a practical demonstration of
their long-term sincerity. They need to disarm. What would any
constitutional party want with over 100 tonnes of modern
sophisticated weapons and bombs?</P>

<P><B>Paul Eedle:</B> Our last question. TineBeag in Dublin asks - Do
you think that a solution satisfactory to all could involve Northern
Ireland staying within the UK but with greater links (including
executive and not just advisory powers) to the Republic of Ireland,
one step short of power-sharing but a constitutional arrangement that
perhaps hasn't been tried anywhere else in the world yet?</P>

<P><B>Ken Maginnis:</B> I think that this is almost what Ulster
Unionists want and have been suggesting with the exception of
executive powers for the Republic. It would simply not be practical
to have another government which has no electoral mandate in Northern
Ireland and no accountability involved in the day-to-day affairs of
this part of the United Kingdom. However there could be something
which was more than advisory which would involve meaningful, ongoing
dialogue on a whole range of issues. All this has been proposed as
far back as 1992 by the Ulster Unionist Party but rejected as
inadequate by Nationalists. There is no practical evidence that the
Nationalists are willing to try to create a series of Confidence
Building Measures which Ulster Unionists have ALWAYS believed are
necessary. After centuries of distrust, the cycle of fear and
suspicion can only be broken in this way.</P>

<P><HR><A HREF="index.html">OutThere logoBack</A> to
OutThere home page</P>
</BODY>
