<html>
<head>
<title>PAF PROACTIVE FILE 19</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG align=middle src="../euforic/images/eustep.jpg"></CENTER>
<CENTER>
<H3>PAF PROACTIVE FILE<BR>
Regular News Update From Eurostep No. 19 Friday 6 September 1996 </CENTER>
</H3>

<P>
<CENTER>
<H4>EUROSTEP<BR>
115 Rue St&eacute;vin, B-1000 Brussels, Belgium<BR>
Tel.: (32)-2-2311659 / Fax: (32)-2-2303780<BR>
E-mail: <A href="mailto:eurostep@knooppunt.be">eurostep@knooppunt.be</A></CENTER>
</H4>
<HR>
<P>
<p align=justify><b>1.	MASSIVE CUTS TO THE EU DEVELOPMENT COOPERATION BUDGET</b></p>
<p align=justify>The European Union is in the middle of the 1997 EU Budget procedure. The Council has proposed massive cuts of 289 MECU to development cooperation expenditure (53% of the overall cut in external relations and a 13% decrease compared to the 1996 Budget). The cuts are particularly evident when one looks at individual development cooperation budget lines - budget lines focused on cooperation measures decrease by 27%; the NGO co-financing line decreases 13.8%; rehabilitation in development countries decreases 23.4%; and other lines such as women and development and landmines are deleted. The amounts cut from these budget lines have been transferred to the EU's MEDA programme (Measures to accompany the reforms to the economic and social structures in the Mediterranean non-member countries) - the Council proposes 842 MECU (a 109% increase) to be allocated to this line.</p>
<p align=justify>The draft budget cuts a total of 546.8 MECU from various existing external relations' budget lines. The agreed ceiling on external expenditure allows at most 312.3 MECU of this reduction to be re-instated. In addition to the re-instating of nearly 300 MECU that amendments tabled at the EP Development Committee will propose, it is expected that amendments by the EP's other two external committees will seek the re-instatement of other budget lines.</p>
<p align=justify>The Development Committee will table amendments to reinstate 1996 budget amounts for development cooperation. To do this they will most likely propose 234.5 MECU be taken from the proposed MEDA line increase and redistributed to developing countries. The MEDA line would then still be increased to 607.5 MECU (51% increase over 1996).</p>
<p align=justify><b>2.	THE GREEN PAPER AND THE LOME CONVENTION</b></p>
<p align=justify>The battle to revamp the lom&eacute; Convention, the trade and aid agreement linking the European Union to 70 ACP states, starts in autumn. European Commissioner Jo&atilde;o de Deus Pinheiro will trigger the long-awaited public debate on the future of the Convention by publishing a Green Paper in October. Comments will then be sought from EU and ACP governments, the European Parliament, NGOs, academics and business leaders.</p>
<p align=justify>Under the convention's rules, negotiations on its future must open at least 18 months before the pacts runs out. To keep this calendar, the Commission will ask ACP and EU representatives to give their views on the future of the convention in the first half of 1997. Pinheiro will then drawn up a formal negotiating mandate for ministerial approval at the end of 1997. Negotiations will open officially with the ACP group in September 1998.</p>
<p align=justify>The Commission says it is going into the difficult debate with a completely open mind. But it will not be easy.</p>
<p align=justify>"Poor nations are loosing their economic significance to us", says Dieter Frisch, a former Commissioner director-general for development. "There is a growing feeling that development policy has not achieved a great deal, especially in the very area where most aid has been directed: Africa. This provides enough pretext to cut development aid at a time of budgetary constraints". Frisch argues that the spirit of North-South partnership and dialogue engendered by the Lom&eacute; Convention are worth preserving.</p>
<p align=justify>The ACP states have not worked out a joint position on the future of Lom&eacute;. But while critical of some aspects of the convention, most ACP representatives insist that the pact should be preserved.</p>
<p align=justify>"The Lom&eacute; Convention has made a significant contribution to alleviating poverty and providing jobs", says Lingston Cumberbatch, current 'president' of the ACP group of ambassadors in Brussels. "What we want to see is a good and effective convention which encourages investments in the ACP states and supports the private sector".</p>
<p align=justify>ACP representatives also say they want a new Lom&eacute; Convention which is "user-friendly and non-bureaucratic". The ACP business leaders argue that the convention is much too complex and technically complicated".</p>
<p align=justify>The Commission's Green paper will look closely at the issue of "differentiation": i.e. suggestions that instead of working with an unwieldy group of  70 ACP nations, the EU should hammer out separate agreements with ACP regions or even sub-regions.</p>
<p align=justify><b>3.	EU-ASEAN RELATIONSHIP</b></p>
<p align=justify>When ten Asian presidents and prime ministers met 15 EU leaders for a summit in Bangkok six months ago, a lot of promises were made by the Europeans while Asian talked about finally finding a seat on the international scene.</p>
<p align=justify>Now they are getting down to business and discovering that things are not that easy. The two sides disagree on many principles and most details. Quarrels over human rights are straining political closeness and spats over labour standards are hindering trade talks. Disappointment with each other and broken ranks on either side are now becoming increasingly evident.</p>
<p align=justify>But trade is, and will continue to be, the crux of the relationship which is bringing Europe closer to China, Japan, South Korea and the nations of Southeast Asia. The two sides also have a political forum in which to discuss security matters -the Asian Regional Forum (ARF)- which is growing in importance almost daily.</p>
<p align=justify>With some 425 million people and high economic growth (its members' combined average annual growth rate is 7.25% - three times that of the Union), the ASEAN bloc also controls some of the world's most crucial shipping routes.</p>
<p align=justify>"Effective recognition of ASEAN's leading role should push the European Union to make it a focal point of its political presence in Asia", said External Relations Commissioner Manuel Marin. Calling for yearly meetings of political experts in fields such as maritime safety, nuclear capacity, drug trafficking and peacekeeping, the Commissioner continues: "Despite many contacts and important programmes, we are witnessing a regrettably static application of our agreement".</p>
<p align=justify>The ARF already provides a forum for discussion on subjects such as nuclear weapons and landmines with all the major players on the Asian continent. It groups foreign ministers of the EU, China, Japan, Russia, the US, India and ASEAN, and Pakistan has applied to join.</p>
<p align=justify>Two events rattled participants at the ARF's July ministerial meeting in Jakarta. But they also demonstrated how important its members perceive the forum to be.</p>
<p align=justify>Arguing that their status as nuclear powers gave them reason to be there in a capacity distinct from that of the EU, the UK and France applied to join, angering their Union partners.</p>
<p align=justify>Subsequently, when Myanmar (Burma) was admitted to the forum, EU governments protested over Rangoon's political and human rights record. Having returned home from the Bangkok summit with the understanding that Europeans would not preach to Asians, the latter were upset by what they saw as Union backtracking.</p>
<p align=justify>Burma is just as divisive an issue within the EU itself. As both France and the UK have economic interests in Burma, they would probably reject the sanctions that other EU partners have already hinted at, and the Union looks set to continue wrestling with Burmese rights problems as it has for years with Indonesia over East Timor.</font></p>
<HR>
<H6><I>Updated on September 25, 1996<BR>
