<h6>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="../oxfam.html">OXFAM UK&I</a></h6><hr><p>


<h2 align=center>AID WORKS</h2>

<blockquote><i>"Properly applied in propitious environments, aid works." </i></blockquote>
<ul>
Development Assistance Committee of the OECD: <br>Shaping the 21st Century: the Contribution of Development Co-operation.</ul><p>


As we approach the next century, we should remember that the campaign to end world poverty was one of this century's greatest initiatives. <p>

<li>   Mortality rates of young children living in the Third World are almost half what they were
50 years ago. <font size=2>16</font><p>

<li>   The number of people with direct access to safe water has doubled in 50 years (from 35 to 70 per cent). <font size=2>17</font><p>

<li>   The percentage of 6-11 year-olds enrolled at primary school rose from 48 per cent in 1960 to 77 per cent in 1995. <font size=2>18</font><p>

<li>   Immunisation has protected more than 100 million infants over a ten-year period and saved more than 20 million lives. <font size=2>19</font> <p>

<li>   Endemic in 31 countries in 1967, smallpox was eradicated in the late 1970s.20 Between 1980 and 1990 the incidence of polio around the world dropped from 630,000 to 116,000.21 Ten years ago, 75 million children contracted measles each year, and 2.5 million died. Today, 50 million fewer children contract measles and one million children die. <font size=2>22</font><p>

<li>   Life expectancy in the Third World has increased from 41 to 62 years in 50 years. <font size=2>23</font> <p>

<li>   Primary-school attendance rose by 29 per cent between 1960 and 1995. <font size=2>24</font>

<p><hr>


<center>
