<head>
<title>CASE FOR AID</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
</a><br clear=all><br>
<h6>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="../oxfam.html">OXFAM UK&I</a></h6><hr><p>

<h2 align=center>
SPEND NOW, SAVE LATER</h2>

Aid takes a long-term view of development and growth, based on the belief that by spending now, we save later. <p>

Aid saves lives by providing vaccines for immunisation, or investing in sustainable social-service provision such as health and sanitation systems. It can also reduce expenditure in the future. Failures to invest in development can contribute to social and environmental crises, conflict, and breakdown in state and community structures, which all carry high costs for rich and poor countries. 
<p>

<h4>Spend now, save lives</h4>

Aid has contributed to the fall in child mortality across developing countries. Even so, almost 20 per cent of children living in sub-Saharan Africa die before they are five. Most die from preventable diseases. At a cost to each British tax-payer of no more than a few pence, those children could be saved. <p>


<h4>Spend now, save money</h4>

Complex humanitarian emergencies have broken out in dramatic form in the last decade. Managing them has been highly expensive for Western governments and their taxpayers.<p>


<h4>The cost of conflict</h4>

<blockquote><i>"The message from the conflict born of this poverty is that international security is best built on International Solidarity, in which the wealthiest nations help the poorest out of the poverty that breeds conflict. It is in our own interests to do so, because our troops will be called upon to serve to prevent the conflicts."</i></blockquote> <p>

<ul>Speech by the Shadow Foreign Secretary, Robin Cook MP, Hansard 17 November 1994.</ul><p>


Since the end of the Cold War there have been more regional conflicts and civil wars than at any time this century. Of the 82 major armed conflicts that occurred between 1989 and 1992, all but three were within rather than between states.25<p>

The cost of fire-fighting such social disasters is high. More money must be spent, sometimes for generations, as communities rebuild themselves. 
Emergency aid has risen dramatically to respond to these crises. But because overall aid levels are not rising, it is at the expense of long-term development budgets.<p>

<li>   ODA's expenditure on emergencies rose from £129 million in 1990/1 to £334 million in 1994/5.26<p>

<li>   The British government's contribution to peacekeeping operations soared from £32 million in 1990/1 to an estimated £275 million in 1995/6.27 <p>


<h4>Bedfellows: poverty and war</h4>

The majority of the internal or domestic wars in the world today are occurring in the least- developed countries. Though many factors contribute to the outbreak of conflict, poverty is a root cause. <p>

States and societies that are poor are prone to conflict. It is very difficult for governments to govern adequately when their people cannot afford to pay taxes, and industry and trade are virtually non-existent. When resources are scarce, they are likely to be monopolised by political lites. Aid can itself then become a source of conflict. <p>

This was true in Somalia, where factions and clans fought over access to food, water points, and goods looted in the capital, Mogadishu. This conflict in turn caused a famine which took the lives of an estimated 250,000 children. The West's ineffective response was to send aid and troops costing billions of pounds. <p>

Long-term development programmes to reduce poverty can help to stabilise societies which are extremely poor.<p>


<h4>Lack of political will</h4>

Nevertheless, aid cannot substitute for political action.<p>


<h4>Disaster preparedness</h4>

Fewer and fewer of the disasters in the world today can be described as natural. They are increasingly complex and man-made, linked to conflict and scarcity of resources, and to international economic policies. Aid can help to avert or mitigate their effect. <p>


<h4>Spend now, save the environment</h4>

Poverty is a major cause of environmental degradation. In countries heavily dependent on natural resources, environmental pressures are increasingly contributing to large-scale food shortages, migration, and conflicts. Regional conflicts in western Sudan and Ethiopia are closely linked to displacement of people caused by soil degradation and desertification. When people are deprived of economic choices by their poverty, they exhaust their natural resources in order to survive Ð for example by cutting trees for firewood or hunting animals to the point of eradication. <p>

In such cases, sensitive aid is a valuable tool which can prevent the destruction of irreplaceable eco-systems and protect resources essential for the future.<p>


<h4>Environmental refugees</h4>

Aid can also reduce the number of environmental refugees. Where poor people lack the knowledge or the resources to adapt to environmental changes, they have no option but to migrate. Well-designed aid can make it possible for communities to manage in new conditions. <p>

<p><hr>
<center>
