<head>
<title>CASE FOR AID</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
</a><br clear=all><br>
<h6>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="../oxfam.html">OXFAM UK&I</a></h6><hr><p>

<h2 align=center>AID IS A HAND-UP NOT A HAND-OUT</h2>

Aid helps people to help themselves. It gives a hand-up to individuals, communities, and nations. It is not the subsidy or hand-out that some perceive aid to be. <p>

It helps people to escape from poverty. It can be a catalyst for long-term change. And by providing resources over a period of time which do not create debt, it gives people the chance to take control of their own development. <p>

As such it is an investment in the future. <p>


<h4>A hand-up for people</h4>

<blockquote><i>"Aid is not just a financial flow and should not be thought of as substituting for private investment...aid is a partnership with the recipient..."</i></blockquote>
<ul>ODA: Fundamental Expenditure Review. </ul><p>

NGOs and official donors have been helping people to help themselves for several decades. They have learned to employ a range of techniques that enable people to improve the quality of their lives. <p>

Improving the sanitation systems in city slums means that children can wash without fear of disease and death. Investing in education means that girls can learn to read Ð and thereby broaden the future for their children. Helping to increase household incomes means that families can save for the future and become economically more independent.<p>


<h4>A hand-up for communities</h4>

Aid can help entire communities and social groups. Good aid invests in services that directly help the poor and meet long-term needs of their communities.<p>

Private markets generally do not invest in basic services that target the poor, such as primary health care or girls' and women's education. In its 1993 World Development Report on health, the World Bank acknowledged that 'private markets will not give the poor adequate access to essential clinical services or the insurance often needed to pay for such services'. <p>

Education is one of the most effective ways of giving women independence and power, and it brings financial benefits to an entire community. The World Bank has shown that health and education programmes bring high economic returns at relatively low cost. It reported that wages increase by more than 10Ð20 per cent for each additional year of schooling.29 The return is often higher among women than men.<p>


<h4>A hand-up for countries</h4>

Aid can be a hand-up not only for individuals and communities, but for whole countries. It can build infrastructure, give support to balance of payments, help to feed the population, transfer skills, and support participation in civil society.<p>


<blockquote><i>"Overseas aid...is a means of bridging the gap between the resources (domestic and foreign) which a poor country has access to, and the resources which it needs before it can achieve growth at a level which will reduce poverty." </i></blockquote>
<ul>ODA, Fundamental Expenditure Review, 1995.</ul><p>


<h4>Aid and private investment</h4>

Aid is one source of capital for the developing world; another is private investment. <p>

Some argue that private investment can do the job that aid does Ð and better. But private investment is not attracted to low-income countries that cannot offer relevant human skills, a productive infrastructure, good economic management or essential public services. Poorer countries need large-scale transfers of financial aid and know-how before these things can be achieved. <p>

In consequence, while private investors are responsible for 60 per cent of capital flows to the developing world, their investment is uneven. Sub-Saharan Africa attracts almost no private capital and therefore depends heavily on aid for 70 per cent of its external capital.32<p>

Of course, foreign aid can pave the way for future private investment. It can strengthen transport and communications systems and energy provision and so directly influence the attitudes of private investors.33 Without progress in these areas, and in education and health, poorer countries are unlikely to attract private capital. <p>


<h4>Emerging democracies</h4>

Aid can help countries along the road to a fairer, more responsible system of government. It can be used to promote participation in the political process.<p>

From providing ballot boxes and monitoring elections to supporting unions and women's organisations and community groups, aid can be an effective tool in helping people establish their democratic rights. It can help to develop a fairer, more accountable system of government, both in developing countries and in the transitional societies of eastern Europe. 
Government to government aid should be conditional on the recipient government's respect for human and basic rights, to ensure that aid is not used for repression or personal gain. Aid can provide a powerful lever to encourage compliance with internationally agreed standards.<p>

<p><hr>
