<title>CASE FOR AID</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
</a><br clear=all><br>
<h6>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="../oxfam.html">OXFAM UK&I</a></h6><hr><p>

<h2 align=center>IN ALL OUR INTERESTS</h2>


<h4>National self-interest</h4>

Aid helps the British economy and also promotes Britain's interests in a rapidly changing world. It is a vital instrument for tackling the transnational problems which affect everyone, regardless of geography. It can create a sense of shared responsibility and citizenship in a world where nations are increasingly interdependent. <p>


<blockquote><i>"There is a strong humanitarian impulse to do what we can to alleviate that poverty. There is an equally strong argument of enlightened self-interest." </i></blockquote>
<ul>Speech by the Rt Hon Malcolm Rifkind QC MP,<br> 
Secretary for State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, Diplomatic Banquet, 11 June 1996</ul><p>


<h4>Aid and the economy</h4>

NGOs believe that aid should reduce poverty and promote sustainable development. We remain critical of any forms of aid that do not primarily seek to achieve these objectives. But we accept that good aid can also benefit Britain's economy.<p>

Britain is in a strong position to supply skills and products for international development, and British firms are competitive in many areas. Economic benefits from aid should support the competitive sectors of British industry, while meeting the development needs of the poor; they should not be a temporary or wasteful subsidy. <p>

On balance the evidence is that those who receive aid are best served by untying aid, preferably by international agreement. Our own national interests also benefit. The OECD has demonstrated that tied aid reduces the value of aid by at least 15 per cent. Government figures (which are not entirely precise) suggest that the British economy earns about £1.40 for every £1.00 that Britain contributes towards multilateral aid programmes.34<p>


<blockquote><i>"We want to see the decline in British Aid reversed and rapid progress made to achieve the UN target of 0.7 per cent of GNP. Cutting the appalling toll of suffering and death from poverty is a moral challenge to all people of good will: meeting it would be good for all, in terms of jobs and economic growth globally. Aid isn't just about giving: British jobs depend on it."</i></blockquote> <p>

<ul>John Monks, General Secretary of The Trades Union Congress.</ul><p>


<blockquote><i>"A small part of the bilateral aid programme specifically supports projects that are developmentally sound and of industrial and commercial significance to the UK. This has enabled Britain to promote hundreds of sound projects in over fifty countries, and has paid for itself many times over in terms of additional UK jobs and exports. As with the rest of the bilateral budget, it has been cut back in recent years. An increase, as part of a larger total budget, would help developing countries and boost British jobs." </i></blockquote><p>

<ul>Alick Goldsmith, Director General, Export Group for the Constructional Industries.</ul><p>

In the long term the economic returns will be even more important. By the end of this century 80 per cent of the world's population will be in developing countries, which will generate 50 per cent of global economic output. Impoverished, war-torn, debt-ridden countries do not provide markets for British goods and services. Investing in their development today can enable poorer countries to become Britain's future trading partners.<p>

Twenty years ago the Asian tigers were heavily dependent on international aid. Now South-East Asia buys some £5 billion of British exports each year, and contains some of our fastest-growing trading partners.<p>


<h4>International influence</h4>

<blockquote><i>"In recent years Britain has punched above her weight in the world. 
We intend to keep it that way." </i></blockquote><ul>

Mr Hurd, then Foreign Secretary, reported in The Daily Telegraph, 1 January 1992.</ul><p>

As a member of some of the world's most influential decision-making bodies, Britain has political and economic influence on the international stage. A substantial aid programme is required if Britain is to fulfil its responsibilities in these bodies. <p>


British diplomatic initiatives are likely to be more effective where they are supported by aid for reconstruction and development.<p>


<hr><p>


<h3>WIDER INTERESTS</h3>

Poverty exacerbates, where it does not create, general international problems. Crime, drugs, migration, the spread of epidemics and preventable diseases, environmental degradation and global warming Ð these are global problems requiring urgent global solutions. It is in the future economic, political, and security interests of richer and poorer countries to invest in aid programmes that can go some way towards meeting these challenges. <p>


<h4>Drug trafficking </h4>

International drugs policies are failing because they place too much emphasis on control and not enough on tackling the root causes, such as rural poverty in the South and social alienation in the North, according to research by the Catholic Institute for International Relations. <p>

Forced eradication of drug crops like coca and poppies can lead to social unrest, instability, and human-rights abuses. Without a reduction in demand for drugs, forced eradication also increases environmental damage by displacing drug cultivation to new areas. <p>

Poor farmers grow coca because their options for earning a legitimate income are so limited. Aid can help farmers to gain better access to domestic and international markets for alternative crops.<p>


<h4>The environment </h4>

Without extensive technology transfer and aid, it is likely that industrialisation in developing countries will generate similar (or worse) destructive side-effects to the ones that are familiar in Northern countries. Goods produced by the most polluting and destructive processes are mostly consumed in industrialised countries, which should share the responsibility for their local and global impact. The principle that environmental protection is in the interests of both the industrialised and developing world is enshrined in international treaties to control climate change and prevent destruction of the ozone layer and biodiversity loss. These treaties were signed at the 1992 Rio Conference on the Environment and Development.<p>

Well-targeted aid can promote cleaner production and help to maintain the productivity of renewable resources, such as fisheries, plantations, and forests. Aid can enable producer countries to earn more by processing and refining their products locally.<p>


<blockquote><i>"The pressures of poverty are eroding the environment of the Third World. Because we share a single globe, that damage threatens the climate on which we depend for our standard of living."</i><ul>
Robin Cook, Shadow Foreign Secretary, Hansard, 17 November 1994.</blockquote></ul><p>


<h4>Global awareness</h4>
If Britain is to play its part in meeting the challenges of the twenty-first century, today's citizens and their children will need to understand the relationships that bind the world's peoples ever closer together. Never before has it been so important to encourage respect for the diversity of cultures that share stewardship of our earth and the complex international relationships that affect us all Ð as consumers and producers, as debtors and creditors, as donors and recipients.<p>

Given resources and commitment, the aid programme could make a significant contribution to this important area of work.35<p>

<blockquote><i>"It is essential if environmental policies are to achieve their objective, that there is wide public awareness of the issues at stake and their importance to the future of the planet and future generations. Education has an essential part to play."</i></blockquote><ul>
HM Government, This Common Inheritance: Britain's Environmental Strategy.</ul><p>


In conclusion, Britain's political leaders must realise that overseas development is no longer a problem for poorer people in poorer countries. Providing more and better-targeted aid within a consistent international policy framework is in the long-term interests of people everywhere. <p>


<blockquote><i>"Over the last thirty years, I have been privileged to witness at first hand the enormous benefits which British aid has brought to many countries, especially in Africa. From the provision of basic services to the promotion of democracy and respect for human rights, I believe that aid has played a vital role in improving people's lives. But the challenges ahead are formidable and the message to donors is clear: now is not the time to cut aid."</i></blockquote><ul>
Rt Hon Sir David Steel MP</ul><p>



<p><hr>
