<html>
<head>
<title>CASE FOR AID</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
</a><br clear=all><br>
<h6>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="../oxfam.html">OXFAM UK&I</a></h6><hr><p>

<h2 align=center>SUMMARY</h2>


<h3 align=center>WHY THIS MANIFESTO?</h3>

Against a backdrop of unprecedented decline in aid budgets in many countries, including our own, this manifesto renews the case for overseas development aid. <p>

We are at a critical point. Non-government organisations (NGOs) that specialise in Third World development believe that the gradual erosion of the aid budget year by year now poses a direct threat to aid effectiveness. The remarkable progress made since 1950 in combating world poverty will not continue into the next century, and may even be reversed. 
Such a retreat might have disastrous consequences for rich countries as well as for poor ones.<p>

Despite this danger, the political will to build on past successes and take a long-term view of aid is collapsing. The aid budget is always an easy target. During a pre-election period, however, when government departments are required to cut costs in a bid to reduce taxes, and domestic issues take precedence, overseas aid is particularly vulnerable. <p>

Yet the moral imperative for aid is stronger than ever. Advances in telecommunications, computers, and transport mean that it is no longer credible to adopt an insular world view. And in a world in which poor countries are forced to compete 'equally' in the global economy, we have more not less responsibility to take care of one another.<p>

In fact, the gap between the richest and poorest countries is wider than it has ever been. A growing number of people in the world are being excluded from global advances, while new challenges are emerging that require instant and international attention. The number of civil wars is increasing, more people are being displaced by environmental degradation, unplanned urbanisation is reaching crisis point in many countries, and old as well as new diseases are posing fresh threats to public health. <p>

This manifesto therefore urges the British government to develop a long-term vision in support of development aid. <p>


<h3>A new vision for aid in the 1990s</h3>

Decisions about the future of development assistance are increasingly guided by immediate political interests. Greater commitment and bolder policies are required if Britain is to address the human and environmental needs of the next century. <p>

For aid is not only justified on moral grounds. It makes economic and political sense. The eradication of poverty is in the economic and security interests of people in both poor and rich nations.

<p>For example, complex humanitarian emergencies like those in Rwanda or Former Yugoslavia cost the British taxpayer huge sums. Many of these conflicts are rooted in poverty. By developing preventive strategies, and investing appropriately in people, aid can help to avert these human tragedies and avoid huge public expenditure. 

<p>NGOs believe that the primary purpose of aid is to reduce poverty in developing countries, but aid also has direct benefits for Britain. It is good for the economy and for Britain's international interests. A portion of the aid budget flows back to Britain in the shape of receipts for goods and services, jobs, and research. In the longer term, it is also an investment. Impoverished, war-torn, and debt-ridden countries will not make good trading partners now or in the future. Today's recipients of British aid are tomorrow's emerging markets. 

<p>Of course aid can only be one element in a strategy to tackle world poverty. Poverty is caused or entrenched by debt, unfair trade, the arms trade and war, low investment in health and education, bad government, and many other factors. NGOs have run high-profile campaigns on these issues and their views are well documented. 

<p>But aid remains important, and this manifesto concentrates on what it can achieve. 

<h3>Our message</h3>

<li><h4>Aid works</h4>

At the right levels, and properly targeted, aid can work. It can help people who are not reached by other capital flows. The international campaign to reduce poverty Ð  in which aid has played a key role Ð remains one of the greatest achievements of this century: this effort must be renewed for the twenty-first century.<p>


<li><h4> Spend now, save later</h4>

Aid can promote long-term development and growth: by spending now, we can save lives and resources, and protect the environment.
<p>

<li><h4>Aid is a hand-up, not a hand-out</h4>

Aid can be a sound investment. It can help people to help themselves Ð and need not be the subsidy or hand-out that some perceive it to be. <p>

<p>

<li><h4> Aid is in everyone's interest </h4>
Poverty and inequality fuel transnational problems like crime, environmental degradation, mass migration, and epidemics. Aid can help to reduce or manage these threats and can therefore benefit both poorer and richer nations. 

<a name="recommendations"></a>
<p>

<h3>RECOMMENDATIONS</h3>

For aid to help in meeting the challenges of the next century, we urge the British government to support the following recommendations: <p>

<h4>Increase aid</h4>

<li>  Official aid should be sustained and increased to meet the challenges of the next century. We recommend a ten-year timetable which sets out year-on-year increases towards the universally agreed target of 0.7 per cent of GNP. (Britain's aid currently stands at 0.31 per cent.) In the first year, the extra cost would be in the region of £200 million.<p>


<h4>Reduce poverty</h4>

<li>  Aid must first and foremost be directed at reducing poverty. We recommend that the <a href="../../oda/index.html">Overseas Development Administration</a> (ODA) increase the poverty focus of its programmes and improve the access of poor people to basic social services such as primary education and health care. We recommend that the ODA should invest further in developing the skills and capacity which people need to participate in their own development and escape from the cycle of poverty. This approach is consistent with the ODA's current policies, which should be promoted in the various international organisations of which Britain is a member.<p>


<h4>Harmonise policies</h4>

<li> All policies that have an impact on developing countries should complement one another and promote development. In particular, the Treasury's management of debt, the ODA's support for structural adjustment, the Department of Trade and Industry's policies on trade and arms sales, and the activities of the Foreign and Commonwealth Office should support rather than undermine the ODA's development objectives.<p>

<p><hr>
<center>
