<head>
<title>CASE FOR AID</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
</a><br clear=all><br>
<h6>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="../oxfam.html">OXFAM UK&I</a></h6><hr><p>

<h2 align=center>THE NEW MORAL IMPERATIVE</h2>

<blockquote><i>"I have seen repeatedly on my travels throughout the Anglican Communion what a vital contribution the British aid programme makes in developing countries. In countries like Sudan it can mean the difference between life and death for thousands."</i></blockquote>
<ul>
	George Carey, Archbishop of Canterbury, June 1996</ul><p>


For so long as poverty and exclusion prevent people from achieving their basic needs, and as long as richer countries can help to meet those needs, the moral case for aid remains. It is this moral imperative that drives the activities of development NGOs, which exist to eradicate poverty and ensure that basic needs are met.<p>

The moral imperative for aid is stronger than ever as we near the end of the twentieth century. Advances in telecommunications, transport, and information technologies have brought us closer together. We can no longer distance ourselves from the suffering of others. <p>

Developed countries contribute in many ways to the growing inequality between nations. They have helped to cause the indebtedness of Third World states, and set trade rules that disadvantage poorer countries. Above all, perhaps, they consume a disproportionate share of the world's resources. Richer countries should therefore accept that they have a duty to reduce world poverty, and share the tasks of managing the world's resources and resolving the world's problems equitably. <p>

In the longer term, it is in the interests not just of ourselves but also our children to create a fairer and more orderly world.<p>



<h4>Future challenges</h4>

Today, one in every five of the world's people is excluded from recent global advances, even in countries that have experienced growth. And the absolute number of poor people is increasing. <p>

In addition, new challenges are emerging. We must deal with complex emergencies that combine war with natural disasters, with rapid unplanned urbanisation, and with the spread of new and old diseases.<p>

<li>   One-fifth of the world's population still live in absolute poverty.7<p>

<li>   35,000 children die every day from preventable diseases.8<p>

<li>   In the developing world, 1.3 billion people lack clean drinking water and 2.9 billion do not have safe sanitation.9<p>

<li>	An estimated 40 million people will be infected with HIV by the year 2000, most of them in the developing world.10<p>

<li>	The poorest 50 countries, mostly in Africa, are home to one-fifth of the world's population but account for less than two per cent of global income.11 <p>

<li>	Nearly 800 million people do not get enough food, and 500 million people are chronically malnourished.12<p>

<li>	About 600,000 women die in childbirth each year.13<p>

<li>	The number of refugees increased nine-fold in 20 years (between 1974 and 1994) to 27 million. Another 15 million are displaced (as refugees in their own country).14 <p>

<li>	As many as 700,000 square kilometres of farmland are abandoned every year because of land degradation and about four million hectares of unirrigated cropland are lost annually as a result of soil erosion.15

<p><hr>
