<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<P>
<CENTER><IMG align=middle src="../euforic/images/eustep.jpg"></CENTER>
<H3><CENTER>PAF PROACTIVE FILE<BR>
Regular News Update From Eurostep No. 28 Friday 29 November 1996
</CENTER></H3>
<H4><CENTER>EUROSTEP<BR>
115 Rue St&eacute;vin, B-1000 Brussels, Belgium<BR>
Tel.: (32)-2-2311659 / Fax: (32)-2-2303780<BR>
E-mail: <A href="mailto:eurostep@knooppunt.be">eurostep@knooppunt.be</A></CENTER>
</H4>
<HR>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>1. MILITARY ACTION STILL REQUIRED IN ZAIRE - EMMA
BONINO</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>European Humanitarian Affairs Commissioner Emma Bonino
reiterated her appeal for military action in Zaire on Tuesday
25 November. She expressed her exasperation over the situation
describing the inability of military chiefs and political leaders
to appraise the conditions, location and the number of people
in distress as &quot;amazing&quot;. Mrs. Bonino said that the
&quot;only straightforward answer to the problem is to organise
a military intervention for assessment in the area.&quot; She
stressed that the international community could no longer tolerate
that the destiny of hundreds of thousands of innocent people be
determined in the absence of international action or relief. Mrs
Bonino had earlier on in the week raised the poignant question
of how many refugees lives should be endangered to merit military
action asking whether the figure 700 000 refugees or a million
was enough to justify action.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Also earlier on Monday the EU Council of Foreign
Ministers meeting on Monday 25 November said that they still felt
an international force was needed to assist the refugees in East
Zaire. France and Spain recalled their willingness to contribute
men to the force, however, British Foreign Minister cautioned
that it was difficult to take any action without an overall view
of the situation. The Council also welcomed the European Commission's
decision to provide a Community contribution from ECHO for the
UN Trust Fund and stressed on the need for the early convening
of an international conference on peace and stability in the region
under the auspices of the Organisation for African Unity and the
UN.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>On the same day the Rwandan government announced
that it will not permit the use of its territory by a multinational
force and added that it viewed military intervention as unnecessary
in contradiction to the advice of the head of the Medecins Sans
Frontieres mission in Kigali.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>2. EU DEVELOPMENT COUNCIL APPROVES OF WIDE RANGE
OF DEVELOPMENT RESOLUTIONS INCLUDING MEASURES CONCERNING CRISIS
IN ZAIRE</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>The EU Development Council approved a wide range
of items on Friday 22 November with the main focus centring on
the persistent crisis in the Great Lakes Region. On this issue
the Council backed the urgent implementation of the UN Security
Council resolution to convey aid to East Zaire and facilitate
free return of refugees to their countries of origin. The Council
also adopted a joint action which calls for voluntary contributions
supporting African participation in a multinational force. A budget
of 15 million ECU is envisaged for this action. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Other items adopted were a) a Human and Social Development
Co-operation policy geared towards the development of man with
particular emphasis on poverty alleviation and sustainable development;
b) a conclusion on anti-personnel mines calling for the implementation
of mine clearance operations, the immediate cessation of the use
and marketing of anti-personnel mines and the creation of an international
planning strategy; c) conclusions on recommending the idea of
equality between men and women in crisis prevention, emergency
aid and rehabilitation; d) conclusions calling for the assessment
of humanitarian aid granted since 1991 in the light of the Court
of Auditors report to be presented before the end of the year.
Readers interested in obtaining copies of the press release of
the Council Meeting can contact the nearest Council office or
the Eurostep Secretariat for details on specific issues. <BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>3. MANUEL OREJA REPORTS ON THE IGC </FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>In his latest report of the proceedings of the InterGovernmental
Conference, EC Audio-visual Commissioner, Marcelino Oreja said
that the recent Heads of State and Governments reaffirmed the
determination to conclude the Conference by the end of June 1997.
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>On the Common Foreign and Security Policy, CFSP,
little progress has been made, the recent Foreign Ministers Meeting
on 28 November failed to resolve a single one of the issues considered
to be stalling progress, i.e. the definition of the objectives
and the structures needed to conduct those policies and the voting
procedures in the Council of Ministers. According to Mr. Oreja
the lack of progress is due to insufficient trust between the
Member States and between them and the Commission. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>On the issue of defence, the Union envisages bearing
a share of peacekeeping and humanitarian operation responsibilities
in other parts of the world. Co-operation with NATO will also
continue. Mr Oreja, however said that a more effective solution
for the foreign policy problem, which is a vital aspect of the
conference, will have to be sought. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Finally a schedule for forthcoming IGC events is
included in Mr. Oreja's report. Readers interested in copies of
the report and schedule for the next two months can contact Marcelino
Oreja at the European Commission, Rue de la Loi 200, 1040 Brussels.
Tel. + 00 32 299 11 11<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>4. UNHCR FOLLOW UP TO CONFERENCE ON REFUGEES</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>In the follow-up to the <I>Regional Conference to
Address the Problems of Refugees, Displaced Persons, Other Forms
of Involuntary Displacement and Returnees in the Commonwealth
of Independent</I> <I>States and Relevant Neighbouring States,
</I>the UNHCR, has initiated a number of activities to involve
national and international NGOs in monitoring the progress made
after the Conference. The principal area of focus will be the
sharing of information among governments, NGOs, the media and
the general public and the enhancement of NGO participation in
the follow-up to the Conference. A directory and database of NGOs
concerned with the refugee problem in the former Soviet Union
is being set up to provide information, including the UNHCR/IOM
bulletin <I>CISCOF NEWS,</I> to the relevant NGOs. All interested
institutions should contact Kirsti Floor, UNHCR Policy Officer
(NGOs) CIS Conference Regional Bureau for Europe to ask for a
questionnaire for the database and further information. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>5. NEW PUBLICATIONS<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<U><B><FONT SIZE=2>Rarer than Rubies</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2> Reflections
on Development Cooperation</FONT></U><FONT SIZE=2> by Max van
de Berg and Bram van Oijk of Dutch development agency NOVIB. <I>A
critique on Dutch aid policies and a fresh assessment of the power
relations and interests that determine it.<BR>
</I></FONT>
<P>
<U><B><FONT SIZE=2>La Coop&eacute;ration Belge au Developpement
</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>Aide ou Business</FONT></U><FONT SIZE=2>
by Pierre Galland and Gabrielle </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Lef&egrave;vre. <I>An examination of development
co-operation in Belgium and its links to business and political
aims of Belgium.</I>(Contact Pierre Galland, 115 rue St&eacute;vin,
1000 Brussels. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Tel. + 231 01 74<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<U><B><FONT SIZE=2>Hunger and the Global Agenda</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>
Who Wins ... Who Loses .... Who Cares?</FONT></U><FONT SIZE=2>
by ACTIONAID.</FONT>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2>A report on the current state of affairs on international
co-operation on food aid presented at the recent World Food Summit.</FONT></I><FONT SIZE=2>
(Copies of the report can be obtained from Laura Kelly, ACTIONAID,
Hamlyn House, Macdonald Road, Archway, London N19 5PG, UK) </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Tel. +171 2821 4101, Fax. +171 272 0899<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<U><B><FONT SIZE=2>The Ministerial Conference in Singapore and
the Developing Countries</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2> An Introduction</FONT></U><FONT SIZE=2>
by Myriam vander Stichele. <I>An introduction to the World Trade
Organisation for NGOs with details on a selection of important
developmental issues to be discussed at the forthcoming WTO Ministerial
Conference in December.</I> (Five available copies of the booklet
remain at the Eurostep Secretariat in Brussels or otherwise contact
Myriam vander Stichele, Tel. +31 20 662 66 08</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Fax. + 31 20 675 71 76)<BR>
