</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Transcript of 'Credit Where It's Due'</title></head><body><img  width=156  height=84 alt="[  ONEWORLD ONLINE ]" src="../owo_logos/online_logo.gif"><p><hr><br><font size=+1>The following is the transcript of <b>'Credit Where It's Due'</b>, a television programme made by Word-Pictures in conjunction with Worldview International Foundation.  <br><b>OneWorld Online</b> thanks Arne Fjortoft for his kind permission to broadcast this WIF/Word-Pictures report.</font><hr><p><center><h1>Micro-loans</h1></center>Micro-loans - very small amounts of money, sometimes no more than a few rupees or taka, loaned to people who cannot afford to offer banks property as collateral -  are of key importance in alleviating poverty. <p>The Grameen Banking system was founded by Dr Mohammed Yunus in 1976 to provide micro-loans to poor people excluded by the conventional banking system - which believes, mistakenly, that poor people are bad credit risks. <p>Women, in particular, have been rejected as customers, by bankers who still see women as 'only housewives' - ignoring the enormous value of women's work, not only in the home but also outside it as agricultural and industrial workers.<p>Two decades later, at the <a href="beijing_intro.html#banking">Fourth World Conference for Women</a> in Beijing, there are suggestions that the World Bank is thinking of following in Dr Yunus' footsteps. The Bank is, at last, considering lending amounts of $100 and up, rather than $10,000 and up - and lending to women.<p>It should not be forgotten, however, that - for many people using the Grameen Banking system - $100 is a small fortune rather than a small loan. <p><hr><p><font size=+1><b><i>TITLE SEQUENCE</i></b></font><p><img width=157 height=117 align=right 1vspace 1hspace src="beijing_pix/yunus_face2.gif"><b>Dr Yunus:<ul>What we are trying to do is to demonstrate that <i>the bankers are wrong!</i> All banks should give loans to poor people.  If banks are not doing [that], then new banks should be created so that everybody can take loans. <p>We are demonstrating that poor people can take money, take credit, pay back [at a] 98%-plus repayment rate - which can change their own life. They don't have to depend on anybody. They're not asking for any mercy from anybody. <i>They simply need a fair chance, and fair deal, and justice. </i></b></ul><hr width=50%><p><center><img width=154 height=117 align=left 7vspace 3hspace src="beijing_pix/yunus_credit.gif"><p><font size=+2><b>CREDIT WHERE IT'S DUE </b></font><br><font size=+1>Dr Yunus and the Grameen Bank</font></center><p><br><br><br><br><br><br>Woman's voice:<ul>Bangladesh has some of the richest soils in the world - but most of us can't benefit from that fact. Out of the 100 million people in our country, 60 million of us own no land at all. Just 8% of the families own nearly half the crop-land - and they keep all the profits. <img width=152 height=117 align=right 20vspace 15hspace src="beijing_pix/yunus_landlord.gif">Our families just work the land for them, and they pay us next to nothing. <p>We would prefer to buy land and become independent farmers - but where could we get the credit? If we borrow money from the rich, they force us to repay our debt at impossible times; they're blackmailing us into selling them at a loss everything we own. <p><i>So they end up with everything - and our families with nothing. And the more inequality there is, the more our fate will slide into their hands. </i><p>As for banks! The only time we ever got credit out of a rich man's bank was when Mohammed Yunus came to visit our village, many years ago.</ul><b>Dr Yunus: </b><ul><b>In the beginning I didn't think about [creating a] bank: all I was trying to do was to take a loan from the bank for poor people in the village that I met. <img width=154 height=117 align=left 15vspace 15hspace src="beijing_pix/yunus_young.gif">But the bank was very reluctant.  They thought it was impossible to lend money to poor people. <p>Ultimately, the only way I could find to get this loan was to offer myself as a guarantor.  <p>So I became a guarantor, and took the money from the bank, and gave the money to poor people.  And I took the responsibility of collecting it back, and paying it back to the bank.  And it worked beautifully! <p>That was in 1976. It was working well, so I got very excited and wanted to expand it to give more people similar loans - to show that poor people can take money and pay it back. And they did.</b> <p></ul></ul><img width=152 height=117 align=right 15vspace 15hspace src="beijing_pix/yunus_banking.gif">Woman's voice: <ul>So Dr Yunus began Grameen Banking, which means "village" banking. We're neighbours - we know and trust each other - so we take turns being guarantors for one other, just like Dr Yunus used to. <p>We meet in the village in groups - and now there are Grameen Banks in over 30,000 villages. We, the people of Bangladesh, are solving our credit crisis ourselves.<p></ul><b>Dr Yunus: <ul>The present banking system is not just, because it only lends money to a very privileged group of people, not the people at the bottom.  So this is what we are dramatising, what we are demonstrating - and we are proving that what we are saying is right. <p>It is happening in Bangladesh, it is being done in many other countries with similar results.  So now it will be very difficult for the banking system, the traditional banking system, to ignore what we have been saying.<p></ul></b>Woman's voice: <ul><img width=154 height=117 align=left 15vspace 15hspace src="beijing_pix/yunus_lurking.gif">Women like us are traditionally supposed to live a very secluded life, always inside the house. <br>In some villages, prayers being offered in a mosque would stop  if a woman passed by. And people said that insects would damage the crops in a field that a woman had walked through.<p> So can you imagine women being allowed to go inside a conventional bank? Much less <i>run </i>the bank, like in Grameen!<p></ul><b>Dr Yunus: <ul>My allegation against the existing banking system is that it is basically an anti-women institution: it doesn't lend money to women. <img width=156 height=117 align=right 15vspace 15hspace src="beijing_pix/yunus_woman.gif"> If you take all the borrowers of a bank together, you only find 1% of [those borrowers are] women.<p>So when I began I wanted to make sure that I don't make the same mistake.  So we are trying to achieve an equal number of both men and women. <p>We noticed very remarkable things happening in the families where we lend money to the women.  In those families more benefits are coming than in the families where we gave money to the men.  </ul><p></b><hr width=40%><center><i><b><font size=+2> The Population Issue </font></b></b></center><p><br><img width=153 height=117 15vspace 15hspace src="beijing_pix/yunus_kids.gif"><p>Woman's voice: <ul>Something that hurts us is people from abroad blaming our children for our hardship. They want us to be forbidden to have more than one or two children. <p>Why don't they blame rich families? The rich make us poor - their children hoard and waste such a lot. But people from the North think they are experts on the realities of our life. <p></ul><b><font size=+1><i> INTERVIEW</i></font></b><p><b>Dr Yunus is interviewed by a senior executive from UNFPA (the United Nations Fund for Population Activities): </b><ul>UNFPA interviewer: May I say to you... that I think there could be reason to be restrictive when it comes to the number of children in Bangladesh -  the realities are such...<p><b>Dr Yunus:  I don't believe in that...</b><p>UNFPA interviewer: You don't believe... <p><b>Dr Yunus: I don't believe in that... no.</b><p>UNFPA interviewer:  No.  That's interesting for those who listen to us also.<p><b>Dr Yunus: I don't think [the] number of people is [the] problem. </b><p>UNFPA interviewer:  You don't think so.<p><b>Dr Yunus: The problems are the institutions, because when [people can] take care of themselves, they can take care of the number of children.  They are wise people.  People are not stupid! </b></ul><p><hr width=40%><p><img width=154 height=117 align=right 15vspace 15hspace src="beijing_pix/yunus_sari.gif">Woman's voice: <ul>Dr Yunus  doesn't believe that people have to be poor.  He told us that poverty could easily and quickly be wiped out if people like us had the freedom and the confidence to do things our own way... instead of a few rich families deciding how everything should be run - usually to their advantage, not to ours.<p></ul><b>Dr Yunus: <ul>I see [the] alleviation of poverty as a do-able proposition. <img width=157 height=117 align=left 8vspace 15hspace src="beijing_pix/yunus_face.gif"><p>We can remove poverty from the surface of the earth <i>only if we can redesign our institutions</i> - like the banking institutions, and other institutions; if we redesign our policies, if we look back on our concepts, so that we <i>have a different idea of poor people</i>. <p>Because at present poor people are looked upon as if they have to be dependent on somebody's handout, on somebody's mercy. They are NOT looking out for somebody's handout, they are NOT looking out for somebody's mercy. <p> <i>They want their legitimate due - and they can handle the rest themselves. They can pull themselves out of poverty.  </i> </b><p></ul>Commentary: <ul>Grameen Banking has now spread all over the world. Over 40 countries have taken it up: <img width=153 height=117 align=right 8vspace 15hspace src="beijing_pix/yunus_fruit.gif">not only poorer countries like Sri Lanka but rich ones like France, Norway and the United States. President Clinton is a Grameen fan. <p>For Dr Yunus, credit is as fundamental a human right as the right to freedom of speech, food, shelter, health, or education.<p></ul><b>Dr Yunus: <ul>Credit is a human right that should be treated as a human right. If credit can be accepted as a human right, then all other human rights will be easier to establish.  </b><p></ul><br><font size=+1><b><i>CLOSING GRAPHIC</i></b></font><p><center><img width=184 height=120 src="beijing_pix/yunus_slogan.gif"></center><p>"In future the question will not be: 'Are people credit-worthy?' but rather:  'Are banks people-worthy?' "- Dr. Mohammed Yunus<p><hr>Footage for <b>'Credit Where It's Due'</b>  courtesy of Worldview International Foundation (WIF) Bangladesh, re-edited by Peter Armstrong. Written and produced by Anuradha Vittachi. <br><hr><img width=100  height=50 align=left hspace=4 src="../owo_logos/online_logo2.gif"><a href="../index.html#regfeat">Regular Features</a><br><a href="../owo_options.html"> Index</a><br><a href="../index.html"> Home Page</a><p></body></html>
