<html><head><title>Fourth Conference on Women - Beijing</title></head><body><h2 align=center><font size=6>B</font>EIJING <font size=6>S</font>PECIAL <font size=6>R</font>EPORT</h2><center><img width=475 src="../owo_logos/online_logoconferences_line.gif"></center><h2 align=center>The Fourth World Conference on Women<br> <font size=-0>Beijing, 4 - 15 September 1995</font></h2><p><b><i>'People who value democracy, who believe in equality, now say that we must change the world so that women and men in equal partnership can really bring about sustainable development.' </i></b><br><center>- Gertrude Mongella, Secretary-General</center><p><h2>Introduction</h2><img align=right width=216 height=273 hspace=10 vspace=5 border=1 src="beijing_pix/womenco.gif"><b>It is tempting to think that there is no point in UN women's conferences:</b> VSO's John Hilary estimates that 50% more women are living in poverty now than 30 years ago. But given that 97% of the UN's permanent representatives are still male, one should probably not expect too many direct gains for women from this most disunited and chauvinistic of institutions. <p><b>The real value of such UN conferences </b>may lie not in creating, or even initiating, substantial improvements - but as a way of giving recognition to the subtler changes that have been taking place in any case, over many years, in other quarters and largely through non-bureaucratic means. And that global recognition can be valuable. The 1992 Rio Conference, for example, attracted enormous attention worldwide and gave value to the work of environmentalists. <p><b>Recognition gives confidence, just as invisibility undermines it:</b> any person who has been oppressed or disempowered can vouch for that.  Women have more than enough competence; confidence is what they  need - both at an individual and at a cultural level. That is to say, confidence not only to believe in themselves but to be believed in by others.</b><p><b>The Fourth UN Conference on Women is a mirror</b> in which we, the one world community, can see how far women have become visible already - and how far they (we!) still need to go to be seen and heard as clearly as men are. The call for equal rights before the law is therefore, unsurprisingly, a key conference theme. <p><b>Another theme is reproductive rights for women</b> - without which women can never be equal with men. The Conference could do well to re-iterate the gains of the 1994 Cairo Population and Development Conference, where the population hot potato was finally acknowledged to be a matter of human rights and not merely national demographics.<p><b>Economic rights are a third essential theme.</b>Women have for generations been fooled into thinking that owning or earning property - whether land or money - is somehow, mysteriously, 'unfeminine'. By this ruse men have kept the purse-strings in their own hands, bamboozling women into dependence on their goodwill. Even now, conventional banks will often not lend money to women without their husbands' signature - on the assumption that only men, of course, would have access to collateral. <p><p><b>But all this is set to change...  </b> <p><b>Keep checking into OneWorld</b>'s Special Report on Women, where we will be bringing you - over the next few days and weeks - our NGO partners' reports of the conference, as well as video-stills and transcripts showing how things can change, and are changing, for the better.<p><br><center><img width=475 src="../owo_logos/online_logoconferences_line.gif"></center><p></body></html>
