<html>
<HEADER>
<TITLE>IGC: Development NGOs call for a New Agenda for the European Union's
external relations</TITLE>
</HEADER>
<body bgcolor=#FFFFFF>
<center><img align=middle src="images/ngdoc.gif" height=120></center>
<hr>
<P>
<center><h3>IGC: Development NGOs call for a New Agenda for the European Union's
external relations</h3>Press Release of  the Liaison Commitee of Development NGOs to the EU (7 October 1996) </center>
<p>
<hr>
<center><H3>* * Europe is turning its back on the poor of the World * *<P>


* * Launch of An Action Plan for European Leaders * *</H3>
</center><p>

An extraordinary European Summit on the IGC has taken place in Dublin in
order to quicker the pace of the IGC process. The European NGDOs,
represented by James Mackie (Executive Secretary of the Liaison Committee)
and Robin Hanan (President of the Liaison Committee Working Group on the IGC
), were also present in Dublin to launch their Action Plan for European
Leaders. They wanted to insist on the fact that the IGC is providing an
important opportunity to give a new vision and direction to the European
Union's external relations as a whole.
<p>
The Action Plan for European Leaders calls on European leaders to:<p>

SEIZE THIS HISTORIC OPPORTUNITY TO ENSURE THAT EUROPE TAKES A PROGRESSIVE LEAD IN WORLD AFFAIRS, by working to:
<ul>
<li>develop a global foreign policy which can play a key role in building a
world with greater peace and stability;
<li>take a leading role in changing unjust and undemocratic international
economic and social systems which are a major cause of instability and
conflict;
<li>move away from a view of security that is based on a military and defence-
centred definition;
<li>develop policies and mechanisms which can facilitate the prevention of
conflicts.
</ul><p>
The statement makes proposals to the IGC to include in the Common Provisions
of the Treaty on European Union (TEU) and the objectives of the Common
Foreign and Security Policy (CFSP) the following fundamental objectives for
ALL the external relations of the Union:
<ul>
i) 	the promotion of economically, socially and environmentally sustainable
patterns of development;<br>
ii)	the promotion of economic, social, cultural, civil and political rights
as agreed in international human rights and humanitarian law;<br>
iii)	greater economic and social equity and justice and equality between men
and women.
</ul><p>
In addition, the Action Plan calls for:<ul>
<li>a renewed emphasis on conflict prevention in the CFSP, taking into account
the contribution of women;
<li>respect for human rights as a basic principle of the CFSP;
<li>legally binding mechanisms to control the arms trade;
<li>greater transparency, openness and accountability with respect to civil
society in Europe and in Africa, Asia and Latin America.</ul>
<p>
The Action Plan was initiated by the Liaison Committee of Development NGOs
to the EU, a network representing over 800 NGDOs grouped in National
Platforms in all 15 EU Member States.
<p>
It is supported by: <a href="../aprodev/index.html">APRODEV</a>, Care International, Caritas Europa, CIFCA,
EuronAid, EUROCIDSE, EFTA (European Fair Trade Association), <a href="../eurostep/index.html">EUROSTEP</a>, the
Youth Forum of the European Union, ICDA (International Coalition for
Development Action), International Save the Children Alliance (ISCA), the
Africa-Europe Faith and Justice Network, <a href="../solidar/index.html">Solidar</a> and WIDE (Women in
Development Europe)
<p>
You can obtain the Action Plan from the Liaison Committee by contacting <a href="mailto:vvanbelle@clong.be">Val&#233;rie Van Belle</a> or <a href="mailto:sbiesemans@clong.be">Sam Biesemans</a> Tel.: 32-2-7438786 or 7438785 - Fax: 32-2-7321934 - E-mail: vvanbelle@clong.be or sbiesemans@clong.be
<p>
<a href="index.html">Liason Committee Home Page</a> / <A HREF="../euforic/igc.htm">Related texts</A>
