</DOCHDR>
<html>
<header>
<title>Development Co-operation Review of Austria</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H3><center><img src="../images/at.jpg"><p></a>
Development Co-operation Review of Austria<br>Summary and Conclusions<P>
<i>OECD Development Assistance Committee</i><p></h3>
<h5>March 1996<br>
For a copy of the full report, please contact OECD Publications, 2 rue Andr&#233; Pascal, 75775 Paris Cedex 16, France
<br>
Home Page: <a href="http://www.oecd.org/dac/index.htm" target="_top">http://www.oecd.org/dac/index.htm</a></h5>
</center><p>
<hr>
Since the last review of the Austrian aid programme by the Development
Assistance Committee (DAC) of the OECD in 1993, the Austrian aid
administration has introduced several changes intended to make
the programme more coherent and efficient. These changes included
a reduction in the number of priority countries, the beginning
of sector and country programming, the nomination of local/regional
aid coordinators and new rules for relations with nongovernmental
organisations (NGOs) which implement the bulk of bilateral technical
assistance. Another important change involves Austria's membership
in the European Union (EU). This membership affects the volume,
composition, coordination and other aspects of the overall Austrian
programme.
<P>
The impact of the changes introduced by the Department of Development
Cooperation (DDC) in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs is, however,
greatly limited by the small share of official development assistance
(ODA)  less than 15 per cent  for which the DDC is responsible.
Responsibility for Austrian ODA is distributed over a number of
ministries and there is a need for more and improved interministerial
coordination. Austria does not have a clear overall strategy to
guide its development cooperation. The ThreeYear Programme of
Austrian development cooperation (which is updated annually) in
effect binds only the small part of ODA administered by the DDC.
Consequently, any positive initiative taken by the DDC can be
offset by actions in other parts of the aid programme and such
instances have occurred.
<P>
The ThreeYear Programme is not discussed in Parliament and the
report on development cooperation, which has to be submitted to
Parliament every three years, appears to receive little attention.
Development assistance has apparently sunk only limited roots
in Austrian politics and public opinion. Development NGOs, which
try to drum up support, do not have a sufficiently broad base.
By contrast, there appears to be relatively strong support in
public opinion and political circles for humanitarian assistance
and for assisting the transformation of Central and Eastern Europe.
<P>
The aggregate volume and financial terms of Austrian aid have
improved in recent years, but its composition and targeting have
continued to raise serious questions. The increase of Austrian
ODA claims in recent years exceeded by far the DAC average, with
the result that in 1994 Austrian ODA in relation to gross national
product (GNP) (0.33 per cent) exceeded the DAC average  a change
facilitated by a decline of the DAC average to 0.30 per cent.
On the other hand, Austria's ODA/GNP ratio is still well below
the average for EU members.
<P>
In relation to GNP, Austria has been the leading donor to the
Central and Eastern European Countries (CEECs) and the New Independent
States of the former Soviet Union (NIS). Until 1993 it was also
one of the largest donors in absolute amounts. Austria's total
aid effort for developing and Eastern European countries is far
above the average of OECD/DAC countries.
<P>
Since 1992 Austrian ODA commitments have been in compliance with
the DAC recommendation on terms, but the share of tied aid has
remained high.
<P>
The Austrian programme has continued to be characterised by a
high share of components for which development considerations
are not the prime motivation. These claims are for aid for refugees
in Austria, imputed costs for developing country students in Austria
and official concessional export credits. The combined share of
these components  which had declined in 1992 and 1993  exceeded
half of ODA disbursements in 1994. There is no doubt that Austria
has for many years assumed a heavy burden with regard to refugees
and is one of the most generous OECD countries in this respect.
At the same time the ODA share claimed for refugee costs in Austria
is four times the DAC average, and the reporting of this expenditure
is probably not entirely in conformity with DAC rules. The reporting
of imputed costs for developing countries students in Austria
also requires review. As to concessional export credits, development
considerations are not the main motive for their extension. A
much stronger involvement of the DDC in the selection and screening
of these credits and their integration into sector and country
programming could strengthen the development linkage.
<P>
Austrian payments to the European Community aid programmes resulted
in an increase in the total volume of aid in 1995. However, this
increase in multilateral aid was at the expense of a small reduction
in DDC
<P>
administered assistance. It appears possible that Austria's EU
membership and its related reordering of the country's ODA could
provide a welcome opportunity to review the composition and reporting
of Austrian ODA and to pursue more vigorously improvements in
various areas, including country programming, policy dialogue,
aid coordination and evaluation.
<P>
With a view to increasing effectiveness and coherence, and in
line with recommendations at earlier DAC reviews, the aid administration
has reduced the number of priority countries for Austrian aid
from nineteen to eight. Most of the remaining former priority
countries have been designated &quot;cooperation countries&quot;.
Both groups of recipient countries are now located in five subregions.
However, since DDC administers only a small share of ODA none
of the priority countries are among the major recipients of Austrian
aid. Concessional export credits and refugee support claims have
a far greater impact on the geographic distribution. Former Yugoslavia
(i.e. Bosnia) has, therefore, been the largest recipient, followed
by Algeria, China and Thailand. Poland has been by far the largest
recipient among CEECs due to debt relief.
<P>
Realising that with the limited volume of its aid, Austria can
only be a &quot;niche donor&quot;, DDC now clearly intends to
concentrate its aid not only geographically but also on sectors
where Austria possesses a comparative advantage. Until now the
sectoral distribution has remained widely dispersed. Education,
transport, energy and manufacturing have been the sectors obtaining
the largest commitments. Debt relief made up a large share in
1993/94 and is likely to remain important in the coming years.
<P>
Nongovernmental organisations occupy a special and important position
in the Austrian aid programme since they initiate and implement
a large share of bilateral technical assistance. This situation
is the result of there being no official agency for the implementation
of Austria's bilateral aid. Since many NGOs raise little or no
funds of their own they rely mainly or exclusively on official
funds and in some respects resemble subsidiary organs of the public
administration in spite of their different legal status. While
in the past NGOs could carry out their activities in many countries
and sectors, they are now under increasing pressure from DDC to
orient their activities towards priority countries and sectors.
As implementing agencies for official aid, the DDC wants the NGOs
to be guided by its sector and country programming. The number
of NGOinitiated projects is declining in favour of projects proposed
by the administration. These changes have created tension since
the NGOs want to be treated as equal partners rather than as implementing
agencies. NGOs also complain about stricter control by the DDC
over their activities and late commitment and payment of funds.
Budget reductions, late payments and a strict application of Austrian
budget rules indeed created serious problems for NGOs in 1995,
and this is likely to be repeated in 1996. While certain changes
and reforms are necessary in the relationship between the administration
and NGOs, there is also a need to maintain a fruitful dialogue
and mutual trust.
<P>
Austria attaches great importance to the protection of the environment
and its declared policy is that all its development cooperation
projects should be environmentally sustainable. Thus the administration
has sponsored assessment of the environmental impact of DDC projects.
Austria initiated a threeyear programme (1993/9S) for the protection
and conservation of rain forests, and its agricultural, tourism
and other projects have a strong environmental component. Almost
all agricultural projects are directed to environmentally friendly
bigagriculture.
<P>
Gender issues are officially considered a priority issue, but
practical measures in this area are still limited. Projects are
not systematically assessed from a gender point of view, and there
are few genderspecific projects. Austria supports relatively few
projects in the fields of human rights and democracy  most are
related to electoral assistance, legal training, resettlement
and reintegration of refugees. The Austrian Government has stated
its belief that starvation and extreme poverty are the most serious
violation of human rights.
<P>
Regarding poverty alleviation, no guidelines have been drawn up
to date and no assessment of poverty reduction programmes has
been made. Relevant activities in the programme involve land and
agricultural reforms to promote equitable distribution of resources
and means of production and integrated rural development schemes.
<P>
The effectiveness and efficiency of Austrian aid is impaired by
the lack of a strategy covering the whole aid programme, the distribution
of responsibility over many ministries, the large number of implementing
agencies and the dispersion of aid over many countries and sectors.
The repeated transfer of DDC between the Federal Chancellery (Prime
Minister's Office) and the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, and its
small staff have also been handicaps. Certain measures taken in
recent years  which are mentioned in the first paragraph  should,
however, lead to improvement. The move towards sector and country
programmes instead of the many isolated projects is particularly
welcome. A first country programme was finalised in 1993. These
programmes, discussed and agreed upon with the partner country,
state the objectives and planned cooperation over a threeyear
period. Being aware of its limited resources and its role as a
&quot;niche donor&quot; Austria intends to concentrate its aid
on small and mediumsized recipient countries and on two or three
sectors per country where it possesses a comparative advantage.
The rising number of local aid coordinators should facilitate
and accelerate this process, and permit Austria's participation
in local aid coordination. The DDC has also carried out a certain
number of midterm evaluations  but no <I>ex post</I> evaluations
 and the Division responsible has submitted proposals to improve
the feedback of &quot;lessons learned&quot;.
<P>
This review suggests that further improvements and a more coherent
development cooperation programme for Austria would be facilitated
by the following measures:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>The articulation of a basic policy by the Federal Government
which would be binding for all components of the aid programme.</li>
<P>
<li>A concentration of most aid activities under a single administration
and a single minister. In particular, the aid administration should
have the appropriate responsibility for those concessional export
credits which are reported as ODA loans to ensure their conformity
with aid policy orientations as well as their integration with
technical assistance.</li>
<P>
<li>Additional staff for the aid administration.</li>
<P>
<li>Clear rules for the selection of implementing agencies and competition
among them for contracts.</li>
<P>
<li>A reform and activation of the Advisory Board for Development
Cooperation and of interministerial coordination.</li>
<P>
<li>The submission of an annual report on development cooperation
to the Austrian Parliament, followed by an appropriate debate.</li></ul>
<p>
<HR>
<H6><i>Updated on September 17, 1996</i><p>
