<html><head><title>'People with AIDS the bosses', says new UN agency chief</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><img src="panos_pix/panos_logo.gif"><br><i>The material that follows has been provided by <a href="panos_info.html"> Panos </i> </a><hr><h3>'People with AIDS the bosses', says new UN agency chief</h3>Geneva: People with AIDS will play a key role at a new United Nations organisation set up to combat the AIDS epidemic, says its new director <p>The new organisation - UNAIDS - starts work on January 1, 1996 and is designed to coordinate the AIDS work of six UN organisations - the World Bank, the World Health Organization, the UN Development Programme, the UN Children's Fund, the UN Population Fund and the UN Education Scientific and Cultural Organisation.<p>Its establishment reflects concerns that previous efforts have sometimes duplicated each other and responds to a new urgency to find more effective strategies to combat the epidemic.<p>Dr Peter Piot, the head of UNAIDS, says the organisation's board of directors will be made up of representatives of community groups and non-government organisations, with a special role for people with AIDS.<p>"This is the first time people from the community level have been on the board of a UN agency," Piot said in an interview with Panos.<p>"They bring the epidemic into the boardroom. They are my bosses - they will ensure that we don't divert our attention from the epidemic to all kinds of political and bureaucratic disputes."<p>Piot has been involved in AIDS prevention since the earliest days of the epidemic, when he worked in Zaire in the early 1980s. He acknowledges there is frustration with how little progress there has been in combating the epidemic.<p>"In the beginning people didn't realise how important AIDS was, or anticipate how it would change the future of mankind," he says. <p>"It took several years before we realized how HIV is transmitted. Then we very quickly developed a test to determine whether someone was infected, and then shortly after that we even had the start of a treatment. But since 1985 or 1986, progress has been very slow."<p>Piot argues that the pandemic is too complex and affects too many different sectors of society and government for just one organisation to come up with the best responses to it.<p>"We have learned that AIDS is a very complex issue. There are no simple solutions for people who are infected or for those who are at risk. Several agencies of the UN have become involved, both in prevention and, to a lesser extent, in care and support of those who are infected.<p>"There has not been much coordination of these efforts. There has been duplication of work in the same country and even conflicts between different agencies. We need to use our resources more efficiently. So much has to be done, and not using resources well is unethical. That is why UNAIDS was created - to improve the UN response and the response of various governments to AIDS."<p>Some critics have claimed that the new organisation will be riven by political struggles and arguments between the different agencies. Piot says he is determined that this will not happen. <p>He also stresses that AIDS must stop being pigeon-holed as simply another disease - that it belongs on a wider political agenda.<p>"We will be working with governments and donors to make them realise that if we don't work together to fight AIDS then we can forget about many other things in terms of economic or social development," he says.<p>"It is clear that AIDS will be with us for generations to come. It is not like an outbreak of something like Ebola virus that strikes and goes away. We have to start thinking about long term approaches."<p>Dealing with AIDS means tackling discrimination in society, he says, but he cautions against raising expectations of how much  the UN can do to change attitudes. <p>"We wish to work on the factors in society that make people more vulnerable to infection such as discrimination against sex workers, migrants or ethnic minorities. <p>"But we have to be realistic. Some communities have unrealistic expectations of what a UN agency can do. An independent NGO (non-governmental organisation) can do a much better job of monitoring human rights abuses than we can. We have to work with the governments that might be violating human rights. We can...mobilise them politically, but we can't change them overnight.<p>"We want to stick our necks out, but there are limits."<p>A priority for the new agency will be to expand efforts to help people living with AIDS and those who are ill, Piot says. <p>"In the past, most emphasis has been placed upon preventing new cases of infection. Of course that will continue. We have got to do a better job of prevention and do more, but now with more and more people becoming infected and becoming ill we cannot continue to ignore the need for care and support."<p>Piot also says he believes that more can be done to provide treatment to people with HIV/AIDS in the developing world: "It is not that expensive to prevent and even cure a number of opportunistic infections associated with AIDS (although not AIDS itself). There is a lot that can be done with drugs made locally, but physicians don't even know about them."<p>One of the biggest potential problems facing the new organisation is funding. Piot insists that, despite the pressure on development budgets, Western governments need to understand that AIDS prevention is an investment and not a cost. <p>Nevertheless, he argues, "we should think not only in terms of money set aside specifically for AIDS but we should also ensure that AIDS is on the agenda of other development projects - such as World Bank loans, women and development projects, health and social services projects." <p>Already there have been major financial disappointments - including the recent news that the French Government has cut its funding commitment to the new organisation.<p>More funds need to come from those countries most at risk, Piot says, not just from the industrialised aid donor countries.<p>"In many countries, AIDS is still perceived as something from the outside. Up to now it was almost entirely supported by external money. It is time to change that," Piot asserts.more ... <p>Some countries are beginning to do so, he says, and he cites Thailand as a "shining example": "The government budget for AIDS activities in Thailand for next year is about US$60 million. That is the same amount of money (UNAIDS) will have for the whole world. Thailand does this because it recognises that it is so important for its own development and for the future."<p>While Asian and Latin American countries may be able to afford to follow Thailand's example, much of Africa is struggling with terrible economic problems, and will have to continue to rely on external money to fund its AIDS care and prevention programmes. For this reason sub-Saharan Africa, Piot says, will be UNAIDS' priority. <p>Piot stresses one point above all else - the importance of involving people with HIV and AIDS in every element of the struggle against the epidemic, from the boardroom to the community.<p>The biggest contribution that people with HIV and AIDS can make, he argues, is "to live as fully as possible and spread the message that life is worth living, and that you can do something about the epidemic.<p>"You must also hang together. Solidarity is extremely important. There is very little anyone can do on their own."<p>©Copyright: Panos 22 November 1995                                                      <hr><a href="index.html"><img src="panos_pix/panos_logo2.gif"> PANOS Home Page</a><hr></body></html>
