<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>PAF PROACTIVE FILE 32</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<P>
<CENTER><IMG align=middle src="../euforic/images/eustep.jpg"></CENTER>
<H3><CENTER>PAF PROACTIVE FILE<BR>
Regular News Update From Eurostep No. 32 Friday 10 January 1997
</CENTER></H3>
<H4><CENTER>EUROSTEP<BR>
115 Rue St&eacute;vin, B-1000 Brussels, Belgium<BR>
Tel.: (32)-2-2311659 / Fax: (32)-2-2303780<BR>
E-mail: <A href="mailto:eurostep@knooppunt.be">eurostep@knooppunt.be</A></H4><A HREF="index.html">EUROSTEP Home Page</A></CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>1. EP AGREES TO LOME IV REVISION AGREEMENT IN
SPITE OF DISAPPOINTING ASPECTS<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>The European Parliament
has issued its assent to revision of the Lom&eacute; IV Convention
signed in 1995 paving the way for a Council's adoption of the
revision. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Rapporteur France Wurtz stated that even though
the results were disappointing with regard to political and institutional
issues, trade and development financing, he urged the EP to consent
to the revision for two reasons: firstly the ACP's wish for the
EP to ratify the revisions as they know they are vulnerable have
very little room to manoeuvre; secondly stalling in consenting
to revision could be used by those who want to diminish EC-ACP
co-operation. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> The European parliament's assent is an indispensable
but  insufficient step for the entry into force of the revised
Convention, particularly its financial protocol for the period
up to the year 2000. All the Union Member States and at least
two thirds of the ACP States must ratify the revised Convention
and its financial protocol for it to enter into force.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>2. NGOS FACE  DILEMMA OVER MAINTAINING NEUTRALITY
IN THE FACE OF      HUMAN RIGHTS ABUSES<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> European development NGOs are increasingly facing
a moral dilemma as to whether to continue  maintain their neutrality
in areas where there have been, gross human rights violations.
At a seminar on &quot;What ethics in humanitarian aid,&quot; organised
by the EC Humanitarian Office last December in Geneva, the majority
of speakers concluded that though principles of independence and
neutrality are fundamental, the Geneva Conventions governing these
principles are no longer suitable. Jaques Lebas, a doctor and
teacher at the university of Paris, said, neutrality &quot;threatens
to subject aid and assistance actions to the good will of the
fighters, factions or active authorities.&quot; Mrs. Emma Bonino
the EC Humanitarian Commissioner replied, &quot;Most humanitarians
play the role of judge and policeman in refugee camps? No, they
do not have the means and it is not their role. But should human
rights not also take into account in humanitarian actions. ..
Our Identity must be independent from foreign policy.&quot; According
to the head of the Portuguese NGO, AMA, Fernando Nobre, &quot;We
(NGOs) have become too professional, too idealistic and too politician.&quot;
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> The issue is particularly relevant given that 94
% of emergency aid transits through NGOs or international organisations
whereas twenty years ago 95% of this aid went through governments.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>3. NEW UN SECRETARY GENERAL TO APPOINT SPECIAL
ENVOY FOR EXPLORATORY MISSION IN GREAT LAKES REGION<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>Kofi Annan the new Secretary
General of the UN stated, in an interview with the AFP last week,
that he planned to appoint a new special envoy for issues concerning
the Great Lakes region. He said that the post may go to Algerian
diplomat Lakhdat Brahimi who had experience with UN in South Africa,
Haiti and Yemen.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Mr. Annan said that he had raised the issue with
Mr. Boutros Ghali, the out-going Secretary General and stated:
&quot;First of all, we shall appoint someone who will visit the
region to discuss with the Heads of State and, after that, we
shall decide how to proceed&quot;. Notably on the convening of
an international conference on the Great Lake issues, he emphasised
that the conference must be &quot;well-prepared&quot; because
of the great deal of suspicion between Heads of State in the region.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>4. EC AND WORLD BANK TO SHARE EXPERIENCE ON EVALUATION
OF PROJECTS<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>The European Commission
and the World Bank plan to share their experience in evaluating
development aid programmes. The first top-level working meeting
on the subject took place in Brussels three weeks ago in the presence
of EU Budget Commissioner, Erkki Liikane; EU Development Commissioner,
Joao de Deus Pinheiro; Director General of Operations Evaluation
at the World Bank, Robert Picciotto and representatives from the
European Bank for Reconstruction and Development and the European
Investment Bank. The main topics of the meeting were on how to
integrate the evaluation in the implementation of programmes,
how to measure the results and which methods to use to evaluate
the results of macro-economic measures.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> The two institutions have agreed to a programme
to evaluate their structural adjustment aid in recipient countries.
In relation to this, the evaluation unit of DG VIII (Development
Department of the EC) and the equivalent service of the Bank will
carry out a joint impact study this year in certain sectors. The
two bodies will also exchange information on the evaluation of
development programmes in transition. This initiative is part
of the EC's financial management efforts in line with &quot;SEM
2000&quot; programme.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>5. ECONOMIC SANCTIONS AGAINST BURUNDI ARE WIDELY
CIRCUMVENTED<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>According to information
from Nairobi, economic sanctions imposed on Burundi by neighbouring
countries after Major Buyoya's coup d'etat have been largely circumvented.
Reports of the availability of petrol, abundant sales of Zambian
cement, salt from Tanzania, beer from Rwanda and household goods
from Kenya bear witness to this. Apparently the high price of
petrol created by the sanctions is an attraction for all kinds
of suppliers. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>6. EU COUNCIL TO DECIDE ON SUSPENDING GSP TO BURMA
<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2> </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>The European Council
of Foreign Ministers will decide on whether to take up the Commission's
recommendation to suspend the General System of Preferences, GSP,
on agricultural and industrial products from Burma on 19 January.
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> However, reports seem to indicate that France and
Germany may not be wholly committed to the penalising Burma. Several
German companies are planning to open an investment office in
Rangoon, the Burmese capital. The Burmese campaigner for democracy,
Aung San Suu Kyi, attacked the German plans saying &quot;We are
not in favour of investments in Burma at this particular moment
because money that gets into the country does not get to the people
that need it most&quot;. The German Asia-Pacific Business Association
regional manager, Wolfgang Niedermark, defended German companies
in a German paper, saying, &quot;We are really business oriented
and we do not have any political ambitions.&quot; Ms Suu Kyi responded
to these comments saying, &quot;With Germany's history and experience
I think it's shocking that any German should say that we're only
interested in economics, we have nothing to do with politics.
The fact that Germany was involved in the second world war was
due to political errors not economic errors.&quot; <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>7. NEW DIRECTOR FOR ECHO<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2> Alberto Navarro Gonzalez has been appointed as the
new director of the European Community Humanitarian Office replacing
Mr. Gomez-Reino who is now Deputy Director General of External
Political Relations.<B><BR>
<BR>
<P>
