</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Reality of Aid</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<P>
<CENTER><IMG align=middle src="../euforic/images/eustep.jpg">

<H3>Reality of Aid 1996:<br>European aid under increasing pressure</H3>
by <i>Mirjam van Reisen</i>
<P>

<H4>EUROSTEP<BR>
115 Rue St&eacute;vin, B-1000 Brussels, Belgium<BR>
Tel.: (32)-2-2311659 / Fax: (32)-2-2303780<BR>
E-mail: <A href="mailto:eurostep@knooppunt.be">eurostep@knooppunt.be</A></CENTER>
</H4>
<HR>
<P>
The European Community's development aid programme consists of
two components.  The programme of development cooperation with
African, Caribbean and Pacific (ACP) countries is based on the
Lom&eacute; Convention, an intergovernmental convention between
the European Member States and the ACP countries.  The implementation
of this agreement is handled by the European Commission and the
ACP countries.
<P>
Secondly there are the programmes usually referred to as &quot;budgetary
aid&quot;.  The legal basis for these programmes comes from the
Treaty of Maastricht, in which development aid is mentioned as
being a specific area of competence for the European Community.
<P>
<B>Lom&eacute;</B>
<P>
In recent years, it has become increasingly clear that the European
Union wants to revise its special relationship with the ACP countries.
 However, an interim revision of the Fourth Lom&eacute; Convention
was signed in early November 1995 in Mauritius.   The revised
Treaty will run for five years, ending in the year 2000.  The
Commission's view of the revision can be clearly understood from
the words of Development Commissioner Pinheiro, quoted in the
Courier; March/April 1995): &quot;<I>This is the last of the Conventions
as we know them</I>&quot;.  Anxiety among ACP countries that their
special status with the EU could disappear after the year 2000
is easily stirred up by such statements.
<P>
The <I>Revision</I> makes a number of important changes to Lom&eacute;
IV.  A striking change is that respect of human rights, democracy
and the rule of law are now essential components of the Convention.
 A suspensory condition is included for cases where &quot;<I>one
party considers that the other party has not fulfilled an obligation
with regard to the essential components&quot;</I>.
<P>
ACP countries will have slightly improved access to EU markets
for agricultural produce.  Both parties agreed that trade should
be high on the agenda.  It was also agreed to use resources for
Structural Adjustment to stimulate regional integration and intra-regional
economic liberalisation.  There was no progress on easing the
burden of debt.
<P>
The negotiations about the financial basis were difficult, and
were only completed just before the European Summit in June 1995,
under heavy pressure from the French Presidency.  The new Financial
Protocol (the financial resources available up to the year 2000)
amounts to 14 623 MECU.  That amount represents no real increase
on the financial resources by comparison with the previous period.
 This decision was strongly criticised by the Joint ACP/EU meeting.
<P>
The way in which European Union foreign policy evolves will largely
determine the future of the Lom&eacute; Convention.  A number
of factors are important:
<P>
- The potential accession of a substantial number of Central and
East European countries to the Community would make them an important
political factor.  They would want to take part in decisions about
EU foreign policy.  They have their own history and foreign policy
interests to bring to the table.  This would form the backdrop
against which they would pronounce judgement on the desirable
foreign policy for the Union.  Central and East European countries
are already associated with large areas of common European foreign
policy.  In future, they would play an increasing role in determining
the European identity;
<P>
- the financial cost of assimilating the Central and East European
countries will be high.  This would lead to increasing competition
for resources in the EU;
<P>
- discussions about the usefulness of development aid, combined
with the meagre prospects for political and economic improvement
in the ACP countries are leading to an unfavourable &quot;aid
climate&quot;;
<P>
- the increasing number of free trade agreements signed by the
European Union means that preferential treatment that ACP states
are granted is becoming less significant;
<P>
- the setting up of free trade areas could lead to discussion
being initiated about whether it would not be better to split
the ACP bloc into regional groups.  This would raise the issue
of the <I>raison d'&ecirc;tre</I> of the ACP as a group.
<P>
The European Commission has set up a working group which is due
to reflect upon the relationship between the Community and the
ACP countries in the next century.
<P>
<B>The EC Development Programme</B>
<P>
The Treaty of Maastricht set out the overall objectives of the
development policy to be adopted by the Community.
<P>
The Treaty established development aid as a subject area which
was unquestionably a matter for the European Community, the so-called
&quot;pillar 1&quot; of the European Union.  The powers of the
Community to implement development programmes is seen as complementary
to actions taken in this field by Member States.
<P>
Although the Maastricht Treaty provides that development aid in
the European Union must be coordinated to a greater extent, there
are a large number of problems standing in the way of a more efficient
policy.  Ultimately it is the Member States who decide what scope
the European Commission has to carry out its work  The Member
States take the decisions within the Council, and the Commission
has to implement them.  The problems facing the Commission are
of an institutional nature:
<P>
- <I>a lack of staff</I>.  Within the Directorate General dealing
with development, there are always a large number of vacancies,
sometimes up to one-third of the total management staff.  In addition,
a large number of temporary external staff are used.  A considerable
proportion of the core tasks are carried out by consultants working
outside the Commission.  In the programmes for Eastern Europe
and the CIS (PHARE and TACIS), the whole cycle of monitoring,
assessment and evaluation is handled by subcontractors;
<P>
- <I>a lack of expertise, mainly in the fields of social affairs
and the environment.</I> In a number of evaluations, it has already
been concluded that the limited number of staff and the lack of
expertise in major areas of policy are having a significant negative
impact on the quality of the programme.  The OECD's DAC committee
recently stated; <I>&quot;The main constraint may be, not refinement
of the policy itself, but the availability of sufficient specialised
staff and contractors for the Commission and its delegations to
carry out the policy in its details.  At present, as noted above,
the Commission needs to assure that it is not deficient in some
of the key fields for working on poverty alleviation - participatory
development, gender, population, health, education, environment
and the social sciences&quot;;</I>
<P>
- <I>an incoherent organisational structure.</I>  Since the appointment
of the present Commissioners, there are four Directorates General
dealing with parts of development policy, as well as the European
Community Humanitarian Office (ECHO).  These DGs are regionally-oriented.
 In addition, Member States have tried to influence the EC development
programme by setting up a bureaucratic web of committees;
<P>
- <I>divergent  objectives of different policy interests</I>.
 The regional orientation of the DGs means that they also have
to deal with other aspects of European foreign policy (politics,
security, trade) in their region.  This is a potential source
of conflicts of interest.
<P>
- a<I> complex budget</I> creates considerable tension between
multilateral and bilateral actions (by the Member States) and
between the resources within and outside the EU budget;
<P>
- <I>increasing pressure from Member States to exert influence
on the EC development policy via a bureaucratic web of committees.</I>

<P>
The Member States can improve aid policy through the Council of
Ministers.  As long as they fail to do so, they are responsible
for the continuation of the implementation problems mentioned.
 The European Commission merely has an executive role.  The Treaty
of Maastricht requires greater coordination of European aid, including
the European Community policy and that of the Member States. 
A large proportion of the coordination is the job of the Commission,
but their is a lack of cooperation from the Member States.  The
main reason for this reluctance is probably that development aid
is considered as a visiting card for the donor country.  It appears
that there is a need for better cooperation on foreign policy
(via the Intergovernmental Conference) before there can be better
coordination of European aid.
<P>
In 1995, a number of important decisions were taken to flesh out
the European development policy.  In additional a large number
of bilateral and regional cooperation and association agreements
were concluded with countries outside the Union.  This contributed
to the development of EU foreign policy.
<P>
<B>Conclusion</B>
<P>
The Maastricht Treaty emphasized the need to coordinate the Development
efforts of the European Union, including the European Community
Program and the Member States, in a complementary but coherent
fashion.
<P>
   
<P>
Important decisions were made during 1995 to advance these objectives
through regulations concerning development instruments. Moreover
a large number of bilateral and regional cooperation and association
agreements were agreed with countries outside the Union. The increasing
clarification of the EU external framework in itself should be
commended.
<P>
  
<P>
 Also important limitations were identified, constraining the
quality of the work of the European Commission on development
cooperation. These limitations are institutional in nature:
<P>
  
<P>
  * extreme limitations in terms of staffing;
<P>
  * lack of expertise in key areas of development; particularly
in social areas and the environment;
<P>
  * the disjointed nature of the organisation and structure of
the implementing Directorates General;
<P>
  * the complexity of the budget;
<P>
  * the contradictions between goals within the scope of foreign,
security, commercial and development policies;
<P>
  * and the way in which the Member States have sought to influence
decisions in relation to the European Community  Program through
a bureaucratic set up of mazes of various committees.
<P>
  
<P>
 External relations of the European Union are changing. Soon the
European Union will probably include 12 new Members States, which
will take almost half of the political weight inside the Community
and with specific interests of their own. This integration process
will consume enormous financial resources. Only the best of programs
will be able to survive competing demands for EU resources.
<P>
  
<P>
The impact of the traditional emphasis on trade of the EU development
program has also eroded as the EU is engaging in a large number
of Free Trade Agreements with other external regions. These developments
will lead to further questioning regarding the future of the EU
development program.
<P>
  
<P>
The key question concerns the relationship between the European
Union and the Member States. That is what the Inter Governmental
Conference in 1996 will deal with, and what makes the conference
extremely important. Also for development cooperation, even if
it will not be explicitly on the agenda. For all those involved
in development cooperation this provides an opportunity. The challenge
will be to formulate common but specific objectives and actions
to develop the future European external relations, which recognizes
and addresses the global social needs as a common European interest.
<HR>

<H6><I>Updated on June 25, 1996<BR>
</I>Developer's Note: These pages were developed for use on the
Netscape browser. Please address comments on content or style
to <A href="mailto:pb@ecdpm.org">Peter Ballantyne</A>, Information
Programme, ECDPM</H6>
