<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Impact of Armed Conflict on Children</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=FFFFFF>
<IMG SRC="unicef_pix/title.gif"><a href="machel2cw.html"><IMG SRC="unicef_pix/graca.gif"></a>
<BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR> 
The <A HREF="http://www.unicef.org/graca">Impact of Armed Conflict on Children</A> is the result of a
two-year process of research and consultation undertaken by Gra&ccedil;a Machel, the
Secretary-General's Expert on the subject and a former Minister for Education in Mozambique. 
<P>
Millions of children are caught up in conflicts in which they are not merely bystanders, but targets. Some
fall victim to a general onslaught against civilians; others die as part of a calculated genocide. Still other
children suffer the effects of sexual violence or the multiple deprivations of armed conflict that expose
them to hunger or disease. Just as shocking, thousands of young people are cynically exploited as
combatants.
<P>
The report says that in the past decade, around 2 million children have been killed in armed conflict, three
times as many have been seriously injured or permanently disabled, and countless others have been
forced to witness or even to take part in horrifying acts of violence.
<P>
As a result, says the report, children are being denied the protection promised them in the <A
HREF="http://www.unicef.org/crc">Convention on the Rights of the Child</A>. War violates every right of a
child &#151; the right to life, the right to be with family and community, the right to health, the right to
the development of the personality, and the right to be nurtured and protected.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
Read more about the <A HREF="http://www.unicef.org/graca">Impact of Armed Conflict on Children</A>.
</BODY>
