</DOCHDR>
<html>
<header>
<title>Development cooperation after the Treaty of Maastricht</title>
</header>
<hr>
<H2><center><img src="../images/nar.jpg"><p></a>
Development cooperation after the Treaty of Maastricht</h2>
<h4><i>NAR Secretariat</i>
<p>
Source: <i>In Brief: Information from the NAR</i><br>No.5, September 1993</h4>
<h5>The full text of the report in English, as well as a list of other publications, are available free of
charge from the Council's secretariat: E-mail: nar-dgis@dgis.minbuza.nl</h5>
</center>
<hr>
<b>On 7 September 1993 the National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) presented
Mr Jan Pronk, the Minister for Development Cooperation, with a report on the consequences of the Treaty
on European Union of December 1991 (the "Maastricht Treaty") for the development cooperation policy of
the European Community.</b>
<p>

<h3>The Treaty of Maastricht and development cooperation</h3>

The Treaty of Maastricht, which was signed by the EC member states at the beginning of 1992, is the first
document to set forth the development cooperation objectives of the Community and its constituent
members. 
<p>
The Minister had requested the NAR to give its views on how, after ratification, the articles of the Treaty
might be interpreted and applied to enable the development cooperation policy of the European Community
and its Member States to be more clearly defined. In June 1992 Mr Pronk and Mr P Dankert, State
Secretary for European Affairs, presented to the Lower House of Parliament a memorandum entitled "The
European Community and Development Cooperation in the light of Maastricht". The Minister for
Development Cooperation's request for a report was based partly on an appraisal of this memorandum
compiled by four members of the NAR in September 1992. The Minister requested replies to the following
questions.
<p>
How is it possible to give effect to article 130v of the Treaty, which stipulates that the Community shall
take account of development cooperation objectives (article 130u) in the implementation of policies which
are likely to affect developing countries? What activities can be initiated now that article 130w enables
decisions to be taken by qualified majority vote? Article 130x makes it possible for the Community and its
Members States to coordinate aid programme policy and implementation more closely. What practical
measures can be taken to give coordination concrete form? What consequences should the Community and
its member states attach to coordination? What specific steps can be taken to give effect to the Commission's
right of initiative regarding the coordination of national development cooperation policies, with particular
reference to positions adopted by member states at international fora and conferences? 
<p>
<h3>Summary of the NAR recommendations</h3>

<h4>Coherence of EC policy and coordination between the EC and the member states</h4>

The NAR takes the view that if Community policy (or a policy proposal) in a certain area puts developing
countries at a structural disadvantage, its implementation ought to be carefully reviewed. If the problems in
question are only of a temporary nature, interim compensatory measures by the EC, such as the gradual
introduction of new policy and assistance to developing countries in the implementation of new measures,
are a logical consequence.
<p>
The NAR stresses the need to initiate operational coordination at the implementation level, in specific,
clearly defined sectors for which programmes can be formulated and put into effect. To this end selection
should focus on specific new areas of activity, e.g. the fight against AIDS in Africa, energy policy in sub-
Saharan Africa, support for the regional economic integration of developing countries and measures to
combat specific environmental problems. Such an approach is preferable to the broad and somewhat vague
proposals for coordination now put forward by the Council of Ministers and the Commission. Operational
coordination in a specific policy area only becomes possible once Community objectives for the area in
question have been formulated. The member states must therefore exchange information on their respective
development cooperation policies. If priority is to be given to coordination at the implementation level, EC
representatives in developing countries must be assigned a leading role and their powers strengthened.
<p>
The NAR advocates that the whole range of conditions attached to member state and Community bilateral
aid flows be effectively coordinated and integrated. It points to the danger of donor requirements ac-
cumulating and becoming increasingly divergent and warns against extending conditionality to too many
areas. Setting priorities, e.g. making aid conditional upon such criteria as good governance and respect for
human rights, is inevitable.
<p>
<h4>The Council of Ministers of the Community and the European Commission</h4>

The Council of Ministers, which, depending on its composition, is responsible for a specific policy area,
should also take responsibility for ensuring coherence, i.e. that its policy ties in with Community develop-
ment cooperation policy. The Commission should report annually to the Council of Ministers and the
Parliament on the degree to which coherence is being achieved. The NAR takes the view that the Council of
Ministers should be empowered to take decisions which are binding with regard to the coordination of EC
and member state development cooperation policies.
<p>
The Maastricht Treaty and the recommendations made by the NAR with regard to coherence and coor-
dination involve new tasks for the European Commission, whose capacity is already limited and has often
been criticised as inadequate. The NAR advocates that those departments of the Commission which are
responsible for development cooperation be strengthened in order to improve organisational aspects of aid
programmes such as efficiency, flexibility, quality and feedback. The NAR regards improvements in these
areas as essential even if the present tasks of the Commission remain unchanged. Adding to the Commis-
sion's responsibilities in the area of aid programme implementation in the short term is undesirable. If EC
aid is extended, the NAR recommends that channels for implementing Community and/or coordinated aid
programmes be selected according to the results of a comparative study of the efficiency and effectiveness of
Community, governmental and possibly non-governmental EC organisations.
<p>
<h4>Common commercial policy and the Lom&#233; Convention</h4>

The NAR would like to see the advantages of the Lom&#233; Convention preserved.    The Convention
functions as an an instrument which combines aid and trade, a "contract" which embraces rights and
obligations and a framework for institutionalised consultation. The NAR recommends that the basis of this
framework be reviewed before the present Convention (Lom&#233; IV) comes to an end, with the aim of
ensuring that henceforth it is based more on development cooperation principles. The review should lead to
greater benefits for the poorest countries and fewer for the richer nations, as a result of which some of the
"most disadvantaged" countries will join the group of developing countries which are parties to the Conven-
tion.
<p>
<h4>European advisory network</h4>

The NAR will continue to promote the development of a European network for advising on development
cooperation policy and proposes that the Netherlands Government request the EC to provide more support
for its activities in this field. The NAR advocates that EC initiatives aimed at formulating a coherent and
coordinated European development policy be linked to the establishment of this advisory network.
<p>
<HR>
<H6><IMG ALIGN=middle
SRC="../images/nar.jpg"> <i>Updated on January 22, 1996</i><p>
